<SLUG> BC-MCCARTHY-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AILING GIRL GETS DEGREE IN DETERMINATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Dennis McCarthy is a columnist for the Los Angeles Daily News.) 
BY DENNIS McCARTHY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You can find the definition of courage and heart
living in a home over on Ballinger Street in the L.A. suburb of
Northridge. Find it in the body and mind of an incredible
14-year-old girl named Ashley Baim.
</P>
<P>
   She just did something that's never been done before in this
city. She went from eighth grade at Frost Middle School straight
through high school in two months _ passing the California High
School Proficiency Examination, the legal equivalent of a high
school diploma.
</P>
<P>
   How she did it _ and why _ is the kind of story that makes you
want to stand up and cheer for this little girl. And cry.
</P>
<P>
   Because with all the wonderful things she has going for her,
there is one thing she doesn't have. Time.
</P>
<P>
   Cystic fibrosis is working its cruel, life-threatening, genetic
disorder on her young body, and the dream of every teen-age school
kid _ someday walking across a high school stage to receive a
diploma with the rest of your classmates _ was taken from her this
June when it became just too hard for Ashley to continue attending
regular school anymore.
</P>
<P>
   So she had to come home to continue school, but she wouldn't let
go of her graduation dream. If she couldn't go to high school, well
_ why couldn't high school come to her?
</P>
<P>
   It did.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Hansen looked down at the middle-school test scores of
her newest home school student, and she shook her head. The kid had
scored 12s on the Kaufman Test of Educational Achievement all the
way across the line. Ashley was already testing academically at a
high school senior level.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the next page that stopped Hansen cold. Even though
there were long absences from school because of Ashley's hospital
stays, her teachers at Frost sung her praises.
</P>
<P>
   ``An outstanding worker,'' one said. ``Tremendously successful
and popular with her peers,'' wrote another. ``Never uses her
absences to shirk responsibilities, always completes makeup and
late assignments,'' said yet another.
</P>
<P>
   In 13 years of teaching home school at Carlson, she had never
seen teachers take the time to hand out compliments like this.
</P>
<P>
   So they crammed _ home teacher and student. Cutting corners on
four years of high school in two months, to make the mid-November
testing. The next test after that wouldn't be until next April _ a
long, eight months away for a kid with cystic fibrosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``She constantly challenged me,'' Hansen said. ``We cut through
a lot of material because Ashley would tell me not to worry about
it, she could already do that. We concentrated hard on essay
writing, because there was still a lot of vocabulary and terms this
little girl hadn't had the chance to tackle yet.''
</P>
<P>
   They worked in half-hour sessions because anything longer than
that and Ashley would begin to lose focus and strength. Because of
this, the plan was to spread the testing _ which is normally done
in three-hour blocks _ over two weeks, 30 minutes a session.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when it came time to take the test, Ashley was so fired
up, she finished it in two hour-and-a-half sessions,'' Hansen said.
``In 40 years of home school in the Los Angeles school district,
something like this has never been done before. Never.''
</P>
<P>
   The call from California Proficiency Testing came the day before
Thanksgiving. Congratulations, your daughter had passed the test,
the man on the line said. Ashley's high school equivalency diploma
was on the way.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Baim put down the phone, and didn't know whether to laugh
or cry. She told her husband, Larry, and they told Ashley's older
sister, Emily, and older brother, Zack.
</P>
<P>
   Then they all called Ashley into the living room.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a couple of more pictures left on a roll in the
camera, and my mom said she wanted to get some more shots of all of
us together,'' Ashley said. ``She said I wasn't smiling enough, so
she was going to tell me something to make me smile more.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told me I had passed. I said: `Yeah _ right, Mom.' `No,
really,' she said. `You passed.' They just called. I let out a big
scream. I was so excited. I really wanted that diploma.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could never have done it without my family supporting me,
and my teachers at Frost who taught me so much,'' Ashley said.
``And, of course, Mrs. Hansen, who became like a granny to me.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
!boxes!
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was a beautiful day for a high school graduation.
Dozens of cars lined Ballinger Street, as about 50 people filed
into the Baim home for the ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen was there, all decked out. Her schoolbooks left at home.
Ashley's physical therapist and respiratory therapist, along with
her doctor at Encino-Tarzana Medical Center, were there. So were a
lot of Ashley's relatives and friends, including Dara Moss, her
``bestest friend,'' Ashley said.
</P>
<P>
   They all stood as ``Pomp and Circumstance'' was played on the
piano, applauding as a young, beautiful girl walked out of her
bedroom wearing a cap and gown.
</P>
<P>
   In the back of the room, Ashley spotted her brother, Zack.
``Love you,'' she shouted out to her older brother, who also has
cystic fibrosis.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody smiled, and wiped away the tears.
</P>
<P>
   And then the assistant principal at Carlson, Gene Nelson, walked
to the front of the living room, presenting Ashley with her coveted
diploma, as Stephanie Hansen looked on, beaming.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I understand, you really nailed that test,'' Nelson
said, as everyone applauded.
</P>
<P>
   Ashley thanked him, hugged her mom and dad, and then invited
everyone to join her for a grad night party in the den.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone ate, and later took a turn belting out a song to
karaoke.
</P>
<P>
   When it came her turn, Ashley sang ``I Will Survive.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
