<SLUG> BC-BKC-SCHOOP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST A LITTLE MORE TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC guard Quincy Wilder left the basketball team
for a day last week and considered transferring because he was
upset over playing time.
</P>
<P>
   Wilder departed last Thursday but returned to the team Friday,
although he was suspended from that night's game against UC Santa
Barbara for missing classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Quincy is having some problems, like every kid who's
been a star,'' USC coach Henry Bibby said. ``I'm sure he's not
getting the minutes he would like. Again, I don't dictate the
minutes, the players do.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to play, you have to show me something. We have
five coaches evaluating who should be playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilder, a junior college transfer from Highline Community
College in Des Moines, Wash., has averaged 5.0 points and 1.75
assists per game in 14.5 minutes of action. He is a former Mr.
Washington, who was considered the top guard in the state two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Wilder has played point guard for the Trojans, although he
played shooting guard in high school and junior college. He
transferred to USC with teammate Brian Scalabrine, who is USC's
leading scorer (14.4 points) and rebounder (7.6).
</P>
<P>
   __ Turner returns: Forward Jarvis Turner will likely start
against Loyola Marymount on Wednesday, after being suspended with
Wilder for missing a pair of classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our policy is you have to go to class,'' Bibby said.
``Absences have to be reckoned with.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Thomas out: Quarterback Jason Thomas, who was expected to
play football and basketball for the Trojans, said he will not play
basketball this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to concentrate on football,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   He redshirted in football this season after undergoing ankle
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   __ It's a football school: Some fans have complained about the
change in the start of last Monday's St. Bonaventure game from 7
p.m. to 5 p.m. The time change was made about three weeks before
the game, because of an ``(athletic) department scheduling
conflict,'' according to a USC spokesperson.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict was that football coach Paul Hackett threw a party
for his wife that evening at a downtown Los Angeles hotel, which
was attended by many athletic-department employees.
</P>
<P>
   __ Moving on up: The Trojans received 24 votes in the Associated
Press Top 25 poll this week and are tied for 38th overall. That's
twice as many votes as the Trojans received last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
