</P>
<P>
   SCI-DENTISTRY (Undated) _ A combination of new technology and
new treatments _ laser beams that work on the hard enamel of teeth
and computerized x-rays _ are promising patients a freedom from
drilling, freedom from anesthesia and freedom from pain. The
treatments appear, in their initial stages, to be safer, more
accurate and faster than traditional methods. By Holcomb B. Noble.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SPACE-STATION (Undated) _ Far above the earth, test pilots,
engineers and scientists have begun practicing the building trades
as they tackle the mammoth job of assembling an international space
station at a truly remote site. The space shuttle Endeavour,
launched Friday with a crew of six, began one of the most
challenging construction jobs in history on Sunday when it joined
the first two pieces of the station together while orbiting 240
miles above the Earth. By Warren E. Leary.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-JOURNALS (Undated) _ In recent years, scientific journals
have become big business, with large commercial publishers entering
a scene once dominated by nonprofit scientific societies whose only
goal was to disseminate scientific information. It is a change that
many academics say has sent prices skyrocketing _ with some
journals now costing libraries more than $15,000 a year. By Carol
Kaesuk Yoon.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WELLS-SQUIDS (Cambridge, England) _ A conversation with
Martin Wells, an expert on cephalopods and grandson of H.G. Wells.
By Claudia Dreifus.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PREHISTORIC-MEDICINE (Undated) _ A traveler out of the past,
the Iceman whose mummified body was discovered in the Tyrolean Alps
in Northern Italy in 1991 has given archeologists and other
scientists a lifelike picture of what people wore and ate and
carried with them on treks into the Alps 5,300 years ago, at the
end of the Stone Age and beginning of the Copper Age in Europe. An
anthropologist reported last week that the Iceman is also providing
a rare glimpse of prehistoric medicine, including his apparent use
of a natural laxative and antibiotic. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MALTHUS-POPULATION (Philadelphia) _ Two-hundred years ago
the Rev. Thomas Robert Malthus, an English economist and
mathematician, anonymously published an essay predicting that the
world's burgeoning human population would overwhelm the earth's
capacity to feed it. His gloomy forecast, called ``An Essay on the
Principle of Population as It Affects the Future Improvement of
Society,'' was condemned by Karl Marx, Friedrich Engels and many
other theorists, and it was still striking sparks at a meeting of
the American Anthropological Society. Despite continuing
controversy, it was clear that Malthus's conjectures are far from
dead. By Malcolm Browne.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ICU-PSYCHOSIS (Undated) _ More and more patients are
experiencing a type of psychiatric disturbance, called ICU
psychosis, as intensive care units proliferate in American
hospitals. Experts are not sure just what causes, but the symptoms
usually disappear once patients leave the ICU confines. By Sandeep
Jauhar, M.D.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FITNESS-ABS (Undated) _ With abdominal training it appears
there is no middle ground. Exercisers are often confused about the
best way to strengthen and tone the midriff. And for good reason:
experts can't seem to agree either. Even the research isn't
definitive. By Liz Neporent.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-OSTEOPOROSIS-MEN (Undated) _ New research is challenging the
medical textbook view of osteoporosis as a largely women's disease
linked to the singularly female experience of menopause. It now
seems that osteoporosis is more common in men than previously
thought and that, although men do not go through menopause, the
main cause of the degenerative bone disorder is the same in both
men and women: an age-related drop in estrogen. By Susan Gilbert.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SKIN-HERBS (Undated) _ A Westchester (N.Y.) County
dermatologist has compiled a list of skin conditions and various
herbs that often are used to treat them. But, he cautions, doctors
should be alerted to their use, especially when used in conjunction
with other medicines. By Nancy Beth Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SEX-HEALTH (Undated) _ Among sexually transmitted diseases,
syphilis, herpes, chlamydia, gonorrhea and HIV are probably the
best known. However, a report released last week shows that two
lesser known infections _ human papillomavirus and trichomoniasis _
actually account for two-thirds of new cases of the diseases. By
Linda Villarosa.
</P>
