<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
 
PROBABLY NO TROPHY FOR McNOWN MANTLE 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA quarterback Cade McNown departs this week for
the Downtown Athletic Club in New York. He's not expected to return
with a certain piece of hardware in his suitcase.
</P>
<P>
   McNown's Heisman Trophy candidacy was consistent this season: He
trailed Texas tailback Ricky Williams in September and he trailed
Williams in November. His brilliant performance in Miami (513
yards, six touchdowns) probably won't change the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   McNown is not expected to win the Heisman on Saturday. In fact,
he might finish third, behind Williams and Kansas State quarterback
Michael Bishop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the fact that people are impressed with Ricky
Williams breaking the NCAA (career) rushing record and rushing for
over 2,000 yards this season, I certainly think he's the front
runner,'' UCLA media-relations director Marc Dellins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hopeful that people waited to send their ballots in.
Anybody who saw Cade play Saturday knows why we feel he's the best
player in the country, and certainly the most valuable.''
</P>
<P>
   __ A theory: UCLA's tackling against Miami was horrific, but the
Bruins' biggest problem was their inability to create turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   For 10 games, the defense caused an average of four turnovers
per game. That's four possessions, which translates to 10-14 points
and about 150 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Miami was the first UCLA opponent that didn't commit a turnover.
Subtract 14 points and 150 yards from the Hurricanes' total, and
suddenly it's a typically porous _ but not pathetic _ game for
UCLA's defense.
</P>
<P>
   Just think how many points Oregon would have scored without five
turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   __ Another theory: When asked if the defense was distracted or
uninterested or simply overwhelmed, one offensive player shook his
head.
</P>
<P>
   ``First play, their leader went down,'' he said. ``From there, I
could see it in their eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   On Miami's first play, senior linebacker Brendon Ayanbadejo, the
emotional leader and big-play maker, sprained the medial collateral
ligament in his left knee. He returned for one play, then watched
the rest of the game on crutches.
</P>
<P>
   __ The schedule: The Bruins will conduct light workouts today
and Thursday, then have full-contact practices Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   They'll take next week off for final exams, then practice Dec.
18-19 and 21-23 before breaking for Christmas. They are due back in
town Dec. 26 to begin Rose Bowl preparations.
</P>
<P>
   __ Which season is this? Monday afternoon, freshmen DeShaun
Foster, Julius Williams and Ken Pritchett defeated three
upperclassmen in several hotly contested basketball games at Pauley
Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got heart,'' Foster said. ``But they can't play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
