<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL RECONSIDERS INSTANT REPLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The legacy of The Call might be more than just a
crushing Seahawks loss. After two weeks of high-profile officiating
gaffes that culminated in Sunday's Seahawks game against the New
York Jets, the NFL is considering a return to instant replay for
this year's playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   League spokesman Joe Browne confirmed Monday that if the owners
approve, ``a limited form of replay for use in the upcoming
postseason is a possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   That won't help the Seahawks, who fell to 6-7 and were all but
eliminated from postseason play when the Jets' Vinny Testaverde was
given a game-winning touchdown despite being stopped just shy of
the end zone in the final seconds of Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Seahawks coach Dennis Erickson said he doubted instant replay
would be instituted before next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will they? Oh, no,'' Erickson said. ``Instant replay will take
forever to get in. It's got to go to the owners, then it's got to
go to the league meetings, then it's got to be voted on. They can,
if they decide they want to, get it in there. ... But, again, you
won't see it until next year, if you see it at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Seeman, the NFL's senior director of officiating, called
Erickson Monday and admitted officials erred. But if instant replay
were in place, it's likely that phone call _ and all of this
controversy _ never would have happened. The new replay system
would likely take the form used in preseason experiments _ with
coaches given a limited number of challenges per game and referees
making the final decision from monitors on the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   But it also would be what one league official called
``liberal,'' meaning that if a coach is out of challenges on a
game-deciding play, he would be allowed an additional one.
</P>
<P>
   Instant replay failed by two votes last year, but several teams
that voted it down seem likely to approve it next time. The Buffalo
Bills, who were hurt by blown calls in a loss to New England Nov.
29, now say they would vote for it, and indications are San Diego
and Tampa Bay also would change their votes. The expansion
Cleveland Browns, led by instant replay proponent Carmen Policy,
likely would vote yes.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks always have voted for instant replay, and Erickson
said the reasons are obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``To right wrongs,'' he said. ``I think there are too many times
that something can be changed that are critical in a game. You've
got to save it for the right time, that's part of the thing too,
but at least you can correct something that's wrong that may cause
the outcome of the game (to be affected).
</P>
<P>
   `` ... They've been voting on it every year, and the same guys
voted against it. Maybe now that they've seen some of these things
happen, they'll sit down and really look at it and decide it's
probably the best thing. Obviously, we need it.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Jets coach Bill Parcells voted against replay.
Last year, he voted yes after the Jets were victims of bad calls by
officials in the final game against Detroit that left them out of
the playoffs. But Parcells said he hates the challenge system that
was tested during the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be opposed to anything that deviates from the premise
of getting the calls correct,'' he said. `` ... There is one
objective _ get the calls right. Not some of the calls, not the
calls in the second half or the last quarter or only in the end
zone. It's to get the calls right.''
</P>
<P>
   The system tried in exhibitions involves giving coaches limited
challenges on calls _ perhaps two per half or two a game _ with the
referee making the final decision after viewing the play on a
sideline monitor.
</P>
<P>
   That would help end the objections to the system in effect from
1986 to 1991, which used a replay official in a booth and was
filled with endless challenges and endless delays, some lasting
longer than five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Few pretend that replay solves everything. Steelers president
Dan Rooney said last week he thinks officials are overly managed
already, leading to indecision.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks-Jets game is an example. Phil Luckett, the referee
in that game, said that once head linesman Earnie Frantz signaled
touchdown, as he did almost as soon as Testaverde hit the ground,
the debate was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because he had signaled a touchdown, so far as we're concerned
it's over,'' Luckett said.
</P>
<P>
   But NFL rules specify that if another official disagrees with
the call, the referee can reverse it. On Sunday night in Minnesota,
referee Bob McElwee reversed himself after he ruled a fumble and
other officials said Steve Stenstrom's knee had hit the ground
before the ball came out.
</P>
<P>
   The difference may be that Luckett, who is well-regarded by
coaches and players, is in his second year as a crew chief and his
eighth as an NFL official. McElwee is in his 23rd year as an
official, most of those as a referee.
</P>
<P>
   P-I Reporter Clare Farnsworth and The Associated Press
contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-98 0035EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
