<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLOWN CALLS DAMAGE NFL'S CREDIBILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The discussion is beyond heated now. It is at full
boil.
</P>
<P>
   After another weekend of abysmal calls, NFL officials are being
lambasted as scared, pathetic weekend zebras.
</P>
<P>
   By now the most reviled man in America, Phil ``I Heard Tails, Or
Was That Heads?'' Luckett, has become a living, and we think
breathing, incarnation of a Chevy Chase character.
</P>
<P>
   If it weren't so tragic watching Luckett and other henpecked
officials cower through NFL games, it would be a downright
knee-slapper.
</P>
<P>
   Except, of course, if you are Seahawk coach Dennis Erickson or
anyone remotely associated with the Hawks. For them, the blown call
that cost the Hawks a victory Sunday against the Jets was a joke
that rendered a perfectly excellent NFL game meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   This undeserved defeat _ the final crush for the underachieving
Seahawks' playoffs chances _ has become more fodder for a national
referendum on the state of NFL officiating. The Hawks' misfortune
is the final piece of glaring evidence that demonstrates NFL
officials need the technical support of instant replay.
</P>
<P>
   Until NFL owners vote again _ and there is growing indication
from the now-incensed owners that instant replay will be reinstated
_ the only thing a victimized team like the Seahawks can do is take
Sunday's travesty as a personal insult.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't a Seahawk fan, coach, player, observer, bartender or
sportswriter who has not waited about four seasons for a win as
captivating, as fantastic, as deserved as the one Jon Kitna &AMP; Crew
were executing against Vinny Testaverde and The Tuna on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It was, simply, a great game _ from Kitna's touchdown bombs to
Testaverde's dramatic decision to run the quarterback draw.
</P>
<P>
   But then, ``the call.'' What a rip-off.
</P>
<P>
   If Erickson has felt his entire tenure in Seattle has been
jinxed, beginning with the end of The Behring Years, what must the
coach really think about his luck now, thanks to Mr. Luckett?
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the NFL made another one of its sorry calls. Yep, the
refs blew your game, the Seahawks were told. Merry Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   On the local level, there was this intense irony to the
officials' horrendous call: It came when Erickson's entire,
embattled tenure was getting a single, if only symbolic, boost of
optimism.
</P>
<P>
   We're not suggesting that beating the Jets would have put the
Seahawks in the playoffs. Nor are we suggesting that Erickson's job
could have been irrefutably salvaged with the win Sunday _ not when
3-0 had fallen to 6-6.
</P>
<P>
   However, if there is such a thing as going down a winner, if
there is such a thing as a moral victory, the Seahawks had all but
secured that. Now, if they do go 9-7 and just miss the playoffs,
who from the NFL office will call and say sorry again?
</P>
<P>
   Some of us knee-jerk baseball fans thought American League
umpire Ted Hendry's ever-shifting strike zone was the ultimate in
officiating buffoonary.
</P>
<P>
   No. Baseball's umpiring woes, which are deeply ingrained because
baseball umps are full-timers with a mega-powerful union, are out
of sight right now, out of mind.
</P>
<P>
   This winter, with the absence of the NBA, our sporting eyes have
fallen squarely on the little juggernaut run by NFL commissioner
Paul Tagliabue. And for the most part, the NFL has been decent
filler.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Flutie has starred as ``The Little Man That Could.'' Randy
Moss and Randall Cunningham have been splendid in Minnesota. John
Elway is making undefeated Denver the epicenter for NFL history.
And best of all, there is a Super Bowl brewing between the Vikings
and Broncos _ a terrific showdown that could help sell a lot of
beer and sport utility vehicles this January.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL should be licking its chops over this steady stream of
great copy and high-flying highlights. Instead, there is
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL did away with instant replay because certain owners
liked the human aspect of a game being officiated on the field.
Also, the delays that took place with review of the videotape was
seen as a monstrous drag on the action.
</P>
<P>
   Hello? Are these the same people who have failed to notice that
with a $17.6 billion TV contract through 2005, the lengths of
today's commercial-packed NFL games are longer than a Ken Starr
investigation?
</P>
<P>
   There is absolutely no logical reason for not reinstating the
one thing that can right a wrong. After the Colts were called
losers against the 49ers; after Flutie and the Bills were robbed in
Foxboro; after the Steelers' coin-toss call fell on deaf ears on
Thanksgiving, and after the Hawks were jobbed in Jersey, there is
no question.
</P>
<P>
   NFL officials have lodged themselves into the top spot of
questionable competence, along with the Republican majority in
Congress, among those whom America depends on to make the right
call.
</P>
<P>
   To err is human. But to err so many times, in so many critical
games, almost certainly means that without instant replay, the
credibility of the NFL is up for grabs, to say nothing of the
competency of one Mr. Luckett.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
