<DOCNO> NYT19981208.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7890 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHUTTLE-STATION-1STLD     12-08 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-STATION-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPACEWALKERS CONNECT ELECTRICAL MODULES &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: updated material included) 
 
By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Astronauts Jerry Ross and Jim Newman, floating outside
the shuttle Endeavour on Monday night, successfully connected
dozens of crucial electrical power and computer signal cables
between American and Russian modules of the new international space
station.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before 10 p.m. CST, Russian ground control teams radioed
commands to their ``Zarya'' power and propulsion station module,
allowing electricity generated by its winglike solar collectors to
flow into the U.S. ``Unity'' module and a pair of essential flight
control computers for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a good connection with good data,'' Endeavour
commander Bob Cabana informed mission control. The shuttle skipper
monitored the status of the current flow between the modules
through a laptop computer aboard Endeavour.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Cabana confirmed the flow of computer signals between
the modules through the new cabling.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. and Russian crew aboard Endeavour joined the Zarya
module to Unity on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's near seven-hour excursion, the first of three planned
by the two men this week, was considered by far the most crucial.
Without the 40 cable connections by Ross and Newman, the power
generated by Zarya would not reach the computers and other
electronics aboard Unity.
</P>
<P>
   Power is essential to Unity, a 33-foot cylinder with a
half-dozen docking ports that will link future station components,
including stabilizing gyroscopes, a U.S. laboratory, an airlock and
more powerful solar collectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The assembly sequence stops if we can't get these avionics
(electronics) working,'' said NASA flight director Bob Castle,
before the spacewalk.
</P>
<P>
   The spacewalkers crawled from an airlock in the shuttle's cargo
bay shortly after 4 p.m. and never looked back as they raced
through their tasks, at one point working 90 minutes ahead of
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me, oh my,'' gushed Ross, his attention momentarily drawn to
the brilliant rays of the sun setting on the Earth's horizon 240
miles below. ``We're going around the world awfully fast.''
</P>
<P>
   The Unity and Zarya modules towered nearly eight stories above
the airlock, secured to Endeavour's docking mechanism for the
series of spacewalks.
</P>
<P>
   The pace with which Ross, Newman and their shuttle colleagues
worked reflected the more than 500 hours of ground training the two
veteran spacewalkers received to prepare them for the often tedious
tasks.
</P>
<P>
   The evening's only setback was the loss of a fist-sized, metal
tool that spacewalking astronauts can plug into station modules to
temporarily park larger pieces of equipment. The socket tool got
away from Ross and rose above the nose of Endeavour before the
astronauts lost sight of it.
</P>
<P>
   Ross, a 50-year-old Air Force colonel who had logged four
previous spacewalks, secured himself on the tip of Endeavour's
50-foot robot arm, which afforded a mobile platform from which to
connect the cables.
</P>
<P>
   Newman, 42, a physicist who conducted a previous spacewalk five
years ago, unstowed each of the snaking 20-foot cables bound to the
outside of the two modules at three different work sites, handing
them to his colleague in a prearranged sequence. Newman worked from
a portable mechanical foot restraint that he moved and plugged into
anchoring receptacles located around the work sites.
</P>
<P>
   Assisting them from inside the shuttle were Nancy Currie,
Endeavour's robot arm operator, and pilot Rick Sturckow, their
timekeeper.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's spacewalk called for Ross and Newman to work first at
the base of the Unity module, which was latched to the shuttle's
docking mechanism, where they connected their first eight cables.
</P>
<P>
   Each time his colleague handed him a new power line, Ross would
remove a protective cover installed before the equipment was
launched to prevent debris from lodging between the connector pins.
Using his helmet light, Ross also inspected the dozens of fragile
pins in each connector to ensure they had not been bent.
</P>
<P>
   Ross carried a ``pin straightener'' tool to correct deviants,
and in one instance he found canted plug pins that he repositioned
before making the connections.
</P>
<P>
   Cold temperatures, as low as 200 degrees below zero, had
stiffened some of the thick cables. More than once, Ross and Newman
jokingly referred to the electrical bundles as ``the octopus'' as
they wrestled them into position.
</P>
<P>
   Once the cables were plugged to a receptacle, a twist of Ross'
wrist moved a locking collar into place to prevent separation. He
also slipped a sleeve of fabric thermal insulation over each
connection.
</P>
<P>
   Ross and Newman finished their assignment by moving to the top
of Unity, where the U.S. module was joined to Zarya. There they
made the rest of the connections.
</P>
<P>
   The final half-dozen connections made it possible for the power
generated by Zarya's solar collectors to flow into Unity.
</P>
<P>
   Ross and Newman worked so quickly that they had time to install
foot restraints and handles on the outside of the two modules,
tasks they had not been slated to attempt until their second and
third spacewalks.
</P>
<P>
   NASA planned to give Endeavour's six astronauts a half-day off
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   today.
</P>
<P>
   The mission's second excursion was scheduled for Wednesday.
After donning spacesuits, Ross and Newman will install a pair of
communications antennas on the outside of Unity, allowing mission
control teams in Houston to monitor activities aboard the new
station over a NASA satellite network rather than through Russian
ground stations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
