<DOCNO> NYT19981208.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7894 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BOWLS-HNS &LR;      12-08 1351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOWLS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
You know you've had a bad day when Steve Spurrier sends
condolences.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I really feel sad for Kansas State,'' Florida's
take-no-prisoners coach said after hearing that the just-declawed
Wildcats had slipped out of the Bowl Championship Series. ``That
game (K-State's 36-33 loss in the Big 12 Championship Game) was the
biggest thing in their school history, and now they're up there
with not much of anything but a bowl trip.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, so San Antonio is hardly anyone's idea of a bad trip, but it
wasn't quite what K-State had in mind. Nor was that the only bit of
inexplicable news as college football's Judgment Saturday and
Selection Sunday created winners, losers and some strange
bedfellows.
</P>
<P>
   Sit by the phone, and suddenly you were on your way to the
Fiesta Bowl. Drop the ball at the wrong time, and you were making
plans to enjoy the River Walk. Get a bad call on a fumble, and next
thing you know, you're staring daggers at a Rose Bowl rep _ just
the sort of fellow you used to love to see coming.
</P>
<P>
   Weird business, to be sure, though losses by Kansas State and
UCLA at least helped sort things out a little bit. That won't keep
the Wildcats and Bruins from feeling sorry for themselves after
redefining the term ``costly turnover,'' and Ohio State no doubt
will continue to plead its ``what about us?'' case from Bourbon
Street.
</P>
<P>
   As the BCS closes down its computer for the year, the cry for a
playoff may be louder than ever, and some of the weekend's more
absurd images just might help move the process along.
</P>
<P>
   While Florida State coach Bobby Bowden sat on his couch and took
in the war of attrition on television, Phillip Fulmer's Tennessee
Volunteers found themselves trailing Mississippi State in the
fourth quarter of the Southeastern Conference Championship Game in
Atlanta. The Vols were able to pull it out, but had they not, it's
likely Ohio State and Florida State _ two teams idle and barely
breathing at the start of the day _ would have been headed to
Tempe, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to have these championship games, I'd like to
see everyone have one,'' Fulmer said. ``It would make it a little
more fair.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time the dust settled on Sunday, Phil Fulmer wasn't the
only one raising the fairness issue. Money talked, bowl officials
listened, and the sacrosanct system _ the one BCS backers are so
intent on saving _ took yet another hit in the credibility
department.
</P>
<P>
   So yes, Steve Spurrier sends his best. He'll also do so from the
Orange Bowl, where his 9-2 Gators are in for a $12 million payday.
</P>
<P>
   As for K-State? It's 11-1 and just a fumble away from Sun Devil
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Enjoy the sights of the Alamo City, Wildcats. And when you
stroll by the river, do your best not to fall in, OK?
</P>
<P>
   Fiesta
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with a season-long theme, the talk isn't so much
about who is coming but who won't be able to make the date.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee started the season without Peyton Manning, the top
pick in the NFL draft, leaving the quarterback job to junior Tee
Martin. The successor to the legend isn't in Manning's league as a
passer, but Martin made the big plays when he had to and did so
again Saturday night in rallying the Vols past Mississippi State
with a pair of late touchdown throws.
</P>
<P>
   Gone, too, is running back Jamal Lewis, who injured a knee in
midseason. A televised report Sunday indicated Lewis could be back
for the Fiesta Bowl, but Fulmer dismissed that as ``extremely
doubtful, since he's just gotten off crutches.''
</P>
<P>
   And just when things were settling down a bit, offensive
coordinator David Cutcliffe was named head coach at Mississippi,
where he starts work this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it'll be a distraction,'' Fulmer said. ``Maybe
it'll be an advantage if we end up with a few different wrinkles
offensively.''
</P>
<P>
   FSU knows something about changing on the fly, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles, upset early by North Carolina State, were just
beginning to roll when quarterback Chris Weinke suffered a
season-ending neck injury. Bowden expects him back next summer, but
backup Marcus Outzen gets the call in the Fiesta.
</P>
<P>
   Having wide receiver Peter Warrick as a pass-catching, running
and passing threat (he threw for a touchdown off an end-around
against Florida) to lean on should make things easier for Outzen.
So should the nation's No. 1 defense, which held rival Florida to
204 yards, the Gators' worst offensive output in more than eight
years.
</P>
<P>
   If this one comes down to a field goal, each team is
well-legged. Tennessee's Jeff Hall and FSU's Sebastian Janikowski
are two of the best in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Sugar
</P>
<P>
   Folks in New Orleans expected Florida State and Kansas State in
what was shaping up as an ``alternative'' national-title game.
Instead, they get Texas A&AMP;M and Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   One is delighted to be coming. The other is not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a goal of winning the national championship,'' said
Buckeyes coach John Cooper. ``Sometimes, you adjust those goals on
the run.''
</P>
<P>
   If Cooper's team shows up in New Orleans with a computer chip on
its shoulder, the Buckeyes might have more than their attitude
adjusted by an A&AMP;M team that may not need a plane to make the trip.
In rallying from 15 points down to stun Kansas State in the Big 12
Championship Game, the Aggies proceeded to knock the Wildcats out
of the Sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a late-season loss to Michigan State, the Buckeyes field
as much talent as any team in the country. Wide receiver David
Boston (from Humble), linebacker Andy Katzenmoyer and cornerback
Antoine Winfield are among the nation's best at their positions,
and quarterback Joe Germaine was beginning to get some Heisman
Trophy mention prior to the Michigan State loss.
</P>
<P>
   Rose
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the joy of being a Rose Bowl rep in the UCLA locker room
Saturday evening in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, don't.
</P>
<P>
   Dreams of playing for the national title turned into visions of
playing a glorified home game, all because of a fumble that
apparently wasn't. Now, the Bruins will have to regroup in time to
face a Wisconsin team that will feel very differently about the
trip.
</P>
<P>
   The Badgers lost to Michigan but earned a three-way tie for the
Big Ten title with the Wolverines and Ohio State. Wisconsin got the
Rose bid by virtue of having gone least recently.
</P>
<P>
   While UCLA rings up points and stats with a passing game led by
quarterback Cade McNown _ who was nothing short of brilliant in the
loss to Miami _ the Badgers grind it out, with huge Ron Dayne doing
most of the damage.
</P>
<P>
   At least this game has the Big Ten-Pac-10 tradition going for
it. It also could turn out to be an old-style Rose Bowl where the
kids from the Midwest go to California, soak up some rays _ then
spend the game chasing their quicker, faster opponents from the
coast to little avail.
</P>
<P>
   That assumes, of course, that UCLA decides to show up.
</P>
<P>
   Orange
</P>
<P>
   Gee, wouldn't Kansas State have looked good here?
</P>
<P>
   Nah
</P>
<P>
   The fix for this one was in last week, but Ohio State was the
one being squeezed in order to make room for Spurrier and the
Gators. Already saddled with 8-3 Syracuse (an automatic BCS
qualifier as the Big East champion), the Orange was determined to
add local color, and orange and blue will do just fine.
</P>
<P>
   Florida isn't up to snuff, as its season-long offensive
struggles attest, but this is a pretty respectable 9-2. The losses,
after all, came against Tennessee (20-17 in overtime) and Florida
State (23-12 in Tallahassee), and we know what those kids will be
up to come January.
</P>
<P>
   Under normal circumstances, the Gators would be a lock in this
one, but circumstances are hardly normal in Gainesville. Defensive
coordinator Bob Stoops has taken the head coaching job at Oklahoma,
while running-backs coach Carl Franks is the new head man at Duke.
</P>
<P>
   Spurrier, of course, remains. And even though his team made the
field, he remains one of the most outspoken advocates of a playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every other sport does it,'' he said. ``Why we can't is beyond
me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-98 0104EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
