<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7895 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BAYLOR-COACH-HNS &LR;      12-08 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BAYLOR-COACH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
WACO _ Several Baylor football players met with athletic director
Tom Stanton late in the season and said they were unhappy and would
consider transferring to another school if Dave Roberts were not
replaced as the Bears' coach, sources confirmed Monday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roberts, who had back-to-back 2-9 seasons at Baylor, was
reassigned within the athletic department Sunday. Stanton would
neither confirm nor deny the players had spoken to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to get into any details of my evaluation,''
Stanton said. ``The kids in the program are important to me. The
opportunity of the kids to realize their dreams is what we want.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be competitive in the Big 12 and go to bowl games.
In order for us to attain that and have the kids move forward and
win, I felt the right step was to change leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   The man believed to be the No. 1 choice of Stanton is former
Alabama coach Gene Stallings, who led the Crimson Tide to the 1992
national championship. Stallings, 63, retired after the 1996 season
and lives on his ranch near Paris, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Stallings was in Jacksonville, Fla., on Monday for a speaking
engagement and could not be reached for comment, but Sunday night
he said he considered a return to coaching ``slim'' but would talk
to Baylor officials if they called.
</P>
<P>
   Stallings is committed to coaching a college all-star team that
will play in Italy in July, but sources say that stumbling block
could be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I began the search process this morning,'' Stanton said
Monday. ``I have a list of candidates that will remain
confidential, but I feel very comfortable with that list.''
</P>
<P>
   Other names believed to be on Stanton's list include former
Auburn coach Terry Bowden, Southern Mississippi coach Jeff Bower
and former Colorado coach Bill McCartney. Also under consideration
is Highland Park High School coach Scott Smith, who could be hired
as an assistant and be groomed to take over as the head coach in
two or three years.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's announcement on Roberts came as a surprise to some
Baylor fans, but the reasons for the action became more clear with
the information about the disenchantment of the players.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore Odell James, the MacArthur product who shared time at
quarterback this season with Jermaine Alfred, was displeased with
his situation late in the year and told Roberts he wanted to change
positions, but Roberts would not comply.
</P>
<P>
   Had Roberts remained the head coach, sources say a few Baylor
players were considering transferring to Stephen F. Austin if
former Baylor coach Chuck Reedy is hired by the Lumberjacks to
replace John Pearce. No decision has been made at SFA. Reedy was
the offensive coordinator at South Carolina and a member of the
coaching staff that was fired at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Sources also say Stanton had heard from disgruntled prominent
alumni who wanted Roberts out, and Stanton learned several of the
Baylor assistant coaches were unhappy working under Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of all these factors apparently played into the
decision Stanton made over the weekend to make a coaching change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent a lot of time reviewing and assessing where we are, as
I do at the end of every season,'' Stanton said. ``It took a little
longer than I anticipated. After the evaluation, I made a
recommendation to president (Robert) Sloan to reassign coach
Roberts. That is a closed chapter now, and we'll move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanton said he wants to find a new coach as quickly as
possible, but he wouldn't rush the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything is possible, but I don't think it's likely something
will happen in the next two or three days,'' Stanton said. ``I
don't have a timetable in terms of saying something will be done in
three or four days. If it takes five days or 10 days, that's what
it takes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may see me as a knee-jerk-reaction guy, but I'm not. I
wanted to make sure whatever decision I made was the right decision
for our players and the university.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, who was the offensive coordinator at Notre Dame under
Lou Holtz, was the first major hire for Stanton after taking over
as the athletic director in the spring of 1996. Stanton was asked
if he now views that hire as a bad decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a fair question, but I'm proud Dave coached here and
don't look back on it as a mistake,'' Stanton said. ``I look at it
as a transition and evolution of our football program.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a certain set of circumstances surrounding our
football program at that time. We were looking for discipline and
wanted someone who had been involved with a big program, along with
someone with private-school experience and expertise. Dave fit the
bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanton said it is ``business as usual'' for the assistant
coaches, but the person selected as the new head coach will have
the final say on selecting his staff.
</P>
<P>
   One assistant coach definitely will not be back. Linebackers
coach Andy McCollum, who is considered the team's best recruiter,
is expected to be named the head coach at Middle Tennessee State
today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
