<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7897 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-H     12-08 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THE last thing you need to hear today is more caterwauling about
the injustices of the Bowl Championship Series. We know it's
unfair, the same as we know war is bad, wine is good, and love can
go either way.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, one grad's anguish is another's alum's ecstasy. None of
you Farmers or Teasips is complaining this morning, are you? Thanks
to the BCS, Texas and Texas A&AMP;M have been afforded the unique
privilege of participating in the Cotton and Sugar bowls,
respectively, on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Longhorns have been playing football since 1893 and
the Aggies since 1894, such a convergence is historic. So historic
that it has never occurred before. But it could have, and probably
should have.
</P>
<P>
   Inequities, lest we forget in our interminable hand-wringing,
aren't exactly a recent phenomenon in the colleges' ever-capricious
postseason. A quick search of the A&AMP;M-Texas archives reveals one
particularly striking example.
</P>
<P>
   In 1941, only a couple weeks preceding Pearl Harbor, D.X.
Bible's then-10th-ranked Longhorns laid waste to Homer Norton's
second-ranked Aggies at Kyle Field 23-0 as if the visitors were
trying to reprise Germany's rout of Poland. A week later, the
'Horns destroyed Oregon 71-7.
</P>
<P>
   Didn't work. See, before thumping the Aggies, Texas had lapsed,
blowing its No. 1 ranking by tying Baylor, then losing to TCU.
Hence, No. 9 A&AMP;M went to the Cotton Bowl as SWC champion by half a
game. The Longhorns, despite having risen back to No. 4, stayed
home.
</P>
<P>
   For reasons lost to the sands of time, the Sugar selected
Fordham and Missouri (getting a 2-0 score to show for the
decision). The Orange, in turn, took TCU over Texas _ the Frogs
had, after all, upset the 'Horns _ to face Georgia. And the Rose
Bowl, snubbing UT's overtures, pitted Oregon State against Duke at
Duke.
</P>
<P>
   The granddaddy bowl was moved to Carolina out of fear of
possible Japanese airstrikes on California. Guess Austin wasn't
quite far enough east. But get this: Minnesota won the national
championship without going anywhere, choosing to stay home with the
whole world suddenly turned upside down. And there were, of course,
no other bowls to barter with back then. To early-1940s Americans,
a term such as ``Insight.com'' would have been as incomprehensible
as Sanskrit.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, today's jumbled BCS mess suddenly seems the stuff
of genius. Nonetheless, as evolved as our society has become, in
theory anyway, can't there exist a more effective way to identify
the national champion?
</P>
<P>
   OK, it's not a simple business to overhaul. Even an eight-team
bracket, a popular solution being bandied about as we speak, leaves
the door open for considerable error. How could you truly defend
leaving an 11-0 Tulane out of such a mix? And didn't Syracuse, a
lowly No. 15 in the BCS, lay a 53-point licking on the Miami team
that subsequently destroyed UCLA's title hopes? Neither would have
made the cut at eight.
</P>
<P>
   But the recent weekend's dramatics suggest a possibly safe
passage through the minefield. The first Saturday in December could
serve, in effect, as a round of 16 for an NCAA postseason football
tournament, with the Big 12 and SEC championship games
grandfathered into the system, serving as two of the matchups.
</P>
<P>
   Were the Big Ten to expand to 12 members and create a title
fight of its own _ a frequent topic of conjecture _ it, too, would
be included in the mix. The other pairings would be determined by a
BCS-type system utilizing seedings not unlike March Madness' to
determine who plays whom and where. Revenues might then be shared
equally among all the qualifiers to alleviate the pressure of
worrying about who gets the home games.
</P>
<P>
   For the eight teams advancing, there would be no more football
until the New Year with the Rose, Fiesta, Sugar and Orange bowls
serving as the Elite Eight round. The break would give the athletes
the same semblance of a Christmas respite they enjoy now, and there
would be nothing to interfere with all the usual pre-bowl color and
pageantry.
</P>
<P>
   The December losers, meanwhile, would return to the pool from
which the other bowls could pick. There would be plenty of
attractive matchups, maybe more than we have at present.
</P>
<P>
   Football's Final Four would follow the second weekend in January
at two of the same four sites _ turnaround time is no problem for
stadiums during the NFL playoffs _ with a third hosting the title
game, always on the weekend before the Super Bowl, when the NFL is
dark.
</P>
<P>
   The rotation for hosting the semis and the grand finale would
work exactly as it does currently. The whopping bonus income
generated by the three additional games would more than compensate
for whatever trivial complications and difficulties are created.
</P>
<P>
   Money may not buy happiness, but we would all agree it tends to
provide a sizable down payment. Eventually, the NCAA and the big
bowls will see the light. Everyone knows there's a more logical,
more profitable way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-98 0106EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
