<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEARY IACENDA TO LEAVE USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC sophomore fullback Ted Iacenda, weary over the
negative publicity and atmosphere that has surrounded his college
career, has decided to transfer to another school.
</P>
<P>
   The former Hart High School star is no longer practicing with
the Trojans and will not play in the Sun Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Iacenda's departure is not football related, but stems from the
emotional rollercoaster he went through for nearly two years after
being charged _ and subsequently cleared _ of sexual assault
charges brought during his freshman year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I needed a change based on my case,'' Iacenda said. ``I
needed to get away because that's been with me since I've been
here. Every time I met with somebody, that would be the first thing
that came to their mind. The dirty looks or people speaking about
it never stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   Iacenda started six games this season, and rushed eight times
for 38 yards. His biggest moment of the season came in the Arizona
State game, when he caught a two-point conversion from Carson
Palmer in the fourth quarter of the Trojans' 35-24 victory.
</P>
<P>
   He started four games as a redshirt freshman before dislocating
his left shoulder. Following last season, he had surgery on both
shoulders and sat out USC's final three games this season because
of lingering soreness.
</P>
<P>
   Iacenda was one of the area's most prolific high school running
backs.
</P>
<P>
   He led Hart to the Division II title in 1995 and was a two-time
Division II Player of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Iacenda scored a Southern Section-record 99 touchdowns at Hart,
and had 604 points in his career, second-most in state history.
</P>
<P>
   He also rushed for more than 4,000 yards, and the Indians were
35-5 in his three years on the varsity. But he has gotten few
carries at USC, where the fullback is not featured in the offense.
</P>
<P>
   Iacenda said he has not decided where he will transfer.
</P>
<P>
   __ Young to interview: Defensive coordinator Bill Young said he
will interview with the University of Hawaii possibly as early as
today for the vacancy created by the firing of coach Fred vonAppen.
</P>
<P>
   The front runners for the job are Utah coach Ron McBride,
Arizona assistant coach Duane Akina and San Diego Chargers coach
June Jones. Young interviewed for the job three years ago, before
vonAppen was hired.
</P>
<P>
   ``They called and asked if I had an interest,'' Young said.
``I'm not sure where I rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawaii athletic director Hugh Yoshida called USC coach Paul
Hackett for permission to speak to Young. Yoshida had also made
inquiries last week about former USC coach John Robinson, before he
took the Nevada-Las Vegas job.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-98 0124EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981208.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7910 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMGEN-MEDICARE-LADN     12-08 0299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMGEN-MEDICARE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S MEDICARE BILL COULD BE BAD FOR AMGEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Looking to reduce Medicare costs, President
Clinton proposed to Congress on Monday a bill that would cut by
more than $2 billion government payments for several drugs,
including Amgen's Epogen.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is trying to close a loophole that
lets health care providers receive significantly more money from
the government for drugs given to Medicare patients than what they
pay manufacturers for the products. The differential amounts to as
much as one-third of some providers' revenues.
</P>
<P>
   For Amgen, the proposed cuts would lower by 10 percent the
amount the government reimburses kidney dialysis centers for the
anti-anemia drug Epogen. How much Amgen actually is paid for the
product by the centers will continue to be negotiated on an
individual basis.
</P>
<P>
   Epogen sales last year amounted to $1.16 billion, or about half
of Amgen's revenue, much of it paid for indirectly by Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, kidney dialysis centers say they have gone years
without an increase in Medicare reimbursement for overall dialysis
care, and argue that the Epogen payments help keep them afloat. A
government panel is now considering increasing dialysis
reimbursement rates and will make a recommendation next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-led Congress failed to pass a proposal similar to
Clinton's latest last year. Should it decline to pass the new
measure in the coming legislative session, Clinton is expected to
implement the cut through Medicare regulations, which do not
require congressional approval.
</P>
<P>
   Amgen shares rose $1.5625 Monday to close at $80.3125.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-98 0124EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981208.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
