<HEADER>
A7955 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-1STLD-WRITETH     12-08 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES(940)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDICIARY COMMITTEE CHALLENGES CLINTON TO CONTEST EVIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: SUBS to reorganize, UPDATE with fresh quotes throughout;
also tightens, deletes redundant material in 2nd take) 
(See also IMPEACH-CLINTON, IMPEACH-DELAY) 
 (ART ADV: Photo of Rep. Henry Hyde is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(htv) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The chairman of the House Judiciary Committee
asserted Monday that his panel had built a ``compelling case'' for
the impeachment of President Clinton &UR; , &LR;  and for one last time he
called on Clinton and his lawyers to contest the evidence against
the president. &UR;  &LR;  The chairman, Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., issued his
challenge on the eve of a critical two-day presentation of the
president's case before the committee.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, White House allies beseeched the president to
do something more dramatic than merely offer a legal defense.
</P>
<P>
   With sentiment in the Republican-controlled Congress hardening
against Clinton, and his fate dependent on perhaps 20 to 30
wavering moderate Republicans, a chorus of political figures called
for one more public apology by Clinton or a dramatic gesture to
reserve the momentum before the full House votes next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know from talking to a number of Republicans that they need
some comfort, some assurance that he understands what he's done,''
said Rep. Peter King, a Long Island Republican who has been trying
to build support for censure instead of impeachment. ``He's got to
make some additions. He's got to come forward.''
</P>
<P>
   King added: ``There's no doubt the momentum is against censure
and for impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats made the same appeal, with some telling the White
House that the president had to show that he was more concerned
with the possibility of impeachment than with protecting himself
from prosecution for perjury after he leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a good idea if the president again faced the
American people,'' said Rep. Martin Meehan, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The White House played down the chance of such an appearance,
saying Clinton had already shown he was contrite about his affair
with Monica Lewinsky and his deceptions about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is second to none in recognizing what was wrong
in his behavior and apologizing to those who he's affected and
hurt,'' said White House spokesman Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   As they moved into the final week of their inquiry, Republicans
on the House Judicioary Committee worked behind closed doors Monday
to refine three or four articles of impeachment against Clinton.
And the White House released the names of 14 witnesses who are to
help make Clinton's defense.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said they would extensively address both
the facts and the law in their appearance before the Judiciary
Committee on Tuesday and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But Hyde dismissed the idea of listening once again to
constitutional scholars and legal experts who would make the case
that the founders did not envision impeachment as a punishment for
personal misbehavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have heard from so many college professors that I think I'm
going to ask if we can get college credit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For almost two months,'' Hyde added, ``I have been pleading
with the White House and committee Democrats to present some
additional evidence that might demonstrate the president's
innocence.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde spoke at a news conference surrounded by four stacks of
legal boxes to remind viewers of the 60,000 pages of evidence sent
to the House by independent counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats shot back that the Republicans were turning American
jurisprudence upside down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not up to someone accused of wrongdoing to prove his
innocence,'' said Rep. Jerrold Nadler, a Manhattan Democrat. ``It's
up to the person who says he's guilty to prove his guilt.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say it is inevitable that the Judiciary Committee
will report out one to four articles of impeachment against the
president by the end of the week. The committee's Republicans were
working Monday on one or two counts of perjury, a count of
obstruction of justice and a count of abuse of power. They called
the drafts a work in progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very fluid,'' said Rep. Lindsey Graham, R-S.C. ``It
depends on where we come out when the evidence door is closed.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, Graham and Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla.,
suggested that Republicans were even considering citing Clinton's
legalistic answers to 81 questions from the House Judiciary
Committee as an instance of lying under oath.
</P>
<P>
   Canady said the answers contained ``willful misstatements of the
facts'' in the way the president characterized his conversations
with his personal secretary, Betty Currie, about gifts he had given
to Ms. Lewinsky and about conversations he had with his secretary
the day after he had denied that he and the intern had an affair
during his deposition in the Paula Jones sexual misconduct case.
``I think that he's lying in those answers,'' Canady said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said they were still debating whether there should
be one count of perjury or two. And they said they were most
divided over whether to charge Clinton with abuse of power.
``That's the one where there's some divergent views,'' said Rep.
Steve Chabot, R-Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Howard Gekas, R-Pa., said he had reservations about
charging abuse of power based on the president's invocations of
executive privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats asserted that the committee was marching ahead with
impeachment even though it had never called witnesses or done
anything to settle discrepancies between witnesses who testified
before Starr's grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats would like the House to censure the president instead
of impeach him. But Hyde said Monday that he had not decided
whether to allow a committee vote on censure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not ruled out but it's not a dead-bang certainty
either,'' Hyde said, adding that he did not think censure was ``an
appropriate sanction.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Before the House Judiciary Committee hears from Clinton's
defenders on Tuesday, it plans to vote to make public the videotape
of Clinton's deposition in the Jones case. Republicans say the vote
is intended to allow their chief investigative counsel, David
Schippers, to show parts of the tape in questioning the president's
representatives or in making his summation.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats were also expected to seek the release of information
still under seal that they consider exculpatory or embarrassing to
the president's accusers. Both Schippers and Abbe D. Lowell, the
Democrats' chief investigative counsel, are to sum up their cases
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   With the committee expected to finish its work by Saturday,
strategists for both parties began turning their attention to the
full House. Speaker Newt Gingrich is expected to gavel the House
into session mid-week and then turn the speaker's podium over to
Rep. Bob Livingston, R-La., the incoming speaker, or someone he
designates.
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats and the White House on Monday began focusing on
20 to 30 Republican moderates who they believe could be persuaded
to oppose impeachment either on the merits or because their
districts voted for Clinton in 1996. ``We've got 10 days here,''
one House Democratic official said. ``There's ample time to
convince them on the politics and the facts themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The list of moderates is heavily tilted to the Northeast. It
ranges from Republicans who have already come out against
impeachment, like Reps. Jack Quinn of New York and Christopher
Shays of Connecticut, to those who have kept their own counsel,
like Reps. Rick Lazio and Michael Forbes, both from Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats were also looking at Rep. Jay Dickey, R-Ark., on the
theory that he could be vulnerable at home if he voted against the
president.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to keep a censure measure from the House floor,
Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas, the majority whip, circulated a letter on
Monday co-signed with Shays arguing against censure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although we disagree on whether President Clinton's lying
constitutes an impeachable offense, we both think every member of
Congress should make that judgment,'' the letter said. ``We oppose
establishing a new precedent _ censure _ when there is an
established method in existence and under way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
