A7963 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LA-COUNTY-FILMING-LAD     12-08 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-COUNTY-FILMING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTY FILM PRODUCTION DOWNSHIFTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hollywood's once-sizzling local production
activity will continue to cool off during the next two years,
officials predicted Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Activity in the key production categories _ television, feature
films and commercials _ will probably be down 8 percent to 10
percent in Los Angeles County during the next two years compared
with its peak in 1997 but should pick up again in 2001, said Cody
Cluff, president of the Entertainment Industry Development Corp.,
speaking at the Valley Industry and Commerce Association's annual
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Production in county areas outside studio lots has already
slowed down by more than 5 percent this year after growing at a
supercharged 78 percent between 1994 and 1997, when total
production days hit 47,669. This year's decline came amid studios
sending crews to lower-cost locations outside California and
becoming more cautious at funding big-budget projects.
</P>
<P>
   Cluff cited continuing economic turmoil overseas. Exchange rates
that make it cheaper to send production to Canada, and that
country's cap on the number of United States workers allowed to
work there drives the price down further.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, protectionist policies in countries such as France
limit the number of screens on which American films are shown and
the amount of hours given over to U.S. television programs,
limiting demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say we're in for a year of slowdown, probably two, and
we should start to turn around again by 2001,'' Cluff said after
his address at the Universal Hilton.
</P>
<P>
   The county has already seen a sharp drop in production activity
in recent months. According to statistics released last month by
the EIDC, activity by film crews shooting on local streets fell by
25.7 percent in September and 18.1 percent in October compared with
the year-ago periods. The slump was due largely to plunges of 41
percent and 44 percent, respectively, in the number of days of
movie production.
</P>
<P>
   Cluff also said employment figures should see some modest gains
this year. The motion picture and television production sector, the
fifth-largest employer in the county, is expected to grow from
235,900 employees last year to 239,200 at the end of this year. An
additional 1,200 jobs will be added next year and 3,600 in 2000,
bringing the total to 244,000, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not looking at significant job increases over the next
two years _ they're relatively modest,'' Cluff said in an interview
after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The growth areas will be in animation and other
technology-related areas, ``which is good news, because those are
the higher-paying jobs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Kyser, chief economist with the Los Angeles County Economic
Development Corp., had predicted job growth of 7,000 to 8,000 in
the industry next year, but said Cluff's less rosy prediction was
reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have strong growth next year, it would be a surprise,
but you always hear rumors that foreign investors are coming in,''
Kyser said.
</P>
<P>
   Kyser said he believes the industry is going through a period of
closer scrutiny on the bottom line. ``Everyone is saying some
practices don't make sense, like opening a lot of high-cost films
against each other, so I think they're adopting a more rational
approach,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Economic surveys show direct expenditures generated by the
industry in Los Angeles County reached $27.5 billion in 1997,
compared with $25.5 billion in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   State Assemblywoman Sheila Kuehl, D-Encino, will hold a hearing
on the industry's economic issues Wednesday from 9:30 a.m. to 4
p.m. at the Hollywood Entertainment Museum, 7021 Hollywood Blvd.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
