A7995 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RADIATION-BANDS-SFCHR     12-08 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADIATION-BANDS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPLEX `SPACE WEATHER' SURROUNDS EARTH 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARL T. HALL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Scientists discovered in the late 1950s that
vast belts of radiation surround the Earth like giant doughnuts.
After looking a little closer, scientists said Monday that the
doughnuts appear to be throbbing.
</P>
<P>
   New evidence shows the belts seem to act like huge particle
accelerators _ grabbing subatomic bits of energized matter from the
sun as they swarm toward Earth, spinning them into orbit at close
to the speed of light.
</P>
<P>
   The findings usher in a new era of forecasting what has come to
be known as ``space weather.'' Success of the International Space
Station construction effort _ as well as the fate of more
down-to-earth communications networks _ depend on making these
forecasts as accurate as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists introduced the findings Monday during a meeting of
the American Geophysical Union, which continues through Thursday at
San Francisco's Moscone Center.
</P>
<P>
   The presentation focused on the two main bands of strong
radiation, resembling inner and outer doughnuts centered thousands
of miles above Earth's surface.
</P>
<P>
   These invisible energy fields make up the Earth's so-called
magnetosphere plied by orbiting spacecraft. The radiation bands
also are called Van Allen belts, for physicist James Van Allen, who
discovered them in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   Periodic surges of radiation can cause abrupt swelling of the
Van Allen belts, scientists said. The belts can shrink just as
suddenly as the radiation dissipates in the magnetic winds
crisscrossing the regions outside the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   A particularly intense episode in May spawned an entirely new,
though short-lived, radiation belt, according to Daniel Baker,
director of the Laboratory for Atmospheric and Space Physics at the
University of Colorado at Boulder.
</P>
<P>
   Using color-coded three-dimensional images and video, he and
other space experts demonstrated how the radiation belts seem to
puff outward from far above Earth's polar cap, then dance toward
the equator, all in a matter of hours.
</P>
<P>
   The radiation belts had been viewed for decades as a more or
less passive reservoir of the sun's radiation. New readings from
orbiting spacecraft create a much different picture, in which
dramatic shifts seem as commonplace as thunderstorms in the
Mississippi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much more dynamic than we thought,'' said Geoffrey
Reeves, space physicist at the Los Alamos National Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Experts also have had to rethink some of the fundamental tenets
about the nature of the magnetic storms and radiation currents that
gird the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Although no one is about to dethrone the sun as the ultimate
energy source on and around Earth, particle-bearing gusts of
``solar wind'' take on wholly different characteristics when they
near the planet.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, scientists said, most of the magnetospheric
high-energy particle activity turns out to be of Earth's own
making.
</P>
<P>
   Transitory gusts of radiation can have devastating effects on
space-linked communications. That was a contributing factor in May,
for example, when 45 million pager customers and several big
commercial data-relay systems lost service in the Galaxy IV
satellite failure.
</P>
<P>
   Blasts of killer electrons in the near-Earth environment also
could damage the delicate control systems aboard orbiting
spacecraft. When storms get too intense, particles tend to build up
inside the vessels before they can safely dissipate, threatening
electrical explosions.
</P>
<P>
   Disturbances in the space environment are expected to become
more frequent as radiation-emitting sunspots intensify, reaching
the 11-year cyclical peak known as the ``solar maximum'' in late
2000 or early 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists hope to design spacecraft with the new findings in
mind, and space ``weather maps'' are in the works to guide mission
controllers through the tempests. In many cases, damage can be
minimized by powering down spacecraft or using backup systems.
</P>
<P>
   It could even lead to decisions to scrap or speed up spacewalks
in order to protect the lives of astronauts working on the space
station. But the risks of rogue electrons in space are hardly the
only dangers that must be taken into account.
</P>
<P>
   Space physicist Terrance Onsager of the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration conjured up a scenario in which
astronauts are given a three-hour window to finish an assignment
before a storm hits.
</P>
<P>
   But if they hurry up to return to a shielded environment,
Onsager noted, they might increase the risk of ripping a glove.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
