<HEADER>
A7997 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GALILEO-JUPITER-SFCHR     12-08 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GALILEO-JUPITER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAFFLING SEISMIC FAULT SEEN IN ICY CRUST OF JOVIAN MOON 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID PERLMAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Scientists reading fresh messages from the
Galileo spacecraft flying past the moons of giant Jupiter are
puzzled as they discover phenomena so curious that they remain
tantalizingly inexplicable _ at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   Teams of researchers reading Galileo's instrument data reported
some of their puzzlement Monday at the annual fall meeting of the
American Geophysical Union in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Their latest findings include detailed and curious new evidence
of a monstrous, twisting seismic fault that cleaves the icy crust
of the Jovian moon Europa _ a fault stretching at least 500 miles
across Europa's surface, as far as the San Andreas runs from the
Mexican border to the Bay Area. And it may be more than twice as
long, but nobody knows _ at least not yet, according to Bruce R.
(Randy) Tufts of the University of Arizona, who is one of the
Galileo mission's imaging team members.
</P>
<P>
   What's inexplicable, however, is why the fault is there at all,
Tufts told reporters, for the crust of Europa is solid ice, as
Galileo's instruments have proved, while beneath it may lie either
a global ocean of warm water many miles deep, or thick layers of
slush, or both.
</P>
<P>
   Earth's crust, however, as Tufts noted, is solid rock, and the
side-slipping motion of the San Andreas is caused by the movement
of huge crustal slabs known as tectonic plates. When the Pacific
Plate grinds past the North American Plate in a sudden jerk of the
San Andreas, watch out! It's an earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the fault on Europa has in the past behaved much like the
San Andreas: The fault's two sides have slipped past each other for
more than 30 miles at some time in the past in a motion that
seismologists on Earth call right lateral strike-slip. Images taken
by the Galileo spacecraft show that it has kinks or jogs along its
length just as the San Andreas system has.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Europa's fault, named Astypalaea Linea after the sister of
Europa in Greek mythology, appears inactive now, for undisturbed
ridges of ice cross it here and there _ a sure sign that no
icequakes have sundered the crust in geologically recent times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's simply a beautiful structure,'' Tufts said in a burst of
enthusiasm, ``and I'd sure like to get to Europa to explore that
fault and trench it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tufts and Torrance Johnson of NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory,
the Galileo mission's project manager, have at least a tentative
explanation for the curious nature of the Astypalaea fault, and for
the myriad of other much shorter faults that create a strange kind
of latticework all over Europa's surface.
</P>
<P>
   They believe that giant Jupiter, around whose massive gaseous
body Europa flies in an elliptical orbit, must exert a powerful
gravitational tug on the icy satellite that varies in strength with
Europa's distance from the planet during its orbit. So Jupiter's
immense gravity must raise giant tides in the ocean beneath the
crust of Europa, tides as high as 150 feet churning every three
days or so beneath Europa's crust, the Galileo scientists believe.
</P>
<P>
   The strange features on Europa were first observed nearly 20
years ago when the two Voyager spacecraft explored Jupiter and its
moons during their ``grand tour'' of the outer solar system.
</P>
<P>
   Now the mysteries of the Jovian environment will be explored in
even greater detail, for scientists are already planning a mission
dedicated to exploring Europa's surface with a tiny spacecraft
weighing barely more than 40 pounds. It is due to be launched in
2003 and will examine the thickness of the moon's ice crust and
finally determine whether in fact an ocean of water _ possibly warm
enough to be hospitable for life _ lies beneath that crust.
</P>
<P>
   It's another piece of the solar system's endlessly curious
features that the robot spacecraft are tackling year after year. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
