<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 11:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8265 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN09-COX     12-08 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't act like a 2-year-old _ get some `good manners'
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ ``Good manners,'' I explained to my young son
Kristofor as I
</P>
<P>
   sat on the bottom step tying his dress-up shoes, ``is what
separates us from the
</P>
<P>
   beasts. Manners allow us all to inhabit the planet without
grabbing each other's food. So remember, no kicking, biting, or
poking with a sharp stick.'' He seemed to be catching on. He was
two.
</P>
<P>
   Then we went to Karen's birthday party. ``When you go in,'' I
instructed the
</P>
<P>
   exuberant little boy in the sailor suit, ``hand the present to
Karen and wish her a happy birthday.'' He gave me a cherubic grin
and rang the bell. Instantly, the door flew open and the birthday
girl grabbed the present from his hands and took off.
</P>
<P>
   Dumbfounded, Kristofor stared up at me quizzically and muttered,
``Her didn't
</P>
<P>
   even hug me.'' Get used to it, I thought to myself, but to the
disappointed little fellow standing empty-handed on the doorstep I
explained that she was probably so excited she'd had a momentary
lapse of what he called ``good nanners.'' He seemed content with
that and headed out in search of his buddies who just happened to
be out back damming the creek with rocks from Miss Peggy's (Karen's
mom) flower beds.
</P>
<P>
   Mothers were gathered on the back porch enjoying a warm Georgia
afternoon,
</P>
<P>
   rocking, sipping lemonade, and comparing adorable kid stories.
It was a real
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee Williams scene. I joined them.
</P>
<P>
   Within moments though, our bucolic reverie was shattered by a
shriek followed
</P>
<P>
   by some major caterwauling. We leaped from the porch to see who
was dying.
</P>
<P>
   We found Karen, party-dress deep in a mud puddle, screeching her
little pink
</P>
<P>
   lungs out. ``Trittipur'' (the closest she could come to
pronouncing Kristofor) it
</P>
<P>
   seems, had unceremoniously dumped her little ruffled backside in
the dirt and
</P>
<P>
   taken off with her tricycle. I caught up with him gleefully
pedaling down the
</P>
<P>
   winding drive. He seemed surprised at my annoyance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why'd you do that?'' I asked, a little out of breath and
seriously embarrassed. He told me bluntly that he had asked Karen
if he could ride the trike, she'd said absolutely not, and so he'd
pushed her off.
</P>
<P>
   I told him he'd been rude but he disagreed. ``My said pweeze,''
he explained
</P>
<P>
   indignantly, ``but her said no.'' I explained ``please'' was
indeed a magic word, but in this case it had not overridden Karen's
desire to maintain her seat on the tricycle.
</P>
<P>
   We sat on the steps and talked for a few minutes before I could
convince him
</P>
<P>
   that the gentlemanly thing to do would be to apologize to Karen.
Reluctantly,
</P>
<P>
   he agreed and went to tell her he was sorry. She bit him. He
slugged her. We went home.
</P>
<P>
   There's a reason for this story. I'm working my way up to a
parable on manners.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday evening the phone rang and being a relatively
curious person, I
</P>
<P>
   answered it. ``May I speak with Elizabeth Schuett?'' a chirpy
little voice asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is she,'' I responded already annoyed because I knew what
was coming. After all, it was dinnertime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi, Elizabeth, I'm Betty Boop of Joe Blow's Insurance in
nearby Doofustown. We hear you're having a birthday pretty soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Silence. I can't help thinking Starr's committee isn't the only
thing that leaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elizabeth, we're calling to wish you a great 65th. Aren't you
excited? Tell me Elizabeth, are you going to have a big
celebration?''
</P>
<P>
   I'm underwhelmed, bordering on fed up. Tersely, I explain that
none of this is really any of her business. Undaunted, she twitters
on. I'm thinking, this kid in addition to being rude, is demented.
But her next statement explains it all:
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you considered any health insurance to supplement your
Medicare?''
</P>
<P>
   ``How old are you, Miss Boop?'' I ask making little effort to
conceal my irritation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-three,'' she bubbles.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're 23 and I'm 65. We have never met and yet you have the
bad manners to
</P>
<P>
   address me familiarly by my first name?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just being friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not friends. You are soliciting. You are disturbing my
dinner and truth is, you really don't give a fat rat's backside
whether I have a happy birthday or not. Right?''
</P>
<P>
   Betty Boop splutters and hangs up - a momentary reprieve. But
there'll be more.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows money-grubbing is more important than manners.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Address mail to
320 West
</P>
<P>
   Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
