   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   SOUPKITCHEN-NUTRITION _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Fifteen years ago, the
symbol of food assistance was the 10-pound block of pale-yellow,
fat-filled, government-issued American cheese. The United States
Department of Agriculture bought surplus milk from dairy farmers,
turned it into cheese and butter, then distributed it to programs
that helped the poor. Today, the agency doesn't buy food until it
surveys food banks about what they want. Cheese and butter have
given way to salmon and green beans. (Keilman, Dayton Daily News)
MOVED.
</P>
