<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What is the death penalty doing to us?
 &HT;    By Ana Pecina Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ So does Martin E. Gurule's death on the run
and not at the hands of an official executioner mean we can't add
another notch to our collective
</P>
<P>
   Texas belt?
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Lone Star State set a record when it executed 37
people. So far In 1998, 17 convicted killers have died from legal
lethal injection. One condemned man received a short reprieve last
week, but we have five more set to go before the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
   Will Gurule's death become an asterisk in the state's needle
marathon? Does it count toward our mission of deterrence?
</P>
<P>
   Sounds callous, I know. But callous were the words of prison
officials who said in very frustrated tones last week that they
hoped the escapee was being eaten up by mosquitos or water
moccasins and then declared it didn't matter to them if he was
found dead or alive. Their frustration is understandable. The
escape made them look bad, and they feared for the lives of
innocents who might be put in danger by Gurule.
</P>
<P>
   What's frightening is that their harsh words are not so far from
our own lips. What's another dead guy at Huntsville?
</P>
<P>
   And still the killing continues, in the death chamber and on our
streets.
</P>
<P>
   East Texans recently learned of the violent death in Houston of
a beautiful
</P>
<P>
   young woman from Lone Star. A 25-year-old man has been charged
with capital
</P>
<P>
   murder in the kidnapping/slaying.
</P>
<P>
   After Gurule's bloated body was found in the river, his victims'
families expressed relief at his death but sadness for the
murderer's family.
</P>
<P>
   People keep dying. Their families mourn. We kill more. They kill
more.
</P>
<P>
   Our state's philosophy seems to be the more murderers it
executes, the better things will get. We may execute the wrong
person one out of seven times, but this will work, really. Trust
us.
</P>
<P>
   So how long before we get to quit locking our doors? Before we
stop having to frighten our children into being careful?
</P>
<P>
   How long before those of us who do not live behind a locked
subdivision gate can take a nighttime stroll without fear?
</P>
<P>
   How long before we are safe?
</P>
<P>
   How long before we become more like the people we are killing _
unfeeling,
</P>
<P>
   uncaring, vengeful, hard?
</P>
<P>
   The death penalty may be working in one way by permanently
removing killers
</P>
<P>
   from society, but what's it doing to the rest of us?
</P>
<P>
   Ana Pecina Walker is managing editor of the Longview
News-Journal, P.O. Box 1792, Longview TX 75606. E-mail:
awalker(AT)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
