</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Oy vey, Mr. Governor
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The headline reads, ``Bush to clarify remarks on
Jesus.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahem, is there a speechwriter in the house?
</P>
<P>
   Cold and clammy, George Bush is jolted upright at night by a
headline he just dreamt: ``Jesus to clarify remarks on Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush didn't dream up the controversy that accompanied him to
Israel for a trip with other Republican governors. He was having to
respond to an ill-chosen quip and some previous comments about
religion.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993 he told of a family discussion in which he asserted that
people who didn't accept Jesus Christ as their savior cannot go to
heaven. That understandably rankled many non-Christians.
</P>
<P>
   Then recently, when asked by a reporter in an elevator what he'd
say to Israeli Jews, Bush self-mockingly said he'd tell them they
were all 'going to hell.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bush since has been doing the damage-control thing.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently he's assuaged the concerns of Anti-Defamation League
officials, with public clarification to come. Oh, jolly.
</P>
<P>
   Too late to say, ``No comment.'' But with this blow-up in mind,
we should hope that we have in Bush a freshly baptized believer in
separating church and state.
</P>
<P>
   Comments from press secretary Karen Hughes put it correctly:
``Judgments about heaven and hell do not belong to the realm of
politics or of this world. They belong to a higher authority,'' she
said. And I trust that in ``higher authority'' she was not
referring to the Legislative Budget Board.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in saying that, Hughes may have inflamed core members
of the Texas Republican Party who believe, o ye brethren, that the
fundamental function of politics is indeed to establish old-time
religion.
</P>
<P>
   See what happens when you bring up religion in public, Governor?
</P>
<P>
   Nothing can inflame so many sensibilities as religion. That's
why government should stay out of it.
</P>
<P>
   A useful phrase for your trips, Gov. Bush: Freig mir nitscht.
</P>
<P>
   Loosely, that's Yiddish for ``no comment.''
</P>
<P>
   This incident should serve as a beacon to Bush as he encounters
shysters of piety who want government to get hip-deep in religion.
Even in a weak-governor state like Texas, Bush can find enough to
do without distractions like this.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile you have lame-duck Alabama Gov. Fob James, recently
defeated despite his transparent appeals to the masses as one who
would impose the majority's faith on others. The James
administration was before a federal circuit court last week
challenging an injunction against majority-sponsored prayer in
school.
</P>
<P>
   While ordering the DeKalb County schools in Alabama to stop
promoting religion, a federal judge had pointed out that students
have broad freedom to practice their faith without government
involve- ment.
</P>
<P>
   How many examples do we need to know that a hands-off approach
to religion is the only way faith can flourish in a democracy?
</P>
<P>
   Can't moral majoritarians like Fob James see what it's like in
church-states overseas, and why the writers of the Bill of Rights
steered clear of that?
</P>
<P>
   What the religious right wants is candidates who pass
theological litmus tests and carry out matters of religion as
policy.
</P>
<P>
   But George Bush should have born-again zeal on this matter.
Should he run for president and be asked to clarify his beliefs on
heaven and hell for the benefit of the Christian Coalition, he
should suggest that it polish up on its Yiddish.
</P>
<P>
   John Young writes for the Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
E-mail: jyoung(AT)mail.wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
