<HEADER>
A8269 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUPKITCHEN-NUTRITION     12-08 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUPKITCHEN-NUTRITION09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEALTH: From shelters to cafeterias, the main concern is
nutrition
 &HT;    By John Keilman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ As the people carry their trays from the serving
area at Dayton's St. Andrew's Episcopal Church, you can frequently
see flashes of green among the heaps of mashed potatoes and slabs
of bread.
</P>
<P>
   Bright boiled peas. Emerald lettuce leafs. Bits of celery
peeking from bowls of chili.
</P>
<P>
   The people who have come to this soup kitchen might be down on
their luck, but they can still have a healthy meal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our common assumption is that poor people don't know what to
eat because they're poor _ and they do,'' said House of Bread
director Jean Taylor, who oversees the kitchen. ``They know very
well that they should have a varied diet.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who feed the poor, from the federal government to local
food pantries, are increasingly aware of the role proper nutrition
should play in their programs. Some say it is paying off in more
healthful diets for low-income families.
</P>
<P>
   ``My general observation is that . . . the nutritional quality
of the foods that are currently coming through the system are some
of the best I've seen in a very long time,'' said Lisa
Hamler-Podolski, director of the advocacy group Ohio Food Policy
and Anti-Poverty Action Center.
</P>
<P>
   The change has started at the top. Fifteen years ago, the symbol
of food assistance was the 10-pound block of pale-yellow,
fat-filled, government-issued American cheese. The United States
Department of Agriculture bought surplus milk from dairy farmers,
turned it into cheese and butter, then distributed it to programs
that helped the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the agency doesn't buy food until it surveys food banks
about what they want. Cheese and butter have given way to salmon
and green beans.
</P>
<P>
   The USDA also prepares its food differently. Where it once
packed fruit in sugar solutions, it now uses natural juice. It
eliminated the use of tropical oils. It developed items such as
lower-fat beef patties and cut the sodium content in cereals.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government also tries to get food stamp recipients
to eat better. While there are no restrictions on what the vouchers
can buy, the feds spend millions to educate food stamp clients.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce McDowell of the Ohio State Agricultural Extension Service
directs the state's voluntary educational programs for those who
receive food stamps. She said 102,000 recipients _ about 1 in 7 _
attended one of the sessions held statewide last year. Instructors
talked to them about reading food labels, meal preparation and food
safety.
</P>
<P>
   Extension Agent Trisha Ansley, who runs the educational program
in Miami County, said she goes to senior centers to talk about
vitamins and minerals and the importance of calcium. She goes to
Head Start classes to speak of healthy snacks and ways to stretch a
family's food budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do a lot of things with . . . using fresh fruits and
vegetables that are in season and are cheaper,'' Ansley said.
</P>
<P>
   Government-backed public school lunches _ which low-income
students can eat free or at a reduced cost _ have also gone
wholesome.
</P>
<P>
   In the Dayton schools, where 75 percent of students get free or
reduced-price meals, cooks have slashed their dishes' fat and
sodium levels, according to Nutrition Services Director Nancy
Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't fried anything to speak of in years _ except french
fries,'' she said. ``And we use olive oil to fry them.''
</P>
<P>
   Food pantries, which rely heavily on donations from the public,
frequently can't be so selective. Even so, the provisions donated
by local residents and food manufacturers have become more
healthful in recent years, according to Burma Rai of Dayton's Red
Cross Emergency Food Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are getting a better nutritional quality of donations, just
because the industry and the public in general are more aware of
the (importance) of nutrition,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that, many food pantries still have a major problem:
They don't have the facilities to accept many fresh fruits,
vegetables, or meats, some of the cornerstones of good nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to move it fast,'' said Lisa Walls, director of
Franklin Area Community Services. ``We don't have much storage
space, and those things are so perishable.''
</P>
<P>
   They are also expensive, which discourages many poor people from
buying them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The foods that are cheap are not the most nutritious foods,''
said Kim Hickock, an instructor who covers nutrition in her courses
at Wright State University's College of Nursing and Health. `` . .
. Canned foods are never going to be as nutritious as fresh and
frozen.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is too worried about that at the House of Bread. It has
cultivated many food sources during its existence, and so on this
day some volunteers are picking the meat from turkey legs donated
by the MCL Cafeteria, while others are preparing 50 pounds of
sliced lamb delivered by a Greek Orthodox church.
</P>
<P>
   Chili and turkey soup are the main dishes for lunch, but they
are accompanied by plenty of other offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, the House of Bread's director and a registered
dietician, said such variety is good for more than a person's diet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to give people choices here,'' she said. ``That gives
them some dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   John Keilman writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
