<DOCNO> NYT19981208.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 11:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8272 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GIFT-BOOKS09-COX     12-08 2079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIFT-BOOKS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Recommended photo and reference books
 &HT;    By Anne Morris and other Cox News staff
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Every year we look at the new crop of holiday
gift books and discover all over again how wonderful so many are.
This year our enthusiastic volunteers share their favorites among
the photo books, anthologies and reference books.
</P>
<P>
   Books _ carefully chosen _ seldom disappoint. An added pleasure
is that you, the giver, can read before you wrap. Here are some
recommended by various members of the Cox Newspaper family:
</P>
<P>
   `Celebrity Caricature in America'
</P>
<P>
   By Wendy Wick Reaves
</P>
<P>
   Yale University Press, $45
</P>
<P>
   Aficionados of caricature can savor a handsome sampling from
America's golden age of that pointed art in ``Celebrity Caricature
in America,'' a hardback catalog of a wide-ranging 1998 exhibit
from the National Portrait Gallery. More than 300 illustrations and
a lively text by curator Wendy Reaves trace the art from the end of
the 19th century to the middle of the 20th, including masters such
as Al Frueh, Ralph Barton, Al Hirschfeld and, perhaps the greatest
of all, Miguel Covarrubias. It's a well-crafted collection that
captures the brilliance of the art as well as the spirit of the
times.
</P>
<P>
   `Icons of Architecture, The 20th Century'
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Sabine Thiel-Siling
</P>
<P>
   Prestel, $29.95
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be an architectural expert to enjoy this
coffee table book, which takes a look at the most significant
designs of this century. Through drawings, stunning photography and
essays, readers get insight into the stories behind the buildings,
from the original ideas to the technological innovation that
created them. A few notables include the World Trade Center in New
York City, Sears Tower in Chicago, village of Seaside in Florida,
Peace Center in Hiroshima, and Guggenheim Museum in Spain. The
essays are not always flattering _ sometimes the architecture is
highly criticized _ but the buildings chosen are spectacular in
their own way.
</P>
<P>
   `American Decorative Arts and Paintings in the Bayou Bend
Collection'
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Fine Arts, Houston
</P>
<P>
   Edited by David B. Warren, Michael K. Brown, Elizabeth Ann
Coleman, Emily Ballew Neff
</P>
<P>
   Princeton University Press, $90
</P>
<P>
   If you've ever toured Bayou Bend, the home of the late Miss Ima
Hogg in Houston, you will appreciate this book. But you may not
appreciate it any more than those who have never been inside but
long to know more about American furniture and art, and the
discerning taste of this unique individual. Miss Hogg, the daughter
of a Texas governor, bought her first piece of colonial American
furniture in 1920 and collected Americana for more than 50 years.
Read this richly illustrated catalog of her collection, and
discover paintings by John Singleton Copley and Gilbert Stuart,
metalwork by Paul Revere, and lovely quilts by unknown artists.
More than 1,100 items in all; a treasure.
</P>
<P>
   `DK Illustrated Oxford Dictionary'
</P>
<P>
   Oxford University Press $45 (after Jan. 1, $50)
</P>
<P>
   I am partial to any dictionary that does not presume I know it
all. (If I did, would I be looking up the spelling of ``potassium''
or the definition of ``knight-errant''?)
</P>
<P>
   In a world chock full of spell-check programs that do not
distinguish between homonyms, a dictionary with pictures is just
what the English teacher ordered. The 4,500 color images are very
helpful (e.g. _ a silicon crystal, Japanese quail, a lacrosse
field). There are even photos of binding knots like the timber
hitch and gastropods such as the great pond snail. This is a keeper
volume for anyone, any age.
</P>
<P>
   `Perennial Gardens for Texas'
</P>
<P>
   By Julie Ryan University of Texas Press, $27.95 (paperback)
</P>
<P>
   For gardeners who love the annual reappearance of shoots and
buds, there's nothing quite like the perennial garden. But Texas,
with its numerous climatic zones, isn't the easiest place to design
and plant a garden that will flourish year in and year out.
</P>
<P>
   That's where Julie Ryan steps in. With regional analyses,
detailed charts, beautiful photos and a wealth of description, the
Dallas writer and photographer provides high-quality guidance for
novices and green thumbs alike. It's a book that any serious
gardener would welcome warmly.
</P>
<P>
   `Cultural Atlas of Africa'
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Jocelyn Murray
</P>
<P>
   Checkmark Books, $50
</P>
<P>
   This 240-page revised edition provides the most up-to-date
geographical information on the vast continent that has undergone
several changes since 1981. The book's 96 maps are the heart of
this atlas, but there is considerable text on the 55 nations'
diverse cultures and their turbulent history through imperialism,
colonialism, independence and political strife. The book's essays
were written by a team of international experts.
</P>
<P>
   `America's Lost Treasure'
</P>
<P>
   By Tommy Thompson
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic Monthly Press, $39.95
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the California Gold Rush madness, a mighty ship
loaded with fortune sank off the Carolinas in a nasty hurricane.
The 1857 tragedy, which claimed 425 lives, was America's worst
peacetime sea disaster. It also swallowed the contents of a gold
mine, impossible to recover.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1985, engineer extraordinaire Tommy Thompson assembled a
crew of scientists, engineers, explorers and historians determined
to reclaim the national treasure. Thirteen years later, Thompson
has captured the eerie beauty of a golden harvest in 8,000 feet of
water with the newest photographic technology. Loaded with more
than 250 photos and illustrations, Thompson's accounts of the
successful mission should appeal to a diverse audience, whether
they read the best-selling ``Ship of Gold'' or not.
</P>
<P>
   `The Complete Bible Handbook'
</P>
<P>
   By John Bowker
</P>
<P>
   DK Publishing, $39.95
</P>
<P>
   No other text has had so great an influence in the world as the
Bible, says John Bowker, professor of divinity at Gresham College
in London. In addition to being a source of religious history, the
Bible has been an inspiration for literature, music and art. Yet,
for all its popularity, it is not easy to understand. Hence the
need for for commentaries like Bowker's handbook, an impressive
500-page book packed with 500 color illustrations and glossaries of
people and places.
</P>
<P>
   Divided into Old and New Testaments and references, with an
extensive bibliography, the nondenominational book is succinct,
easy to use and attractively designed. In addition to commentaries
of familiar biblical passages, there are specific discussions on
birds and plants in the Bible, women in ancient Israel, burial
practices, trade and travel in New Testament times, and maps of
biblical sites as they are today.
</P>
<P>
   `Bruce Springsteen: Songs'
</P>
<P>
   By Bruce Springsteen
</P>
<P>
   Avon Books, $50
</P>
<P>
   Fans will be delighted with ``Songs,'' which holds the complete
collection of Springsteen's recorded album lyrics over 25 years. At
the beginning of each section, Springsteen writes about the
thoughts and experiences that led him to create his works of art.
He discusses searching for tone, the atmosphere in the studio and
being inspired by authors (Flannery O'Connor) and film (Terrence
Malick's ``Badlands''). Plenty of personal photographs dot the
book, as well as reproductions of handwritten sheets where he
drafted songs or titles.
</P>
<P>
   `Ancient Mexico: The History and Culture of the Maya, Aztecs and
other Pre-Columbian Peoples'
</P>
<P>
   By Maria Longhena
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, Tabori &AMP; Chang, $60
</P>
<P>
   In this book, the author presents the glory and collapse of
several civilizations that flourished in Mesoamerica between the
middle of the second millennium B.C. to the 16th century. It
includes not only the Olmecs, Mayas and Aztecs, but also several
other cultures that developed highly sophisticated art forms,
writing systems and complex mathematics.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the illustrations that are the forte of this coffee
table book. With beautiful images of archaeological sites and
findings, the pleasure of flipping through the pages is
indescribable. The drawings that reconstruct cities and temples
provide an insight into these people who left us with an incredible
wealth of artifacts that assure us of their significance in
history.
</P>
<P>
   `Star Wars: The Visual Dictionary _ The Ultimate Guide to Star
Wars Characters and Creatures'
</P>
<P>
   By David West Reynolds
</P>
<P>
   DK Publishing Inc., $19.95
</P>
<P>
   `Star Wars: Incredible Cross-Sections _ The Ultimate Guide to
Star Wars Vehicles and Spacecraft'
</P>
<P>
   By David West Reynolds
</P>
<P>
   DK Publishing Inc., $19.95
</P>
<P>
   Star Wars fans can't wait until May, when ``Episode I: The
Phantom Menace,'' George Lucas' newest film in the series, opens.
Until then, they have to satisfy themselves with the trailer for
the film _ or with these two books. Looking like children's books
but probably aimed at adults, the shiny, glossy, slim volumes are
packed with photographs and diagrams fans will adore.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that band playing in the cantina in ``Star Wars?'' You
can find out the name of the band _ Figrin D'An and the Modal Nodes
_ as well as the names of all their instruments (ploong sounder,
peel rod, fanfar, kloo horn). And anybody who used to play with
X-wing fighters as a kid will like the cross-section of the plane,
containing everything from the proton warhead to the laser cannon.
</P>
<P>
   `Values of the Game'
</P>
<P>
   By Bill Bradley Artisan, $30
</P>
<P>
   Forget the NBA lockout. Forget the selfishness and greed that
has crippled the best players of the sport. In ``Values of the
Game,'' ex-Knicks star Bill Bradley explains why basketball still
matters. In 10 essays complemented with photographs of past and
present NBA legends, Bradley reflects on such values as teamwork,
discipline, passion, courage and imagination. His musings mix the
insight of a two-time NBA champion with the eloquence befitting a
Rhodes scholar and former U.S. senator.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a world full of unrealized dreams and baffling
entanglements, basketball seems pure,'' Bradley writes in his
introduction. ``We know, of course, that it isn't. It has its own
share of greed, violence and obsession with the culture of
entertainment. Yet even in the midst of these distractions, there
is still the game.'' Amen.
</P>
<P>
   `Lewis &AMP; Clark, Voyage of Discovery'
</P>
<P>
   By Stephen E. Ambrose
</P>
<P>
   Photographs by Sam Abell
</P>
<P>
   National Geographic Society, $35
</P>
<P>
   This book is outstanding both in text and illustrations.
Ambrose, author of ``Undaunted Courage,'' provides a shorter, but
informative, text about the Lewis and Clark expedition from St.
Louis up the Missouri River to the mouth of the Columbia River, and
return. There are reproductions of Karl Bodimer paintings of the
Indians, copies of maps by William Clark and others, and perfectly
composed and lighted photographs of scenes along the explorers'
route in 1803-1806. A treat for the mind and the eye.
</P>
<P>
   `Paintings that Changed the World: From Lascaux to Picasso'
</P>
<P>
   By Kraus Reichold and Bernard Graf
</P>
<P>
   Prestel, $29.95
</P>
<P>
   The ability to translate a vast array of feelings and emotions,
state of mind and sensibilities through the arrangement of colors,
brush strokes and shapes is the gift of the artist. Since time
immemorial people have painted on cave walls, tree bark, house
walls, paper, canvases.
</P>
<P>
   In this book, Kraus Reichold and Bernard Graf review the history
of painting, and to some extent the history of ideas, through
representative art works. The authors provide an opportunity to art
lovers and history aficionados alike to appreciate the importance
of the artwork and its creator. Spanning the history of art from
cave paintings to Andy Warhol, this coffee table book is a
beautiful source of entertainment and information.
</P>
<P>
   `The World of William Steig'
</P>
<P>
   By Lee Lorenz
</P>
<P>
   Introduction by John Updike Artisan, $50
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere between cartoon and fine art lies the weird and quirky
world of William Steig. You can witness his evolution as an artist
in this volume, which reproduces more than 400 illustrations in
black-and-white and color from Steig's 70-year career. (He's
currently 90.)
</P>
<P>
   I loved his New Yorker covers and cartoons, sent Christmas cards
made from his designs, and read to my children ``Sylvester and the
Magic Pebble,'' for which he won the Caldecott Award. I find the
pictures in this book endlessly entertaining, the text interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
