<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 11:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8275 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-GAMES09-COX     12-08 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-GAMES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Santa's Nintendo 64 and PlayStation picks
 &HT;    By Gregory Kallenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Things would be different if I were Santa.
First, I'd introduce a more fit, sleeker Santa. One who didn't
smile as much. I would take advantage of modern fabrics and be more
of a Gore-Tex Tommy Hilfiger meets Calvin Klein kind of jolly old
elf. Reindeers would be replaced by a natural gas-powered,
atmosphere-friendly magic sleigh. Lastly, I wouldn't ever deliver
another PC game again.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. This Santa would go totally console. If the kids
wanted video games for Christmas, hello Nintendo 64 and
PlayStation, goodbye PC and Mac.
</P>
<P>
   The advantages are clear. With a new PC costing at least $2,000
(and most new PCs souped up solely so we can play games on them),
the $130 price point for both consoles is very attractive. Even if
you have a computer, a microchip or RAM update, which is required
if you want to play the newest and coolest games, costs about $500.
</P>
<P>
   Also, with Nintendo 64 and PlayStation there is no crashing of
the system, no updates to make and no $100 joysticks to buy. The
consoles have even taken away the headache of having to check
gaming sites daily for patches so that your game works properly.
With Nintendo and PlayStation, all you do is drop the game in,
attach to your television and play. Easy.
</P>
<P>
   So with that in mind, this Santa has made his list, checked it
twice, picked all the games that I think are nice. Console Santa is
coming to town!
</P>
<P>
   Best all-around games
</P>
<P>
   These are for the best of the best girls and boys. But note: Not
all of these games are for kids. Console Santa says check out the
ratings on the back before buying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Metal Gear Solid'' _ If I were really Santa, Christmas might
not happen because of this game. I have spent an embarrassing
amount of time on this title. Konami's two-disc game has a deep,
addictive story line. You are Solid Snake enlisted by a top secret
government agency to stop the launch of a nuclear missile. While
this is a shooter game, it is also about stealth. PlayStation,
$49.99.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Legend of Zelda: Ocarina of Time'' _ One of the most
anticipated titles for the Nintendo 64 since, well, the last
``Zelda.'' I actually saw a grown man throw a tantrum in a
videogame store because they had sold out. You are Link and must
save the peaceful land of Hyrule from the King of Thieves. This is
very immersive, time consuming and makes a great gift if you never
want to see your kid again. Nintendo 64, $59.99.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oddworld: Abe's Exodus'' _The sequel to the freaky ``Oddworld:
Abe's Oddyssey.'' This latest version boasts a two-disc adventure
in which you, as the ``so ugly he's cute'' Abe, must stop the
Glukons from using your people's tears for beer. It's an odd world
indeed. PlayStation, $49.99.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parasite Eve'' or ``Xenogears'' _ You can't go wrong with
either of these games from the makers of ``Final Fantasy.'' Both
are incredibly cinematic role-playing games. While the fighting
takes place in a semi-boring turn-based environment, both games are
``must haves'' for any good gamer boy or girl. PlayStation, $49.99
(for each). Best shooter games There's been a lot of talk about
violence being inspired by videogames. One look at a couple of
these games and that revelation is not surprising. But hey, what
can Console Santa say? They're fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turok II: Seeds of Vengeance'' _ This is one of the most
advanced, goriest shooters for the Nintendo 64. You are Turok and
with an arsenal including a grenade launcher, shotgun and chainsaw,
you wreak havoc on dinosaurs and people alike. Nintendo 64, $64.99.
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Wars: Rogue Squadron'' _Ever thought of yourself as a
Jedi warrior? Well, now you can prove yourself to the Alliance.
``Rogue Squadron'' puts you to the test in this first-person
shooter. In this game you'll fly in your X-Wing and battle the
nastiest of the At-At Walkers. Nintendo 64, $54.99.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tenchu: Stealth Assassin'' _Not a shooter in the truest sense
of the word but stands up to all the others in this category. In
``Tenchu,'' you are a ninja using every traditional weapon possible
to attain your honor. Throwing stars, crossbows and poison rice
balls are just a few of the tools you'll use as you take on the
title of a stealth assassin. PlayStation, $49.99.
</P>
<P>
   ``Colony Wars: Vengeance'' _ The new incarnation of Psygnosis'
hit space shooter adds a complex story line and more detailed
graphics. In the game, you must defend your home planet from a band
of savvy, bloodthirsty marauders. The game remembers your actions
and, as a result of them, plays one of six endings. PlayStation,
$44.99. Best sports games
</P>
<P>
   A great gaming alternative for kids are the sports games. The
only violence you'll find in these titles is the occasional
``roughing the passer'' call.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cool Boarders 3'' _ For all the ``sweet shredders'' out there.
``Cool Boarders'' includes competition and trick modes along with a
wide selection of boards and gear. This game is definitely the best
snowboarding simulator available and should appeal to any and all
fans of skiing down a mountain on one wide board. PlayStation,
$44.99.
</P>
<P>
   ``NFL Quarterback Club '99'' _ This definitely has the best
graphics of any of the football games. With its sharp players, you
get to see every bone-jarring, earthshaking hit. Season modes and
head-to-head are both available. Nintendo 64, $64.99.
</P>
<P>
   ``NBA Live '99'' _ Electronic Arts once again proves it still
makes the best sports games out there with its rim-ringing ``NBA
Live.'' One highlight of this game is the facial expressions the
computer-animated players have when they foul or get fouled. You
can watch Dennis Rodman blow his stack as he commits the fifth
foul. Cool. PlayStation, $44.99, Nintendo 64, $59.99. Best kids
games
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for games that are fun for everyone, this is
Console Santa's best for the little ones and the big ones alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glover'' _ What do you get when you cross a wizard's magic
with the Hamburger Helper glove? You get cute little Glover,
everyone's favorite hand covering. Of course, with the good comes
the bad. As Glover, you must battle your evil twin brother (an evil
glove) as you try to bring peace to your kingdom. Nintendo 64,
$59.99.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Bug's Life'' _ Based on the hit movie. You are the
haphazard, quick-witted Flik, the ant. In the game you are trying
to save your anthill from spiders, grasshoppers and other crawly
critters. The game contains some of the best graphics anywhere and
includes parts of the movie. PlayStation, $44.99.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crash Bandicoot: Warped'' _ Crash is back with another
mind-twisting adventure. In this latest installment, you are able
to fly planes, get extreme on Jet Skis and ride on the back of
tigers. Join him as you travel through time and help him solve the
nail-biting problem of how to stop Dr. Cortex once and for all.
PlayStation, $44.99.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Kallenberg writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
