<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, Dec. 8, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Wednesday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JUPITER-OCEANS (San Francisco) _ Here's a possible 21st-century
job title: ``astro-oceanographer.'' In close-up photos, the many
moons of Jupiter appear eerie and alien. But three moons probably
have something in common with Earth: ice-covered oceans, according
to scientists. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   BEQUEST-POOR (San Francisco) _ Some of San Francisco's poor
residents would get free medical and dental care as a result of a
fortune left them by Zygmunt Arendt under a city proposal to
distribute the bequest. Arendt, a recluse who left at least $4.5
million in stocks and real estate in a handwritten will, died last
Jan. 24. By GREGORY LEWIS.
</P>
<P>
   DOMESTIC-PARTNERS (San Francisco) _ A bill that would require
health insurers and HMOs to provide domestic partners coverage to
businesses that want it _ once passed by the state Legislature, but
vetoed by then-Gov. Pete Wilson _ is back in the mill. By MICHAEL
DOUGAN.
</P>
<P>
   OLD-FORESTS (San Francisco) _ More than two dozen U.S.
corporations, half of them Fortune 500 companies, have promised to
stop using or selling paper and other wood products made from the
world's disappearing old-growth trees. By JANE KAY.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ This is the season to teach your kids
about money, say financial experts. They are not suggesting a
miserly Christmas, just a time when you teach your children to
spend within their means by establishing a holiday budget to help
them decide what they afford for themselves and others. By PAMELA
YIP.
</P>
<P>
   E-MAIL-MANIA (San Francisco) _ E-mail is increasingly becoming
the preferred mode of correspondence. But for businesses, e-mail
has become too much of a good thing. As a result, some companies
are using software designed to sort, direct and answer e-mail
queries automatically. Others are contracting with companies in the
growing e-mail call center industry to solve the problem. By WENDY
TANAKA.
</P>
<P>
   BOFA (San Francisco) _ San Francisco Treasurer Susan Leal says
Bank of America is destined to lose some of the business it has
historically done for City Hall as a result of its merger with
North Carolina-based NationsBank. Currently, Bank of America
handles some 90 percent of the city's banking business, moving
millions of dollars in payroll and payments. By GEORGE RAINE.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NERVE-DISEASE (Albany, N.Y.) _ About 2 million people in the
United States suffer from peripheral neuropathy, a little-known
disease of the peripheral nerves. They are the nerves that connect
the central nervous system, including the brain and spinal cord, to
the muscles, skin and internal organs. The ailment can cause a
condition similar to carpal tunnel syndrome. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-ETIQUETTE (Undated) _ For the holidays you might prefer
a free turkey or a bonus. Instead, your boss is throwing an office
party. What to do? For those who value their job, attendance is
mandatory, says Barbara Pachter of Cherry Hill, N.J., co-author of
``The Prentiss Hall Complete Business Etiquette Handbook.'' By KATE
GURNETT.
</P>
<P>
   BEAUTY-PIGGY (San Francisco) _ Everybody's gotta get into the
act! Even Miss Piggy. Yup. She's got her own perfume, joining the
ranks of Cher, Linda Evans (remember Cristal?), Joan Collins and
Elizabeth Taylor. By CYNTHIA ROBBINS.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-GIFTS (Undated) _ If you need a stocking stuffer for the
reader on your list, pick up a copy of Alec Guinness' delightful
``My Name Escapes Me _ The Diary of a Retiring Actor.'' By BOBBIE
HESS.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MARILYN-MANSON (San Francisco) _ Perhaps hoping to derail the
dangerous new trend of violence by musicians against journalists,
the publisher of Spin magazine is pursuing both criminal and civil
actions against shock-rocker Marilyn Manson for an alleged attack
on Spin executive editor Craig Marks Nov. 23. By JANE GANAHL.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OLIVE-OIL (San Francisco) _ They stand in a huddle, sniffing
tiny cups. They take sips, rolling the liquid over their tongues
and sucking in a bit of air to develop the flavors. ``Fruity, with
a peppery finish,'' says one. ``Buttery, pleasantly bitter,'' says
another. Good lord. Not another wine tasting. That is SO '80s. No,
it's an olive oil tasting, and it's all the rage. By DEBBY MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-REPLAYS (San Francisco) _ For the NFL playoffs, the league
is thinking about allowing each team to challenge one play per
half. But the limit would be liberal, allowing a club to use an
extra challenge on any last-minute, deciding play. This sort of
flexibility is fairly out of character for the NFL. So is the
spontaneity behind the replay suggestion. By GWEN KNAPP.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The year is coming to a close,
and it's time to revise the Dictionary of Distraction. In the last
year we've been driven nuts by euphemisms and cliches. For one
thing, we have new euphemisms for sex that have made the national
agony more agonizing. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Sometimes, when I really want to
scare myself, I imagine turning on the radio after an earthquake
and finding silence where KCBS should be. Whatever would I do?
Probably go insane, that's what. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
