<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 11:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8320 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IVOR-PETER-FONDA-ART-     12-08 1282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-PETER-FONDA-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETER FONDA'S UNEASY RIDE TO THE TOP 
</HEADLINE>
  World rights except Great Britain and Australia 
 Color slides and black and white photos of Peter Fonda and
Katherine Heigl in ``The Tempest.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    At 59 Peter Fonda has finally emerged on the Hollywood scene as
the most famous of the famous Fondas. It's taken him a long time.
 &HT;    He struggled for decades to emulate his dad Henry, Hollywood's
rock-solid attraction, who died in l982.
 &HT;    Then it was Jane's turn to become the hot Fonda: Fonda the sex
symbol, and the Oscar winner. Today Jane has taken herself out of
movies _ concentrating on her latest role as devoted wife to
entertainment mogul Ted Turner.
 &HT;    Then Bridget, Peter's daughter, had her flurry with fame and is
still going strong with her latest film ``A Simple Plan.''
 &HT;    But today it's finally Peter's turn. At last Hollywood regards
him as a star in his own right.
 &HT;    He started of course with a humdinger: He was ``Easy Rider'''s
wild Captain America in the '60s, riding a motor bike in black
leather and shades, popping LSD with cohorts Dennis Hopper and a
callow Jack Nicholson.
 &HT;    His role as the maverick biker in the l969 film mimicked his
real attitude to America in that era of Vietnam. Moviegoers around
the world loved it; Hollywood gave him the cold shoulder.
 &HT;    He continued to work in low-budget movies like ``Outlaw Blues''
(1977) and the cult film ``Love and a .45'' (1994). None of them
put him into Hollywood's actor's A-league.
 &HT;    ``I became an outsider. I moved to a ranch in Montana and did
the few films that were offered to me. I never thought I'd have a
chance to come back to the fold.''
 &HT;    Now he's an elder statesman, almost as respectable as his dad.
Last year he wrote a book about Henry Fonda called ``Don't Tell
Dad.'' Earlier this year also, he won praise and an Oscar
nomination for his role in ``Ulee's Gold.'' Jack Nicholson went
home with the best actor statuette but suddenly Hollywood was
paying attention to the former black sheep of the Fonda family.
 &HT;    Back in the early days when I interviewed him, he was troubled
young actor, caught up in the drug scene with a career as erratic
as his own behavior. But times have changed _ and so has Peter.
 &HT;    Now he's about to show up in another eye-catching serious role,
in special effects extravaganza, ``The Tempest,'' (airing on NBC
Dec. 13) an inventive retelling of Shakespeare's magical tale of
love, betrayal and freedom.
 &HT;    This time they've set the story on a mysterious isle in a
Mississippi bayou during the Civil War. Fonda plays Gideon Prosper,
who has abdicated his position as overseer of the family
plantation, choosing instead to devote his time to magic and
sorcery. The movie co-stars John Glover as Gideon's scoundrel
younger brother and Katherine Heigl Prosper's devoted daughter.
 &HT;    At 59, in blue jeans and cowboy boots with as much silver as
brown in his hair, his face handsome but leathery from long days in
the Montana Big Sky country, he sits in a suite at a ritzy hotel in
Pasadena, Calif., happily talking about his latest role and his
path in life.
 &HT;    ``I know Shakespeare's 'Tempest' and this is fairly on target
but set in a different time. It deals with deceit, brother against
brother. The special effects are really cool.''
 &HT;    It sometimes seems that Peter's acting career might have been
programmed into his DNA?. ``This is nothing genetic,'' he insists.
``The fact that my father and my sister, myself and my daughter are
all actors has nothing to do with genes. Had it something to do
with genes, I would have been manipulating them a long time ago.
But as I grew older people were saying, 'You look like your dad.'
In fact my bone structure is the same as his, but I really look
more like my mother around my eyes.''
 &HT;    Many in Hollywood said his part in ``Ulee's Gold'' _ playing a
grizzled, ex-Vietnam veteran turned beekeeper coping with his
grandkids _ was the role that has reestablished him as a leading
Hollywood star. And most also agree it was a typical Henry Fonda
role.
 &HT;    For a long time Peter might have resented that kind of talk. Not
anymore. ``I don't think of getting out from underneath the shadow
or the identity of being Henry Fonda's son. It hasn't been
something bad for me,'' he now observes.
 &HT;    ``It's an honor to be compared to his style of acting. And it's
interesting that the last thing he was seen doing was basically `On
Golden Pond' _ with a downturned mouth, grizzled and wearing wire
rimmed glasses, just like my character in `Ulee's Gold.'''
 &HT;    Growing up as a Fonda was never an easy ride for Peter. In many
ways his life was a constant struggle to win his father's approval.
The only problem was it wasn't winnable and even if it had been his
father couldn't have told him so. ``My father was a very shy man.
He didn't know how to communicate with anyone _ but particularly
with his children.''
 &HT;    Yet he was all they had. Peter and Jane were raised by their
father after their mother, socialite Frances Seymour Brokaw Fonda
committed suicide in l950 in a rest home where she was recovering
from a nervous breakdown.
 &HT;    ``My father never told Jane and I that mother had taken her own
life. We had to learn that from magazine and newspaper stories. I
know now he didn't do it to be cruel. He just didn't know how to
find the words to tell us.''
 &HT;    And just hours after his wife died Henry stepped on stage to do
a Broadway performance. That so upset Peter, who was 10 at the
time, that he shot himself through the kidney and liver with a
.22-caliber pistol.
 &HT;    Their father eventually remarried three times and with each
marriage he became further estranged from his two oldest children.
 &HT;    Peter remembers his dad as a tightlipped man who could never
express his emotions and bottled them up in a mask of disapproval.
``His silence was always a factor in our relationship. At the
dinner table not a word would be spoken.''
 &HT;    Peter and Jane, he says, thought their father was, ``this madman
who wouldn't smile or anything.''
 &HT;    In l979 Fonda was preparing to direct a low-budget film called
``Wanda Nevada.'' There was a small role in it perfectly suited to
his dad.
 &HT;    ``I literally had to cajole him into taking the role and he was
miserable the whole time. But then he sent me another of his famous
letters to tell me it had been one of the best experiences of his
41 years in the business.''
 &HT;    Peter says he worked hard to mend fences with his dad. And his
book about the man who was one of Hollywood's legends was softer
than most thought: ``I didn't have to tear his memory to shreds
because we had made our peace before he died.''
 &HT;    In ``Ulee's Gold'' he found a role that told the world that
Peter Fonda has finally grown up.
 &HT;    Now Peter has only one regret: That his dad isn't alive to see
his return to the mainstream: ``I think it would have amused him
greatly, that I have _ even in some small way _ become him. The
wonderful thing about having had Henry Fonda for a father is that
he is always within reach. I have just to turn on the TV _ and he's
there. It's a great legacy he's left me and the world.''
 &HT;     c.1998 Ivor Davis  (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based
<TEXT>
reporter.) &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   ------
 &UR; (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, contact New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS at 1-800-972-3550 or
212-499-3333, or by fax at 212-499-3382.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly column with color art.) &QL; 
 &UR; -------------------------------------------------
</P>
