<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8438 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-08 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL E-MAIL, IMAGINARY FRIENDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember when nothing came between Brooke Shields and her
Calvins?
</P>
<P>
   What if you could have e-mailed Shields back then? Would you
have asked her any questions? About modeling maybe? Or her family
life? Calvin Klein is betting on it.
</P>
<P>
   In an innovative new ad campaign for his cK one fragrance, the
fashion designer has set up Internet addresses for the three
characters depicted in his print, radio, and TV ads.
</P>
<P>
   The only catch is, the characters are make-believe.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. When consumers send e-mail _ any kind of message _
to these nonentities (Tia, Robert, and Anna), the characters will
respond with vivid details about their imaginary lives.
</P>
<P>
   It's an on-line soap opera. And a smart interactive marketing
tool to connect consumers to the product, which was launched in
1994. ``The next cK one generation has different values and
communicates in a very modern way,'' says Klein.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have is a new kind of intimacy that's really a
paradox _ people all over the world are more in touch than ever,
but they're doing it one-to-one on e-mail and the Internet. When we
take this new campaign to e-mail, it makes it very personal. People
are sharing more and they want to know more,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the company _ which sells 10 fragrances along with
clothing _ reports that the public has always been interested in
the models in its ads. ``I think the images really strike a chord
with our consumers,'' says Diana Lin, a spokeswoman for Calvin
Klein Cosmetics Co., a licensee of Calvin Klein Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, previous ads have had real people in them, like Kate
Moss and Marky Mark. One has to wonder, do consumers really want to
spend time writing to phony individuals? There's Anna, a
13-year-old schoolgirl; Tia, a TV advertising producer in her 20s
who just relocated to New York from Seattle; and Robert, a married
30-something director of TV commercials who _ at the moment _
thinks he might be in love with Tia, whom he just met in London
while shooting a dog food commercial.
</P>
<P>
   People love drama, according to Tobe Berkovitz, a professor of
advertising at Boston University. ``Is this any more pathetic than
weeping as Jimmy Smits dies on `NYPD Blue'? This is an actor on TV
and people are sobbing as this guy expires.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good way to tap into all the cyber stuff that is hot
at the moment. . . . It's a pseudorelationship. All you get back
are preprogrammed little messages. . . . But look how many people
live for chat rooms and who knows who you're chatting with?''
</P>
<P>
   More important than the e-mail, of course, is the question _
will consumers buy the fragrance? To date, Klein has sold more than
$390 million of the light unisex scent in the United States, making
it Klein's best-selling fragrance, and clearly, this campaign will
only attract more attention. Says Berkovitz, ``All that really
matters to the marketer is: Does the audience get involved?'' So
even if people don't buy the fragrance and instead send hate mail,
the campaign will still be a success because, he says, ``they're
responding.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the campaign started in mid-November and it will hit
TV and radio airways in Boston Thursday. Print ads have already
debuted in the December issues of various magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers who've written to tia(at)ckone.com,
robert(at)ckone.com, and anna(at)ckone.com have learned a lot about
the trio. During Tia's first week on the job, for example, she was
sent to London, which annoyed Jason (another character), back in
Seattle. ``Never mind that this is the biggest opportunity I've
ever had in my life, all he can think about is how it affects
him,'' she complains, while also noting that a guy named Ian
``hasn't quit hitting on'' her since she arrived in London.
</P>
<P>
   Robert has revealed that his life is ``quite literally, going to
the dogs. I have been sequestered in London for the past week,
logging in 18-hour days and slowly but surely losing my grasp on
reality. And to what end? A bloody dog food commercial.''
</P>
<P>
   Anna's communication is much more vague, but she has mentioned
her ``life is ruined'' and that the party was a bad idea. ``I can't
talk now because I've got too much to do trying to figure out if
there's any possible way to save my life before my mom gets back.''
</P>
<P>
   The characters' e-mail arrives sporadically, just as real e-mail
does. Once a consumer sends an initial message, the characters will
keep writing to them regardless of whether the consumer writes
back. To stop the chatter from the Klein characters, consumers just
have to send the message ``get lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Lin says the company will introduce seven new characters in
1999. While models will be used in TV and print ads, the dialogue
from the characters will come from employees at the New York ad
agency Wieden &AMP; Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   So can consumers expect the characters to talk about cK one all
the time? No, promises Lin. ``There's nothing promotional at all,''
she says. ``These are real voices.'' In cyberspace at least.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
