<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINISHING OFF A DINNERTIME DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At many Thanksgiving gatherings, the accepted way to announce
that one has eaten one's fill is a low, resonant moan, the sound of
satisfaction liberally seasoned with regret. But at the celebration
Natasha Bello took part in, the grateful diners had enough energy
left over to debate whether ``I am finished'' was more correct than
``I am done.'' ``Who's right?'' she wants to know.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, I'm not sure Miss Manners would condone either choice.
Unless someone is asking for the rest of your pumpkin pie, there's
no need to declare that you're not going to eat any more; your
companions will surely notice, if they're interested. And when
offered more, you say ``No, thank you'' _ not, please, ``I'm
stuffed!''
</P>
<P>
   And when it's waitpersons who are asking if you are finished,
``May I take your plate?'' is a more discreet inquiry than either
``Are you finished?'' or ``Are you done?'' (Though almost anything
is better than ``Are you still working on that?'' _ an appalling
expression that manages to imply both that you're doing a chore,
rather than enjoying yourself, and that you're not doing it fast
enough.)
</P>
<P>
   But I digress; this was a usage question, and my favorite usage
chroniclers offered plenty of answers. According to the
Merriam-Webster usage arbiters, I'm done (or I am done) seems to
have moved in on the traditional form, I have done, during the 19th
century. Following the usual historical pattern, traditionalists
responded by spending the first half of this century preaching that
I'm done was improper usage, and demanding that we say I'm finished
instead.
</P>
<P>
   But in truth, I'm finished had only a slightly longer pedigree,
for it too was moving from the I have to the I am construction. As
recently as 1985, the M-W usage dictionary can point to an English
teacher _ albeit in a German classroom _ who was insisting that
students use I have finished, and marking I'm finished wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The real surprise, though, is that I'm through _ which took root
around the same time as I'm finished _ somehow sneaked under the
radar of the word wardens. A few tiny skirmishes at the border, a
Bing Crosby hit song, and I'm through was one of the family, while
I'm done is, obviously, still struggling for respectability in some
circles. Most of us can give thanks, however, that if we want to
say it, we can say it any way we like: We're through, we're
finished, we're done.
</P>
<P>
   Doom and gloom
</P>
<P>
   Well, not quite done. My explorations of auxiliary-verb
territory reminded me of an earlier query from Marie Masse of
Topsfield. Why, in an October column, had I written ``our doom is
come'' rather than ``our doom has come''?
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't sure why, aside from the fact that it sounded right,
but the association that first surfaced from the subconscious was
Tennyson. ``My doom is come upon me'' _ isn't that what the Lady of
Shalott said, more or less? But I hadn't read the poem in many a
year, and in fact, the lines I was misremembering go like this:
</P>
<P>
   The mirror crack'd from side to side;
</P>
<P>
   ``The curse is come upon me,'' cried
</P>
<P>
   The Lady of Shalott.
</P>
<P>
   Did I read a bowdlerized version, long ago, or simply edit it
unconsciously in the years since? In any case, Tennyson would
probably have written it my way, back in 1830, had he known that
100 years later, the curse would have a meaning that would make
schoolgirls giggle at his poor bewitched beauty.
</P>
<P>
   But whether it's curse or doom, why is it is come upon me, not
has come? It's because come, along with a few other English verbs
``of motion and position,'' can be conjugated with the original
auxiliary, be, as well as with the later have. ``He is gone is
still used to express resulting state,'' explains the OED, ``while
he has gone expresses action.''
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare does it, of course: Richard II says Bolingbroke ``is
come to open / The purple testament of bleeding war.'' The King
James Bible, too: ``Behold, he is come out to fight.'' This is not
a usage we're likely to have much need of, but its immediacy gives
it a drama lacking in the has form of the verb. To return to the
table, Dinner is served has an obvious advantage over the equally
grammatical and accurate dinner has been served _ except for guests
who prefer cold turkey.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (What's the word? Write or e-mail yours to Jan Freeman at The
Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378; freeman(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
