<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8444 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-GARRITY-PHOTO-BOS &LR;      12-08 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-GARRITY-PHOTO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE RECORD FOR BUSING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ There is the myth of white flight, he says, the notion
that when the buses rolled to desegregate the Boston public
schools, white parents suddenly flooded out to the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   There is the myth that busing could have included the ring of
suburbs around the city and been less disruptive and more fair.
</P>
<P>
   And a myth, too, he deems the notion that the remedy to
desegregate Boston's schools somehow failed.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four years after his court order desegregating Boston
schools, with anger toward him still fresh among many parents, many
of the same issues still unresolved, and the Boston Latin School
case being appealed to the nation's highest court, Judge W. Arthur
Garrity, Jr. is trying to set the record straight.
</P>
<P>
   That record is in 60-odd boxes of Garrity's papers on the case
that were donated this week to the University of Massachusetts at
Boston: eight crates full of correspondence, much of it death
threats and hate mail, another filled with dozens of doctoral
theses on the case. It includes the dockets to the 17 appeals to
his decision, and Garrity's point-by-point refutation of factual
errors he says he found in the chapter entitled ``The Judge'' in
Common Ground, the late J. Anthony Lukas's best-selling and
Pulitzer Prize winning chronicle of Boston desegregation.
</P>
<P>
   For those who sift through the files, Garrity promises, there is
also the demographic data debunking the notion of white flight as a
result of the busing order, the memos and reports proving that he
carefully weighed and reasoned through different remedies for
desegregation, and attendance records, by race, for every single
school day in Boston between 1974 and 1990, when the case was
officially closed.
</P>
<P>
   For such a public case, Garrity says, it is only appropriate
that the historical record be on public display at a public
university. But for the judge, it is also a way of showing the
facts behind what he sees as the myths that still persist, of
countering his common portrayal as an aloof theoretician playing
social engineer from his comfortable home in Wellesley.
</P>
<P>
   And in a wide-ranging interview at his office overlooking Boston
Harbor from the new federal courthouse, Garrity, now 78, continued
to defend his decisions in the Boston case, which landed on his
desk by judges' lottery in 1972. If he has regret, it is mostly
that the desegregation solution for which he was so reviled has
come unraveled with the challenge to race-based admissions at
Boston Latin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came up with certain solutions, and damn,'' he says,
shaking his head. ``It was working quite well, really. That's all
been undone, and something's going to have to be proposed. So you
go out and come up with a lot of surrogate concepts, but I just
don't know if any of those are going to work.''
</P>
<P>
   He was so much the target of vitriol and death threats after his
June 21, 1974 decision that he had two US marshals outside his home
for nearly four years, from September 1974 to February 1978.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, he says in reflection, was that the city's leaders
and parents never signed on to the essential mission of the court
order.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question has been whether it's a race case or an education
issue,'' he said. ``You try to make it both, but before you got to
improving education, you had to give the black students and parents
the same opportunities you did others. That was the constitutional
part of it. The constitution does not have any requirement for
education, that's left to the states.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was first a race case. We tried to make it an education
case as well. The parents and the city leaders have never looked
upon the case in that fashion. They think of it principally as
being a schools, an education case, and incidentally a race case.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalls the story of a breakfast meeting with businessmen
downtown where one prominent banker buttonholed the judge and
insisted that his organization would do anything to help Boston
public schools. But desegregate the schools? Count him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you started to talk about giving one race any remedy for
past injustice, that was not something he wanted to talk about,''
Garrity said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't even trying to improve the racial climate,'' Garrity
added. ``I was trying to vindicate constitutional rights of some
black students who were being bused past white schools, who were
going to schools with all white faculty, schools that had leaking
roofs and facilities that were being absolutely neglected, had
inferior, if any, textbooks. The thing was absolutely horrible when
I came in. It was horrendous.''
</P>
<P>
   Then-mayor Kevin White and others argued that the plan should
have included the city's suburbs. But Garrity continues to insist
that that would not have worked _ with the papers at UMass
outlining his argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the fact that Brookline is surrounded by Boston, you
couldn't convert Brookline schools reasonably into the Boston
school system because you don't have authority or jurisdiction to
make orders against persons who are not in some fashion responsible
for the wrong that's being righted. You can't go out and drag in
anyone you feel like.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as the case provoked disruption, he insists that it has
had benefits. Restructuring the system made it possible for people
without political connections to be hired as teachers.
</P>
<P>
   While the percentage of white students dropped from nearly half
to less than a fifth of the public school population, Garrity says
that white flight from busing was a myth. One third of the families
with children under 18 left the city between 1970 and 1980,
according to the census. But the records at UMass, he says, show
that the same pattern of whites moving to the suburbs started in
the 1950s, and was no more true in Boston than it was in the rest
of eastern Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Garrity refuses to comment on whether his plan has been a
success. He acknowledges that the issue of race and education has
changed. He himself overturned a system of quotas at Boston Latin,
arguing that court decisions required the remedy for desegregation
be more tightly tailored to past discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen, he said, whether the Supreme Court will
entirely abandon affirmative action in the schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been asked and tried to answer truthfully, would I have
done anything differently,'' he said. ``Looking back to the
circumstances confronting me at the time, I would not have done
things any differently. I thought I did what I had to do, I did
what I thought was reasonable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
