<SLUG> BC-MCGRORY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET'S TALK ABOUT PETER LYNCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN McGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   His close and casual friends say that Fidelity mutual fund
legend Peter Lynch is a difficult man to dislike. True enough, but
I've come to the point where I'm more than willing to try.
</P>
<P>
   He is everywhere. His long, gaunt visage, his scrubby salt and
pepper locks, appear on national television countless times each
day. He is riding on airplanes with Don Rickles. He is waiting in
line at the Registry of Motor Vehicles. He is running on a bucking
treadmill aside Lily Tomlin. He stares out from billboards, from
glossy magazine advertisements, from the Internet, uttering such
pseudo-sage, oversimplified pablum as ``Know what you own and why
you own it.''
</P>
<P>
   He has arguably become the most visible Bostonian in America,
emblematic of too much of what this booming city has become. It
used to be that Boston was more about compassion, about livability,
about knowledge, about things that transcend the singular pursuit
of wealth. Over the last couple of years, it is gliding towards a
boutique version of New York, too money-crazed, too morally craven.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling is everywhere. The average immigrant family can't
afford a decent apartment in even the most downtrodden
neighborhoods of the city. Back Bay condominiums are selling for
upwards of $400 a square foot. Swiss chocolates on Newbury Street
fetch $1.50 a bite. A 40-yard line ticket to the Patriots is $50,
and that's not enough to keep them from leaving town. The financial
district is crammed with young men in French blue shirts talking on
cellular phones about vacation plans to Bali.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Boston has become a city that kneels at the
altar of the almighty dollar, the metropolitan equivalent of John
Updike's most famous character, Rabbit Angstrom, rolling around his
bed on a pile of gleaming Krugerrands. Don't get me wrong. I love
money. I think about it all the time. I'm thinking about it right
now. But there has to be something more.
</P>
<P>
   I just spent 2 1/2 years in a national capital obsessed with
oral sex, only to arrive in a provincial capital obsessed with
itself. To be sure, some of that self-importance is good. Parks are
better. The city is cleaner. The harbor is beautiful, and the
bounty of construction cranes is the harbinger of even better times
to come.
</P>
<P>
   But the flip side is complacency. No more arguments on the haves
and have nots. Rather, the debates are about skyscrapers and
stadium luxury boxes, the political satisfaction found in the
flowers planted on Blue Hill Avenue, never mind the hopelessness of
those who look out on them.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us back to Peter Lynch. His business legend is well
deserved, especially judging from the type of hard numbers by which
Boston now judges itself. In 13 years as a money manager, he racked
up a cumulative gain of 2,700 percent, taking the Magellan Fund
from $20 million in assets to over $14 billion. He was the premier
stock picker in the nation, his golden touch making it possible for
millions of Americans to buy houses and send children to college.
``He is the Walter Cronkite of financial services,'' said Fidelity
executive Paula Polito.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, he is described by his friend, Boston advertising
titan Jack Connors, as ``an enormously decent guy.'' He donates
swaths of time to charity _ two full days a week, by his own
estimate. He is a tireless philanthropic fundraiser, a major and
valued patron of the Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in reality, at Fidelity, there are signs that Lynch is
allowing the legend to overtake the man. He lacks, if you will,
that elusive quality of duende, and his television presence invites
the use of the remote control. One Fidelity president recently
bristled to Globe business columnist Steven Syre, ``What fund does
Peter Lynch run?'' None, actually. Lynch, semi-retired and
fabulously wealthy, hasn't managed any Fidelity money in nearly
nine years.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, other critics have questioned the elementary
investment advice he espouses in his two best-selling books and in
the Fidelity advertising campaign _ counsel such as, if you like
L'eggs pantyhose, invest in its maker, Hanes. With that kind of
advice, I'd own the Capital Grille, and that stock has been flat
for years. ``It is simplistic,'' says Tobias Levkovich, a senior
analyst for Smith Barney in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Some colleagues whisper that he treasures the publicity, and
without fresh accomplishment, reaches into his past for
contemporary fame. Allies argue he does it for the good of his
company. Lynch himself says he does it as a public service, because
people should know more about investing. But will they, really,
with Lynch slogans like ``Do your homework'' and ``Understand the
market?'' Which leaves only the Lynch-like question, ``What is he
doing and why is he doing it?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Brian McGrory is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
