<HEADER>
A8447 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-08 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FRUSTRATIONS OF AN UNDECIDED GOP HOUSE MEMBER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Call me a CUHR.
</P>
<P>
   As a Composite Undecided House Republican, I hate the box I'm
in, and I get no comfort from the fact that for once this box is
not of my own, squishy-minded making but is entirely President
Clinton's doing.
</P>
<P>
   I know what the wise guys are saying, that Acting Speaker Tom
Delay of Texas is spreading the message that the next 10 days or so
is purely for TV and that he already has a 10- to 15-vote margin in
favor of at least one perjury-based impeachment article. But I know
different, because Delay's message _ just like the
Gingrich-Livingston speakership _ forgets about the 30 to 35 of us
who like to make up our own minds. And on this one, animus and
party are not enough; this vote goes in my obituary.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, a bunch of things bother me about this mess, but
eight in particular stand out:
</P>
<P>
   --This is another government shutdown in the making, longer and
more traumatic than what Newt put us through pointlessly in 1995.
If no one can tell me there is even a chance that Clinton can
actually get thrown out of office by the Senate, then a yes vote
can come back to haunt me; people will say I helped put the country
through another wringer for no purpose whatsover.
</P>
<P>
   --Worse, I do not want to have to answer to bankers, business
guys, and investment types in my district who yell at me that I'm
putting the financial markets and the economy at risk. The prospect
of instability made them nervous last summer; they're getting itchy
again, and I can't come up with a reason to justify making the
United States look like Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   --I hate it when my so-called leaders take a hike and leave my
rear end exposed. I can't believe Bob Livingston is having Delay
front for him on the biggest issue next to war any of us faces. If
he ducks on the big ones, who cares what he does on appropriations
bills?
</P>
<P>
   --Even worse, for people asked to make tough decisions, it
doesn't help when the stand-in leaders tell you things that aren't
so, like Delay's bull-bleep about censure. We now know it has a
larger presence in American history than impeachment does, and we
know there is nothing even remotely violative of the Constitution
about it. To the contrary, it is an entirely legitimate option.
</P>
<P>
   --But that's not all. Delay is actually trying to rig the
impeachment issue's time on the House floor so that we are
forbidden to discuss censure, forbidden to consider it, and
forbidden to vote on it. My leaders know and all my colleagues know
that if the House is permitted to work its will, around 20
Republicans will vote for some form of censure and then vote
against impeachment. That being the case, some of us will have to
think hard about refusing to be put into an either-or box by our
so-called leaders.
</P>
<P>
   --But Delay and his henchmen are going even further. Their
latest maneuver, and it is proof that they know they have yet to
assemble a hard majority for impeachment, is that they are trying
to change the meaning of impeachment. He and Henry Hyde acolytes
like Bill McCollum of Florida are actually telling me that
impeachment can be censure, that it doesn't have to be followed by
a Senate trial, and that incompetent McCollum had the gall to say
impeachment could be a ``scarlet letter'' for Clinton to wear
forever.
</P>
<P>
   Well phooey on them. Elliot Richardson was right when he said a
vote to impeach means a vote to have a trial and remove him from
office, period.
</P>
<P>
   --And it might help if the case were in evidentiary shape for
such a momentous vote, but it isn't. Some of us remember what
Hyde's guy, David Schippers, promised two months ago, noting, for
example, that Monica Lewinsky's credibility could be legitimately
questioned. Schippers then promised that ``at an appropriate stage
of the proceedings that credibility will of necessity be assessed
together with the credibility of all other witnesses in the light
of all the other evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   So what happened?
</P>
<P>
   --Finally, we know that there are at least two unexploded bombs
out there before we are asked to put our reputations on the line
and cast votes. One is Hillary Rodham Clinton; the other is her
husband, who everyone knows could change this atmosphere utterly by
being a little more contrite and a little more forthcoming (say by
changing the word ``mislead'' to ``lie'').
</P>
<P>
   That's why we are undecided, and that's why we are worried.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
