A8456 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAPA-TEEN-GANGS-BOS &LR;      12-08 1267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAPA-TEEN-GANGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAPA VALLEY FIGHTS GANG THREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAPA, Calif. _ When the seventh, eighth and ninth teenagers hit
the ground with gunshot wounds as they waited for their morning
bus, the illusion of an idyll fell with them.
</P>
<P>
   The incongruous reality is that lush Napa County, along with its
celebrated vineyards, quaint downtown and cozy B&AMP;Bs, has a gang
problem it can no longer ignore.
</P>
<P>
   Anxiety is high. Both the people who live in the neighborhoods
that two rival gangs claim as their own and the people who depend
on wine-tasting tourists for their livelihoods worry they will be
harmed.
</P>
<P>
   High school senior Yissel Lopez says her mother has taken to
insisting she stay indoors at night. A car cruising with its
headlights off now causes Francisco Lopez , no relation, to flinch
reflexively. The former amateur boxer with aspirations to the
ministry says he fears being caught in the cross-fire on his way
home from junior college.
</P>
<P>
   In the four weeks since nine people were shot in 72 hours,
locals who were shaken by the city's first-ever drive-by killing
last April have flocked to community forums to insist something be
done to keep Napa County from becoming another Detroit or Los
Angeles. The district attorney's office has created a new full-time
position: gang prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a problem that is not going to go away,'' said Napa
Police Chief Dan Monez , who now has two officers charged with
keeping tabs on gang members and potential gang members full-time.
``It's a phenomenon that is very, very difficult to deal with, but
we have some hope here that at least we can manage it and minimize
the violence.''
</P>
<P>
   The violence _ which, until this year, mostly took the form of
clubbings, beatings and the occasional stabbing _ has not been
limited to any single neighborhood or ethnic group in this
predominantly Hispanic city of 70,000.
</P>
<P>
   The 17 year old facing attempted murder charges in the bus stop
shootings is white and from a middle-class family and a suspected
gang affiliate, police said. One of five people being prosecuted
for the drive-by fatality is also an Anglo. No suspects have been
pinpointed in the other multiple shooting in an apartment complex
parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   But the two gangs causing the majority of trouble identify
themselves by their ties to Mexico, even if not every member is
Mexican. Affiliates of the Surenos, Spanish for southerners, tend
to be relatively recent immigrants. The more Americanized Nortenos,
or northerners, come from families who have been in the states for
two generations or longer. The Nortenos wear red, the Surenos blue.
Police estimate that the gangs may have 300 members between them,
although no more than two dozen willing to war with more than spray
paint or sneers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this year alone, police have had to respond more than
half a dozen times to reports of gunshots, sometimes bullets fired
in the air, sometimes at a house, said Napa Police Sgt. John
Kostelac . It is uncertain whether those shootings were
gang-related, he added, but with back-and-forth retaliations
becoming common occurrences, the suspicion is that they were.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't random,'' said Lars Christensen(cq), principal of
Napa High School, whose 2,200 students are forbidden from wearing
gang colors or flashing gang signs on campus. ``It started six
months ago with a feud involving adults and young people. . .And
some very petty arguments have ended in some catastrophic
results.''
</P>
<P>
   Gangs, as local authorities and residents explained it, have
gained a foothold in Napa County, population 120,000, for the same
reasons they have in large urban areas more readily associated with
violence. Some pointed to an increase in single-family homes,
leaving youths unsupervised. Others said too many Hispanics in the
poorer sections of town have too little to look forward to, since
they perform most of the menial, low-paying tasks in the wealthy
wineries that have made Napa world famous.
</P>
<P>
   Here as elsewhere, gangs can give youths a sense of recognition
and belonging, however misbegotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was at that age, it was all about acceptance,'' said
Daniel Fiske , teen director at the Napa Boys &AMP; Girls Club and
himself a former Norteno. ``It was cheap to be a gang member _ all
you needed was a pair of Dickies and a white T-shirt. It was
something to do, and there's not enough for kids to do around
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Word around town is that the latest shootings, which gravely
injured a 14-year-old boy in a poorer neighborhood known as
Westwood, date back to the deadly April drive-by. That fight began
when a group of Nortenos who were changing a flat tire traded
insults with a group of Surenos who happened by in a car. When the
argument was over, a 17 year old lay dead.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since, there has been an escalation of violence,
culminating in the bus stop ambush beneath a highway overpass, just
past a muted mural of Our Lady of Guadalupe.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come here to get away from it, but you can't get away
from it anymore,'' said Manuel Alvarez, 18, who shuns the gangs but
worries that Surenos will hassle him because he has relatives who
are Nortenos. ``I guess for some kids around here that means a lot
more pressure to pick a side.''
</P>
<P>
   The sides, in fact, have been drawn for some time now in this
town tucked into the mountains north of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Napa police and politicians first confronted a gang problem in
1992, after noticing graffiti and an increase in fighting. A task
force of sorts was formed, but fell apart within months, said Scott
LeStrange, chief deputy of Napa County's District Attorney's
office. People did not believe the problem was deep-seated, he
said, adding that ``we do now, because the bullets are flying.''
</P>
<P>
   As Mayor Ed Henderson put it, ``We thought we had it under
control. We learned that you can't just sit back when the numbers
go down. . .We're jumping on it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials from around the country now meet
regularly to coordinate their efforts. Father John Brenkle of St.
Helena Catholic Church said one group he belongs to, the
Sonoma-Napa Action Project, has decided to take on street violence.
One of their long-range goals is to persuade businesses in Napa,
where unemployment is a low 4 percent, to create better-paying jobs
for youths.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have a choice: We can divert these kids to healthy
programs and or to Juvenile Hall,'' said Father Brenkle. ``But if
you don't get jobs for these kids, you're kind of spitting in the
wind.''
</P>
<P>
   But Daniel Howard, executive director of the Napa Valley
Conference and Visitors Bureau, said no public officials have yet
called asking for help combatting gangs with jobs or internships.
No tourists, and 5 million of them visit Napa County annually, have
called with concerns about the gangs either, he said. The gangs, he
said, are not an issue for them.
</P>
<P>
   To Fiske, the former Norteno turned teen director, any lack of
urgency on the part of Napa's elite means the county is unlikely to
triumph over gangs while it can. He pointed to a concrete symbol of
the crisis: the club's new center sits empty and unfinished for
lack of funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't blame the gangs on the parents; you can't blame it
on any one thing,'' said Fiske, 22, who got out five years ago in
part because he was maturing, in part because his friend was shot.
``You have to blame it on the community. These are our kids and
it's our problem. Everyone's. Now let's do something about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
