<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8458 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUERTO-DEBATE-BOS &LR;      12-08 1328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUERTO-DEBATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUERTO RICANS IN US FEEL A STAKE IN ISLAND VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The street signs surrounding the brick-faced Villa
Victoria complex are a constant reminder of the country they left
behind.
</P>
<P>
   Paseo Borikn. Paseo San Juan. Paseo Aguadilla.
</P>
<P>
   In this slice of the South End, the oldest Puerto Rican
neighborhood in Boston, residents are preoccupied with Sunday's
plebiscite in Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it should become a state,'' said Nelson Rios, 43, as
he walked past Escuelita Borikn, Spanish for ``little Puerto Rican
school.''
</P>
<P>
   A few feet away, 65-year-old Jorge Flores shook his head. ``The
young people want statehood; I say keep it the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate, always heated, has divided Puerto Ricans since US
troops seized the Caribbean island in 1898. For years, most Puerto
Ricans favored remaining a US commonwealth. Now, as many wonder if
this plebiscite will propel Congress to allow Puerto Ricans to
decide their own fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``How long do we have to wait?'' asked Federico Sierra, the
owner of Sierra Travel on Tremont Street in the South End. ``It's
been so many years that we've been living in limbo. The people have
the right to decide.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 3 million Puerto Ricans live in the continental United
States. In Massachusetts, the 1990 Census counted more than 151,000
Puerto Ricans, the largest Latino group in the state.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, the Puerto Rican barrio that existed in the South End
30 years ago dispersed to Jamaica Plain, Mattapan, Roslindale, and
Roxbury during urban renewal.
</P>
<P>
   In those neighborhoods, bodegas stock El Vocero and other Puerto
Rican newspapers. Daily stories on ``el plebiscito'' are splashed
on the front pages. On local Spanish radio and TV programs, the
plebiscite dominates the news.
</P>
<P>
   Felix Arroyo, the director of the Egleston Square Neighborhood
Association and a member of the Boston School Committee, said he
checks the El Nuevo Da Web site several times a week to read the
latest on the plebiscite. He phones his father and daughter, who
live in separate Puerto Rican towns, asking for the latest.
</P>
<P>
   He said he feels politically exiled because he, and other Puerto
Ricans living on the mainland,can't vote on an issue he has been
talking about since he was a child in Arecibo.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was growing up, my father was for commonwealth, my
mother for statehood. I wanted independence,'' said Arroyo, who
still is an independentista.
</P>
<P>
   Although the plebiscite results are not binding, many believe
the vote will push Congress into action _ especially if there is
overwhelming support for statehood.
</P>
<P>
   But Arroyo wonders if Washington lawmakers will listen to the
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can ask to be free. We can ask to become a state, but
Congress has the ultimate decision,'' he said. ``I wonder what we
are doing. Is this just an exercise?''
</P>
<P>
   Big turnout expected
</P>
<P>
   The plebiscite is the brainchild of Governor Pedro Rossell, a
statehood proponent who plans to lobby Congress to take action.
Last March, the House of Representatives passed, by one vote, a
bill authorizing a US-backed plebiscite.
</P>
<P>
   A Senate version of the bill died, mostly because Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott opposed it. The Senate did, however, for
the first time in history, pass a resolution in favor of an
island-led vote.
</P>
<P>
   More than 80 percent of the eligible voters on the island are
expected to cast ballots Sunday, _ a huge turnout by US standards.
Most either favor statehood for the island and its 3.9 million
residents or want to remain a US commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
   But the ballot offers three other choices, which are expected to
dilute votes of the main camps: becoming a free associated state,
becoming an independent nation, or none of the above.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are very concerned about what's going to happen,'' said
Tony Molina, publisher of El Universal, a Spanish weekly he
publishes from his Jamaica Plain home. Molina says he gets about 35
letters a week on the subject and twice as many phone calls. ``Many
people are upset that they can't vote.''
</P>
<P>
   While they are US citizens, many Puerto Ricans are rankled by
their lack of political clout. Puerto Rico has one delegate to the
US House, but that member cannot vote on the floor. And Puerto
Ricans cannot vote in US presidential races.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Congress continues to pass laws that affect Puerto
Ricans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to remain second-class citizens,'' said Carlos
Linera, director of the regional office of the Puerto Rico Federal
Affairs Administration in Boston, who said political
representation, not economic issues, drives him to want statehood.
</P>
<P>
   He considers Puerto Rico a modern-day colony. ``When you have a
Congress that has plenary powers over you and you have no voice in
that Congress, you're a colony,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Linera says economics is not fueling the debate, many
disagree. Often it is what Puerto Ricans bring up most.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say if it becomes a state the cost of living will go up,
but I don't know about that,'' said Dalia Rodriguez, a 53-year-old
Salvation Army worker who was sitting under a hair dryer at
Elegance Beauty Salon on Tremont Street. ``It's expensive to live
there and if we become a state and have to start paying taxes, it's
really going to hurt the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many Puerto Ricans living on the mainland, she plans to
retire on the island. And like many in Massachusetts, she's
listening to Spanish radio programs, watching Telemundo and
Univision, and reading Puerto Rican newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Gender gap cited
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rodrguez's sentiments are typical among older residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ones who favor commonwealth status are the (Luis) Munoz
Marin crowd,'' said Molina, the newspaper publisher, speaking of
those who came of age when Munoz Marin became the first elected
Puerto Rican governor in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   ``Statehooders are a younger crowd, a new generation. More
progressive,'' Molina said. He said everyone goes through an
independence phase during their high school or college years.
</P>
<P>
   For Giovanna Negretti, 27, it's not a phase.
</P>
<P>
   Although polls show little support for independence, she hopes
to change a few minds the day of the vote. She plans to fly to the
island to let her voice be heard the only way she says she can _
through protest.
</P>
<P>
   Negretti, of Jamaica Plain, is the interium president of the
Massachusetts chapter of the National Congress for Puerto Rican
Rights, a group that advocates ``decolonization,'' although the
group isn't pro-independence.
</P>
<P>
   She said she is angry the governor pushed for the plebiscite at
a time when families are still rebuilding after the destruction
caused by Hurricane Georges and when hundreds of homes in the
mountainside still don't have electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Ricans think they can't survive without the United
States, she said, but they are mistaken. She said the island could
survive on money from tourism, trade with Latin America, and from
charging the United States to keep its military bases there.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the main reasons she wants independence is so Puerto
Rican culture does not die.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it becomes a state, our identity will be lost,'' Negretti
said. ``It will be like Hawaii and my grandchildren will have to
look up arroz y habichuelas (rice and beans) in the dictionary.''
</P>
<P>
   So on Dec. 13, she plans to meet friends somewhere in Puerto
Rico and protest, waving a Puerto Rican flag and wearing a bandana
on her head. ``I want to look really radical to scare people,'' she
said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome, Linera, is, like many Puerto Ricans,
hoping for a resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we are, 1998, about to turn the millennium, and the US is
still in this situation,'' he said. ``It's ridiculous that Puerto
Ricans, who have been American citizens since 1917, have to beg for
an opportunity to define our political status.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
