<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-FEARS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Y2K WORRY LEADS SOME TO SURVIVAL PREPARATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKESIDE, Calif. _ The hut was junk-pile crude: lawn chairs for
the frame, plastic scraps and frayed blankets for the walls, and
everything from cotton rags to shredded cardboard to palm fronds
for filling in the holes.
</P>
<P>
   The would-be survivalists _ a doctor, a school nurse and a
computer programmer among them _ built the shelter-for-one in a
matter of minutes and pronounced it both habitable and homeworthy.
They also hoped they would never have to live in one like it.
</P>
<P>
   But the half-dozen or so students at a recent Southern
California survival seminar want to be ready for the worst come
Jan. 1, 2000. That's when doomsday scenarios have computer networks
going haywire, resulting in no power, no water service, no fuel, no
ATMs, and delayed food distribution. Survivalists warn that only
optimists and idiots will approach the next century unprepared for
an unnatural disaster.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not just conspiracists and crackpots who are preparing
for the possibility of the end of the world as we know it. Although
the numbers are understandably uncertain, it appears that tens of
thousands of Americans are steadily stockpiling food, squirreling
away cash and even putting down payments on remote, Y2K-proof
developments. The Internet is littered with Web sites, chat rooms
and bulletin boards devoted to surviving the coming century.
Manufacturers of hand-held water filters and freeze-dried food
report soaring sales from first-time customers. And land owners and
developers from northern New Hampshire to central Colorado to Moose
Pass, Alaska, are marketing safe havens for the savvy and scared.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned that time to fix the software glitch known as the
Millennium Bug is running out, plenty of computer specialists are
among them.
</P>
<P>
   Worried that milk won't get to market and the hungry will riot,
Steven E.C. Sroczynski is shopping for a 42-foot sailboat. He plans
to spend New Year's 2000 on it, and remain on the water until order
is restored. Srocyznski is an executive with Visionet Systems Inc.,
a Princeton, N.J., software provider which also helps companies
identify and correct their Y2K woes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a believer that there will be a breakdown in society,''
said Sroczynski, noting that his two sons and former wife will be
spending the turn of the century in a well-stocked cave outside
Birmingham, Ala. ``. . .We could end up with martial law, which I
expect will happen at least regionally.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry Snyder, who does similar Y2K-related work with
Sophisticated Systems Inc. an hour north of Detroit, plans on
having at least $30,000 cash on hand, just in case the banks are
forced to close. His pantry will be packed, and there will be extra
gas to run a back-up generator. ``I don't know what will go
wrong,'' he said, ``but I'm not one of those guys who says there's
no problem.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who need somewhere to escape to, Russ Vorhees is
developing Heritage Farms 2000: 500 lots priced at $10,000 for a
five-year lease. The development in Arizona's White Mountains
promises water from a spring-fed lake, continuous power and a
``21st Century'' communication system. Already his Web site has
received thousands of ``hits,'' Vorhees said, with half of the
serious inquiries coming from telecommuters and computer
specialists ``who want an insurance policy in a rural area.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a matter of life and death; that's the way we see
it,'' said Susan Conniry, who, with her husband Tom Beasley, runs
Conniry's Native Skills and Wilderness School in the hills just
northeast of San Diego. ``I don't like to be negative, because we
could still pull it out of the hat. But we could also find
ourselves in big, big trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Conniry and Beasley live on eight acres, and have gardens and a
well for water. But come 2000, they won't be home. Instead, after
teaching their students how to collect and filter water, build
fires from scratch and forage for food, the longtime naturists plan
to put civilization even further behind them.
</P>
<P>
   For those who plan to do likewise, they recommended carrying
Katadyne hand-held water filters, which cost upwards of $200. But
San Diego-based Suunto USA, which distributes the Swiss-made
filters, is already sold out for 1998; even with the factory
working three shifts, new orders cannot be filled before March,
said President Henri Syvanen.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this Y2K thing goes all the way,'' Beasley said, as he
sifted water through sand and charcoal, ``it could go to the Stone
Age. I don't anticipate that happening, but you never know.''
</P>
<P>
   Few but religious extremists anticipate such an apocalypse.
Still, no one is certain exactly what will happen when the clock
strikes midnight, ending one millennium and starting the next. The
fear is that the computers will read 2000 as 1900, touching off a
series of crashes that could halt everything from the stock market
to stop lights to payroll checks. Alarmists warn that prison
security systems could crash along with the computers. Utilities
could be disrupted. Depending on the forecaster, electricity and
water is not expected to be restored for days, weeks or months _
though the utilities themselves express confidence there will be no
such disruptions.
</P>
<P>
   As David Hall, a senior consultant with Cara Corp., an Oak
Brook, Ill., company that developments Y2K risk-management programs
for corporate clients, put it: ``People really believe in Y2K
trouble or they really don't.'' For his part, Hall plans to spend
New Year 2000 in New Mexico at one of his daughter's ``just in
case,'' although he is upbeat that most companies can overcome
their software problems before then.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-98 1325EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981208.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8469 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLENNIUM-FEARS-2ND &LR;      12-08 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-FEARS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 LAKESIDE, Calif.: ... before them.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Based on a study of 15,000 companies worldwide, the
Connecticut-based GartnerGroup consulting firm estimated that 23
percent have have no plans or resources in place to address their
Y2K issues. Computer failures could hit 15 percent of US companies
hard enough to keep them from performing their primary missions, at
least briefly. Among the least prepared were businesses with 2,000
or fewer employees, including local governments and the health-care
and oil and gas industries. Among the best were financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   The GartnerGroup report concluded: ``a bomb shelter mentality is
not called for,'' but prepare for an outcome similar to a major
storm. That includes having at least two week's salary in cash,
along with a five-day supply of medication, food and fuel. Even
optimists suggest keeping flashlights and spare batteries on hand,
along with paper copies of financial transactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an unprecedented event in the history of the planet,''
said Richard Hunter, the firm's vice president and director of
research. ``That may sound hyperbolic, but it's a simple statement.
. .Overall it's not going to be a disaster, but it certainly may be
unpleasant.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, computer programmers are working frantically to
find the problematic chips and fix the software flaws. But as the
deadline approaches, they say the challenge will go unmet by many
industries and municipalities. Compounding the urgency are
computers whose clocks will tick over in 1999 as new fiscal years
get under way, jump-starting sporadic Y2K trouble even before 2000.
</P>
<P>
   As Kyle Anderson, marketing manager for a young Chicago area
firm that develops software for the aircraft industry, sees it,
that's reason enough to make preparations. His family, his
brother's family and his grandmother _ 11 people in all _ will
start 2000 at his parents' home in a relatively rural part of
Illinois. They hope to be celebrating; they plan to be prepared.
With a well and a generator already on the property, Anderson said
he will spend several thousands of dollars gathering food and other
essential supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a long time to convince my family that this is
something they should pay attention to, that I'm not some kind of
Internet wacko,'' he said. ``It has that flavor of a conspiracy.
But it's not the reality. It's not about people sitting in a dark
star chamber plotting the demise of the world. There's evidence to
support some pretty scary theories.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most popular is that, with the electricity out, homes
unheated and people unprepared to feed their families, mass rioting
will break out. Looting will ensue. Those who have will be forced
to flee by those who do not. As a result, a high level of paranoia
exists among some survivalists, who refuse to divulge the locations
of their new communities.
</P>
<P>
   Pete, whose group included a computer programmer, a nurse and a
small-business owner before it began falling apart in recent weeks,
would say only that he continues to look for land several hours
north of Phoenix. Still hoping to put together a community of 12
families, he did not want his last name used and declined to
specify how they would defend themselves against marauders if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't get specific about any of our plans,'' said Pete, who
sells medical rehabilitation supplies. ``We're looking to be away
from the city and to make sure we're safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Gallegos is offering the people who buy into his community
another sort of safety: guaranteed power and communications. High
Valley Cyber Development is being built especially for companies
that want to ensure continuity of business. A 60,000-square-foot
mall will provide office space, with 120, $120,000 homes located an
easy walk away. Construction is expected to begin early next year
in south central Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a reasonable alternative to the survialist
mentality,'' said Gallegos, High Valley's chief operating officer.
``It recognizes there will be problems but doesn't run away from
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, when Y2K was barely a blip on anyone's computer
screen, Peter de Jager was considered a prophet of doom. Now the
Canadian computer expert and internet author worries that the panic
has gone too far. It is not, he stressed, ``the end of the world.''
People need not stockpile weapons and hide in the woods. Still,
even his he anticipates thousands of computer failures. Four-to-six
weeks of ``chaos'' can be expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no other word for it. . .,'' de Jager said. ``My
message has always been the same: The code is broken. We have a
deadline. The consequences could be nasty. Let's fix it. . . &UR;  &LR; Today
a tremendous amount of work has been done. Are we going to get it
all done? No.''
</P>
<P>
   De Jager went on to recommend having a month's worth of food,
water and fuel on hand. Anything more, he said, is overkill.
</P>
<P>
   The group Edward Thompson is heading up from Hot Springs,
Montana, feels otherwise. It is stockpiling four years worth of
food. Thompson said the group _ which so far includes his family,
his daughter's family, and at least three unrelated families _ also
plans on building an underground shelter that can hold as many as
50 people. In case they can't locate enough affordable land to the
north in time, he noted that they have identified caves where they
can live out any trouble for free.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just believe in being prepared,'' said Thompson, a disabled
mechanic who is a state leader for an internet group known as
Intentional Communities for Surival and Y2K Preparedness. ``I've
looked at all the scenarios and if you believe in the worst, you
many as well go sit in church because it's all over. But I am
expecting there will be major changes in the way we live.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most people, Eric Johnson, a Phoenix computer programmer,
said he doesn't know how much damage to expect. He too had
considered relocating to a rural area, then decided that running
away would be wrong. So he's been peppering his local utilities
with questions about their preparedness and assessing his family's
own needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people are going to get hurt because there
are going to be severe disruptions. . .,'' Johnson said. ``What I'd
really love is to look foolish on Jan. 1. I'd love to stand up and
let everyone have a good laugh at my expense. Unfortunately, that's
not in the cards.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
