<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCCER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARENA LEAVES BIG SHOES TO FILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bruce Arena's first game in charge of D.C. United in April 1996
gave only a hint of the team's potential. United lost to San Jose
in the inaugural Major League Soccer game, but Arena immediately
made drastic personnel changes, showing that he recognized talent
and was resourceful enough to acquire it.
</P>
<P>
   What Arena proved over the next three years was just as crucial
_ he could manage a team, mix various personalities and talents. He
remained faithful to his beliefs and to his tactical schemes. These
qualities helped engender faith and respect from his players.
</P>
<P>
   Arena's work culminated in a victory by D.C. United over Vasco
da Gama of Brazil for the InterAmericana Cup title Saturday night
in Fort Lauderdale, Fla. This could prove to be a historic
accomplishment as FIFA prepares to launch a World Club Championship
tournament next year.
</P>
<P>
   The InterAmericana Cup, contested between North and South
American champions, has had an uneven history since its start in
1969. It meant so little to Vasco da Gama that the club was willing
to extend its road trip to nearly a month and play the second leg
in Florida instead of Rio de Janeiro.
</P>
<P>
   Vasco's players clearly suffered a letdown after having lost to
Real Madrid in the Intercontinental Cup in Tokyo during the week,
but United's victory adds an important dimension to future
competitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had won, everyone would have given little importance to
the title,'' Vasco da Gama defender Mauro Galvao said. ``Now the
competition becomes important. This is football. This is why the
people always have to come to see what will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Arena takes over the US national team on a full-time basis.
He leaves United to Thomas Rongen, a succession which is baffling
to many involved with the Revolution. Rongen failed to leave a
positive stamp on the Revolution after guiding them for nearly two
years and was quickly forgotten after being succeeded by Walter
Zenga.
</P>
<P>
   Rongen failed to capture the imagination of the public in the
Boston area. Players had very mixed evaluations of him. Many
defended his methods and expressed belief in his tactics, even
after having clearly lost faith by the middle of last season.
Others became serious critics of Rongen, and he became involved in
an ugly dispute with David Nakhid, who accused him of creating a
racially insensitive atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Had the Revolution somehow been able to hire Arena after the
1996 season, it is difficult to believe the team would have
followed the path of the last two years. But the Revolution were a
rebuilding project, while United is a maintenance project. General
manager Kevin Payne and Arena, who retains his office and a strong
influence on D.C. United, believe in Rongen enough to have given
him a two-year contract worth about $200,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
   Payne said he wanted a coach who was ``grounded in American
soccer'' and had also considered former US national team coach Bob
Gansler.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow Rongen fit the requirements, though he is Dutch. This
shows some of the problems with typecasting coaches and players and
the semantics of designating domestic and foreign players in a
country with anything but a homogeneous population. Former D.C.
assistant Bob Bradley would have been the natural successor to
Arena. Bradley proved himself by guiding Chicago to the MLS Cup,
though with only a utilitarian influence from US-born players. Also
considered was Ivo Wortmann, the Brazilian who revamped the Miami
Fusion and became an Arena assistant on the national team. But both
Bradley and Wortmann were unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   Working in Rongen's favor are his espousal of tactical schemes
similar to Arena's and his ability to collect and manage the
diverse talent of Tampa Bay in winning the 1996 MLS regular-season
title.
</P>
<P>
   D.C. United must believe it is getting the Rongen of that '96
regular season, when his tyrannical tendencies were balanced by
general manager Farrukh Quraishi. Rongen won only 17 of 60 games in
regulation with the Revolution, and only six of those were
accomplished without Zenga in goal.
</P>
<P>
   Hermosillo helps
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Hermosillo was expected to lead the Los Angeles Galaxy to
the MLS Cup final in October. But the Galaxy fell to the Chicago
Fire, and Hermosillo returned to Mexico. Now Hermosillo has helped
Necaxa to the Mexican League final by scoring twice in a 3-2
victory over Atlas Sunday. Atlas's defeat prevented an all-Tapatio
final, since CD Guadalajara won the other semifinal against UNAM
Pumas, thanks to a Luis Garcia bicycle kick, which he sent past
Jorge Campos . . . Inter coach Gigi Simoni's job was on the line
two weeks ago, but his team defeated Real Madrid (3-1) in the
Champions League and Salernitana (2-1) in a Serie A match. That was
not enough, though, and Simoni was fired. His replacement, Romanian
Mircea Lucescu, has failed to win in his first two matches, and
during a 1-1 tie with Vicenza Sunday, Nigerian defender Taribo West
tossed his shirt at Lucescu after being replaced. West had
performed well under Simoni, who indulged West's regular absences
from preseason training because of sometimes outlandish excuses.
But West changed positions under Lucescu and now could be headed to
England. Lucescu will have to gain control over the situation
quickly _ Inter visits Sturm Graz in Austria in the Champions
League Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Respite for good reason
</P>
<P>
   Celtic has expanded its horizons in recent years, employing
Albanian, French, German, Icelandic, Italian, Polish, Portuguese,
and Scandinavian players. The Glasgow club has had great success
recently with Slovakian midfielder Lubomir Moravcik. But one of the
latest additions, Croatian-Australian Marko Viduka, left the team
and will be missing indefinitely. There is a good reason for
Viduka's absence. He is apparently the victim of post-traumatic
stress relating to the civil war in Yugoslavia. ``It was only after
I arrived in Glasgow last week that I started to realize how much I
had been affected by events in Zagreb over the last few months
where I had been under enormous personal pressure,'' Viduka said.
``I just hope everyone realizes this is not easy for me and
appreciates my honesty.'' . . . Rumor of the week, according to the
News of the World: Paul McCartney could become the owner of
Everton, the Liverpool club which is about to be purchased by
theater impresario Bill Kenwright, McCartney's former schoolmate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
