<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON BUSTLES AT CHRISTMASTIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boston's holiday season is in full swing, and will culminate
with the grandest and most festive First Night anywhere _ after
all, it is the first of the First Nights.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The season offers one of the grandest and most varied holiday
``strolls'' anywhere. Begin, say, in the historic Faneuil Hall
Marketplace filled with colorful shops, eateries, music, and
decorations along its cobblestone walkways, then amble down to
Downtown Crossing with its huge department stores along with
specialty shops, then head along Tremont Street to Boylston, with
its unique collection of stores, then into Copley Place, where you
can enter an indoor wonderland of lavish shopping, and continue
across an enclosed walkway into the Prudential Center for even more
variety. Now open in the Prudential Center is Marche Restaurant,
the largest restaurant in the city; it offers a fantasy island of
dining rooms where diners go to food stations, pick the ingredients
they want, then watch the Marche cooks go into action. It's just
about a two-mile dazzling showcase of holiday ideas.
</P>
<P>
   To really celebrate properly, spend a night or two in the city
at special holiday rates and enjoy enchanting festivities. At the
Four Seasons, there are Teddy Bear Teas; the Ritz-Carlton has
Nutcracker brunches; the Boston Park Plaza offers a Sugarplum
Festival and lunches; and the Fairmont Copley Plaza provides gift
wrapping in its ornate lobby (proceeds go to charities). For
information on packages and special events, call 888-SEE BOSTON or
visit www.bostonusa.com.
</P>
<P>
   Among holiday happenings is a visit to the Enchanted Village,
filled with animated figures, teddy bears, and more in a miniature
New England village of the past. The attraction used to be found in
Macy's (the former Jordan Marsh) and now graces City Hall Plaza in
a great white pavilion. Meanwhile, ``Black Nativity'' is on at
Tremont Temple; Boston is ``Nutcracker'' happy with the annual
holiday treat from the Boston Ballet on at the Wang Center, and
just across the street The Ballet Theatre of Boston is offering its
version at the Majestic Theater. Also, you can try out the ice
skating pond on Boston Common; catch the Christmas Revels at
Sander's Theater in Cambridge; take one of the nightly Holiday
Trolley Tours from Old Town Trolley; or join in the 225th Boston
Tea Party reenactment Dec. 13 at 5:30 p.m. at Old South Meeting
House and follow the ``Indians'' to the waterfront for the dumping.
More festivities: a Nutcracker luncheon at the Four Seasons on Dec.
12; a Christmas concert at Old North Church on Dec. 13 at 4 p.m.;
and the ``Messiah'' at Trinity Church in Copley Square also Dec. 13
at 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   And this is only a sampling of happenings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Holiday festivities
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Coolidge yule
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A free Christmas Open House will be held at the President Calvin
Coolidge State Historic Site on Dec. 12 from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. The
Coolidge Birthplace will be decorated in the style of 1872, the
year Coolidge was born. ``A few evergreen boughs, some fruits and
nuts, perhaps a small gift or two _ that was a Coolidge
Christmas,'' said William Jenney, site administrator. The Plymouth
Notch, Vt., site is a pristine mountain village that remains much
as it was when Calvin sledded down hillsides as a boy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Lantern tours
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mystic Seaport Lantern Light Tours, now in their 20th season,
are offered now through Dec. 20, Thursday through Sunday evenings.
Tours depart every 15 minutes from 5 p.m. and take about an hour
and 10 minutes. Reservations are required ($18 adult, $14 for
youths 5-15; not recommended for those under 5); call
888-9-SEAPORT.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-98 1330EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981208.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8477 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-NOTES-BOS &LR;      12-08 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT IN THE WORLD IS NEW? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One thing you can almost count on when you revisit Walt Disney
World is that something new and nifty will have sprung up. Here are
a few examples of what's ahead or has just arrived at the
ever-expanding Florida resort:
</P>
<P>
   --``Fantasmic.'' Dancing waters, flashing lasers, shooting
comets, swirling stars, and lots of other special effects combine
in this 25-minute production, now playing at the new Hollywood
Hills Amphitheater at Disney-MGM Studios. The production has Mickey
Mouse in a dream battle against assorted villains. We bet we know
who wins.
</P>
<P>
   --Test Track. This long-delayed ride comes to Epcot in early
1999. It will be the fastest, longest thrill attraction at Disney
World as visitors ``test-drive'' the latest in spiffy vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   --Cirque du Soleil. Anyone who has seen this blend of acrobatics
and special effects knows just how special it is. Seventy-two
artists will perform in a custom-made theater in Downtown Disney
West Side, beginning Dec. 23. Tickets ($56.50 plus tax for adults
and $45.20 plus tax for children 3-9) are already on sale.
</P>
<P>
   --Asia. The newest theme park, Animal Kingdom, expands its
attractions this spring with an area devoted to the rain forests
and wild creatures of southern Asia, and includes a white-water
rafting journey. Until then, you'll just have to content yourself
with the park's African safari ride, its 1,000 animals, 4 million
plants, 500 acres, six restaurants, Dinoland (which includes a
dinosaur-dominated thrill ride), and four stage shows, including
the ``Festival of the Lion King,'' a musical production that gives
you a taste of just how spectacular the Broadway show must be.
</P>
<P>
   --The Rock 'n' Roller Coaster. Coming to Disney-MGM Studios in
the summer, this wooden coaster will be the first Disney World ride
featuring a high-speed launch and head-over-heels twists and turns,
all to the blare of rock 'n' roll from speakers within the
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   --The All-Star Movies Resort. This will be the third of Disney
World's value-priced resorts ($74-$89), with a decor that revolves
around Disney movies. The first phase of the 1,920-room resort
opens next month.
</P>
<P>
   --More good stuff. Other attractions include two new miniature
golf courses in the spring, and three Magic Kingdom attractions:
the return of the Main Street Electrical Parade this summer; ``Buzz
Lightyear's Space Ranger Spin,'' which is already spinning; and a
ride based on the adventures of that bumbling bear, Winnie the
Pooh, opening this summer. All that you need to see everything is
time and money. But save some of each because you can be sure there
will be even more new attractions in the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   (For guest information, call 407-824-4321 or visit
www.disneyworld.com. For reservations, see a travel agent or call
407-W-DISNEY.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Travel Trivia: Where in the Walt Disney World resort will you
find make-believe snow? (Answer at end of column.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Quotable: ``Welcome, friends, distinguished guests, and those of
you wearing funny animal hats.'' _ Robin Williams, as the voice of
the robot guide in Walt Disney World's ``Timekeeper'' attraction at
the Magic Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a name: The petting zoo at Walt Disney World's new Animal
Kingdom theme park is known as the Affection Section.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of Disney animals: The Animal Kingdom isn't the
first time animals have appeared in a Disney park. When
California's Disneyland opened in 1955, a circus was to be one of
the attractions. But once a herd of llamas got loose and thundered
through the park. Another time, a panther and a tiger broke through
a partition and engaged in a death battle inside their cage during
a parade on Main Street, USA. The circus plan was quietly dropped.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right: From a letter sent to the Orlando tourism people:
``Please send me four Disney World tickets _ I'll send you the
money later.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hit the road, toad: The Magic Kingdom at Walt Disney World has
an attraction coming to Fantasyland next summer called ``The Many
Adventures of Winnie the Pooh,'' and the park promises ``one hunny
of a ride.'' Undoubtedly it will be, but, alas, it replaces
``Mister Toad's Wild Ride.'' Sure, the special effects in ``Toad''
were primitive by today's theme-park standards, but many nostalgic
parkgoers held the attraction so dear to their hearts that an
Internet-based campaign to ``Save the Toad'' drew a response from
thousands of fans. But the ride has closed, and we are among those
who shed a tear for the toad.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Advice to go: A robot at Walt Disney World's
``Extra-TERROR-estial Encounter'' advises: ``Please gather all your
belongings, including smaller carbon-based life forms.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Showtime: ``It's Tough to Be a Bug'' at Walt Disney World's
Animal Kingdom is a thoroughly entertaining, eight-minute 3-D
presentation, with a host of surprising special effects. What's
more, this is one attraction that's fun well before it begins. For
starters, the path to the theater winds beside the 145-foot-high
Tree of Life, which overflows with detailed images of more than 325
animals. And in the theater lobby are colorful posters for such
buggy Broadway productions as ``Beauty and the Bees,'' ``Web Side
Story,'' ``The Grass Menagerie,'' ``Barefoot in the Bark,'' ``My
Fair Ladybug,'' ``Little Shop of Hoppers,'' and ``A Cockroach
Line,'' billed as ``one singular infestation.'' Why, you'll even
hear hits from those musicals being played by an insect orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Did you guess it? You'll find ``snow'' at the Blizzard Beach
water park and, during the holiday season, on a Christmasy street
at Disney-MGM Studios. Also, one of the two aforementioned
miniature golf courses will have a snow theme. Both will open in
spring as part of Disney's Winter Summerland, adjacent to Blizzard
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)nws.globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
