<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8478 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PSYCHO-VINCE-VAUGHN-N     12-08 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PSYCHO-VINCE-VAUGHN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VINCE VAUGHN: SERIAL KILLER? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ contact New York Times Syndicate Sales Representative
Nirdi Relis at (212) 499-3333; fax (212) 499-3382.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     (She also has information on how to subscribe to ``HIGH STYLE
AND MORE,'' a complete lifestyle and entertainment package composed
of stories _ with accompanying B&AMP;W and color art _ from numerous
publications issued by Fairchild Publications.) 
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``e'' entertainment news files.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
 &HT;    TWO COLOR SLIDES of Vince Vaughn are available by mail (or
overnight delivery, using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number)
AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to purchasers of this article. Please specify
that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ---------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 By MOLLY KNIGHT 
 c.1998 Fairchild Publications  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The actor who is gracing GQ's December cover and
reprising the role of Norman Bates in the remake of ``Psycho''
doesn't give fashion much thought. But he does have an unusual
penchant for shopping sprees.
</P>
<P>
   When Vince Vaughn, 28, travels to various film locations, he
goes baggage-free. Upon arrival, he embarks on a daylong shopping
expedition, or he sends his girlfriend, to pull together whatever
it takes to get him through his time on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like carrying bags, so when I get to a place I just
buy clothes there,'' he says. ``Jeans, T-shirts, maybe a suit to go
out in.''
</P>
<P>
   Such are the contradictions in the life of one of Hollywood's
fastest rising stars, an actor who says he doesn't care a wit about
fashion but has twice been nominated for VH1 Fashion Award's ``best
personal style.'' (He lost out to Will Smith in'97 and Chris Rock
in '98.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm flattered that they consider me to have style,'' Vaughn
says. ``But it's just not where my focus is. I don't spend a lot of
time on how I look or what's cutting edge. I just pick out clothes
I like and are comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Designers coddling Vaughn with trunkfuls of clothes, beware.
Still the fashion industry shouldn't take it personally. He feels
the same way about cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cars aren't my thing, fashion's not my thing,'' he said. ``I
couldn't tell one type of car from another, but I could tell you
which one I like. In the same way, I couldn't tell you a Calvin
Klein from an Armani suit, I could just tell you which one I like
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Given his devil-may-care attitude, it's little wonder that he
arrived for his interview wearing an untucked, rumpled, brown
checked buttondown shirt, black jeans and black shoes.
</P>
<P>
   He actually looked fairly bleary-eyed. Sliding into a chair at
the Cupping Room restaurant in New York City's Soho district,
Vaughn was quick to note that his fatigue had nothing to do with a
late night on the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been up all night reading scripts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A native of the Chicago suburb of Lake Forest, but a Los Angeles
resident, at least Vaughn's not pulling all-nighters in strange
hotel rooms. While in New York wrapping up publicity for the
release of ``Psycho,'' he's been staying with his girlfriend,
actress Joey Lauren Adams (``Chasing Amy''), in her new Soho
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   He may have been tired, but Vaughn was prepared for the
inevitable question _ why remake a classic Alfred Hitchcock film?
</P>
<P>
   ``At first it was freaky, but the thing that interested me was
the chance to work with Gus Van Sant (``Good Will Hunting,''
``Drugstore Cowboy'') because I like his films,'' Vaughn said. ``I
didn't think it would be disrespectful to Mr. Hitchcock, or to
Anthony Perkins. Those who were involved in Hitchcock's film,
including the original scriptwriter and Hitchcock's daughter, were
all very supportive and excited about it. They gave their
blessings.''
</P>
<P>
   While ``Pyscho'' is a classic, Vaughn has only seen it twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once as a kid, and when I found out I'd be playing the part,''
he said. ``My thing was not to go and mimic Anthony Perkins. I
don't think that would be respectful to him. Instead, I decided to
approach it as a play, like something powerful you see once on
stage and then take the material and interpret it differently.''
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of attacks from critics about the remake, Vaughn
is armed with his defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to writing, music or film, people tend to think
of them as sacred things,'' he said. ``But the material is written
to be interpreted, and whenever you're afraid to do something like
this, you're missing the opportunity to grow and learn.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing Vaughn's learning these days is how to get accustomed
to his celebrity. Hiding behind the stubble of an unshaven face,
the 6-foot-5-inch actor said it's becoming more difficult to go
unnoticed in public.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get recognized more now than I used to,'' he said. ``I like
to go out and have fun with friends, but when people recognize you,
it gets to be more work than play. It's nice, but draining in
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn had better get used to recognition _ and fast. As soon as
fans see him in the role of film's most infamous killer, avoiding
stargazers won't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   In wasn't until ``Swingers,'' the '96 surprise-hit independent
film, that Vaughn was catapulted from a relatively unknown actor to
a recognizable name in the cast of Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   After playing the part of Trent, a slick but lovable Los Angeles
swinger, Vaughn went on to land roles in a series of films,
including Steven Spielberg's ``The Lost World,'' ``The Locusts,'' a
drama co-starring Ashley Judd, ``Return to Paradise,'' with Anne
Heche, ``A Cool, Dry Place'' and ``Clay Pigeons.''
</P>
<P>
   Although dressing up may not be his thing, Vaughn had a little
fun with clothes in the past _ the same kind of fun a kid might
have dressing up for Halloween. For his role as the serial killer
Lester in the comedy noire ``Clay Pigeons,'' Vaughn picked his
entire wardrobe. An avid fan of country-music star/actor Dwight
Yoakam, Vaughn chose outfits inspired by Yoakam's style, like
Lester's black leather pants and fringed suede shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn has had enough with psychotic killers for the time being
and is moving on to his next projects, two Westerns.
</P>
<P>
   In the first, written and directed by Yoakam, Vaughn will star
with Billy Bob Thornton, Peter Fonda and Paul Reubens.
</P>
<P>
   The second, written by Vaughn's friend and ``Swingers'' writer
John Favreau (``Favz'' as he is known to Vaughn), is about a
Western gunfighter who happens to be an Hasidic Jew.
</P>
<P>
   It's clear from his frequent references to friends and family
that, celebrity status aside, Vaughn's not lost sight of the days
when he played the role of an admiring fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember one time I asked for autographs,'' he said. ``I
was a kid, and I asked two Chicago Bears players, Doug Plank and
Walter Payton. But after I got them I wondered, what the hell am I
gonna do with these?'' &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; c.1998 Fairchild Publications &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-98 1333EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981208.0084 </DOCNO>
