<HEADLINE>
WYMAN-GORDON FINDS ITSELF IN A STOCK TAILSPIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was one of those nose dives, fast and steep, that might make
oxygen masks fall from a jet cabin's ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   But it was shares of Wyman-Gordon Co. that fell hard last week,
plunging by about a third within days. Problems at Boeing Co., a
big customer and leading indicator for the aircraft industry, sent
Wyman-Gordon into a stock tailspin, from 16 on Nov. 27 to 10 13/16
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   It's no longer surprising when a small or midsize stock falls
out of favor and gets chopped by 30 percent or 40 percent in a day.
But that kind of punishment is usually reserved for the high
fliers, not an industrial company that makes its money forging
metal into high-precision parts.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders haven't had much to cheer about since Wyman-Gordon
was named the Globe 100's company of the year in May, based on a
strong gain in 1997 sales and profits. The stock is down about 47
percent since then, slumping with the rest of the market over the
summer, rallying in the fall, and giving the gains back last week.
The stock hit a three-year low of 10 1/2 last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts think the reaction to the latest Boeing news _
48,000 layoffs by the end of &UR;  &LR; 2000 and lower aircraft production
plans _ punished the stocks of many suppliers too severely. The
percentage decline of Wyman-Gordon shares was nearly twice that of
Boeing itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the news certainly is not positive, this is a cyclical
business and many (related) businesses were factoring in the cycle
peaking in 1999,'' said analyst David Pizzimenti of Schroder &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, the world's largest aircraft maker, said it was on
schedule to produce 550 aircraft this year and expected to build
620 more next year. But production now is expected to fall to 490
in 2000. Analysts had already forecast a production decline in
2000, but the new target was slightly lower than expected.
</P>
<P>
   More than 80 cents of every Wyman-Gordon sales dollar comes from
the aerospace business, and Boeing is a huge customer. Wyman-Gordon
forges landing gear and other airframe components for Boeing's 727,
747, 757, 767, and 777 aircraft. Even more of its precision parts
find their way into Boeing jets, through engines made by General
Electric Co., Pratt &AMP; Whitney, Rolls-Royce, and CFM International.
</P>
<P>
   One plus hidden in the weaker aircraft production schedule:
replacement-part demand for jet engines already in service.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the people are overlooking is that it's not just about
how many aircraft are being built,'' said analyst Thomas Lewis of
C.L. King &AMP; Associates. ``It's about how many are being flown. . .
. The number of aircraft that take off and land each day keeps
going up.''
</P>
<P>
   No one expects Boeing's bad news to filter into Wyman-Gordon's
results in the near future. The company said it was in general
agreement with analysts' earnings forecasts of about 40 cents per
share for the company's fiscal second quarter, to be reported Dec.
17. Ditto predictions for earnings covering the full fiscal year,
which are in the range of $1.60 per share.
</P>
<P>
   That means Wyman-Gordon shares are trading very cheaply, at
slightly less than seven times expected earnings for the current
year. So why are investors so skittish?
</P>
<P>
   They flinch at any sign of decline in the cyclical aerospace
business because the last one was so severe. The long and tough
slide, coupled with cuts in defense work through the first half of
the 1990s, was torture for smaller companies.
</P>
<P>
   Wyman-Gordon shares lost about two-thirds of their value over
1990 and 1991, and remained stuck there for another three years.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts believe the news is not nearly so dark this time for
the North Grafton, Mass. company. For one thing, they believe the
coming decline will not be as severe as the one suffered at the
start of the decade. For suppliers like Wyman-Gordon, circumstances
are a lot different.
</P>
<P>
   Wyman-Gordon bought out its leading competitor in 1994, and has
made other arrangements that would ease the effects of a downturn,
like its joint venture this year combining titanium casting
businesses with Titanium Metals Corp. Analysts also point to more
strategic relationships between suppliers like Wyman-Gordon and
their biggest customers, avoiding cycles in which each took turns
gouging each other.
</P>
<P>
   Wyman-Gordon continues to talk about diversification and its
interest in making acquisitions to help broaden business. But
aerospace has become a bigger part of the company's sales in each
of the last three years, expanding to 81 percent from 73 percent.
Sales to the second-leading industry, energy, have increased nearly
25 percent in the last three years, but make up a slightly smaller
slice of the total sales pie.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
