<SLUG> BC-LEVINGSTON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COMMITMENT TO HIS MARLBOROS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN LEVINGSTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Why's everyone giving the tobacco companies such a hard time?
I, for one, am squarely behind my Marlboros. Since I fired up my
first cig back around age 12, I've never been separated from my
Marlboros for longer than 15 to 20 minutes _ except while sleeping,
of course. Philip Morris has done nothing but right by me. It makes
a fine product, a good puff, and I'll defend the company till the
day I die _ probably earlier than most.
</P>
<P>
   And I've got my work cut out for me. That settlement the tobacco
companies signed recently with 46 states is the biggest test yet of
my commitment to my Marlboros. Under the agreement, the companies
will have to cough up $206 billion over 25 years. That money isn't
going to come from nowhere. Tobacco firms have never meant me any
harm. And so I feel obligated to do my part in return for the many
years of pleasure they have given me. In other words, I gotta get
puffing.
</P>
<P>
   I don't make a lot of money. In fact, I barely get by. I work at
one of the hospitals here cleaning up the place. If you had to see
what I see, you'd smoke, too. Especially if you got a glimpse of
the lung cancer patients. All the experts say it's lower-income
people like me who will carry the load for the tobacco companies.
All our heavy puffing is financing the payout. I accept it as an
honor.
</P>
<P>
   Right after the settlement was signed, the tobacco companies
announced they were jacking up prices. I'll pay. Whatever it takes,
sign me up. I'm working out a plan on how I can keep puffing for
Philip Morris _ no matter what the cost. I have a clunker of a car
that's worth a few hundred bucks. I'm ready to unload it when a
pack of Marlboro gets up around that level. My old man, who also
trusted in his Marlboros, left me his little house when he died,
prematurely. It's gotta be worth several thousand bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Just in case I run out of things to sell, I got me a little gun.
I have no qualms about robbing, even murdering, for the cause.
Let's not forget, all those honest lawyers who drew up the
settlement also have to get paid. They worked hard to get the
government off the backs of the tobacco companies. Now all they
want is their fair nickel or two: altogether, they'll divide $1.25
billion right off the bat then get about $500 million a year. That
works out to about $40 million for each lawyer. I really gotta get
puffing.
</P>
<P>
   My mind's at ease knowing I couldn't devote myself to a finer
company than Philip Morris. Why, just yesterday I opened a magazine
and saw the most inspiring ad. On one page was a big photo of a
rugged-looking man displaying a box of succulent peaches. He's a
volunteer at the Houston Food Bank. On the opposite page, in big
lettering, are the words: ``I help hungry people get fresh and
wholesome food. And that just feels good.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad explains that Kraft Foods and its parent Philip Morris
support the food bank. ``It's just a part of our commitment of
giving to people in need,'' Philip Morris says in the ad.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure when the time comes Philip Morris will set up a
cigarette bank for poor, good folks like me who may not be able to
afford their Marlboros anymore.
</P>
<P>
   I'm glad this settlement came along. It finally proved something
once and for all. Now I know beyond a doubt that I am committed to
my Marlboros, or dare I say addicted?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Levingston's e-mail address is leving(at)bu.edu)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
