<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHICH WAY FOR SOCIAL SECURITY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For all the numbing complexity of the issue, on the table as the
White House pursues an evaluation of Social Security, are two new
proposals and one old one.
</P>
<P>
   The first new proposal is associated mainly with conservatives.
It is to abolish Social Security as we know it now _ a safety net
for the elderly involving large transfers from the well-to-do to
the poor _ and replace it with a system of mandatory individual
investment accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The second new idea is asssociated with some liberals. It is to
beef up Social Security's funding and invest a large portion of its
burgeoning reserves in the stock market. A new semi-independent
agency would be created to oversee the government's big new stake
in Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   The familiar old proposal is to do again what a small bipartisan
panel of politicians and bankers led by Alan Greenspan did in 1982:
keep the present system and adopt some combination of modest
benefit cuts and slightly higher taxes to preserve its balance over
time.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of clarity emerges from a new study by a panel of
experts that quietly appeared last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evaluating Issues in Privatizing Social Security'' was issued
by the National Academy of Social Insurance. A panel of 20 experts,
led by Peter Diamond of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology
and Michael Boskin of Stanford University, worked for 30 months to
achieve a relatively high degree of consensus about the underlying
economics of various plans while permitting participants to differ
about political value judgments. A three-quarters majority was
required for the panel to make any particular recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the report was marred by the late-stage resignations of
four members, including co-chairman Boskin, who had served as chief
economist to President George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the NASI report still stands well above any others as a
dispassionate analysis of the basic issues. Even when it stacks its
own deck, as it does in one critical respect, the report
illuminates more than it obscures. (The full text can be found on
the Internet at www.nasi.org/evaliss/front.htm.)
</P>
<P>
   The report identified three broad questions at the heart of the
matter:
</P>
<P>
   1. Should there be more advanced funding of Social Security? The
panel recommended yes _ to strengthen national savings and foster
growth. That would mean some combination of benefit cuts and tax
increases, sooner rather than later, to minimize the adjustments
necessary to achieve the desired effect.
</P>
<P>
   2. Should Social Security funds be invested in the stock market,
either by the government or individuals? The panel found that the
financial risks of investing in stocks would be worth the rewards,
but differed sharply on how to go about it.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, the panel estimated that a low-cost, low-service
plan for individual accounts overseen by either by Wall Street
firms or a government agency would cost $25 to $50 per participant,
as opposed to the $16 per-person cost under the Social Security
Administration. On the other, the panel suggested that if the
government itself took the plunge, a semiindependent agency modeled
on the existing 401(k) plan for government employees could limit
political interference in investment decisions and corporate
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   3. Should the system remain a single collective plan that
guarantees everybody a certain level of support (a defined benefit
plan)? Or should it create individual accounts and require only
defined contributions, expecting that some would do better than
others in managing their funds? The panel divided sharply on the
question.
</P>
<P>
   The single most controversial aspect of the report _ the respect
in which it stacks the deck from which it deals, by giving short
shrift to the alternative _ is the unqualified recommendation that
the government foster investment in stocks instead of bonds. Never
mind that a good deal of work exists now to show that the lavish
rates of return to stocks promised by various advocates of
privatization are illusory.
</P>
<P>
   With the global stock markets fluttering near record highs,
after an almost uninterrupted 16-year bull market, the experts
propose to bet the integrity of the national pension system _ of
the political stewardship of the economy itself _ on the likelihood
that the world has seen its last sustained bear market.
</P>
<P>
   Does that sound prudent to you?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
