A8500 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      12-08 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH JOHNSON GONE, MOORE IS MR. RELEVANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Marty Moore, a k a Mr. Irrelevant, is
becoming The Man On The Way Up.
</P>
<P>
   He is the hot topic of conversation, as much as Scott Zolak was
when it was speculated he might start in place of Drew Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   After Ted Johnson had his arm ripped up by Jerome Bettis on the
second play of the Patriots' 23-9 win over the Steelers Sunday, the
middle linebacker ran off the field, spotted Moore on the sideline
chatting with special teams coach Dante Scarnecchia, and shouted,
``Marty!''
</P>
<P>
   In a burst, Moore was out on the field just as the Steelers were
breaking the huddle. He called the play and was ready to go.
</P>
<P>
   He flowed into that play, called the defensive signals for the
remainder of the drive, then trotted off the field to find he was
in there for good because Johnson had torn his right biceps tendon
and is out for the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Ted was just nicked up or something and he'd be
right back in there,'' said Moore, ``but then I was told he was
out. So I took a deep breath . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   As did most of Patriots Nation.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was Moore now in the regular defense, but he was doing
that in addition to his special-teams assignments.
</P>
<P>
   He needed the breath because he knew he wouldn't have many more
to take. Playing all out on special teams is one of the most
exhausting jobs on the football field. Add middle linebacker
responsibilities to that and what you have is one tired hombre.
</P>
<P>
   Next Sunday against the St. Louis Rams, Moore will get some
help. Todd Collins is expected to shift to the middle and play a
lot there. Tedy Bruschi will also get in, but Moore will get his
share of time, and that should not be alarming to the masses.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, now in his fifth year, has defied the odds since he was
the 222d _ and last _ player taken in the 1994 NFL draft after his
career at the University of Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Most players taken last don't stay in the league for five years,
but Moore carved out a niche for himself as a special-teams cover
player the Patriots couldn't live without.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has seen me play linebacker,'' said Moore when asked
about the fans' uneasiness over this development. ``I do it in
preseason, but that doesn't really count. I know people are
wondering, `Can Marty Moore play in the regular season?' That's
where self-motivation comes in, and showing everyone I can play
every-down linebacker.''
</P>
<P>
   Self-motivation is what Moore's career is about. Down-to-earth
and humble, he is the kid who always sits up front in class and
listens to every word the teacher says. He does that to prepare for
times like this. He's done that ever since the Mr. Irrelevant
designation _ which goes to the last draft pick each year _ became
a point of interest around the country. There is even an annual
event to salute the pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember people telling me after that event in California
that guys who are picked last never make it in the NFL,'' said
Moore. ``That started to give me the motivation to prove people
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mr. Irrelevant thing doesn't bother me because I think
it's a good accomplishment on my part. When you look arund the
league, there aren't too many guys around drafted last. For me to
say I've been here for five years and done things that last picks
have never done . . . for me, that's an accomplishment I'm proud
of.''
</P>
<P>
   It hurts to see his friend Johnson out for the season, but he
said, ``It's something I've been preparing myself for. I haven't
had the opportunity to play the last three years because Ted has
stayed healthy and played so well, but this is my job. I have to do
the job when I'm called upon.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins, who missed three weeks with a groin pull, will have to
play the inside position. Back when Bill Parcells used the 3-4
defense, Collins was an inside linebacker, but when the alignment
was changed to a 4-3, he became an outside man to take advantage of
his speed, which always has been his major attribute.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Carroll said Collins may be starting, though all three
linebackers will be used in a rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone through a lot of adversity on this team, but guys
keep stepping up and doing the job,'' said Collins. ``I don't think
we've had our team together all year. The years I've played with
Ted, you know how good he is. But you want to use positive energy
and say, `Boy, if we can overcome this one, it makes your team
stronger.' You can't use injuries as an excuse. You rely on
everyone on your roster. They have to be ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins isn't awed by the assignment. He knows he won't be in
the middle the entire game. He knows he'll be more involved in
nickel situations than he has been all season, but he says it's
just a matter of ``doing a little more studying.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not surprising something like that would happen to Ted,''
said Collins. ``It's been that kind of a year when everyone is
vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was the chief signal-caller on defense, but Collins has
performed that duty over the years as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ted and I both make the calls from the sidelines,'' he said.
``It's not going to be different other than moving over a couple of
feet. We'll be fine. I'll be giving Marty a breather every now and
then. Tedy will be in there. I just hope I can give Tedy more of a
breather. When I was out, he was out there for 75 plays a game. We
just have to bond together. This could be a trap game for us if we
let it. But I think everyone knows what's at stake, and we all want
to rise to the occasion. We don't want to make any excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be irrelevant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
