<HEADLINE>
CARROLL SUDDENLY OFF THE HOT SEAT _ FOR NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Winners and losers. Men on the way up and
men on the way down. One day you're on the Butch Hobson Highway to
Oblivion, then suddenly, you own a home in Pigskin Pleasantville.
</P>
<P>
   It is the way of professional sports, and Patriots coach Pete
Carroll has lived on both sides of the line in the last three
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Kraft won't admit it, but Carroll no doubt was on the firing
line after the Patriots fell to 5-5 with the loss at Buffalo last
month. The owner expects this team to go deep into the playoffs,
and there was no postseason on the horizon after the Rich Stadium
debacle.
</P>
<P>
   But the Patriots have been born again in the last three weeks,
and no one has made a bigger comeback than Carroll. This might be
local sports' greatest rescue since the 1988 Red Sox ripped off 19
of 20 to solidify the standing of ``interim'' manager Joe Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, Drew Bledsoe saved his coach's job with the
back-to-back miracle finishes against the Dolphins and Bills. Kraft
wouldn't have pulled the plug during the season, but there can be
little doubt that Pompon Pete was gone if this team finished .500
and out of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Now it looks like Carroll has qualified for a third year of that
five-year contract. Barring an 0-3 finish, the Patriots are a lock
for the playoffs, and that should be enough to prevent Kraft
(believed to be the man who invented the T formation) from
admitting a mistake and finding another coach.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll was relaxed at his day-after press gathering Monday.
There were no hard questions about his future or the Tuna. No
attack-dog journalists pinned him up against the wall. Even the
weather cooperated. The record-setting 79-degree December day no
doubt was delivered by the Grid God to make California Pete feel at
home.
</P>
<P>
   He talked about Marty Moore, Chad Eaton, and Terry Glenn. He
talked about Ted Johnson's biceps and Bledsoe's finger. He was calm
and composed. He was the embodiment of Coach Light.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going for it,'' he said. ``I like the intensity this
team shows. I like the confidence we're showing now. I feel
strongly about our chances to build momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this team understanding the way I approach them? I think
they are. They're responsible enough to hang in there when things
are tough. That's not to give away the power of being the leader,
but I think it empowers them.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the Carroll way. He will not smack his players upside the
head. He thinks of himself as one of the guys and hopes his players
are mature enough to ``get it done'' without being bullied. When
the Patriots play well and win, his system is applauded and all is
well in Foxborough. When the Patriots get skunked by the Jets,
Dolphins, and Falcons, Pete is too soft.
</P>
<P>
   There is still much about which to be concerned. The Patriots
have no running game. And they are still making too many September
mistakes _ illegal motion, delay of game, cheesy holding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had five penalties in seven or eight plays,'' said the
coach. ``We were going in the tank for a while. It was an
opportunity for us to fall apart. We had some noise problems. The
offensive linemen have to hold their position. We can't allow it.''
</P>
<P>
   If sloppy mistakes foil this team, the coach will be held
accountable. And let us not even contemplate the horror if the
Patriots go to New Jersey two days after Christmas needing a win
against the (gulp) Jets to make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been saying this for a while,'' Carroll said. ``We're
gonna get better. We can be stronger than we were at the finish of
last season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have the talent. They are supposed to win most of
their games. They are supposed to beat the Bills, Dolphins, and
Jets on the strength of their roster. When they lose to these
teams, we look at the coach. When they win, we cite their superior
talent. This puts Carroll in a no-win position.
</P>
<P>
   But he has won the last three. And the fire has been
extinguished. He's secure. For at least another week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
