<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AXELSSON EARNS CHECK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ P.J. Axelsson can't wait to get to the rink these days.
That's how well the Bruins are doing, as reflected in their 7-1-4
record the last 12 games. Everything is fun again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing pretty good right now,'' said the Bruins'
third-line left wing, who has Rob DiMaio and Tim Taylor skating
with him for the second consecutive season. ``We're playing
together and we're staying with the game plan. We're making the
right decisions. Now we always want to play games, of course. It's
the same as last year, where we always want to keep going.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps, of course, that Byron (Dafoe) is doing so well back
in goal for us. He's been awesome, just as he was last season, too.
He wins plenty of games back there for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Axelsson's game is about checking. That's his specialty despite
his build _ 174 pounds on a 6-foot-1-inch frame, about 4 or 5
pounds more than he weighed last season. He plays against the other
team's top scoring and makes them work for their goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the offseason, when I go back home to Gothenborg,
Sweden, I lift weights about four times a week, as well as doing a
lot of running and biking,'' said Axelsson. ``Frankly, I need all
the weight I can put on my body, especially when I get in the
corner. I like that part of the game, the hitting. I'm not a big
guy, but I do like to hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to do the same stuff as last season, and
that's best done by keeping everything simple. That's the fun part
of the game for me, checking. That's my job.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a price to pay for that role. Axelsson suffered two
concussions in a week earlier this season. The first was against
Montreal when Dave Manson elbowed him in the head. A week later,
Buffalo's Matthew Barnaby was the aggressor.
</P>
<P>
   Axelsson, who played his 100th NHL game against Montreal Nov.
27, missed a total of four games because of the concussions, ending
his streak of 97 consecutive regular-season and playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   His parents first put skates on P.J. when he was 3 years old.
``I live about 200 yards from the rink,'' said Axelsson, who lifts
weights twice a week during the season to maintain his
conditioning. ``I also played soccer, but hockey was always my
favorite sport. The fact that it's such a fast game is what turned
me on about it most.''
</P>
<P>
   There might even be a Frank J. Selke Trophy as the NHL's best
defensive forward in Axelsson's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about that,'' he said. ``I'm just trying to go
out and play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
