<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8512 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COMMENT-BOS &LR;      12-08 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE RULING ON OFFICIATING: OUT OF BOUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Enough with the officials already.
</P>
<P>
   As with everything else in American sport today, the mounting
complaints about NFL officiating have gone from fair criticism to
absurd blather. They have gone from making good points to beating a
dead horse. It all has gotten absurd, as about everything in sports
seems to become after a week or two of the media overdosing on the
topic of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The Thanksgiving Day Lions-Steelers coin flip mistake that
started it all was roundly and rightly mocked, and the erroneous
calls at the end of the Patriots' victory over the Buffalo Bills
Nov. 29 were duly noted and dissected.
</P>
<P>
   Now we have the touchdown mistakenly given to the Jets' Vinny
Testaverde Sunday that lifted New York to a 32-31 victory over the
Seattle Seahawks. The level of noise surrounding this issue has
become as grating to the ear as a Metallica concert in barely 24
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Two readers wrote to the Globe about this issue last week and
made good points. One quite rightly claimed that making NFL
officials full-time would not solve the problem of inconsistency or
pure folly on the part of the men in charge of NFL law enforcement,
as major league baseball's umpires and the NBA's referees regularly
have proven.
</P>
<P>
   The other letter raised an even more salient point.
</P>
<P>
   ``President William Jefferson Clinton lied under oath before a
grand jury and everyone thought it was OK and no big deal,'' the
reader wrote. ``An NFL official makes a couple of mistakes during a
football game and everyone is terribly upset. Am I missing
something?''
</P>
<P>
   Aren't we all?
</P>
<P>
   It is fine and well to criticize NFL officials when they're
wrong, which we welcome the opportunity to do every time it
happens. But Sunday in Pittsburgh, for example, a ball was ruled
trapped that made nearly every ``expert observer'' in the press box
groan. All had clearly seen a catch made and said so.
</P>
<P>
   Then the replay came up, and it was just as obvious that the
receiver had indeed lost control of the ball, pinning it against
the ground, which happens to be illegal. No one made note of that
in the next morning's papers because the call was right, not wrong.
</P>
<P>
   What had happened there was the same thing that happened at
Giants Stadium Sunday when Testaverde was awarded a touchdown he
was a half-yard short of reaching. The official who made the call
never saw the ball. He saw only Testaverde's helmet break the plane
of the goal line and assumed it was a score.
</P>
<P>
   He had a bad angle, just as the men and women in the press box
in Pittsburgh had a bad one on that trapped ball. So get over it.
</P>
<P>
   Although instant replay is an important tool capable of
reversing some officiating errors the NFL unwisely is choosing to
ignore, it will not solve all the problems and correct all the
mistakes. Nor should it.
</P>
<P>
   Sports were meant to be played by human beings and officiated by
them. That, by its very nature, implies mistakes will happen. Some
of them, like Bill Buckner's error or Johnny Pesky's alleged
double-clutch throw, become part of the lore of the games we love.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally _ as with the phantom roughing-the-passer call on
Ray Hamilton years ago in a Patriot playoff loss to the Raiders _
an official's call becomes part of the lore, too.
</P>
<P>
   That is as it should be, unless we want the games to be played
by robots and the outcomes to be written in stone before they're
played. Mistakes are part of sport, so they are part of officiating
as well. When the call is bad enough, we have every right to talk
about it and argue over its importance. That's part of the fun of
being a fan.
</P>
<P>
   But the topic of NFL officiating costing teams games and
championships has grown absurd. On Sunday, the Seahawks gave up 32
points to the Jets and blew a 15-point lead. Had they stopped the
Jets from scoring on any one of their other drives, Testaverde
could have run that quarterback sneak to Connecticut and it
wouldn't have mattered.
</P>
<P>
   So the officials didn't lose that game. The Seahawks did.
</P>
<P>
   Same with the Bills. Was the interference call that gave New
England the ball at the 1 pivotal? Absolutely. Did it mean a Bills
linebacker then had to bite on a terrible play-action fake by Drew
Bledsoe and leave Ben Coates wide open in the rear of the end zone
for the winning score with no time on the clock?
</P>
<P>
   I think not.
</P>
<P>
   What seems to be happening is that mistakes and inconsistencies
by NFL officials have become the life raft for players who haven't
played well enough to win. That is not to say such errors should be
tolerated or that all the technology possible for correcting them
shouldn't be adopted.
</P>
<P>
   It's just that I'm tired of hearing that a football game of 130
or 140 plays turns on one errant flag or missed call at the wrong
moment. The fact is, games are won and lost by players more than by
any other factor. More than coaches who one week are called
geniuses and the next week called idiots, and far more than
officials, even the ones who stink.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
