<P>
   MISS-MURDERS (Columbus, Miss.) _ Peggy Cantelou, a grandmother
of seven whose Southern accent is as soft and sweet as divinity
candy, carries a baseball bat with her when she steps out to get
the morning newspaper. Since the killings of three older people in
this drowsy Mississippi city in just seven weeks, she seldom goes
anywhere alone. Like other older people in Columbus, a city of
23,000 people just across the Alabama border, she has learned much
about home security systems, neighborhood watches, and looking over
her shoulder. In a city where it was once considered polite to
speak to strangers, a simple ``hello'' can draw a quick, hard
stare. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
