NATO as its foreign ministers meet. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   CHECHNYA-KIDNAP (Moscow) _ The severed heads of three Britons
and a New Zealander are found, victims of one of the biggest
businesses in Chechnya: kidnapping. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   UNICEF-LITERACY (United Nations) _ A Unicef report says nearly 1
billion of the world's 6 billion people are illiterate and more
than 130 million children have no access to school of any kind. By
Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ The World Briefing column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-IBM (Undated) _ AT&AMP;T buys International Business Machines'
global communications network for $5 billion in cash, marking its
latest effort to extend its reach to big business customers. In
addition, AT&AMP;T will provide a ``significant portion'' of IBM's
voice and data services, while AT&AMP;T will use IBM to provide some
data processing and data management, the companies say. AT&AMP;T says
it could receive $2.5 billion in additional revenue during the
accord's first full year. The I.B.M. network provides services to
several hundred large global companies, tens of thousands of
smaller businesses and more than 1 million individual Internet
users in 59 countries. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   GE-APPOINT (Undated) _ Gary C. Wendt, who built GE Capital into
one of the world's most powerful financial-services companies, will
step down at year's end and will be succeeded by Dennis D.
Dammerman, a senior vice president, finance, and chief financial
officer at the parent company, General Electric. By Reed Abelson.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:45 p.m., the industrial average was
down 8 points, the Nasdaq index was up 12 points. Elsewhere, prices
rose 0.6 percent in Tokyo and fell 0.8 percent in Hong Kong. They
declined 0.8 percent in Frankfurt, rose half a percent in London,
fell 1.5 percent in Brazil and rose 0.7 percent in Mexico. On the
American debt market, the long bond was up 9/32 point at midday,
with the yield at 5.02 percent.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ The focus of the Microsoft
trial turns today to the question of whether a browser and an
operating system are separate products. The Government will call an
industry pioneer, David Farber, a telecommunications professor at
the University of Pennsylvania. He is expected to testify that a
browser is a freestanding application and not a necessary part of
Windows; the Justice Department asserts that Microsoft integrated
its browser into its operating system to gain a competitive
advantage against Netscape. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The business travel column.
</P>
<P>
   GULF-OIL-CUTS (Undated) _ Oil ministers of the six-nation Gulf
Cooperation Council agree to reduce production, starting in March.
Their decision follows a call by Saudi Arabian Crown Prince
Abdullah that they should not shrink from taking further measures
to shore up oil prices. By Agis Salpukas.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
