<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVING KIDS GIFT OF LASTING VALUE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA YIP 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the season of temptations _ too much food, too much
drink, and if you're a child, everything you've ever wanted for
Christmas is in your face.
</P>
<P>
   Odd as it may seem, financial education experts say this is an
opportunity to teach your kids about sound money management by
demonstrating discipline in this time of excess.
</P>
<P>
   They are not suggesting a miserly Christmas, just a time when
you teach your children to spend within their means by establishing
a holiday budget to help them decide what they afford for
themselves and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can show them about planning and making a list,'' said
Paul Richard, director of education at the National Center for
Financial Education in San Diego, a nonprofit education
organization that teaches consumers personal finance skills. ``If
they run out of money, have them create `service cards' and have
them earn the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Financial illiteracy is a big problem today. Look at the record
numbers of personal bankruptcies by people who think that credit
cards, like Santa Claus, have endless financial resources.
</P>
<P>
   This dangerous lack of knowledge explains why a group of
education and financial leaders throughout Texas are trying to
start a statewide group of the Jump$tart Coalition for Personal
Financial Literacy. The nonprofit group, based in Washington, D.C.,
is trying to raise personal finance knowledge among students so
that they will be financially competent when they graduate from
high school.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
REALITIES VS. ADS
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At a time when television is bombarding them with holiday
advertisements, some cost comparisons help kids realize that they
can't have everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a family, you may set joint priorities _ for instance,
buying a real tree or taking in a performance of `The
Nutcracker,''' said Sharon McLean, executive director of operations
at Consumer Credit Counseling Service of the Gulf Coast Area in
Houston, which helps consumers with credit problems. ``Demonstrate
how you have to cut the budget in other places to allow for these
special events.''
</P>
<P>
   Look for ways to let your children know how much it costs to
celebrate Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Point out all of the expenses associated with the season, from
decorations to entertaining to presents,'' McLean said.
</P>
<P>
   For good measure, take your children shopping with you and use
the trip as a lesson on comparing prices and quality. If they spot
something that's more expensive than you can afford, remind them of
the spending limit you had set, and how important it is to stick to
it.
</P>
<P>
   When they hit financial limits, rather than giving them the
money, show them how to economize.
</P>
<P>
   Suggest that your children make gifts instead of buying them.
This will help you teach them the true spirit of Christmas, which
isn't about seeing how many presents you can get or give, but about
enjoying family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christmas time is a time to remember people for the nice
things they did for you, not a time to be showered with gifts,''
Richard said.
</P>
<P>
   When you do give gifts, don't go overboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Start family traditions and focus on really enjoying the
holidays together, rather than spending your time at the mall
trying to hunt down an impossible-to-find toy,'' McLean said.
</P>
<P>
   With so much temptation for greed and excess during the
holidays, this would be a good time to teach your children what the
spirit of giving is really all about by giving back to the
community through volunteer service or by donating goods or money
to a charity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to do so is to appeal to children's passions,''
McLean said. ``If your child is fond of animals, consider donating
to an animal shelter or zoo. Choosing charities your children can
connect to emotionally will help sow the seeds for a lifetime of
giving.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PARENTS MUST SET EXAMPLE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Parents need to be in the forefront of their children's
financial education because home is where young people say they
learn the most about managing money.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Mom and Dad aren't savers, don't expect the kids to save,''
Richard said.
</P>
<P>
   If your children get money as holiday gifts, have them use some
of the money to set up a savings or investment account, rather than
spending it all at once. That way, their money will last longer for
them and even grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personal finance has evolved into a very complex life skill
that if we are not educating our children in, by the time they
graduate from high school, they are going to make mistakes,'' said
Dara Duguay, Jump$tart executive director.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pamela Yip can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to pamela.yip(at)chron.com, or call
(713) 220-2000 and enter access code 1003. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
