<SLUG> BC-SF-BLACKOUT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSIVE BLACKOUT HITS SAN FRANCISCO AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LARRY D. HATFIELD  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A massive power failure brought San Francisco to
a standstill at the height of the morning rush hour Tuesday,
freezing traffic, stranding commuters in dark tunnels, and
otherwise creating havoc.
</P>
<P>
   The blackout, which also affected other parts of the San
Francisco Bay area when a Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric power plant in San
Mateo shut down, began at 8:17 a.m. and still had much of the
region blacked out hours later.
</P>
<P>
   A PG&AMP;E spokesman said more than 372,000 customers were without
service during the height of the outage.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E spokesman Corey Warren said power was being restored
station by station, with manual switching required to restore
electricity city block by city block.
</P>
<P>
   According to PG&AMP;E spokeswoman Mary Rodrigues, the center of the
problem was a PG&AMP;E substation in San Mateo. The substation takes
high-voltage power from transmission lines and lowers it to a
voltage that can be used by consumers. She said an unexplained
problem still under investigation caused the substation to shut
down. At that point, automatic switches were triggered to isolate
the area supplied with electricity by the substation.
</P>
<P>
   Without the switches, all of Northern California could have lost
power. Power authorities said it would take up to five hours to
repair the substation.
</P>
<P>
   An unknown number of people were evacuated from subway tunnels.
</P>
<P>
   At San Francisco International Airport, flight operations
continued using separate power but some flights were diverted to
Oakland and San Jose to reduce traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency power lighted the airport terminals but computers were
not working, making it impossible to check in passengers, airport
spokesman Ron Wilson said. Airport personnel used bullhorns to
alert travelers to flight delays.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic lights at intersections throughout the city were off and
some electric buses were stuck in the intersections, blocking
traffic. The police and parking control officers directed traffic
at others.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Willie Brown urged people to remain calm. His spokesman,
Ron Vinson, urged people to go home.
</P>
<P>
   The police reported no looting or other problems.
</P>
<P>
   At the Macy's department store on fashionable Union Square,
security guard Dennis Avant said he used a crowbar to rescue people
from elevators on the first and seventh floors. People were still
stuck at mid-morning on some floors, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific Stock Exchange stopped trading as computers failed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-98 1406EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
