<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-ETIQUETTE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARK: IT'S BUSINESS AS USUAL AT YULETIDE OFFICE PARTIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATE GURNETT  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the holidays you might prefer a free turkey, a gift
certificate or, if you're especially lucky, a bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, your boss is throwing an office party. And charging
admission.
</P>
<P>
   As precious shopping time ticks away, you'll be stuck in a dark
ballroom, balancing hard cubes of cheese and rubbery broccoli on a
napkin, making dull chitchat. It's like work.
</P>
<P>
   It is work, business etiquette experts say. And for those who
value their job, attendance is mandatory. ``It's not really
optional,'' said Barbara Pachter of Cherry Hill, N.J., co-author of
``The Prentiss Hall Complete Business Etiquette Handbook.''
</P>
<P>
   So if you can't escape, you can get through. Experts offer tips
to guide you through the potential hell of the holiday fete. You
may not like them, but they are good etiquette!
</P>
<P>
   First, don't relax. As we said before, this ain't no party. Not
really. Your role here is to network.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not there to talk to people you know,'' said Ann Marie
Sabath of At Ease Inc. in Cincinnati. ``The way you act is going to
affect your next promotion. If you mix and mingle, they might
connect you with larger clients who mix and mingle. It's as
important as how you act at that second or third job interview.''
</P>
<P>
   What, no noisemakers? No flirting? No fun? Not these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's known as economic insecurity,'' said M. Thomas Inge, a
humanities professor at Randolph-Macon College in Ashland, Va.
``Everybody's scared to death they're going to lose their job. And
jobs are hard to get in all this economic downsizing. You can be
the best salesman, and tomorrow, through no fault of your own, you
could be out of a job.''
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, the office party was known to be a rather wild
affair, Inge said. ``People did certain things they'd be
embarrassed about the next day, but there was a certain allowance
given. It was like the old-fashioned Mardi Gras _ the beggar was
king for a day. No matter what your status in life, it was a nice
relief from the pressure to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Those were the days when ``the guy who had his eye on the
secretary all year finally went up to her, with a couple of drinks
under his belt, and said what he felt,'' Inge noted.
</P>
<P>
   Today that spells sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just in insecure times. Look what's going on in the
White House. This has frightened everybody,'' he added. ``You can't
just let your hair down _ or your pants as well.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If there are cocktails at the office party, ignore them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a business/social event, and business rules apply. You
may be out of the office, but your behavior will come back to haunt
you,'' Pachter said.
</P>
<P>
   So how do you do it _ and stay sober? Talking to strangers is
often the last thing on most people's Christmas list. The dread
will disappear once you learn how to socialize, said Pachter, who
teaches interactive skills.
</P>
<P>
   See it as a challenge, she said. Meet three people you didn't
know before. And greet people like old friends _ with a warm smile
and handshake. Speaking of handshakes, guys, grasp the woman's hand
firmly. The days of the three-fingered wimpy pinch are over. To
make conversation, experts say, ask lots of questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where are you from?'' is a good start. ``How about that
game?'' is another. ``Read news magazines,'' Pachter said. ``There
are appropriate topics _ not sex, religion, politics. Don't even go
there. Talk entertainment, the weather, what people are doing over
the holidays.''
</P>
<P>
   It won't hurt to toss out a few compliments. ``Gee, you really
know your stuff.'' Or something as simple as ``You look nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Folks remember compliments fondly. Snideness and sarcasm prompt
fantasies of revenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``People perceive you as interesting if you are sincerely
interested in them,'' said Sabath, author of ``Business Etiquette:
101 Ways to Conduct Business with Charm and Savvy.'' The true bore
is someone who talks too much, not too little.
</P>
<P>
   If you're trapped by a dullard who drones on endlessly, pull out
your previously practiced exit lines. Such as: ``Excuse me, I've
got to get some broccoli.'' Or: ``It's been a pleasure talking to
you.'' Or: ``Well, I'll see you at work!''
</P>
<P>
   And if talk turns troublesome? Ignore rude remarks or
inappropriate jokes, experts advise. ``Just move along. And
certainly don't waste your time or energy discussing it,'' Sabath
said. Treat even those people you really can't stand with respect.
And don't pick a fight.
</P>
<P>
   For the times when a spouse makes an uncouth crack, Miss Manners
offers this solution: ``Say with affectionate shock (raised
eyebrows but warm, almost-patronizing smile), `Brandon! That came
out wrong! They'll think you meant to be insulting!'''
</P>
<P>
   It helps to prepare your date or spouse by noting whom they will
meet and what is expected of them. Your companion's behavior ``does
represent you,'' Sabath said. Also, dress appropriately.
</P>
<P>
   Hilka Klinkenberg, managing director of Etiquette International
in New York, recalled a young investment banker on the fast track
who arrived at an office party in ``a very short, very tight, very
sexy, low-cut clinging black lace dress over a nude underslip,''
prompting office gossip for three subsequent weeks. ``It became
about her being a hot young chick as opposed to her being a
competent young professional,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   While different industries tend to have somewhat different
cultures, the bottom line is that people are making assessments
about you, said Klinkenberg, author of ``At Ease ...
Professionally.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
