<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-MAIL-MANIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANIES FIND WAYS TO MANAGE DELUGE OF ELECTRONIC MAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WENDY TANAKA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Electronic mail is increasingly becoming the
preferred mode of correspondence. But for some businesses, e-mail
has become too much of a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   Companies are deluged daily with hundreds of messages they can't
possibly respond to in a timely fashion, if at all. As a result,
customer service can lag and business opportunities can slip away.
</P>
<P>
   To counteract these potential losses, some companies have
created internal systems that use software designed to sort, direct
and answer e-mail queries automatically. Others are contracting
with companies in the growing e-mail call center industry to solve
the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Brigade Solutions Inc. is set up like a traditional call center,
employing 50 ``cyber representatives'' in San Francisco and in
India _ where lower-cost, highly skilled labor is plentiful _ who
read e-mail questions sent to businesses and shoot back answers,
usually within 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Brigade was launched in February with $300,000 in seed money
from its founders, Brian Jeffries and Russ Cohn. The company is now
awaiting an infusion of about $2.5 million from a venture capital
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Fortune 500 companies out-source customer service,'' said
Jeffries, 32, the president and chief operating officer of Brigade.
``It's a pain not to out-source what's not the core of your
business.''
</P>
<P>
   The company so far has three corporate clients, including San
Francisco-based Intellipost Corp., an on-line direct marketing
company. For confidentiality purposes, Brigade would not name the
other two customers.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for Brigade started percolating a few years ago when
Jeffries and Cohn were working as management consultants in South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brian and I built call center operations for large telecom
firms,'' said Cohn, 28, the chief executive. ``We saw the Internet
as a way to do this better, faster and cheaper.''
</P>
<P>
   The entrepreneurs said Brigade charges clients significantly
less to sort, direct and answer e-mail than it would cost if the
customer had its own system.
</P>
<P>
   For answers to simple e-mail inquiries, Brigade charges between
$1 to $2 per response. This compares with about $4 per response
using an internal system, according to Forrester Research Inc., a
market analysis company in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The Brigade representatives start by writing answers to the most
frequently asked questions received by a client. Then those
responses go into a ``knowledge base.'' Jeffries said about 70
percent of the responses can be answered through the knowledge
base, with minimal tweaking. The remaining 30 percent of e-mail
requires more attention.
</P>
<P>
   Using Chevron Corp. as a hypothetical client, Jeffries said,
``Chevron might get e-mails about where the closest service station
is. That doesn't take a rocket scientist.''
</P>
<P>
   On a more technical question about how Chevron gasoline is
formulated, he said, a Brigade representative would need to forward
it to an appropriate Chevron manager.
</P>
<P>
   Brigade is targeting large companies, those that receive at
least 3,000 electronic inquiries a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to build a small number of very large accounts,''
Cohn said. ``The death of many service companies is that they have
too many customers, and not enough services. We're not following
the FedEx model. We're not stamping out parts.''
</P>
<P>
   While Cohn notes that one of Brigade's largest accounts right
now is Intellipost, he sees opportunities outside the technology
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a pretty big market for us in any industry,'' Cohn
said. ``High-tech companies get the most e-mail, but banks and
airlines should care the most.''
</P>
<P>
   John McCormick, an analyst with Frost &AMP; Sullivan Inc., a
technology research company in Mountain View, Calif., said Brigade
likely would capture a small segment of the growing e-mail call
center industry.
</P>
<P>
   McCormick said industry sales are about $11 million. He
predicted that by 2002, sales will jump to $103 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've looked at live services,'' he said, referring to
companies such as Brigade. ``I think it's going to be a niche
market because they're much more expensive than automated
solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Automated solutions are the handful of software companies that
sort, direct and answer e-mail queries. McCormick said the one-time
cost of acquiring this software could run from $900 to about
$14,000 _ much less than the $1 million annual revenue stream
Brigade is looking for from each customer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies don't really like recurring costs,'' McCormick said.
``If you buy automated solutions, you can take the hit up front.
It's like buying a house or renting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
