<SLUG> BC-NERVE-DISEASE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NERVE DISEASE OFTEN LEADS TO FRUSTRATION FOR SUFFERERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Cathy Sharp thought her feet hurt because she
stood all day at her bank teller job.
</P>
<P>
   A doctor diagnosed a bone spur, then neuromas or nerve tumors.
When the pain returned, Sharp was told she had a condition that is
similar to carpal tunnel syndrome but in the feet.
</P>
<P>
   After three surgeries, Sharp, now 51, was optimistic. Then the
pain came back. ``When I got back on my feet, there was immediate
burning,'' she said. ``My feet were on fire. The longer I'd be on
my feet, the worse it would become.''
</P>
<P>
   That was more than five years ago. Since then, Sharp lost her
job at the bank in Greenwich, N.Y., spent a lot of her savings and
almost gave up trying to find the cause of her pain. A New York
City neurologist finally gave her an answer at the end of 1996:
peripheral neuropathy.
</P>
<P>
   About 2 million people in the United States suffer from this
condition, a little-known disease of the peripheral nerves. They
are the nerves that connect the central nervous system, including
the brain and spinal cord, to the muscles, skin and internal
organs.``It's not a designer disease,'' said Bill Shankland, who
lives in Gloversville, N.Y., and was diagnosed with the condition
seven years ago. ``If somebody has multiple sclerosis or muscular
dystrophy, they immediately understand. People have just never
heard of peripheral neuropathy.''
</P>
<P>
   Most often the symptoms appear in the hands and feet, with
burning, itching, numbness and intolerance to heat and cold. The
disease can also affect balance or the ability to walk, by
interrupting nerve signals between the central nervous system and
the feet. Some people with neuropathy need to use a wheelchair and
many use canes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody who has neuropathy has a different story, but it's
basically the same story of going from doctor to doctor. It's
really a battle,'' Sharp said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the challenge is that the neuropathy may be caused by
one of 200 other problems, including diabetes, thyroid problems,
alcoholism, HIV, cancer and the autoimmune condition of
Guillain-Barre Syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   More often than not, doctors are unable to determine a specific
trigger. In those cases, the disease may progress as the body's
antibodies mistakenly attack the peripheral nerves. The damage may
be to the nerve covering, known as myelin, or to the nerve itself,
known as the axon.
</P>
<P>
   There is no cure. There are treatments, however, like regular
infusions of immunoglobulin or chemotherapy and steroids, that may
slow the deterioration in some patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our understanding of peripheral neuropathy is not where it
needs to be,'' said Dr. Neil Lava, a professor of neurology at the
Albany Medical College.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since there are so many different causes, what helps you may
not help somebody else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shankland, a retired New York state worker, had numerous
problems just getting a diagnosis. ``I got the runaround,'' he
said. ``I went from doctor to doctor. They talked about gout,
bursitis, arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your legs prickle and sometimes you feel like there's a bug
bite and you need to itch it. You get a lot of prickling and a lot
of pain. It's excruciating.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, he's still walking, thanks to monthly infusions of
immunoglobulin. During one of his treatments, he met Sharp.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the first time we had talked to anyone who had it,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The two have since started a support group, the Northeast
Neuropathy Association, for others with the condition. Over the
past year, they've had five meetings and recruited 60 members.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to your body, you have to be your own advocate
or you're all done,'' Sharp said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For information about the disease, call the Neuropathy
Association, based in New York City, at 800-247-6968.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
