<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAUTY-PIGGY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LATEST CELEBRITY SCENT IS A PIGLET OF A PERFUME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Even Miss Piggy is getting into the perfume act,
joining the ranks of Cher, Linda Evans (remember Cristal?), Joan
Collins and Elizabeth Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, says Topper Schroeder, president of Gendarme Fragrances
in West Hollywood, Calif., who pitched the idea to Henson
Productions, home of the porcine princess, ``I figured, hey, if
Elizabeth Taylor can do it, why can't she?''
</P>
<P>
   There's only one drawback to having the ditzy diva tout her own
scent _ you're not going to find her making in-store appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder describes the scent as ``lighter than Pleasures''
(last year's runaway best-seller from Estee Lauder), ``and it lasts
a lot longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Developed for Gendarme by International Flavors and Fragrances
(IFF) by Jean-Claude De Ville (who formulated Wilkes Bashford's
eponymous new scent, plus Tresor for Lancome and Eternity for
Calvin Klein), Moi is officially a floral chyphre, that is: flowers
and wood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted something that was very romantic,'' Schroeder says.
``But I am allergic to everything and wanted a fragrance that
didn't make me sneeze.''
</P>
<P>
   The top note is a dewy tangerine and mandarin; the floral heart
is zinnia, hydrangea and rose petal. And the dry-down is sensual
and unique, Schroeder says, because it includes hazelnut. ``Miss
Piggy likes to eat hazelnuts and loves the smell of them. So they
are in the base along with warm blonde wood.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, blonde. ``You've got to play it pretty straight when
you do satire,'' Schroeder says.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomingdale's has the exclusive on Moi, which retails for $24.
A limited edition fragrance _ there were only 50,000 bottles
produced _ each bottle is numbered. ``We're not going to get rich
on this one,'' laughs Schroeder, who says that his deal with Henson
isn't about licensing fees.
</P>
<P>
   Gendarme, by the way, has two more Henson-based fragrances in
the works, one for Animal and one for Kermit. Can Oscar the Grouch
be far behind?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New on the market from Francois Nars, that adorable French guy
whose makeup looks were featured on the recent Marc Jacobs and
Darryl K runways, is Lip Lacquer, nine new pots of lip color that
are more than a gloss and less than a lipstick.
</P>
<P>
   Nars likes to name his products for classic movies, so there is
Cabiria (sheer copper), Baby Doll (cotton candy pink), Butterfield
8 (sueded brown) and Tiffany (cinnamon), to name a few. Slicked on
the lips, they give shiny, sheer, but intense color. That's a nice
combo that works well for spring with the season's new glistened-up
faces.
</P>
<P>
   Find it at Saks and Sephora for $19 a pot.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While you're in your local Victoria's Secret buying Christmas
lingerie and other pretties, check out the flashy new makeup
display with what seems like hundreds of products. There are 10 lip
products, from conditioning balm and plumper to lip pencils, two
glosses and four kinds of lipstick (matte, long wear, creamy,
intense color and sheer color).
</P>
<P>
   Packaged in shiny silver and clear compacts, the Vicky's line is
priced just under Clinique and is very high quality. The colors are
amazing. My favorite: Torch, a blue red.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the products are innovative, like the Trick Stick
Concealer Crayon, which comes with its own sponge smoother, and
Dash Me a Line eye pencils created in a no-drag formula. They slide
on like silk, don't pull the eyelid, and smudge like crazy, if
that's the way you like it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of Vicky's, Stephanie Seymour, the supermodel who
sports the Angels line along with Tyra Banks, has just written a
book called ``Beauty Secrets for Dummies'' ($19.99), a collection
of tips about skin care, beauty emergencies, discovering a personal
style and sussing out beauty bargains.
</P>
<P>
   The book itself, a large paperback, is quite a bargain, just as
Stephanie is quite the dish. But if you're looking for something
simple and understandable, this isn't it.
</P>
<P>
   For everything you've always wanted to know about face lifts,
there is Joan Kron's new book, ``Lift: Wanting, Fearing and Having
a Face-Lift'' ($23.95).
</P>
<P>
   Kron is a former New York Times and Wall Street Journal reporter
who has covered plastic surgery for Allure and has had a couple of
lifts herself. She writes in a comfortable, conversational style
and addresses many of the fears and concerns of plastic surgery
candidates _ like where do you hide the scars, does it really hurt,
how long does a lift last and how to choose a surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   This 264-page volume might be a handy desk reference before you
make the cut.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
