<HEADER>
A8592 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-08 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE YEAR OF SEX, LIES, CLICHES AND EUPHEMISMS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The year is coming to a close, and it's time to
revise the Dictionary of Distraction. In the last year we've been
driven nuts by euphemisms and cliches.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, we have new euphemisms for sex that have made the
national agony more agonizing. It just isn't the same as 25 years
ago when expletives were deleted, and the constitutional crisis was
about a president who tried to subvert his enemies with federal
agencies and his own goons.
</P>
<P>
   The following are the catch phrases of 1998, and their true
meanings:
</P>
<P>
   ``Constitutional crisis.'' Oral sex, according to House
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inappropriate.'' Oral sex, according to Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perjury.'' Lying about oral sex. Used by Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Misled.'' Lying about oral sex. Used by Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clinton legacy.'' Oral sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oral sex.'' Not as much fun as it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bipartisan.'' Sane Americans don't buy any part of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monica.'' 1998.
</P>
<P>
   While the press has been awash in the above words, American
business has been busy making the language safe for monopolies,
profit and lower wages.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday the New York Times had the following sentence on its
front page: ``The downsizing is coming just when a strong job
market, mainly in the service sector, offers new jobs, softening
the blow considerably.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: ``Learn to make a half-caf cappuccino, and you can
make half the rent.''
</P>
<P>
   True, some of these terms are not new in 1998, but have been
accepted into usage by newspapers instead of plain English. We live
in a country where no one is fired anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Downsizing.'' You, too, can have a new job in America's
booming economy. As in: ``Would you like to super size those
fries?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Private industry'' or ``private sector.'' Where bureaucrats
could earn more money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The service sector.'' The part of the private sector that pays
minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Asian crisis.'' Something happening over there. Replaces
``Pacific Rim.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Corporate culture.'' Self-canceling phrase, often employed
with verb ``clash.'' Used when a North Carolina bank, say, takes
over a California bank and engages in uncultured behavior like
firing female executives or not promising to make loans to
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Merger.'' Monopoly in the making. Two banks, computer
companies or oil companies become one bigger one, thus allowing
higher profits and fewer workers. According to big business'
biggest friend, Bill Clinton, mergers are good if they lead to
``lower prices and higher-quality services.''
</P>
<P>
   See ``misled.''
</P>
<P>
   Psychology and medicine are always growth areas in the language,
and this year has been no exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patients' bill of rights.'' When in the course of HMO events,
it becomes necessary to be billed, thou shalt be patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``Road rage.'' The jerk in the other car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intensity.'' A compliment to say about yourself when you've
acted like a jerk. As California Assemblyman Kevin Shelley said of
15 aides who've quit or been fired: ``My intensity in my job is one
of the reasons I've been successful, but that same intensity
creates an environment that is unduly stressful for a number of
employees.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Assisted suicide.'' Self-canceling phrase. Cancels self.
</P>
<P>
   ``Viagra.'' A great medical advance, but a bigger advance for
Internet joke Web pages. Replaces ``Prozac.'' You take it orally.
For sex.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
