<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WHY I WRITE: THOUGHTS ON THE CRAFT OF FICTION &QL; 
 &UR; Edited by Will Blythe (Little, Brown, $23)
</P>
<P>
   ``Writers when they're writing live in a spooky, clamorous
silence, a state somewhat like the advanced stages of prayer but
without prayer's calming benefits,'' Joy Williams says. ``A writer
turns his back on the day and the night and its large and little
beauties, and tries, like some half-witted demi-urge, to fashion
other days and nights with words. It's absurd. Oh, it's silly,
dangerous work indeed.'' Amy Hempel borrows a thought from Tom
Waits on the difficulty of sitting down at a keyboard and trying to
say something in a new way: ``Your hands are like dogs, going to
the same places they've been.'' Ann Patchett admits that one of the
reasons she became a writer was the cachet of the writing life. And
Rick Moody and his mom, Margaret F.M. Davis, offer separate views
on his childhood and how it produced an adult who writes. We are
happy to report that this collection of essays pays as much
attention to the drudgery as to the rapture, and consequently to
the soul of the craft. Among the other contributors: Barry Hannah,
Jim Harrison, Robert Stone, Mark Richard, Jayne Anne Phillips,
Terry McMillan, Denis Johnson, Thom Jones, Richard Ford, Rick Bass,
Mary Gaitskill and Lee Smith. And here is James Salter: ``In the
end, writing is like a prison, an island from which you will never
be released but which is a kind of paradise: the solitude, the
thoughts, the incredible joy of putting into words the essence of
what you for the moment understand and with your whole heart want
to believe.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; EVERYTHING AND A KITE &QL; 
 &UR; Ray Romano (Bantam, $22.95)
</P>
<P>
   You know how we feel about the recent glut of books by
comedians, a veritable conga line of failed humor. Imagine our
surprise when we learned that Romano feels the same way. He spends
a whole chapter lamenting his lack of talent as a writer (``Talking
and writing are totally different,'' he says. ``In conversation I
can feign intelligence.''). This gives rise to an obvious question
_ why, Ray, why? _ and an obvious answer: Someone paid him to try
to be funny for 200 pages, and he spent the advance, so he couldn't
back out. Reason to rush out and buy it, don't you think? We have,
and we are here to tell you that Romano does not earn your dollar.
He is personable (a leg up on Whoopi Goldberg, Chris Rock, Paul
Reiser and other pioneers of the comedian-book genre), and he tries
mighty hard, but he is not funny. Just richer. Our advice: Go buy
Steve Martin's book, and have a better time. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; MAY THE CIRCLE BE UNBROKEN &QL; 
 &UR; Lynn C. Franklin (Harmony, $24)
</P>
<P>
   In 1966, Franklin gave her newborn son up for adoption. She was
19 and unmarried. Her parents were supportive, but there was never
any thought that Franklin could raise the baby alone, no
possibility that she might keep him. And so, she writes, ``I had
five days in the hospital to shower upon my baby all the maternal
love I would be allowed for the next 27 years.'' In April 1993,
Franklin was reunited with the son she had given up. She describes
here both the separation and the reunion, and she uses her own
experience to explore the changing face of adoption _ its
practical, emotional and legal issues as seen from the perspective
of birth parents, adoptive parents and the children they share.
It's a thought-provoking look at a process that is full of joy and
sorrow and that is changing as it is demystified. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ANCIENT MEXICO &QL; 
 &UR; Maria Longhena (Stewart, Tabori &AMP; Chang, $60)
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, bigger is better. Text takes second billing to
visuals in this handsome coffee-table book, which opens with a
stunning succession of two-page photographs. There are aerial views
of the great stepped pyramids of Pre-Columbian cultures, and
close-up, nose-to-nose photographs of extraordinary masks (the most
impressive is a funerary mask carved from jade and covered with a
mosaic of turquoise, pyrite and shell _ it is presented in such
size and proximity that you almost imagine expression in its eyes).
Longhena traces the mosaic of civilizations that flourished in
Mesoamerica between the second millennium B.C. and the 16th
century. Included are the Olmecs, the Zapotecs, the Teotihuacan
culture, the Maya and the Aztecs, as well as minor cultures that
contributed to economic and artistic development. The book also
offers site plans, reconstructions of temples and cities, and the
remarkable artworks of these ancient peoples. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; DEVASTATION! &QL; 
 &UR; Lesley Newson (DK, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   What, no quicksand? There's not much else missing from this
survey of dreadful things. It covers earthquakes, floods, volcanic
eruptions, tornados and hurricanes, lightning storms, droughts,
famines, fires, avalanches, plagues, epidemics and _ we are not
making this up _ locust swarms (the ``pest'' category also includes
rats and beetles, but the locust pictures are better). This is a
book version of those television specials that show us unfathomable
things. Boats deposited on rooftops. Ocean waves crashing through
windows. A huge cloud of volcanic dust and gas pursuing a truck
full of fleeing people. An airplane dangling from a tree. And
water, lots of water everywhere. Our Most Horrifying Photograph
Award goes to that of France's rampaging Ouveze River, which in
1992 sent a 50-foot-high wall of water through the town of
Vaison-la-Romaine, killing 38 people. It's so terrible that we
cannot look away. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Correspondent Anne Stephenson can be reached at
amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
