<HEADLINE>
EX-SENATOR RE VISITS BASKET BALL CAREER IN SEARCH OF VAL UES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
Values of the Game 
Bill Bradley (Artisan, $30) 
 
 By BILL HILL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would be normal for any presidential candidate to spend much
of his time writing position papers. Serious thoughts on foreign
policy, global warming, Social Security. Really weighty issues.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is Bill Bradley _ who left the U.S. Senate in
1996 after representing New Jersey for eight years and who,
although still an undeclared Democratic candidate for the White
House, formed an exploratory committee on Dec. 4 that can raise
money for a campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has spent his ``time off'' teaching at Stanford and
Notre Dame. And, he has written a book about basketball. Or is it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Values of the Game'' is actually a collection of 10 essays
about virtues, about lessons learned through basketball that can be
applied to everyday life. However, be forewarned: The game that
Bradley remembers and loves so dearly rarely resembles the
run-and-gun or shoot-the-trey style now marketed by the NBA (when
the owners and players aren't at odds over who should be the Kings
of Greed).
</P>
<P>
   Bradley knows of what he speaks. He was an All-American at
Princeton and an Olympian who delayed his pro career for two years
to attend Oxford University as a Rhodes Scholar. He then spent 10
years with the New York Knicks, two of which culminated with his
team's winning the NBA championship.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 essays are titled: Passion, Discipline, Selflessness,
Respect, Perspective, Courage, Leadership, Responsibility,
Resilience and Imagination. They are a collection of Bradley's
thoughts, as well as those of people who have influenced him and
the game. A couple of examples, attributed to UCLA coach John
Wooden: ``Failing to prepare is preparing to fail,'' and ``It is
what you learn after you know it all that counts.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkled throughout the 160-page book are nuggets of advice
that any aspiring athlete would do well to read, such as this one,
which influenced Bradley's intense work ethic as a youngster: ``If
you're not practicing, just remember _ someone, somewhere, is
practicing, and when you two meet, given roughly equal ability, he
will win.''
</P>
<P>
   At times, the lessons Bradley seeks to teach seem elementary,
until you stop and think about how the game is being played and
marketed in this era. As Bradley writes, ``The game is struggling
to keep its integrity alive.''
</P>
<P>
   The book, which also has more than 100 classic basketball photos
of many of the game's greatest players, is meant to be more than a
sermon on how to succeed on a basketball court. It is intended to
make us think about how things such as passion, discipline and
selflessness can be be watchwords for success in life. And most of
the time, Bradley succeeds.
</P>
<P>
   A choice example comes from his essay on selflessness:
</P>
<P>
   ``I can learn more about people by playing a three-on-three game
with them for 20 minutes than I can by talking to them for a week.
I once hired a news director for my U.S. Senate offices in New
Jersey. I liked him, but it wasn't until I played basketball with
him that I knew I'd made the right choice. I found out he was a
hard worker (he went for the rebound), competitive with a fierce
desire to win (he played close defense), and unselfish (he screened
away from the ball).''
</P>
<P>
   Hmmm. It would be a good guess that Bradley, if elected
president, won't be interviewing too many of today's ``stars'' for
Cabinet positions. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
