<SLUG> BC-PAGEEXPRESS-BUDGET-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 PageExpress budget for the week of Dec. 7, 1998
<TEXT>
<P>
   PageExpress, a new service from The New York Times Syndicate,
consists of paginated pages built with content from Cox Newspapers
and The New York Times News Service. The pages are easy to retrieve
from a web site and you can use them just as they are or customize
any or all of the elements -- text, fonts, photos and graphics --
to suit your needs.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on these pages, or to view a sample, use
your web browser to visit http://nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   For the password to download and use the pages, call John
Gardner, pagination consultant for The New York Times Syndicate, at
917-224-4381 or e-mail him at pages &LR; nytsyn.com.
</P>
<P>
   Unless otherwise noted, pages are available after 2 p.m.
Tuesday, Dec. 8
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS Open Scott Berg's biography of Charles Lindbergh at any
point, and you will find it instantly interesting, no matter that
you already know the story of the handsome young aviator. A Q&AMP;A
with the author puts to rest the notion that an authorized
biography tells less than an unauthorized one. WITH: SKUBE ON BOOKS
-- Postmodern theorists made fools of themselves, appropriating
words and ideas from sciences they scarcely understand and
bankrupting what intellectual integrity they can still claim. WITH:
REVIEWS -- As Phillip Lopate practices it, the personal essay is a
dramatic form. He rebels against the notion of the essay as ``a
mild tea cozy.'' WITH: NY Times Best Sellers List.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (Available by 2 p.m., Thursday, Dec.10) Like a
pile of gaudily wrapped gifts during the December holidays, this
film season will likely contain plenty of surprises -- both good
and bad. Here's a peek at what Hollywood is putting out in the next
several weeks to pull folks into movie theaters. WITH: REYNOLDS Q&AMP;A
-- A discussion with actor Burt Reynolds, who stars and directs in
TNT's latest film project, ``Hard Times.'' To no one's surprise,
Reynolds plays a hard-edged cop framed for a street killing.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS (Available by 2 p.m. Friday, Dec. 11) It will be a grim
Christmas this year for the residents of the poor nation of
Honduras. It's been over a month since Hurricane Mitch rampaged
through Central America, leaving 11,000 people dead and hundreds of
thousands homeless. In Honduras alone, a country of 6 million
people, more than 1 million have lost everything they owned. The
storm is over, but reconstruction may take years. Many relief
organizations are working around the clock to bring aid to this
shattered country, but it's an uphill battle.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD The perfect Christmas cookie: it has just a few ingredients
-- easy to find and not too difficult to mix or to bake. It might
be crunchy, but it isn't necessarily chocolate. And most of all, it
is more delicious than any other. WITH: COOKBOOK -- Holiday bakers
who want to add a new cookie or two to their perennial favorites
are in for several treats from this year's batch of cookbooks.
WITH: SKUBE ON BEER -- Winter beers aren't just for Christmas eve.
These are beers for firesides on cold evenings throughout the
winter -- heartier and stronger than what you'd drink at a summer
picnic.
</P>
<P>
   PERSONAL TECHNOLOGY Let your fingers do the walking this holiday
season. Why not join the millions of shoppers doing their holiday
shopping online? You can shop at 4 in the morning or 11 at night,
and you never have to worry about finding a place to park.
Electronic commerce -- known to most consumers as online shopping
-- is rapidly becoming a booming business. WITH: DIGITAL DIVIDE:
Schools with computers are now facing training their teachers on
how to use them in the classroom. WITH: TECH BRIEFS -- Try going
online for mortgage shopping; innovative Web site for clothing
store acts like a fitting room. WITH: TECHNOBUDDY -- A UPS device
offers cheap insurance against damage from power surges. WITH:
TECHTOOLS -- The 1999 Grolier multimedia encyclopedia has its share
of problems, but on the whole it is a very useful reference work.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE &AMP; HEALTH AIDSVAX -- Dan Flinchum doesn't much like
needles, but he is about to become the first volunteer in Atlanta
to be inoculated with AIDSVAX, the first vaccine for the AIDS virus
to be widely tested in the United States. This is not the end of
AIDS. The vaccine may not work. Even if it does, it will take years
of further testing and tweaking before it is approved for
widespread use. WITH: AIDSVAX-TESTS -- HIV vaccine researchers know
they will need luck if they are to meet President Clinton's goal of
developing a working HIV vaccine by 2007 -- a goal some believe is
impossible. WITH: HEAD LICE -- Come to school right away. Your
child has head lice. What's the big deal, you wonder? It's a simple
matter of giving them a shampoo treatment and running a load or two
of laundry. Think again. WITH: HEALTH BRIEFS -- A study released by
the Texas Department of Health found that 43 percent of high school
students and nearly a third of middle schoolers chewed tobacco or
smoked it on at least one day in the previous month.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL Button up your overcoat. It's time for chestnuts roasting
on an open fire in the Big Apple. Here are 10 fantastic ways to do
the holidays up right while staying in New York City; and there's
plenty to see and hear, smell and taste as December rolls on toward
1999. WITH: TRAVEL NOTES --Increasing emphasis on on-time
performance has led many airlines to draw a harder line against
oversized carry-on luggage. WITH: TRAVEL BRIEFS -- Temporarily
vacant private homes in London can be a reasonably priced and
comfortable alternative to the city's hotels, others.
</P>
<P>
   WHEELS The '99 Grand Cherokee retains the menacing grille with
seven vertical slots and the big tire-accommodating trapezoidal
wheel openings. But most everything else -- notably the interior --
has been reworked to make it more appealing visually and more
comfortable physically. WITH: THE MECHANIC -- When thinking about
gifts this holiday season, why not consider automotive accessories;
you can make it practical yet personal.
</P>
</TEXT>
