<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOFA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO MAY SEEK NEW BANKING PARTNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The city's treasurer vowed there would be a
``shake-up'' in the relationship City Hall has with BankAmerica
since the bank's merger with North Carolina-based NationsBank.
</P>
<P>
   Treasurer Susan Leal said Monday she was seeking bids for
services and discounts on fees that she believed San Francisco was
entitled to as Northern California's largest banking customer.
</P>
<P>
   BankAmerica handles some 90 percent of San Francisco's banking
business, moving millions of dollars in payroll and payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to look at who can best take care of the money, but
you also look at who is headquartered in the city and who is going
to be a good corporate citizen,'' Leal said. ``There will be a
shake-up, and I think there is definitely a strong feeling in the
city to move away from Bank of America.''
</P>
<P>
   BankAmerica has struggled in recent weeks with what it says are
unfair perceptions that the merger of Charlotte-based NationsBank
and BankAmerica Corp. of San Francisco has resulted in a flight of
women executives, an ambiguous commitment to lending to minorities
and a loss of interest in California business.
</P>
<P>
   Two City Hall sources said Hugh McColl Jr., the BankAmerica
chairman and former chief executive of NationsBank, had talked in
the past several days to Mayor Willie Brown, apparently to allay
concerns that the bank's commitment to community development and
philanthropy had lessened.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's press secretary, Kandace Bender, would not confirm
details of the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   McColl is scheduled to deliver two speeches to reassure
California customers: one at the Commonwealth Club in San Francisco
on Jan. 12, the other at Town Hall in Los Angeles on Jan. 13. He
also will meet with state and city officials in San Francisco and
Los Angeles ``to say we are unwavered in our commitment to the
community, both on the lending side and the philanthropy side,''
said BankAmerica spokesman John Keane.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to assure them that (the management team) has the
resources to accomplish our mission in California,'' Keane said.
</P>
<P>
   Leal said she was concerned about perceptions of a cultural gap
between the Charlotte-based management team and the more liberal
politics of the Bay area. Regardless of whether such a gap existed,
she said, she is inclined toward beginning relationships with other
banks because it makes economic sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is what is good for the city,'' Leal said.
</P>
<P>
   BankAmerica has handled almost all the city's business for some
80 years. NationsBank acquired BankAmerica in September, sending
many of the merged corporate functions to Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo is the only other major bank that complies with the
city's requirement of providing benefits to unmarried couples and
some other prerequisites for municipal contracts.
</P>
<P>
   However, Leal said, Wells Fargo would have to resolve its
differences with organized labor before being considered. Wells
Fargo is a major lender to Oregon Steel, which has a facility in
Pueblo, Colo., that has locked out 1,000 employees in a contract
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   City officials, including City Attorney Louise Renne, last week
criticized BankAmerica for demoting or replacing its women
executives, calling it unfair and unprofessional treatment.
</P>
<P>
   But Keane said since the merger, women were playing a greater
role on the board of directors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
