A8743 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COUNTRYMUSIC-ENCYCLOP     12-08 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNTRYMUSIC-ENCYCLOPEDIA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST DON'T LOOK FOR THE DIXIE CHICKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SHIRLEY JINKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From Fiddlin' John Carson to Crazy Water Crystals, the recently
published Encyclopedia of Country Music attempts to be a complete
tell-all of eight decades of country music. It's ``the greatest
compendium of information about country music ever produced,''
proclaims the dust jacket.
</P>
<P>
   Really? Gosh, let's sit down for a minute.
</P>
<P>
   It's big, all right. It's dry. It's thorough. You probably have
relatives who'd love it. Cost is $49.95, through Christmas, at
least. Then it becomes $55.
</P>
<P>
   The 4-pound book contains 634 pages and 1,300 entries that are
recent enough to include the dates of death for Tammy Wynette and
Roy Rogers (but not Gene Autry or Jerry Clower).
</P>
<P>
   It took 137 authorities to write the thing, including many
Texas-friendly writers such as Kevin Coffey, Rick Mitchell, Don
McLeese, Guy Logsdon and Charles R. Townsend.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, this very Nashville-focused effort is pretty
complete in its cataloging of western swing and cowboy music
pioneers, and even in its coverage of modern Texas-music icons.
</P>
<P>
   We couldn't wait to find out who made the cut, and who was left
out.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Texas-music fans, there are entries for Junior Brown, Guy
Clark, Lyle Lovett and Nanci Griffith. Tommy Duncan, Steve Earle,
Butch Hancock, Don Edwards, Joe Ely, and the Flatlanders all made
it in, but then again, so did the Four Guys and our own Ricky Lynn
Gregg.
</P>
<P>
   Also in: Don Walser, Delbert McClinton, Chris Wall, Leon Rausch,
and West Texas dance legend Hoyle Nix. Tommy Duncan and the Chuck
Wagon Gang are in there. Ditto Dale Watson and Wayne Hancock.
</P>
<P>
   Don't look for Alvin Crow or Clay Blaker or Terry Allen, though.
No Dixie Chicks, no Lloyd Maines, no Old 97's.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Willis is listed, and her marriage to Bruce Robison
mentioned, but there are no listings for either Bruce or brother
Charlie Robison.
</P>
<P>
   The very-alive Bill Mack is duly noted. But the equally kicking
Johnnie High isn't, though he certainly has started enough
Nashville careers.
</P>
<P>
   The Austin, Texas, entry (glaringly, there isn't one for Fort
Worth) offers this: ``Austin's prominence as a country music
capital has declined since the 1980s, partly because the city never
built a recording complex that could augment its numerous live
performance venues.'' Thank you, Bill C. Malone. We Texans know
it's all our fault.
</P>
<P>
   Thank goodness, writer Don McLeese of Austin does the balanced
``Austin City Limits'' entry that immediately follows.
</P>
<P>
   Some entries are wickedly anecdotal, others miss the good stuff.
Robert Earl Keen is listed, his ``Picnic'' album noted, but there
is no word about the incendiary car incident itself at Willie's
picnic.
</P>
<P>
   That's odd, considering that Ty Herndon's entry actually begins
with his Fort Worth arrest in 1995 on indecency and drug charges.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Lawrence's conviction on spousal abuse this year also made
his entry. Heh-heh.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas recording pioneer Jim Beck is noted, along with the sad
tale of his death by recording chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Urban Cowboy'' gets an explanatory listing. So do the
``Louisiana Hayride'' and the ``Big D Jamboree.''
</P>
<P>
   One very fine entry explains conjunto. Gene Fowler explains
border radio. Someone even attempts to explain line dancing.
</P>
<P>
   You want obscure? Read up on Diesel Only Records, a '90s label
out of Brooklyn, N.Y., that only issues 45s on vinyl. There's even
a listing for Crazy Water Crystals, a Mineral Wells-based early
sponsor of country acts.
</P>
<P>
   Gilley's has a listing. Why doesn't Billy Bob's Texas, or Gruene
Hall? Staying in business must be less folkloric than being
torched.
</P>
<P>
   That opens up an entire category of whys. Why, why, WHY does the
small-time '90s group Boy Howdy merit an entry, when it lasted only
six years and never had a hit? Why is George Ducas in there, when
Walter Hyatt is not?
</P>
<P>
   Why Cledus ``T.'' Judd?
</P>
<P>
   And why on earth is Billy Ray Cyrus' entry as long as that of
legendary Sun Records?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, that's right: The acknowledgments say entries were included
``based on their impact on country music.'' It's as clear as a big,
refreshing glass of Crazy Water Crystals.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The Encyclopedia of Country Music
</P>
<P>
   Paul Kingsbury, editor, for the Country Music Hall of Fame and
Museum
</P>
<P>
   Oxford University Press
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Shirley Jinkins writes on country music for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 548-5565. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-98 1543EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981208.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
