<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8755 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT &LR;      12-08 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STIR-FRIED BUT STIRRED LESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stir-frying is one of the fastest cooking methods possible,
especially if you have the same kind of high-powered wok burner as
your neighborhood Chinese restaurant. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of course you don't. But if you keep ingredients and,
ironically, stirring to a minimum, keep the heat high and forget
about a wok, you can keep the cooking time for a good stir-fry to
just about five minutes.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You don't want a wok because home stoves, unlike the large
pit-burners in Chinese restaurants, are flat-topped. For best heat
distribution, you want a flat-bottomed skillet, the larger the
better and preferably nonstick.
</P>
<P>
   The heat must be kept high to insure nicely browned _ even
slightly charred _ meat and vegetables; for the same reason,
stirring should be minimized. The final key is to keep it simple:
too many ingredients slow you down and eventually overload the
skillet, so that browning becomes impossible. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For speed and simplicity, I often use hoisin sauce when
stir-frying. Since it is made from fermented soybeans, chili,
sugar, ginger and garlic, it contains pretty much the same
ingredients that you may spend an extra 5 or 10 minutes measuring
and preparing.
</P>
<P>
   And because it usually contains flour or cornstarch, it
automatically glazes and thickens the dish. (When you buy hoisin
sauce, look for a brand whose first ingredient is fermented
soybeans rather than sugar or water: the flavor will be more
intense. And avoid those with artificial ingredients if possible.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For many stir-fry dishes made at home, hard vegetables like
broccoli or asparagus need to be parboiled, or precooked. So in
this super-fast stir-fry, I stick to bell peppers, onions or both;
they turn tender and sweet in three or four minutes.
</P>
<P>
   If you cut the chicken _ or beef, turkey, lamb or pork, if you
like _ in small cubes or thin slices, the cooking time for it is
even less. I include nuts for flavor, texture and speed _ I don't
chop them at all.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In fact, this stir-fry is so fast that the first thing you need
to do is start a batch of white rice. In the 15 or 20 minutes it
takes to cook, you will be able not only to prepare the stir-fry,
but also to set the table and have a drink. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   10-MINUTE STIR-FRY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon peanut or vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 cups red pepper strips, onion slices or a combination
</P>
<P>
   1 pound boneless, skinless chicken breast, cut into {- to }-inch
chunks
</P>
<P>
   1 cup halved walnuts, whole cashews or other nuts
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons hoisin sauce. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Place the oil in a large, nonstick skillet (12 inches is
best), and turn the heat to high; a minute later, add the
vegetable(s) in a single layer and cook, undisturbed, until they
begin to char a little on the bottom, about 1 minute. Stir and cook
1 minute more.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add the meat, and stir once or twice. Again, cook until the
bottom begins to blacken a bit, about a minute. Stir and cook
another minute; by this time the vegetables will have softened and
the meat will be done, or nearly so (cut into a piece if you want
to check). Lower the heat to medium.
</P>
<P>
   3. Stir in the nuts and the hoisin sauce. Cook for about 15
seconds, then add 2 tablespoons of water. Cook, stirring, until the
sauce is bubbly and glazes all the meat and vegetables. Serve
immediately, with white rice. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
