<HEADLINE>
CELEBRATING A BRILLIANT MASTER OF THE SHORT STORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the 17 years of its history, the Library of America has
commemorated scores of bygone native authors, from Charles Brocken
Brown in the late 18th century to masters of our own time window _
William Faulkner, John Steinbeck and James Baldwin among them.
</P>
<P>
   Now the series focuses for the first time on an author still
living. She is Mississippi's Eudora Welty, honored in her 90th year
with two volumes _ one containing her five novels, the other
collecting her short stories, essays and autobiographical writings.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1990s, much of my reading time has been given to
Library of America titles. The series has been a humbling
revelation, identifying blind spots in my reading activity. I am
less well-read than I supposed, and these volumes containing the
works of our writers anointed with greatness help fill the gaps.
</P>
<P>
   There's some gap-filling to be accomplished in the matter of
Eudora Welty. I supposed, too, that I had a clear handle on her
fiction, but there's much catching up to do.
</P>
<P>
   I first heard her name mentioned in a college course on the
American novel. Along with other English majors, I ridiculed behind
his back our fatuous, effeminate professor, but hindsight assures
me he was a fine teacher. He urged us to read Welty's 1946 novel
``Delta Wedding,'' and I did, with appreciation, and from that
point I wrongly considered Welty a novelist.
</P>
<P>
   I had a chuckle festival reading ``The Ponder Heart'' soon after
its 1954 publication, and chuckled some more a few years later when
David Wayne starred in its dramatization on Broadway. Then there
was a long wait for another Welty novel, until 1970, when ``Losing
Battles'' appeared. Two years later came ``The Optimist's
Daughter,'' which snared the Pulitzer Prize that I interpret as
valedictory for Welty's body of work. I rate both the long-ago
``Delta Wedding'' and ``Losing Battles'' as superior to the prize
winner.
</P>
<P>
   All along, I was ignoring Welty's short stories, even while
reading in critical essays that the short form is her true
strength. I was familiar with the oft-anthologized ``The Wide Net''
and ``The Bride of Innisfallen,'' and that was about it _ until
1980, when ``The Collected Stories of Eudora Welty'' appeared, and
I began to sense what I had been missing.
</P>
<P>
   Welty surely deserved the Pulitzer for her collected stories,
after Katherine Anne Porter, Jean Stafford and John Cheever all
won, in turn, for their volumes. But 1980 was the year of John
Kennedy Toole's ``A Confederacy of Dunces,'' and Pulitzer jurors
climbed on the bandwagon for posthumous tribute. Besides, Welty
already had a Pulitzer ... and that's how literary politics works.
</P>
<P>
   So here I am, having read all of Welty's novels and not nearly
enough of her stories; that's pleasure to be accomplished. Yet most
prospective readers want novels, as Welty's publishers did, and I
offer a brisk report.
</P>
<P>
   The larkish ``The Robber Bridegroom,'' technically her first
novel (1942), isn't so much novel as distended fable; ``Delta
Wedding'' must be considered her full-length debut. It's a subtle,
sympathetic view of genteel Southern society in modern transition.
``The Ponder Heart'' is a short story in design, stretched to
novella length with a trim of fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing Battles'' is set in the 1930s and is effective as a
sociological period piece, as a proud family strives to preserve
its way of life (and loses the battle). ``The Optimist's Daughter''
is high-class soap opera, a triangle affair between a daughter, her
father and his second wife.
</P>
<P>
   Welty's fiction combines elements of the abnormal and grotesque,
but she's milder than Flannery O'Connor and Carson McCullers, and
closer in psychological substance to Katherine Anne Porter. Of them
all, she has the best ``ear,'' finding the key to character in the
way people speak.
</P>
<P>
   In Eudora Welty's world, no life lacks drama, no life lacks
value.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 390-7731. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
