A8771 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURRAY-COLUMN09-COX     12-08 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Bad taste at Sunday lunch
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ What with my wife out of town, I stopped by one
of the nice family restaurants hereabouts for Sunday lunch. I
arrived just in time to join the church crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Just in time, too, as it turned out, for a sermon. The fellow in
the group next to my table was well into his message of the day. I
couldn't help but listen, try as I might.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got friends _ good friends _ who are on their way to
hell, no two ways about it. I keep telling them and telling them.
And they keep saying that one of these days they'll do something
about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well.'' Here he paused for effect. ``One of these days it's
gonna be too late.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a general murmur of agreement all around. But
something about the fellow's tone bothered me. It was not so much
one of concern as an impending I-told-you-so.
</P>
<P>
   Moving right along ...
</P>
<P>
   ``People in the church might have thought I'm a racist 'cause I
objected to that black boy coming to our services. Well (pause)
they thought wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the fact he was coming to church that bothered me.
No-sir-ree. It was THE REASON he was coming that bothered me. And
that reason, as we all know, was to get to meet white girls.''
</P>
<P>
   I was just picking at my food at this point. I couldn't imagine
what in the world had happened to my appetite.
</P>
<P>
   The next part of the sermon heartened me, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``And those Baptists. Just look at the mess they've gotten
into.''
</P>
<P>
   Being a Baptist, I was glad to hear that he wasn't one of us. As
for the mess, who knows what he was referring to. Baptists are in
one or another so often it's difficult to keep count.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the ecumenical critique continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know why the Catholics can't ever get anything
accomplished? I could tell 'em if they asked me.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody asked but he went on anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it is, they need to stop praying to the Virgin Mary and
start praying to the Man upstairs instead, uh-huh, and then maybe
they'd get somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny thing, I attend vespers on occasion with Catholic friends.
I've yet to hear a prayer offered up to Mary. But maybe I'm not
paying good attention.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, this closing word, which I caught only in passing:
</P>
<P>
   ''... and for the life of me I don't know how those Jehovah's
Witnesses can stand themselves. All they ever do is go around
criticizing other religions.''
</P>
<P>
   By then I'd finished my meal and was on my way out when I
realized I'd forgotten to leave a tip. I arrived back at my table
just in time for the benediction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heresy, heresy,'' he was declaring, for whatever reason I
didn't know.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. Under my breath, I couldn't help from joining in:
</P>
<P>
   ``Amen, brother. Amen!''
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News,
</P>
<P>
   is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)prodigy.com; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
