<SLUG> BC-FOOD-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ART OF THE EDIBLE EDIFICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Using gingerbread, rather than granite, anyone can be a Donald
Trump or even a Stanford White this season. And many are trying.
</P>
<P>
   For the last few years, just for fun, employees of the World
Monument Fund have built a landmark building in gingergread. Last
year, it was Hagia Sofia in Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
   This year, with the Municipal Art Society, the group has asked
15 teams of architects and designers to create structures like the
arch in Washington Square, the Chrysler Building and a 1713 Russian
Orthodox church, Kizhi Pogost in northern Russia, with 21 onion
domes.
</P>
<P>
   The models were sold at a benefit auction Tuesday night. Some of
them will remain on display all week at the Municipal Art Society,
457 Madison Avenue (51st Street).
</P>
<P>
   Chefs have also taken up gingerbread architecture. A team of
Restaurant Associate chefs, with Susanna Lazzari of La Guli Pastry
Shop in Astoria, Queens, have reproduced five 18th- and
19th-century New York region churches in gingerbread, including the
1873 First Methodist Church in Red Bank, N.J., and the 1863
Riverdale Presbyterian Church, designed by James Renwick.
</P>
<P>
   They will be on display through New Year's weekend at the
American Festival Cafe, 20 West 50th Street, from 7:30 a.m. to 11
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Winston's Fifth Avenue town house has been reproduced in
gingerbread by Jacques Torres of Le Cirque 2000 and decorated with
a $2 million diamond wreath necklace. It's on display at the
jewelry shop, 718 Fifth Avenue (56th Street). The necklace will be
sold to the highest bidder (gingerbread included). A portion of the
sum will go to a charity selected by the buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Grace's Marketplace, 1237 Third Avenue (71st Street), is selling
gingerbread birdhouses, each about 12 inches high, for $65. And
Coco Cafe, 7 East 59th Street, has gingerbread ornaments for the
home. They are $5.50 each or $30 for six.
</P>
<P>
   For those who want gingerbread houses that look like their own
homes, Rebecca Russell will create them, with the help of a
photogra0h, starting at $200. She also has prefabricated houses
starting at $25. Her number is (212) 255-7530.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone interested in making a gingerbread house can buy a kit at
Eli's Manhattan, 1411 Third Avenue (80th Street), and at the
Vinegar Factory, 431 East 91st Street, for $14.99. And a roll of
Maury's gingerbread, with enough dough to slice and bake a
10-by-15-inch sheet, is $4.99 at City Bakery (22 East 17th Street)
and in some supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   Three rolls make a modest cottage. After making it, you get to
nibble away at it. It will bring out your inner termite.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
