<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOM ROBBINS IS ANYTHING BUT HALF ASLEEP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Whatever happened to Tom Robbins, author of ``Another
Roadside Attraction''?
</P>
<P>
   _ D.B., Keller, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Robbins is working on a new novel, his first since 1994's
``Half Asleep in Frog Pajamas,'' but neither a publication date nor
title has been announced. The 62-year-old writer has taken up to
six years between new novels since his first, ``Another Roadside
Attraction,'' was published in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Robbins read excerpts of his new book at a Washington
writers' conference. Robbins, who begins his novels without knowing
where they will end, had written more than 500 pages at the time of
the reading.
</P>
<P>
   To send him a letter, write to Tom Robbins, Union of Mad
Scientists, Box 338, LaConner, WA 98257. You also can send e-mail
to Robbins in care of his publisher, Bantam Doubleday Dell, at
bddweb(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why did ``Grace Under Fire'' go off the air?
</P>
<P>
   _ D.R., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: The ABC sitcom ended production in February after five
seasons. Only 14 of a planned 25 episodes had been completed for
the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grace Under Fire,'' led by stand-up comedian Brett Butler, was
a Top 10 show for most of its first three years. It fell to No. 62
in its last year.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the blame for the show's abrupt demise was placed on
Butler, who had sought drug treatment during a previous season,
according to reports in USA Today and other sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have decided to suspend production on `Grace Under Fire' so
that Brett may have time to resolve personal issues,'' the show's
production company, Carsey-Werner, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why is Stanford's mascot a Cardinal with no ``s'' instead of
the Cardinals?
</P>
<P>
   _ W.D., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: Cardinal is singular because it refers to a color rather than
birds or Catholic Church officials.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford adopted Cardinal as its athletic nickname in 1972 to
replace Indians. The change was prompted by concerns that the
Indians name and a mascot caricature were insensitive to Native
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford teams were called the Cardinals until 1930. The
school's mascot now is The Tree, which has been a symbol of the
school since its founding.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
