<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern happenings
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Thomasville, Ga. _ Victorian Christmas Thursday and Friday is
an old-fashioned holiday celebration on the bricked streets of
downtown, including shopping, carriage rides, storytelling, music,
entertainment, Father Christmas and food. Victorian costumes
encouraged. 1-800-704-2350. Also, Saturday at the Lapham-Patterson
House Historic Site: ``Pages From Christmas Ages,'' an evening of
holiday storytelling. 912-225-4004.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chatsworth, Ga. _ The Chief Vann House Historic Site hosts
``Candlelight Christmas Evenings'' Thursday through Saturday,
honoring a tradition begun in 1805 when Cherokee Chief James Vann
invited Moravian missionaries to his mansion for one of the first
Christmas celebrations in the Cherokee Indian Nation. 706-695-2598.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Helen, Ga. _ ``Deck the Halls,'' Saturday at Unicoi State
Park. Learn to make a wildlife tree for your backyard and make
ornaments that are edible for wildlife, and other Christmas nature
crafts. Choir music will be featured Saturday night in decorated
Unicoi Lodge, which will have a holiday buffet for $6.95. The gift
shop, featuring local crafts, will be open. 706-878-3983. (For
lodging packages, call 706-878-2201.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Opelika, Ala. _ The North Opelika Historic Neighborhood is the
setting for ``Victorian Front Porch Christmas'' Thursday-Sunday.
Porches of more than 30 turn-of-the-century homes are decorated
with life-size Santas, children, angels and other figures by local
artist Jan Jones. Streets open for driving and walking tours
Thursday, Friday and Sunday. 1-800-321-8880.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Montgomery _ Alabama Shakespeare Festival presents ``Toad of
Toad Hall,'' A.A. Milne's adaptation of the classic Kenneth Grahame
story, ``The Wind in the Willows.'' Opens Thursday. Through Dec.
31. 1-800-841-4273.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Franklin, Tenn. _ The 13th annual ``Dickens of a Christmas''
Saturday and Sunday in the restored Victorian downtown features
costumed characters, ``living windows'' of artists and
craftspeople, strolling minstrels, street vendors, horse-drawn
carriages, theater performances, and traditional food.
615-791-9924.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Memphis _ Christmas at Graceland through Jan. 8 features the
same decorations Elvis used to decorate the trees _ one in every
room _ at his mansion. Special exhibits include toys he gave to
Lisa Marie throughout her childhood. 1-800-238-2000.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hattiesburg, Miss. _ Victorian Candlelight Christmas Saturday
and Sunday features luminaries lining the streets of the historic
district, a gifts bazaar, carriage rides and entertainment.
601-545-7620.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Winston-Salem, N.C. _ Old Salem Christmas on Dec. 19
celebrates the simple back-country Christmas as Moravian brass
bands roam the streets playing carols. Restored buildings are lit
with beeswax candles. 1-888-860-4069.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hendersonville, N.C. _ The Historic Johnson Farm Country
Christmas Open House on Saturday features music, hot cider and
tours of the late 19th-century tobacco farm that became a popular
summer retreat in the early 20th century. 704-891-6585.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dillsboro, N.C. _ The 14th Annual Dillsboro Lights and
Luminaire is Friday and Saturday. The four-block downtown with
50-plus shops, galleries, restaurants and inns will glow with
luminaries and white lights. For information, call the Jackson
County Chamber of Commerce at 1-800-962-1911.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Seagrove, N.C. _ The Fourth Annual Christmas in Seagrove Open
House Weekend is Friday through Sunday at the studios of 14 local
potteries in the historic pottery community. 336-873-7966.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pine Mountain, Ga. _ Fantasy in Lights, Callaway Gardens'
ride-through light and sound holiday celebration, opens Friday.
Through Dec. 27. 1-800-225-5292.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pigeon Forge, Tenn. _ Dollywood Smoky Mountain Christmas
through Dec. 30 includes more than 2 million lights, holdiay
entertainment, festive foods and shopping. 423-428-9488. Dixie
Stampede Dinner and Show, a Dollywood Prouction, presents
``Christmas at Dixie'' with 32 horses in a holiday show that
includes a live nativity scene and Santa arriving in a sleigh.
1-800-356-1676. Winterfest Trolley Tour of Lights at 6:30 p.m.
Mondays, Wednesdays and Fridays during November and December ($3
per person; reservations recommended) from the Funtime Trolley
Station. 423-453-6444.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
