<HEADER>
A8789 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GETAWAY09-COX     12-08 1478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Williamsburg puts on finery with celebration fit for 1774
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLIAMSBURG, Va._ Christmas arrived in the Colonial capital on
a beautiful July day _ or so it seemed.
</P>
<P>
   As 18th-century-style troubadors sang of wassailing on
snow-covered ground, temperatures peaked near 80 degrees during the
Grand Illumination weekend that climaxed Sunday night with stirring
fife and drum corps concerts and booming fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   By late Sunday afternoon, crowds estimated at 30,000 had flooded
into the173-acre living history village known as Colonial
Williamsburg, where it's always 1774.
</P>
<P>
   They ambled up and down the mile-long Duke of Gloucester Street
to view the 18th-century style decorations _ all natural, including
pine boughs, cones, dried pods, pomegranates, pineapples, lemons,
limes and apples. And they awaited dark when candles would glow
from windows of the more than 500 restored or re-created public
buildings, houses, taverns and trade shops.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere, the buzz was the unseasonably warm weather.
</P>
<P>
   How hot was it?
</P>
<P>
   It was so hot most folks opted for summer picnic attire, and
those who insisted on wearing their favorite Christmas sweaters
looked positively wilted.
</P>
<P>
   It was so hot you wondered if the apples on the della robia
wreaths on doors might bake.
</P>
<P>
   It was so hot one carriage driver swore it had been cooler back
in July.
</P>
<P>
   And at the beverage stands that had been set up to serve the
crowds, icy cold bottles of water far outsold libations such as
steaming cider and cocoa.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the heat, most seemed happy to be a part of the
throng.
</P>
<P>
   The Hughes family from Annapolis, Md. _ all dressed in shorts
mom threw in the car at the last minute _ were taking advantage of
the balmy conditions. Colleen Hughes watched her husband, Harold,
and children Kelsey, 8, and Cameron, 4, frolic with a glider
airplane on a sloping field near the power magazine across from the
Courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like Christmas and it looks like Christmas, but it
doesn't feel like Christmas,'' she says. ``But it's sooo glorious.
We think of it as a Christmas gift.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with the Fourth of July, Christmas _ especially the
weekend of Grand Illumination, always the first Sunday in December
_ is the busiest time of the year for Colonial Williamsburg.
</P>
<P>
   During the past weekend, there was no room at the Inn. That is
the Williamsburg Inn, as well as the Lodge, Woodlands and
Governor's Inn, the group of Colonial Williamsburg-owned hotels.
They were booked solid months ago, and by Friday every nearby
lodgings had no vacanies.
</P>
<P>
   Through the remainder of the holiday season, it will be
difficult but not impossible to find a place to stay. Reservations
at both Colonial Williamsburg lodgings in the historic area and the
many motels and hotels within a few miles are limited. You'll have
a much better chance if you travel midweek.
</P>
<P>
   In the Visitors Center and other ticket venues, the Sold Out
signs had gone up over most of the special day and evening programs
such as Holiday Decorations Walking Tours, Holiday Lanthorn
(lantern) Tours of Trade Shops and ``Dance, Our Dearest Diversion''
at the Capitol. Carriage rides sold out for the entire day by 10:30
a.m. Saturday and weren't even offered Sunday because so many
pedestrians were expected. Lines to tour the most popular historic
sites such as the Governor's Palace were even longer than usual.
Some visitors reported waiting up to an hour to get inside.
</P>
<P>
   Programs will remain in high demand through Jan. 3. But keep in
mind that you can enjoy the decorations and the historic ambience
even if you don't take part in the special programs.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, there are no lines at the Abby Aldrich Rockefeller
Folk Art Center, featuring its annual holiday exhibition, ``Toys
and Joys,'' or at the DeWitt Wallace Gallery, featuring ``Treasure
Quest: Great Silver Collections of Colonial Williamsburg'' and
``Furniture of the American South.''
</P>
<P>
   And while you may find that ticketed dinner events and musical
programs _ such as the wonderful ``Profound Joy,'' traditional
music and song presented by acoustic soloist Timothy Seaman _ are
sold out, wandering entertainers pop up on the streets and in the
taverns.
</P>
<P>
   Getting a table in one of the historic area's taverns _
Christiana Campbell's, King's Arms and Shields _ was a challenge
for those without reservations on Grand Illumination weekend and
will continue to be. Waits were long for Chownings _ the only
tavern to offer first-come, first-serve seatings. Even Trellis, a
popular restaurant in Merchant's Square, adjacent to the historic
area, turned the hungry away (unless they wished to wait for a 9:30
p.m. seating).
</P>
<P>
   The key to enjoying Grand Illumination weekend in Colonial
Williamsburg is planning ahead. A year ahead isn't a bad idea. A
desk clerk at Williamsburg Lodge said some people come every year
and make their next year's reservations when they check out.
</P>
<P>
   But for regulars such as Georgia and Vince Cassano of Virginia
Beach, 50 miles away, the inconveniences are worth it. They didn't
need overnight lodging, but they couldn't snag a parking place
nearer than a mile away.
</P>
<P>
   After the fireworks ended, they stood near _ but not too near _
a roaring bonfire, drinking in the festive scene as a ladies' choir
sang ``Walking in a Winter Wonderland'' on the Courthouse steps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been to some (illuminations) when it was so cold we wore
hooded coats and gloves and brought wool blankets and sat real
close together and were still freezing,'' says Vince Cassano.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just love the Colonial period,'' says Georgia Cassano.
``There's something about it that is just magic.''
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there:
</P>
<P>
   AirTran is offering a special sale of $49 each way to Newport
News/Williamsburg through Thursday; otherwise, it's $59 each way on
a 14-day advance purchase.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tickets: The best deal is a Patriot's Pass, which is good for
one year. Cost is $34 for adults; $19, children. Includes
orientation walk, history walks, all exhibits and museums, and
discount on evening events (except during the holiday season).
One-and two-day passes are also available.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Staying over: The Colonial Williamsburg lodgings are heavily
booked through the rest of the month, but there is limited
availability, primarily on weekdays. Call 1-800-447-8679. (This
number is also for dining and ticketed program reservations.) For
lodging outside the historic area, call the Williamsburg Hotel &AMP;
Motel Association at 1-800-899-8462 or check online at
http://www.williamsburg.com/index.html
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dining: The taverns in the historic area are the most fun
places to eat, because you'll not only dine on historically
inspired dishes by candlelight (at night), but you'll be
entertained by performers who stroll from room to room. Our
favorite is King's Arms Tavern, where the specialty is ``Mrs.
Vobe's Dinner,'' including the most unusual but very tasty peanut
soup, pan seared chicken, Smithfield ham with a raisin currant
sauce, cornbread dressing and pecan pie. (The roast pork ``game of
the day'' entree was also a winner as was the lamb.) Other options
include Christiana Campbell's Tavern, Shield's Tavern and
Chowning's Tavern. Reservations: 1-800-447-8679.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Planning ahead: Call 1-800-447-8679 to request a copy of
``Your Official Guide to Christmas Past'' for 1998 and indicate
that you want to receive a mailing as soon as tickets for 1999
holiday programs are scheduled. As Christmas is considered peak
season, it's not too early to go ahead and secure a room for next
year. You'll have to guarantee the reservation, but you'll be set.
The priciest accommodations are at Williamsburg Inn (in the
$300-plus range), followed by Williamsburg Lodge ($200-plus) and
Woodlands and Governor's Inn ($100-plus). Ask about packages, but
don't anticipate any ``deals.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Call Colonial Williamsburg at 1-800-447-8679.
</P>
<P>
   A horse and carriage passes the Courthouse on Duke of Gloucester
Street in Colonial Williamsburg's Historic Area. Holiday programs
at Colonial Williamsburg offer a pleasing holiday escape from the
hustle and bustle and commercialization of modern life, to time
long before the phrase, 'batteries not included.' Credit: Colonial
Williamsburg
</P>
<P>
   During Colonial Williamsburg's first-ever holiday decorations
symposium, participants will learn to create their own
Williamsburg-style celebration. Colonial Williamsburg floral
designers, bakers and chefs teach participants to make interior and
exterior decorations, gingerbread houses and create memorable
holiday meals. Credit: Colonial Williamsburg.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
