r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX     12-08 0454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME PHRASES NEVER GET WORN-OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unlike clothing, where everything old is new again, verbal
expressions, particularly slang, usually become extinct long before
the generation that coined them.
</P>
<P>
   For example, I never hear anyone shouting ``Power to the
people!'' or ``Way to go, Daddy-0!'' anymore. When was the last
time you heard someone utter the words ``Make love, not war'' or
``Thank you. Your thoughtfulness is appreciated?''
</P>
<P>
   OK, scratch that last one. That phrase isn't obsolete yet, but
it is definitely on the endangered-sentences list.
</P>
<P>
   However, as a parent, I miss one expression most of all.
</P>
<P>
   Remember when your children were young and just starting to
assert their independence? I can recall so many occasions when I
tried to help my toddlers with a task and they told me, ``I can do
it.'' No matter how big a rush I was in or how much they were
struggling, they wouldn't allow me to assist them. Even now, I'm
having flashbacks of little shoes on the wrong foot and shirts
buttoned awry. When he was 3, my son put his pants on backward and
insisted on wearing them that way all day.
</P>
<P>
   That reminds me of a joke that I heard once: You know it's time
to go on a diet when you put your pants on backward and they fit
better.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, after much tongue biting and hand wringing, I finally
saw my kids reach the point where they could indeed do it and do it
well. They mastered the fine art of using a spoon, knife, and fork.
We're still working on chewing with our mouths closed, however.
When they select their clothes and dress themselves, everything
actually matches.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, we've come a long way but in the process, something got
left behind.
</P>
<P>
   What ever happened to, ``I can do it?''
</P>
<P>
   Now, when I say, ``I need for someone to take out the garbage,''
no one volunteers, ``I can do it!''
</P>
<P>
   When I ask whose turn it is to do the dishes, I'm never told,
``I can do it!''
</P>
<P>
   My car is sitting in the driveway covered in mud, but when I
suggested that the boys wash it for me, one of them said, ``I think
the weatherman said it's going to rain tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then never mind,'' I replied sarcastically. ``I wouldn't want
you guys to get wet. You might catch a cold.''
</P>
<P>
   Their solemn response was familiar:
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you, Mom. Your thoughtfulness is appreciated.''
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St.,
Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
