<DOCNO> NYT19981208.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8812 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIVE-OIL-HNS &LR;      12-08 1332
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIVE-OIL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLIVE OIL FAD SPREADS, AND SO DO THE PRODUCERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DEBBY MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ They stand in a huddle, sniffing tiny cups. They
take small sips, rolling the liquid over their tongues and sucking
in a bit of air to develop the flavors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fruity, with a peppery finish,'' says one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buttery, pleasantly bitter,'' says another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well-balanced with herbal flavors and a nice assertiveness,''
chimes in one more.
</P>
<P>
   Good lord. Not another wine tasting. That is so '80s.
</P>
<P>
   No, it's an olive oil tasting, and it's all the rage.
</P>
<P>
   California is in the throes of another food revolution,
reminiscent of the boutique vineyard explosion that put California
winemaking on the world map in the 1970s and '80s.
</P>
<P>
   Little artisan grower-producers of condiment-quality olive oils
are popping up all over the place, growing from three or so in 1990
to more than 50 today.
</P>
<P>
   In just the past few years, 1,000 new olive trees have been
planted in California. Robert Mondavi has plans to plant as many as
2,000 trees on acreage recently cleared of grapes.
</P>
<P>
   What it all means is that we're in for a whole new breed of
cocktail party bore, the olive oil snob.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the vocabulary is developing, and it's not just ``extra
virgin'' (which means first pressing) anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freerun'' (the oil that drips from the paste, without further
extraction techniques). ``Stone mill vs. hammer mill'' (traditional
granite wheel vs. enclosed metal mechanical crusher).
``Unfiltered.'' ``Olio nuovo.'' Go ahead. Join the party chat.
</P>
<P>
   These and other terms turn up in a proliferation of new books on
olives, oils and oil making that have hit the shelves. Every foodie
magazine this year has carried full features on the stuff. You
could go blind prowling through the Internet, flitting from Web
site to Web site devoted to olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can go take a look and a taste or two, right now.
</P>
<P>
   December is high season for olive harvesting, and since the oil
ideally should be pressed within 24 hours of picking, it's a busy
time in the mills.
</P>
<P>
   At Mill Valley's Frantoio restaurant and olive oil mill last
week, Ridgely Evers and his wife, Colleen McGlynn, oversaw the
pressing of 2 1/2 tons, just one day's harvest of their 4,500 olive
trees in Healdsburg for their Da Vero label. They expect to produce
in the neighborhood of 600 gallons of oil, up from 25 gallons their
first year in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The olive harvesting season runs from late October to March,
depending on weather and desired degree of ripeness, and Evers and
McGlynn's ranch is now close to completely harvested.
</P>
<P>
   They found an empty container and brought a few ounces of the
freshly pressed oil to the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike wine, once olive oil is pressed, it's a finished
product,'' Evers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes out of the spigot, it's done,'' McGlynn agreed,
drizzling some of the stunningly green, startlingly pungent olio
nuovo over her garbanzo bean soup. ``It needs no further
manipulation.''
</P>
<P>
   The whole trick to making a good olive oil, then, is simply
using good olives. And getting the oil out of them as quickly as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Off the tree, olives are susceptible to mildew. A bruised olive
might begin to rot.
</P>
<P>
   It's nice to have a mill nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Frantoio (named for the Italian word for olive mill), opened
three years ago to capitalize on the emerging popularity of olive
oil and Tuscan-style cooking in California. The restaurant produces
its own line of olive oil, and makes the mill available to other
growers such as Evers and McGlynn to crush olives _ pits and all,
by the way _ for independent labels.
</P>
<P>
   Other mills have come into being as the need has arisen, some
even closer to the olive orchards.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, Gregory Reisinger, president and general
manager of B.R. Cohn's Olive Hill oil company, drove a truckload of
petite picholine olives _ which mere moments before had been
dangling from limbs in the Sonoma sun _ 2 miles to a mill in Glen
Ellen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to have to take them to Modesto,'' he said. ``We'd
have to wait until we had picked enough to be worth the trip.''
</P>
<P>
   That was in 1992, when vintner Bruce Cohn first made good on his
``threat'' to make oil from the 500 neglected 120-year-old olive
trees that dotted his vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Cohn and a cooperative of 14 investors, including
Chalone, Lila Jaeger, Iron Horse and Spectrum Naturals, established
the Olive Press to accommodate the pressing needs of oil producers
in the area, many of whom, like Cohn, were winemakers who had olive
trees on their property.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper heiress Nan McEvoy went them one better. Upon learning
that the Petaluma ranch property she purchased in 1990 was strictly
zoned for agricultural use, she planted 11,000 olive trees and had
a state-of-the-art olive press built right on the ranch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get interested in food, it kind of takes over,'' she
said last month during the ranch's fourth annual harvest.
</P>
<P>
   Like Frantoio and the Olive Press, McEvoy's mill is available
for crushing olives of other growers. The cost to the customer
depends on the quantity of olives and the method used. The classic
granite wheel and painstaking sinolea oil extraction are more
expensive than the modern metallic hammer mill and mechanical
separation. Both are used at the McEvoy Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   The Olive Press uses only the hammer mill method; Frantoio uses
only the granite wheel and traditional mat pressing. Of the various
approaches, Reisinger said, ``The best technology is the one you've
invested in.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the method, the experience is exhilarating. It's loud,
aromatic and, in some cases, slippery. Machinery rumbles. The air
smells intensely green and fruity as the newborn oil dribbles into
holding vats. Oil makers sample the fresh unfiltered stuff, judging
body, color and flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Reisinger coughed once or twice when the peppery single-varietal
picholine oil hit the back of his throat.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something people say in the industry,'' Evers said with
a laugh. ``A `one-cough, a two-cough or a three-cough' oil.''
</P>
<P>
   Evers blends four Italian olive varieties to achieve a
Tuscan-style balance. He selected his trees by finding the grower
of an Italian oil he admired and importing saplings to his
Healdsburg ranch.
</P>
<P>
   McEvoy uses the same four Italian varieties, in about the same
proportions.
</P>
<P>
   Other producers use different varieties and blends, even
extracting oil from humble mission and manzanilla olives _ ``eating
olives,'' you might call them.
</P>
<P>
   Still others are resurrecting long-forgotten orchards. And new
varieties are being test-farmed in 10 California locations,
according to Reisinger, past president of the 7-year-old California
Olive Oil Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``My only concern right now with some of the plantings is a
focus on Italian varietals,'' he said. ``I would like to see French
varietals, Spanish varietals. I think that's what will put us on
the map.''
</P>
<P>
   By ``us,'' Reisinger means all California gourmet olive oil
producers. It's a friendly community.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I like about the olive oil industry is how people will
share their ideas and their experiences,'' he said. ``Anything that
benefits one person benefits the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   California olive oil accounts for no more than a tenth of a
percent of the world's olive oil at present. Boutique olive oil is
expensive, running in the neighborhood of $20 for 12 ounces, and is
not yet a profitable endeavor for most of its manufacturers, many
of whom came into the field with fortunes made elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``To buy property in Sonoma just to produce olives would make no
sense financially,'' Reisinger said.
</P>
<P>
   Cohn, who moonlights as manager of a rock band, tells his
version of an old joke: ``You know how to make a small fortune in
olive oil? Start with a large one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
