<DOCNO> NYT19981208.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8851 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-GIFTS-HNS &LR;      12-08 1243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-GIFTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIR ALEC GUINNESS OFFERS A LESS-THAN RETIRING TALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOBBIE HESS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If you need a stocking stuffer for the reader on
your list, pick up a copy of Alec Guinness' delightful ``My Name
Escapes Me _ The Diary of a Retiring Actor.''
</P>
<P>
   Now available in paperback from Penguin Books ($12.95, 198
pages), the diary looks back at 18 months in Guinness' life from
January 1995 to June 1996. An homage in the form of a preface is
written by author John le Carre, whose character George Smiley was
brilliantly brought to life on TV by Guinness.
</P>
<P>
   Le Carre begins by saying, ``He is not a comfortable companion.
Why should he be? The watching child inside the 80-year-old man has
still found no safe harbors or easy answers. The deprivations and
humiliations of three quarters of a century ago are unresolved. It
is as though he were still striving to appease the adult world
about him; to winkle love from it, to beg its smile, to deflect or
harness its monstrosity. ... God forbid that I should paint him as
a stern man. Alec's bubbling laughter and good fellowship, when
they come, are all the more miraculous for the uncertain weather
that preceded them.''
</P>
<P>
   The man Sir Alec shares with the world is many men _ a devoted
husband, caring father, an aging actor coping with the ills of old
age, a modern man who takes swipes at politicians and fools (not
necessarily in that order), a reader with a wicked sense of humor,
a traveler who inhales the world around him.
</P>
<P>
   Living outside London, Guinness and his wife, Merula, deal with
everyday living _ feeding the goldfish in the pond, selecting which
wine to pour with dinner, picking the best of the evening's
offerings on television, which book to take to bed.
</P>
<P>
   Following are some of Guinness' musings:
</P>
<P>
   New Year's Day, 1995: ``A sudden little blizzard made us too
apprehensive to drive the couple miles to Mass in the evening, so I
threw a log on the fire and mixed a lethal cocktail called, I
believe, the Claridge (half-and-half gin and French vermouth, with
a good dash of Cointreau and apricot brandy). That kept our eyes
slightly unfocused on the TV production of ``Cold Comfort Farm.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Feb. 14: ``A Valentine card in a tiny illiterate hand.
Surely I can't have sent a card to myself. Now that Dr. Alzheimer
looks as if he may be extending a welcome to me I can no longer be
sure of these things.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, June 7: ``Took delivery of a splendid new Wheel-Horse
motor mower called Toro. It seems capable of doing almost
everything but cook dinner. It looks lovely at the moment but I see
an alarming glint in the lady gardener's eye _ I think she is
imagining herself winning Le Mans or Monaco.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Oct. 25: ``On Monday night the heavens fell; or,
rather, Merula did, heavily, tripping on a paving stone. She has
broken her right hip and was in great pain, which she bore with her
usual fortitude. ... She is being operated on as I write. ... The
hospital has just telephoned to say all went well.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Jan. 6, 1996: ``When I played Malvolio in a poor TV
`Twelfth Night,' Larry (Olivier) came to the final run-through ...
Just before we went on the air he said to me, `Marvelous, old cock!
I never realized Malvolio could be played as a bore.' Such-like
encouragements were part of his repertoire. Yet I was fond of
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, May 6: Ealing Studios never succeeded in killing me in
spite of some quite good tries, the first of which was during the
making of `The Lavender Hill Mob.' Rehearsing a brief scene in
which Stanley (Holloway) and I were required to escape from the top
of the Eiffel Tower, the director (Charlie Crichton) said, `Alec,
there is a trap door over there _ where it says Workmen Only _ I'd
like you to run to it, open it and start running down the spiral
staircase. Stanley will follow.' So I did as asked. A very dizzying
sight to the ground greeted me. But I completed half a spiral
before I noticed that three feet in front of me the steps suddenly
ceased _ broken off. I sat promptly down where I was and cautiously
started to shift myself back to the top, warning Stanley to get out
of the way. `What the hell are you doing?' the director yelled.
`Down. Further down.' `Further down is eternity,' I called back.''
</P>
<P>
   Guinness has always been one of my favorite actors. He is now
one of my favorite writers. ``My Name Escapes Me'' is a charming
glimpse into the life of a complex yet simple man _ sometimes
cantankerous, often amusing, always bright. I can't think of a
better way to spend a few hours than curled up with this
all-too-brief glimpse into the life of a great actor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Red Zone.'' By Tim Green. Warner Books. $24. 325 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth mystery by the former NFL pro is an intriguing look
at the world of professional football.
</P>
<P>
   Madison McCall is the top defense lawyer for her Austin, Texas,
firm. When a partner dies, the firm presses her to take on its
sports agency clients, which she balks at. However, when the dead
partner's aide, Chris Pelo, gets his walking papers, McCall agrees
to help him renegotiate the contract of Luther Zorn, an inside
linebacker for the Florida Marauders.
</P>
<P>
   Before the contract is worked out, Marauder owner Evan Chase is
killed, and Zorn is the prime suspect because he was having an
affair with the owner's wife. Next, Zorn's girlfriend disappears,
and evidence linked to Chase's murder is found at her home.
</P>
<P>
   McCall is sure that Zorn is being set up, but by whom and why?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Red Zone'' is one of the better mysteries of the last few
months _ good plot, well-paced, interesting characters, decent
dialogue. And you don't have to be a football fan to enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Widow Killer.'' By Pavel Kohout. Translated by Neil
Bermel. St. Martin's Press. $24.95. 391 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Kohout's murder mystery, set in Prague in the final months of
the Third Reich, is a good book, but a very difficult one to
navigate because there are two books here. One is a compelling tale
of a sadistic killer; the second is a look at the relationship
between the Czech police and the Gestapo.
</P>
<P>
   The widow of a German general has been murdered and then
ritualistically carved up. Jan Morava, a young assistant detective
for the Prague police, is given the case. Since the widow was a
German, the Gestapo assigns Irwin Brubeck to the case. But Brubeck
has a second assignment _ to spy on the Czechs so that when the end
of the war nears, the Germans won't be overtaken.
</P>
<P>
   As more widows are butchered, Morava and Brubeck begin to
respect each other. Each man has a romance, but both use their
lovers as bait to lure the killer into a trap. Unfortunately,
Morava's love is killed because the Gestapo did not fulfill its
commitment. Almost crazed, Morava pushes on, and he and Brubeck
learn the killer's name, but they cannot find him. As the Russians
near Prague, the killer joins a rogue group of Czech Revolutionary
Guards and begins killing at random.
</P>
<P>
   Bermel does an excellent job of translating. Kohout offers up a
truly terrific mix of characters in a very good plot. But the moral
dilemmas thrown at the main characters really slow the story down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Widow Killer'' should have been one of the best mysteries
of the year. But Kohout overreaches. A good editor could have made
this work.
</P>
</TEXT>
