<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8886 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-REPLAYS-HNS &LR;      12-08 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REPLAYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFS' MISTAKES COSTLY IN MANY WAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GWEN KNAPP  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ On its back page Monday, a New York tabloid
called NFL officials divine.
</P>
<P>
   ``God's a Jets fan,'' the headline in the Post said, after the
men in stripes, working in increasingly mysterious ways, handed the
New York Jets a win over Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The league begged to differ. On Monday, finally, belatedly, the
NFL declared its officials far too human.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the New York headquarters came the news that the league
would consider using limited instant replay in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets game Sunday left no choice. The officials, just when
they needed to be on their best behavior, gave Vinny Testaverde a
last-minute touchdown that he never scored.
</P>
<P>
   This was too much, in the week after two respected team owners
paid $50,000 for the luxury of criticizing them, in the week after
officials gave New England more do-overs than a parent teaching a
4-year-old how to play checkers.
</P>
<P>
   It all kept adding up. From Indianapolis to Oakland to Arizona,
everyone had a genuine gripe. This was fast becoming the Season
Through the Looking Glass, heavy on pass-interference
hallucinations.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the NFL put out the word that the officials weren't
making more mistakes than usual. They had just made a few at the
wrong time _ on an overtime coin toss that robbed Pittsburgh and
two final plays that beat Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   But in Monday's instant-replay proposal, the league acknowledged
the obvious _ that errors on last-second plays are less forgivable.
</P>
<P>
   For the playoffs, the plan would allow each team to challenge
one play per half. But the limit would be liberal, allowing a club
to use an extra challenge on any last-minute, deciding play.
</P>
<P>
   This sort of flexibility is fairly out of character for the NFL.
So is the spontaneity behind the replay suggestion. What next?
Dropping the television blackout rule, just because everyone has a
warm spot for Al Davis?
</P>
<P>
   The NFL finally wised up because the only option was sticking
with an argument that defeated itself. The NFL favors the human
element in officiating, with all its flaws. But, in defense of its
crews last week, it tried to strip the soul out of a game's final
plays, pretend that they have no special value.
</P>
<P>
   Stick with that theory, and the word ``clutch'' fades from the
sports vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   Why is Mitch Williams a goat for giving up a three-run homer? A
lot of relievers give up three-run homers. Because Williams gave
one up in the bottom of the ninth inning of Game 6 in the
Phillies-Blue Jays World Series. His team had a lead before he
threw the pitch, and a long winter after he threw it.
</P>
<P>
   He took away his team's last chance. But at least, he was a
player. When an official does the same thing, it's intolerable.
Human, yes, but still intolerable.
</P>
<P>
   For the NFL, the problem reached critical mass last weekend. The
AFC East standings are now hopelessly warped. The Patriots and Jets
each have a win they don't deserve. The Bills have a loss they
don't deserve.
</P>
<P>
   The mistakes may not cost anybody a playoff berth in the end.
But here's one small measure of the errors: Doug Flutie's low-ball
contract with Buffalo is laden with incentives. If the Bills finish
over .500, he gets a big salary bump for each additional victory.
His 1999 salary is supposed to be based partly on this season's
earnings. With the bogus defeat against New England, Flutie stands
to lose at least $750,000 in the next 14 months.
</P>
<P>
   For the league as a whole, the losses are intangible, but still
devastating. Consider this snide exchange in the ABC booth Monday
night, when the Green Bay Packers had 3 seconds left against Tampa
Bay, a two-point deficit and no shot at a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a touchdown or bust.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, maybe not a touchdown or bust.'' A small laugh. ``There
could be pass interference.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's ever seen pass interference called on a Hail Mary?''
Another small laugh. ``I haven't seen it in eight days.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL started this season in a funk, tedium dominating on
every channel. It has recovered magnificently, with the perfection
of the Broncos, the dramatic struggles in Green Bay, the revelation
of Flutie, the revival of Randall Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   The AFC East is spectacularly competitive. The NFC is terribly
flawed, but in 13 days, there will be a showdown that no one could
have imagined. Saints vs. Cardinals, with a possible playoff berth
in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, more and more games are being decided in the final
seconds. Sports leagues thrive on this sort of suspense, on
``touchdown or bust,'' with no disclaimers needed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-98 1700EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981208.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8890 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTLAND-PHEASANTS-AR     12-08 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTLAND-PHEASANTS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 TARVES: greenish color.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The rearing process begins when the season ends in February and
the female birds are lured into cages by food and then put into
fields with cocks. Once in place, pheasants stay put. ``Pheasants
would walk everywhere instead of flying if they could,'' Andrew
said.
</P>
<P>
   Eggs are laid in late March or April and, aided by incubation,
hatch in May. In the early weeks, the chicks are fed pelletized
food, but within six to eight weeks, their diet includes barley,
wheat and maize from the estate. They are then transferred to
100-square-yard release pens in the woods with room to roam. By 12
weeks they are trying out their newly sprouted flight feathers.
</P>
<P>
   By October, some 9,000 grown pheasants are on the estate. There
seem to be as many skittering across roads and darting around stone
walls as hunkering down in wooded areas, copses or overgrown
cottage ruins. ``Like any of us, they like warm places,'' Lord
Haddo said. They take to the air only when roused, springing from
the ground in bursts of energy that last only eight seconds before
they have to glide to a landing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have eight guns and four wives for lunch,'' Lord Haddo
cheerfully told the women in the kitchen, who were cutting up
chicken parts and smoked bacon for the noontime huntsman's pie. The
``guns,'' the invited shooters, were arriving in the driveway,
every one in olive tweeds, a tattersall shirt, game-bird necktie
and insulated wellies, the all-purpose Wellington boots, which have
sheltered the feet of farmers and outdoors people in the British
Isles for generations.
</P>
<P>
   A typical ``driven'' shooting goes to six sites during the day,
with retreats from the chill wind to break into flasks of mulled
wine. At each drive, or spot where birds are driven out, there are
numbered stakes known as pegs, corresponding to the number the
individual shooter has for that drive.
</P>
<P>
   Once they are in place, 20 men known as beaters come up gingerly
behind the birds, waving flags and shaking rough-hewn wooden
rattles. A first-time visitor asked Andrew if it was the tradition
to use blue flags. ``No,'' he confided. ``It's just that fertilizer
sacks come in that color.''
</P>
<P>
   It is part of the beaters' skill not to scare all the birds up
at once, and they scatter from cover and soar over the shooters in
waves. Most make it to the other side of the clearing. Dogs tear
through the brush after fallen birds and bring them back to one of
the five pickers-up, who put them in their side bags.
</P>
<P>
   The cry ``Don't shoot'' goes up if the bird is an owl, a
songbird, a hawk or some other protected species. ``Continental
Europeans will shoot anything that moves,'' Lord Haddo said, taking
his own shot at Britons' favorite targets. Andrew summoned a look
of disgust. ``The French shoot larks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A qualmish question about killing birds came up, and Lord Haddo
turned mildly scornful. ``I would say the expression `birdbrain'
applies perfectly to pheasants,'' he said. ``I'm often amused when
people talk about giving birds their rights. Well, if you gave
pheasants rights, they'd all be in jail for murder and gang rape.
They are ferocious to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The higher the flight, the greater the sporting challenge and
the happier the estate owner. ``Exciting birds,'' Lord Haddo
exclaimed as a clutch rose above the trees. ``It's my challenge to
put as high a bird as possible out. Low birds should not be shot
at. They should be allowed to fly another day.''
</P>
<P>
   At one drive, Lord Haddo quietly told a newcomer whose aim kept
dropping: ``Make sure there's a bit of sky. Otherwise, the beaters
can get anxious.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the beaters feel they've chased all the birds from one
spot, they blow a whistle, and the group moves on to the next
drive. On the Haddo estate, an old British railroad maintenance car
attached to a John Deere tractor transports the keepers. The guns
in their tweeds travel in cars.
</P>
<P>
   As Lord Haddo, 43, strides his grounds, the history of his own
family, one of Britain's oldest, precedes him. Forty thousand of
the original 65,000 acres had to be sold off in the 1920s to
satisfy bad debts, but Lord Haddo is quick to defend the family
honor. ``I stress that it wasn't things like gambling. It was bad
business sense and too much benevolence.''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out a low red-brick building in a hollow and said
that is where his great-grandmother raised exotic pheasants. Two
hillsides bear monuments memorializing two ancestors _ one a young
colonel who died in the Battle of Waterloo, the other the fourth
Earl of Aberdeen, who was Britain's prime minister from 1852 to
1855.
</P>
<P>
   Back at Bain of Tarves, Duncan and his workers went through the
messy business of handpicking and cleaning the day's pheasants.
Hearing that his visitors had been on a shoot that morning, Duncan
talked about how much people here love their blustery outdoors, and
he asked excitedly if one of the pickers-up had been a woman with a
black dog.
</P>
<P>
   His visitors nodded yes. ``That's my wife,'' he said. He looked
longingly out the factory window at the swirling gray skies closing
in on a newly harvested barley field and a forest of spruce, pine
and larch. ``She's got a fine, bonny job,'' he said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO ORDER
</P>
<P>
   Scottish pheasant is available at specialty stores in New York
and by mail order. Here are some sources:
</P>
<P>
   Agata &AMP; Valentina, 1505 First Ave. (79th Street), (212)
452-0690; $8.95 a pound for male pheasant and $9.95 for female
pheasant; requires three days' notice for orders.
</P>
<P>
   All Food Emporium stores offer Scottish pheasant, at $18.99 a
pound. They require a week's notice.
</P>
<P>
   Balducci's, 424 Avenue of the Americas (Ninth Street), (212)
673-2600; pheasant, $12.49 a pound; requires three days' notice for
orders.
</P>
<P>
   Grace's Marketplace, 1237 Third Ave. (71st Street), (212)
737-0600; $8.99 a pound; requires two days' notice for orders.
</P>
<P>
   The Vinegar Factory, 431 E. 91st St., (212) 987-0885; $8.99 a
pound; requires two days' notice for orders.
</P>
<P>
   Scottish pheasant can also be ordered by mail from D'Artagnan,
(800) 327-8246 or www.dartagnan.com. Male pheasant are $16.95 each
(about 2 pounds); female, $14.20 each (1.25 to 1.75 pounds).
</P>
