<SLUG> BC-NYLITE(SMILE)-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: on you!' ' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Questions about love, marriage and sex were posed to kids ages
5 to 10. Some of their answers below are enlightening: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WHAT DO MOST PEOPLE DO ON A DATE?
</P>
<P>
   `On the first date, they just tell each other lies, and that
usually gets them interested enough to go for a second date.`
</P>
<P>
   (Mike, 10)
</P>
<P>
   CONCERNING WHY LOVE HAPPENS BETWEEN TWO PARTICULAR PEOPLE:
</P>
<P>
   `No one is sure why it happens, but I heard it has something to
do with how you smell. That's why perfume and deodorant are so
popular.` (Jan, 9)
</P>
<P>
   CONCERNING WHY LOVERS OFTEN HOLD HANDS:
</P>
<P>
   `They want to make sure their rings don't fall off because they
paid good money for them.` (Dave, 8)
</P>
<P>
   HOW CAN YOU TELL IF TWO ADULTS EATING DINNER AT A RESTAURANT ARE
IN LOVE?
</P>
<P>
   `Just see if the man picks up the check. That's how you can tell
if he's in love.` (John, 9)
</P>
<P>
   HOW A PERSON LEARNS TO KISS:
</P>
<P>
   `It might help to watch soap operas all day.` (Carin, 9)
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO MAKE LOVE ENDURE:
</P>
<P>
   `Don't forget your wife's name...That will mess up the love.`
</P>
<P>
   (Roger, 8)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THOSE CRAZY PRESBYTERIANS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   After the revival had concluded, the three pastors were
discussing the results with one another.
</P>
<P>
   The Methodist minister said, `The revival worked out great for
us! We gained four new families.`
</P>
<P>
   The Baptist preacher said, `We did better than that! We gained
six new families.`
</P>
<P>
   The Presbyterian pastor said, `Well, we did even better than
that! We got rid of our 10 biggest trouble makers!`
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Deep Thinking &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A day without sunshine is like, night.
</P>
<P>
   Those who live by the sword get shot by those who don't.
</P>
<P>
   He who hesitates is probably right.
</P>
<P>
   The colder the X-ray table, the more of your body is required on
it.
</P>
<P>
   If you must choose between two evils, pick the one you've never
tried before.
</P>
<P>
   Borrow money from pessimists _ they don't expect it back.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUOTABLES FROM NBC'S 'THE TONIGHT SHOW WITH JAY LENO' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``The number one Christmas toy continues to be this stupid Furby
thing. People just act silly over this. It said on the news that
this Furby is a wonderful educational tool. Once you realize you
spent $30 for one, you'll never do anything that stupid again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``First 'Antz' was a big hit, now 'A Bug's Life. Both these
movies have done huge dough. If I had known insects were gonna be
so popular, I would've sold the rights to my old apartment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's something scary. Republican congressman Ed Pease of
Indiana was robbed at gunpoint. In fact, someone yelled, ``Stop,
thief!'' and 200 congressmen froze.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what the Republicans call a woman who hasn't had sex
in seven years? A nymphomaniac.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How many people have done some of their Christmas shopping on
the Internet? I don't know. I tried it, but I feel funny about
giving porno as a Christmas gift.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUOTABLES FROM 'WEEKEND UPDATE' ON NBC's 'SATURDAY NIGHT LIVE' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans are having a breakdown. They've gone mad with
this impeachment thing. They can't let it go. It is an obsession.
They're stalking the President. You have fighters in Islamic Jihads
watching this going, 'Boy, these guys hold a grudge. I mean, let it
go, fellas.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans just can't believe we're not buying this.
Clinton lied to the country and we just don't care. It's like when
they tried to sell professional soccer to Americans. No matter how
right it seemed we were just like ``No, sorry, just don't like
soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
``This week the Republicans brought out other people who lied under
oath about having sex and went to jail for it, (including) a female
psychiatrist who performed oral sex on her male patient. Hey, if
that doesn't cure depression, nothing will.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A new study on smoking released this week shows that people
who quit gain an average of 18 pounds. Tobacco executives are
already lobbying for a new label warning on packs of cigarettes:
'WARNING: QUITTING SMOKING MAY CAUSE SWELLING OF THE ASS.'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CITY STREETS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The male vocal group Lionheart performed recently at the Church
of St. Mary the Virgin in Manhattan. The audience was completely
absorbed in the chants of 12th-century Paris when a shrill ring of
a cell phone brought everyone rudely back to the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   To general astonishment, a woman left her seat, phone to her
ear, and walked behind a nearby sarcophagus where she proceeded to
talk. The audience could hear her, and members of the group on
stage later told me she was telling the person at the other end of
the line that she was ``at a Lionheart concert'' and that ``they're
singing Renaissance music.'' (Note: It was really medieval, but
what's a few centuries?)
</P>
<P>
   The piece over, the men in the ensemble stopped and looked in
her direction, but she continued talking, oblivious to the fact
that now everyone was looking at her. Finally, an irate member of
the audience walked over and urged her to stop or leave.
</P>
<P>
   She then proceeded up the side aisle, still talking, and turned
into a small chapel to continue. The audience was incensed. Another
member walked over, took her by the arm and led her out of the
church, still talking.
</P>
<P>
   Resuming the concert, Richard Porterfield, a member of the
group, said, ``This piece, appropriately, is about the world going
to hell.'' The audience laughed and the concert continued; the
intrusion of the modern era was over.
</P>
<P>
   _ Suzanne L. Ford
</P>
<P>
   On a recent theater trip to New York, Margie and Harry Sheld of
Las Vegas overheard the following conversation before the opening
curtain:
</P>
<P>
   First woman: ``I found a good second-hand store on 26th
Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Second woman: ``Don't go there. It's no good. I bring my stuff
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Nina, the 9-year-old daughter of Ann and Jonathan Dachs, wanted
to know what all the fuss was about when the Starr report came out.
Her parents answered her question as diplomatically as possible.
Nina then asked what the president's punishment would be and, after
a discussion of the process, was told that he could possibly be
indicted.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, when she saw her father reading the paper,
Nina asked whether the president was going to be oranged. After a
second or two, the light dawned. ``You mean impeached, don't you?''
her father asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yes, I knew it had something to do with fruit,'' she
replied.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever the Bell family gets in the car for a trip, long or
short, there's a fight over the CD player. Martin Bell, the father,
wants Bob Dylan; Daniel, the teen-age son, wants Green Day or
Offspring, and Frances, the 9-year-old daughter, screams for the
Spice Girls or some other group du jour. Mrs. Bell tries to play
peacemaker.
</P>
<P>
   One day, as they got into the car anticipating another round in
the music wars, Frances commented that her third-grade class was
studying Bob Dylan. Mrs. Bell asked if she told the teacher that
her Daddy listens to Dylan, hoping that her daughter might now
recognize that Dylan was indeed special.
</P>
<P>
   Frances replied with disdain: ``Everybody's father listens to
Bob Dylan.''
</P>
<P>
   While on the subject of Bob Dylan, Stephen Tympanick thinks this
could be filed under ``you know you're old when ...'' He was at a
yard sale in the Hamptons, perusing the knicknacks, when he saw a
teen-age boy carrying an LP of Dylan's greatest hits.
</P>
<P>
   The boy joined his father and enthusiastically blurted: ``Look
Dad, I found a record by Jakob Dylan's father! I didn't know he was
a musician, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Sue McMahon found a flowering amaryllis bulb in her neighborhood
hardware store and went up to the cashier to pay for it. The clerk
had a problem getting the machine to sum up the purchase with the
tax and called for help. Behind Ms. McMahon, a male customer
shuffled restlessly, constantly checking his watch.
</P>
<P>
   When the transaction was finally completed, the man gave vent to
his irritation. ``That was an awful lot of trouble for an onion,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   A recent story on ``Alice in Wonderland'' reminded Eleanor Roth
of an experience she had in California some time ago.
</P>
<P>
   She was watching her grandniece riding a Wonderland children's
carousel when she noted that the Mad Hatter had a number on his
hat. Why, she wondered, and turned to the young mother standing
next to her. ``Are you familiar with `Alice in Wonderland?''' she
asked.
</P>
<P>
   The woman looked blank. ``I'm from out-of-town,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BILL'S WORLD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   What the kids on Santa's lap are saying: ``Do your elves have a
pretty good 401(k) plan?''
</P>
<P>
   _ (Bill Tammeus, The Kansas City Star)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
