  THIS IS THE STATES NEWS SERVICE BUDGET FOR DEC.
8, 1998. IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS, PLEASE CALL US AT 202-628-3100.
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONNECTICUT -- HUD. Hartford Mayor Michael Peters and Phoenix
Home Life Mutual Insurance Co. CEO Robert W. Fiondella will journey
to Washington tomorrow to talk about Hartford's revitalization
efforts with HUD Secretary Andrew Cuomo. Maggi
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA -- GLADES. Environmentalists squared off Tuesday with
sugar growers, private-property rights activists and taxpayer
advocates during a public hearing on an ambitious $8 billion,
20-year restoration plan for the Florida Everglades. Williams
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA -- SPEND. A final look at campaign fundraising and
spending in the Hollings-Inglis and Coverdell-Coles Senate races.
12-15 inches. (Possible.) Williams
</P>
<P>
   -- WOMEN. More than half of Georgia's displaced homemakers live
in poverty, among the worst in the country, according to a report
released by Women Work! The National Network for Women's
Employment. 8-10 inches. Berman
</P>
<P>
   INDIANA -- AGRICULTURE. Months after the near collapse of the
Long Term Capital Hedge Fund, the Senate Agriculture Committee,
chaired by Sen. Dick Lugar, announced it will hold a hearing next
week. (Working.) Wolfberg
</P>
<P>
   LOUISIANA -- SOCIAL. Sen. John Breaux, D-La., joined a chorus of
Democrats and Republicans vowing a bipartisan effort toward
privatizing some of the nation's Social Security system. But
political leaders said that any reform still faces formidable
political pressures. Stricherz
</P>
<P>
   NEVADA -- THYROID. Scientists renewed their efforts Tuesday to
inform the public about fallout exposure from nearly 100 surface
atom bomb tests at the Nevada Test Site in the 1950s and 1960s,
suspected of causing thyroid cancer. But they issued a joint
warning against developing a national screening program to detect
thyroid cancer because they said it might cause more harm than
good. Preston
</P>
<P>
   NEW JERSEY -- SOCSEC. A wrap-up of today's conference on
reforming Social Security, sponsored by the White House and
attended by Rep. William Pascrell, D-Paterson. Kane
</P>
<P>
   NEW MEXICO -- UDALL. Congressman-elect Tom Udall and his wife
Jill will pack their car New Year's day and head east to Washington
to begin the newest chapter in his political career. But before he
leaves, Udall is faced with the triple task of closing down his
state office and campaign headquarters and establishing his New
Mexico and Washington congressional offices. Gorman
</P>
<P>
   OHIO -- FARM-BILL. (Working for weekend.) With bad weather and
plummeting commodity prices, the 1996 Freedom to Farm Act faced its
first real test since its passage. This year, Congress ended up
doling out nearly $6 billion in emergency spending to help farmers
through a tough season -- problems that may have been solved
through the crop subsidies that were slashed in the farm bill. Does
the bill adequately address the needs of farmers? Hurt
</P>
<P>
   PENNSYLVANIA -- RICK. Sen. Rick Santorum, R-Pa., laid out a
daring plan aimed at privatizing part of the nation's Social
Security system. Reactions from local congressmen. Stricherz
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS -- REAX. Rio Grande Valley lawmakers are refraining from
commenting on the Judiciary committee hearings. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   -- TRADE. Local business groups on the agenda for the 106th
Congress concerning fast track and sanctions (Possible). Brown
</P>
<P>
   WYOMING -- SULLIVAN. Former Wyoming Gov. Michael J. Sullivan,
who was sworn in Tuesday as the U.S. ambassador to Ireland, will
face an unusually difficult first diplomatic assignment when he
starts work in January. Davant
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
