<HEADER>
A8978 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ITALIAN-BOOK-REVIEW-N     12-08 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALIAN-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SIMPLE ITALIAN FOOD': DISTINGUISHED IN ITS SIMPLICITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As testament to the modern celebrity of chefs, Mario Batali's
name appears in larger type than the title of his new book,
``Simple Italian Food'' (Clarkson Potter, $30). And there is a
full-length photograph of Batali clad in chef's whites and orange
kitchen clogs, baring hairy legs.
</P>
<P>
   It's a lot to swallow on a cookbook cover. It's probably best to
keep it open at all times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perfectly pristine ingredients, combined sensibly and cooked
properly, are what make Italian food taste so good,'' writes
Batali, the chef at Po and Babbo in Greenwich Village in New York
City. This is a truism spouted in various forms by many American
chefs.
</P>
<P>
   But when you're trying to distinguish yourself as a chef, it
takes courage to serve straightforward food. Which is why for many
of them, it is more about talking the big game than playing it.
They slip in that extra, unnecessary ingredient. They use tomatoes
out of season. They put too much topping on their bruschetta.
</P>
<P>
   But Batali means what he writes. His recipes deliver the honest
flavors of Italian cooking. And they do it in tantalizing ways.
</P>
<P>
   Mostaccioli with fennel, mint and bread crumbs, a simple pasta
dish, is pure-tasting and delicious. Whole mint leaves, sprinkled
in at the very end of cooking, give the dish a lively edge and
offset the heat from red pepper flakes. And it takes no time to
cook.
</P>
<P>
   Green gnocchi with caduta di formaggio (or ``snowfall of
cheese'') also had a surprise. A little grappa stirred into a
cheese sauce made with Gorgonzola, asiago and plenty of butter
added depth to what could easily be a heavy, monotone sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Small touches in the recipes, like pomegranate seeds in a fennel
and blood-orange salad, and a heady black pepper-oregano oil
sprinkled over crostini with broccoli rape are what make this book
great.
</P>
<P>
   Though there are minor errors, like the omission of salt in the
mostaccioli, they are merely nicks in an otherwise smooth
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Batali reminisces about his years cooking at Trattoria La Volta
in northern Italy and in the Village, but I must admit, I was more
drawn to the recipes than the stories.
</P>
<P>
   You may recognize some of the dishes from the menus at his
restaurants. No matter. Whether they are being served to you or you
are preparing them, they are smart. They are, as promised, simple.
And they make Batali a distinguished chef, even without that goofy
cover photo.
</P>
<P>
   GREEN GNOCCHI WITH CADUTA DI FORMAGGIO &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Simple Italian Food'' by Mario Batali &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   1 pound russet potatoes, scrubbed
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds spinach, stemmed, rinsed and partly dried
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 extra large egg, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sea salt
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces Gorgonzola cheese
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons unsalted butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons grappa
</P>
<P>
   { cups freshly grated asiago cheese
</P>
<P>
   \ cup chopped chives.
</P>
<P>
   1. Place the potatoes in a saucepan, and cover with water. Bring
to a boil, and cook until very tender, 20 to 25 minutes. Drain.
</P>
<P>
   2. Meanwhile, place the spinach in a deep pot with a lid. Cook
over medium heat, allowing the spinach to steam in its own liquid,
1 to 2 minutes. Transfer the spinach to an ice bath to stop the
cooking. Drain well, then wrap the spinach in a clean dish towel
and twist to extact as much liquid as possible. Chop very fine.
</P>
<P>
   3. When the potatoes are cool enough to handle, peel them. Using
the finest setting, run the potatoes through a ricer or food mill
onto a cutting board. Add the spinach. Sprinkle the flour over the
potatoes and spinach; make a well, add the egg and kosher salt, and
knead to form a dough.
</P>
<P>
   4. Divide the dough into 4 balls. Roll each ball into 1-inch
thick ropes, and cut each rope into 1-inch long pieces. Roll each
piece off the tines of a fork to form the classic gnocchi shape.
Place on a lightly floured baking sheet, and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   5. In a deep pot, add the sea salt to 6 quarts of water, and
bring to a boil. While the water heats, in a 12-to-14-inch saute
pan, mash together the Gorgonzola and butter until smooth. Stir in
the grappa, and simmer over medium heat for 4 minutes. Keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   6. Drop the gnocchi into the boiling water, and cook until they
float to the surface, about 1 minute. Do this in 2 batches. Drain
well, and add to the cheese sauce, increasing the heat to medium.
Toss to coat the gnocchi. Add the asiago and chives; toss again.
Pour into warmed bowls, and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
