<SLUG> BC-FOOD-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN TEMPERING, OIL IS A VIRTUE  
 STANDING IN FOR HEAVY CREAM  
 OF ARMAGNAC AND OLD PRUNES  
 POOR MAN'S CAVIAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MELISSA CLARK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I have heard that you can avoid the long process of tempering
chocolate by adding a few drops of oil as you melt it. Is this
true? If so, does it affect the taste or consistency? Which oil is
best to use?
</P>
<P>
   A. You've heard right: A little bit of oil added to melted
chocolate can often allow you to forgo the rather exacting process
of tempering it.
</P>
<P>
   Tempering chocolate (melting it, cooling it and then gently
melting it again) creates a lustrous, stable medium that can be
turned into a glossy coating for candies, fruit, cakes and cookies,
or used to create fanciful decorations like ruffles, curls and
lace.
</P>
<P>
   Tempering requires care and practice, as the temperature at
every step must be carefully watched. But by simply stirring 1
tablespoon of oil or other liquid fat (like melted clarified butter
or vegetable shortening) into every 3 ounces of melted chocolate,
you can create a mixture that approximates tempered chocolate and
that is colloquially called ``quick-tempered'' chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, when a recipe calls for tempered chocolate, you
may use the quick-tempered kind. But because it has a thinner
consistency than conventionally tempered chocolate (because of the
added fat), it may not work quite as well when you are making some
types of decorations. It may also not hold up as reliably if the
chocolate is meant to be stored for a long period. But for home
cooks making chocolate to be consumed within a few days, it's
generally fine.
</P>
<P>
   You can use any type of oil to quick-temper chocolate, but
neutral oils, like canola, vegetable or safflower, won't interfere
with the flavor of the chocolate. On the flip side, butter and nut
oils (like hazelnut or walnut) can add a delightful nuance.
</P>
<P>
   Standing In for Heavy Cream
</P>
<P>
   Q. Can evaporated skim milk be substituted for heavy cream in a
recipe? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It depends on the recipe. Substituting evaporated skim milk
for cream in equal measure works beautifully in baked goods,
custards, creamy soups and cream sauces.
</P>
<P>
   But be warned: Evaporated skim milk has a slightly cooked,
processed flavor compared with the fresh dairy taste of cream. If
the dish you are preparing is well seasoned with spices, chocolate,
garlic or chilies, you can make the swap without much harm to the
flavor. But delicate cream sauces won't fare as well.
</P>
<P>
   For foods that are not cooked, like a whipped-cream topping or a
mousse, try substituting either cottage cheese or part-skim ricotta
cheese for the cream. But first eliminate the curds by whirling the
cheese in a food processor or blender until it is very smooth (this
will take at least a full minute or two). Plain yogurt is another
good stand-in for cream in uncooked dishes, but since it tends to
curdle, it can't be used as easily in cooked dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, for a creamy but creamless soup, try simmering a potato
in the soup broth and then pureeing the mixture. The starch in the
potato thickens the soup without adding fat.
</P>
<P>
   Of Armagnac and Old Prunes
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a jar of prunes in Armagnac that I bought in France 15
years ago. It has never been opened, the seal was never broken, and
the jar has been stored most of the time in a dark cabinet. Do you
think the prunes (and the Armagnac, for that matter) can still be
eaten?
</P>
<P>
   A. According to both the California Prune Board and the Food and
Drug Administration, the prunes and Armagnac should be perfectly
safe, and probably delicious. Armagnac, like most spirits, keeps
for decades and can improve over time. In this case, it acts as a
preservative, protecting the prunes from both desiccation and rot,
and probably imbuing them with a luscious, heady flavor.
</P>
<P>
   But be wise: Open the jar, and sniff. If the contents smell at
all suspicious (like vinegar or worse), use common sense and throw
it away.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Man's Caviar
</P>
<P>
   Q. Recently I tasted something called Southern caviar, an
appetizer concoction that contained no caviar but was very tasty. A
recipe would be appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   A. Southern caviar, also called poor man's caviar, is a savory,
vegetable-based spread or dip that is supposed to take the place of
expensive, real caviar as an hors d'oeuvre or appetizer (not that
anyone would be fooled).
</P>
<P>
   While it can be made from any number of vegetables, eggplant is
by far the most popular, especially in the South, where some
scholars say the vegetable was introduced, perhaps via the West
Indies, by African slaves or Sephardic Jews, or both.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a versatile recipe that is good as a spread with crudites
and toasted baguette rounds, and even better as a sauce for pasta
or a side dish for poultry or meats. And I suppose you could also
pile it onto a blini.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHERN CAVIAR
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour, plus 15 minutes for cooling
</P>
<P>
   1 large eggplant
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons packed fresh Italian parsley
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons packed fresh celery leaves (optional)
</P>
<P>
   2 scallions, white part only, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 large clove garlic
</P>
<P>
   \ cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon capers, drained (optional)
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon salt, or more to taste
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Hot pepper sauce to taste.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Prick eggplant all over with a
fork, and place it on a foil-lined baking sheet. Bake until
eggplant is very soft, 45 to 55 minutes. Let cool completely, and
then scoop out flesh, and reserve.
</P>
<P>
   2. In bowl of food processor, combine parsley, celery leaves,
scallions and garlic. Pulse until mixture is finely chopped, about
1 minute.
</P>
<P>
   3. Add eggplant, olive oil, lemon juice, capers, salt, black
pepper and hot-pepper sauce, and process until mixture is quite
smooth. Taste, and adjust seasonings. Refrigerate until serving.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: about 1{ cups.
</P>
</TEXT>
