<SLUG> BC-MARILYN-MANSON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTACKS ON JOURNALISTS RAISE NEW CONCERN IN MUSIC WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE GANAHL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Perhaps hoping to derail the dangerous new trend
of violence by musicians against journalists, the publisher of Spin
magazine is pursuing both criminal and civil actions against
shock-rocker Marilyn Manson for an alleged attack on Spin executive
editor Craig Marks Nov. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Vibe/Spin Ventures released a statement last week that reads:
``The increasing violence against music journalists ... is
profoundly disturbing. We hope that by drawing attention to these
matters, we can encourage members of the music community to resolve
their differences in a civilized manner.''
</P>
<P>
   This most recent incident _ involving Manson and Marks _ gave
every music journalist pause. These details were strangely
underreported in the mainstream press: At Manson's Hammerstein
Ballroom concert in New York City, Manson, who recently made
headlines for setting his dressing rooms on fire in Poughkeepsie,
N.Y., asked Marks to come backstage after the show. When Marks got
there, Manson allegedly shook his hand, then hushed the backstage
crowd so he could announce to Marks, ``You know, I can kill you,
your family and everyone you know.''
</P>
<P>
   Manson then allegedly signaled his bodyguards, who shoved Marks,
37, against a wall, and lifted him up by his neck until his feet
were off the ground, choking him until he nearly passed out. Marks
had his bruises checked out at a nearby hospital; he then went to a
police station and filed a report. The police are investigating the
incident to determine whether criminal charged should be filed
against Manson.
</P>
<P>
   Why was Manson so angry with Spin? Because Marks decided not to
use Manson, a two-time Spin cover boy with a penchant for
near-naked, gender-bending costumes, for the front of the January
``year in review'' issue. In other words, this was not payback for
a negative article or a bad review.
</P>
<P>
   Marks, who has stopped giving interviews now that litigation is
pending, last week told one of the Internet's largest music-news
sources, Sonicnet, that he thought the alleged attack was
premeditated, and that he was set up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what (Manson) hoped to gain,'' Marks is quoted as
saying. ``It seems like an action that reeks of desperation.''
</P>
<P>
   Interscope Records, Manson's label, is not talking about the
incident. And the normally vociferous Manson has remained silent
about the incident, although he noted on his Web site that he and
Marks had indeed had a ``conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him ... I simply no longer wanted to work with him or
his magazine that obviously has a lack of respect for musicians and
their fans.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The violence was not the first between artist and journalist.
Earlier this month, Jesse Washington, editor of the hip-hop
publication Blaze (also a Vibe/Spin publication), was attacked by
three men and seriously beaten, allegedly because of something he
wrote. He claimed that one of the attackers was hip-hop producer
Deric ``D-Dot'' Angelettie, who has now been charged with the
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Washington also alleged that this summer, former Fugee Wyclef
Jean pulled a gun on him during an argument about coverage of his
new album. Jean denies the claim and no charges have been filed in
that incident.
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, way back in the '70s, the hottest
musician-vs.-magazine feud anywhere was between the Eagles and
Rolling Stone. Fed up with R.S. dismissing them as faux California
Cowboys, the Eagles challenged the magazine writers to a softball
game. The stakes? Whoever won the game could write a story about it
in the hallowed pages of the rock publication.
</P>
<P>
   When the Eagles creamed the ``desk jockeys,'' they were
merciless in their hilarious write-up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
