<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LYING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS CAN'T FORCE THE `L' WORD OUT OF CLINTON LAWYER 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: STANDS for CLINTON-IMPEACHMENT; story could go with
IMPEACH-STRATEGY)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton has been ``misleading,''
``evasive,'' ``incomplete,'' and even ``maddening,'' in his
statements under oath and to the American people, but he has never
lied, White House Special Counsel Gregory Craig said Tuesday at
Clinton's impeachment hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Try as they might, Republican members of the House Judiciary
Committee could not get Craig to say the ``l'' word.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Craig, did the president lie to the American people when
he said, `I never had sex with that woman'?'' asked Rep. Bob
Inglis, R-S.C., referring to Clinton's affair with former White
House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``He certainly misled and deceived ... '' Craig replied before
Inglis cut him off and said, ``Well, wait a minute now. Did he
lie?''
</P>
<P>
   Craig answered: ``He misled them and did not tell the truth at
that moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Inglis paused a moment, shook his head and asked Craig again if
Clinton lied when he denied having an affair with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, he doesn't believe he did,'' Craig answered.
</P>
<P>
   Inglis, grimacing, asked how the president could believe he told
the truth. Craig said the president's idea of sex came from the
dictionary and that under the dictionary's definition, Clinton and
Lewinsky did not have sex.
</P>
<P>
   Although Craig did not say which dictionary the president used
for the definition, Webster's New World Dictionary, 2nd College
Edition, defines sex as ``anything connected with sexual
gratification or reproduction or the urge for these.'' However, a
second definition of the word defines it as ``sexual intercourse,''
which would exclude Clinton's relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla., pressed Craig from a different
angle, asking him how the president was not lying when he testified
to lawyers for Paula Jones in her sexual harassment suit that he
could not remember whether he had been alone with Lewinsky. The
congressman said Clinton's testimony was particularly hard to
believe since according to Lewinsky's unchallenged testimony, the
president had had oral sex with the former intern eight times by
that point.
</P>
<P>
   Craig said that the president's answer was ``evasive and
misleading'' but that Clinton had ``tried to be narrowly
accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaking a copy of Clinton's testimony in his hand, Canady said:
``I don't see how anyone in this country could believe that this
was a truthful answer in light of all the evidence that is before
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Elton Gallegly, R-Calif., attempted one last time to get
Craig to admit that Clinton lied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think he (Clinton) has violated his oath to the
American people in telling the truth, the whole truth, and nothing
but the truth?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did not violate his oath,'' Craig said calmly.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously frustrated, Gallegly voiced what many of his
Republican colleagues _ including some moderate Republicans _ have
said publicly and privately. ``Quite frankly, this is an insult to
our intelligence and, frankly, indicates that the president is
still not telling the truth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
