<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABELS-HUMOR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READ THIS LABEL! LAUGH OUT LOUD!
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's so funny about a bottle of steak sauce, a can of beer or
a bag of caramel corn?
</P>
<P>
   Normally, not much _ unless you're Newman's Own steak sauce and
your label reads ``Preferred by 9 out of 10 cows.''
</P>
<P>
   Or you're a can of Miller Lite assuring consumers that ``Miller
Time is unaffected by Daylight Saving Time.''
</P>
<P>
   Or you're a bag of Lenny &AMP; Larry's caramel corn Power Pops,
encouraging snackers to ``Dump it all over the floor and roll in
it, devour it like a wild animal ...''
</P>
<P>
   Taking a cue from their brethren in advertising, the folks who
design product labels seem to have discovered their sense of humor.
The witticisms range from self-deprecating jabs at the product to
irreverent designs to cheeky one-liners hidden in the fine print.
</P>
<P>
   Small, offbeat companies like Lenny &AMP; Larry's naturally have
more leeway to joke around on their packaging than their stodgy
multinational counterparts. But even a few mainstream corporations
are lightening up.
</P>
<P>
   Take Miller Brewing Co.'s Miller Lite brand. The beer cans are
covered with slapstick cracks like ``This beer has your name on it.
No, wait, it has our name on it. Whatever.'' and ``Union Made For
Your Drinking Pleasure'' and ``No Batteries Required.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish-language version warns ``No Se Use En Pinatas.''
(Translated: Do not use in pinatas.)
</P>
<P>
   Snapple bottle tops inform drinkers they can ``Win Nothing
Instantly!'' and Lever Brothers' Surf laundry detergent would be
delighted for you to call with questions or ``if you think spending
an afternoon talking about laundry might be fun ... Operators are,
as they say, standing by.''
</P>
<P>
   Humorous packaging gives a product a distinct personality. Or it
becomes a forum for the packager's, uh, sillier side. Pasta-sauce
king Paul Newman, for instance, is responsible for much of the
vaudevillian humor on his Newman's Own line of edibles.
</P>
<P>
   ``No label goes out without his approval,'' notes company Vice
President Bill Lee. ``This is not his main livelihood, so he ends
up trying to have fun with the business.'' (Note: Newman moonlights
as an actor.)
</P>
<P>
   Take the company's balsamic vinaigrette bottle: It features a
fantastical anecdote about two Italian brothers, Balsa and Mick,
who duel to their deaths, prompting their grieving mother, Violetta
Vinegar, to christen a new grape _ Balsa-Mick _ in their memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks to Newman's Own,'' the bottle reads, ``their names live
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Newman's Own has, on occasion, been taken to task for its wit.
``People have gotten upset about a few of the labels,'' Lee admits.
Like the cartoon on the Caesar salad dressing bottle depicting ol'
Julius with a knife in his back: Too violent, folks complained.
Some vegetarians found the steak sauce quip a bit offensive.
</P>
<P>
   But that's nothing compared with the furor a company called
Senate caused when it got a tad too cute with a clothing label:
``Machine wash cold. No bleach. Tumble dry low. Remove promptly.
Don't iron decorations. Destroy all girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate, which makes in-line skating accessories, chucked the
loaded phrase after the news media picked up on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our intention wasn't to be hateful,'' says marketing manager
and in-line skating notable Arlo Eisenberg. ``We were trying to be
ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   The company still makes strange cracks on its clothing labels.
Another tag reads: ``This would be a clever place to put something
funny.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We challenge ourselves to be unconventional here,'' Eisenberg
notes.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley's Mixture, a Canadian cough suppressant recently
introduced in the United States, pulls no punches on its label. The
alcohol-free cough syrup, notes company President Frank Buckley on
the back of every box, has one problem: ``... to be real honest, it
tastes real bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Calido Chile Traders uses a similarly unconventional selling
point for its Batch No. 114 Jamaican Hot Sauce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pain,'' reads the label, ``is good.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
