<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9044 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INFANTS-HEARING-TEX     12-08 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INFANTS-HEARING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS GROUP LEADS NATIONAL PUSH FOR MANDATORY HEARING TESTS FOR
NEWBORNS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sleeping newborns, row upon row, are wheeled out of the nursery
and into the quiet room next door. Most hardly stir as the tiny
probe makes a soft click in their ears.
</P>
<P>
   But that small click is important. The sound that echoes back is
analyzed by computer to determine how well the infant's ear is
hearing. On average, one of every 300 babies is found to have some
hearing loss. If the problem is detected at this early stage, it
could possibly save the infant countless hours of frustration and
lost learning opportunities, scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose your baby couldn't hear. How could she tell you? asks
Terese Finitzo, the clinical audiologist who heads the Sounds of
Texas project, an innovative effort to screen all newborns for
hearing loss before they leave the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all about potential and letting the child develop
normally,'' said Finitzo, who also currently leads the national
Joint Committee on Infant Hearing, which advocates universal
newborn screening. The committee includes the American Academy of
Pediatrics, the American Academy of Otolaryngology and several
hearing and education groups as well as representatives from state
health departments.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds of Texas, which began in Fort Worth and Dallas, is one of
11 statewide screening programs nationwide. Serving about 70,000
babies annually, it's also the largest.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of infant hearing screening programs note that the
tests are quick, inexpensive and painless; more importantly, they
can prevent delays in language development and socialization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Babies can't tell you that they can't hear, and parents,
pediatricians _ all of us _ tend to mistakenly label toddlers and
preschoolers as behavior problems when the reality is, they can't
hear, and we don't know it,'' Finitzo said. ``Hearing loss is
typically not diagnosed until about age 3 in this country, and
that's too late.''
</P>
<P>
   Kids with hearing problems often fail to distinguish phonetic
sounds and miss the key building blocks of language development.
The problems come to the forefront when the kids are old enough to
begin reading.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children who do not hear well do not learn language well, and
children who do not know language do not learn to read well. If we
get them help early, they develop normally,'' Finitzo said. ``The
detection of hearing impairments allows us to connect children to
services that can help them reach their full potential and have the
best opportunity to be productive adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can prevent illiteracy,'' Finitzo said.
</P>
<P>
   For Ian Herring, who will be 3 in February, Sounds of Texas has
already made a difference. Ian was diagnosed with a mild to
moderate hearing loss the day he was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a total shock. He was perfectly healthy with no known
risk factors, and we have no family history of hearing problems. We
would not even have thought to ask for a hearing test,'' said Julie
Herring of Watauga, a suburb of Fort Worth. ``Ian got hearing aids
by the time he was 6 months, and he wears them full time except
when he's asleep. He hasn't had any trouble with them because he
realized real early that they make a big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   A teacher with the deaf program at Snow Heights Elementary works
with the family to teach Ian to listen to sounds, and to reinforce
his speech with speech therapy and sign language.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a speech evaluation at the first of the year when he
was turning 2, and he was right on track for a normal 2-year-old.
He definitely would have missed out on a lot if we had not found
out about his hearing loss so early,'' his mother said.
</P>
<P>
   Finitzo said this kind of progress is not unusual when the
hearing problem is identified early. ``We now have very good
research to show that if we can find these babies at birth and get
them into a program before they are six months of age, they will
have normal or near-normal language development by age 3.
Follow-ups at age 5 show they maintain those gains,'' Finitzo said.
</P>
<P>
   Each day, an average of three Texas babies is born with some
degree of hearing defficulty. If every Texas baby born this year
were screened, about 960 would be identified with hearing losses,
the Texas Health Department estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The Sounds of Texas has so far identified about 2,400 babies
with mild to profound hearing losses at birth. Cost for testing is
about $25 to $30 per baby.
</P>
<P>
   Finitzo is scheduled to meet with the governor's committee on
early childhood initiatives Thursday in Austin, the state capital,
and hopes to get a bill introduced in the next session of the
Legislature to mandate universal newborn screening throughout the
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of my goal is to demonstrate to legislators and the
governor that this is a way of really changing the lives of a lot
of children in Texas,'' said Finitzo.
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on health issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
