<HEADER>
A9049 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OXYGENBARS-TEX     12-08 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OXYGENBARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUSTOMERS PAY THROUGH THE NOSE FOR A BREATH OF FRESH AIR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At Woody Harrelson's new ``super-oxy-herbar'' in trendy West
Hollywood, health-conscious consumers can follow up their Shaman
pizza with a snort of joy.
</P>
<P>
   That's ``joy''-scented oxygen-enriched air, $15 for 20 minutes.
Not in the mood for joy? Try ``clarity,'' or ``energy,'' or
``mint-flavored'' air for the same price.
</P>
<P>
   Plain air will set ya back 13 bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Why would people buy oxygen when, supposedly, it is in plentiful
supply right under their noses? Isn't free air good enough anymore?
Is it even legal to suck up this stuff?
</P>
<P>
   Let's take those questions one at a time.
</P>
<P>
   The November opening of Harrelson's O2 (that's ``oh-two'')
planted oxygen bars on the communal radar screen for the first time
since their inconspicuous American debut in 1996. Mimicking a trend
that started in Japan, more than 60 oxygen bars operate in the
United States, according to Mark Zarubi at the National Oxygen Bar
Association (NOBA) in Reno, Nev.
</P>
<P>
   Don't waste your time looking for one in Texas, though. State
laws have thus far prevented any authorized oxygen-snorting venues
from opening.
</P>
<P>
   Oxygen bars developed based on the belief that purer air
promotes better health: The air we breathe normally contains 21
percent oxygen; depending on the method of delivery an oxygen bar
uses, it can theoretically provide air containing up to 99 percent
oxygen. Whether that's actually beneficial is up for debate.
</P>
<P>
   By law, oxygen bars can't make any medical claims. But they can,
and do, promote themselves as a sort of groovy way to spend a
half-hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``We treat it like a new experience, (like) bungee jumping,''
says Kevin McFarland, chief of operations for O2 Zone LLC in Reno.
``It's a thrill.''
</P>
<P>
   McFarland sells equipment and ``know-how'' to oxygen bars all
over the world. He has helped establish 51 in the United States, he
says, plus bars in Antwerp, Milan, Taiwan, Rio de Janeiro and, most
recently, Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   A typical session at a McFarland-supplied oxygen bar might go
something like this: Take a seat at the counter and pick your
flavor _ tropical punch, tangerine twist, lime smoother, eucalyptus
mist, etc. ... Drape the clear polyethylene tubing over your ears
and in front of your nose so that the two tiny plastic prongs are
pointing at your nostrils (sounds very attractive, no?). Now,
breathe deeply.
</P>
<P>
   Or you might choose a ``facial cascade,'' available at
McFarland's Scottsdale, Ariz., location. Place the Darth Vader-like
hood over your face and let the oxygen shower your kisser.
</P>
<P>
   McFarland, an engineer who bought the O2 Zone from Zarubi in
March, believes the potential customer base for oxygen bars is huge
_ even if the vast majority of users never return for a second
shot. NOBA's Web site optimistically predicts oxygen-bar
entrepreneurs can ``turn 25 cents into a $20 bill,'' and the
organization sells a $79.95 information manual to parties
interested in opening their own oxygen establishments.
</P>
<P>
   But the business side of the oxygen-bar phenomenon can get a
little sticky _ especially when the federal government's official
position is that the bars shouldn't be open.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really don't know of any instance where someone could
operate an oxygen bar without being in violation'' of Food and Drug
Administration regulations, says FDA spokesman Brad Stone.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA considers medical oxygen, Oxygen USP, a drug, and as
such it is available only by prescription. The plastic tubing
apparatus that delivers the oxygen from the tank, called a medical
cannula, is also available by prescription only.
</P>
<P>
   But oxygen bars have finagled around most state and federal
measures in a few ways. First, most don't use medical oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   McFarland's clients dispense either aviation oxygen, the kind
pilots use, or oxygen produced by generators that separate O2 from
the surrounding air. Both of those can deliver air with up to 99
percent oxygen, the same as medical oxygen, but are not
specifically regulated by federal and most state agencies. (The
only difference between aviation oxygen and medical oxygen is that
the former doesn't undergo the same strict pharmaceutical controls
placed on the latter, says Angela Bensel in the Texas Department of
Health Drug and Medical Devices Division.)
</P>
<P>
   Second, the cannulas McFarland sells are slightly different from
medical cannulas and therefore not prescription devices.
</P>
<P>
   Third, the FDA's jurisdiction extends only to interstate
commerce, meaning it can stop businesses from sending prescription
equipment and drugs across state lines, but otherwise has little
direct authority. Because McFarland avoids dealing in prescription
oxygen and devices, he is not in any direct violation of the rule.
</P>
<P>
   McFarland and Zarubi say they have been operating with the FDA's
tacit approval for almost two years. Zarubi, who opened the
original O2 Zone oxygen bar in February 1997, says an FDA official
even visited his operation ``with pen and paper in hand, ready to
issue a citation, and upon seeing our process, he couldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the FDA's assertion that no oxygen bar, as they are
typically conceived, could be operating legitimately, the agency
has taken limited action against the businesses. According to
Stone, most of the oxygen bars that the FDA has become aware of
have either failed financially or have been closed by state or
local authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA ``has had more than ample opportunity to squash this
thing for at least two years now, and they've chosen not to,''
Zarubi notes. ``They'll tell people oxygen bars are illegal, but
they don't take any action against it. One, because they don't have
the power to do it, and two, because there's really no law against
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The true test of survival for oxygen bars will likely be whether
the general public buys into the novelty or accepts the purported
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of oxygen therapies contend that inhaling the gas
boosts energy levels and can help relieve a variety of ailments,
including headaches, allergies and depression. Some users have even
suggested it improves their sex life.
</P>
<P>
   Mainstream science is skeptical of these claims, at best. ``For
normal people, I can't imagine it's going to do a whole lot,'' says
Dr. Alvin Mathe, director of the Wound Healing and Hyperbaric
Medicine Center at the Osteopathic Medical Center of Texas. ``It
may provide a brief period where you feel better.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathe notes that the hemoglobin in our blood is already 98
percent to 99 percent saturated with oxygen. Upping that another
percentage point isn't going to make a significant or long-term
difference. Plus, to get the pure oxygen from a tank into your
body, you would need either a very tight-fitting mask or ``a tube
down your throat,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   Devices like the one described earlier _ with the two prongs
shooting gas toward the nostrils _ allow much of the oxygen to
escape, Mathe says. ``With those cannulas, if you work hard, you
can get it to 35 percent oxygen,'' he notes.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, breathing a half-hour's worth of concentrated oxygen
every now and again probably can't hurt you either, Mathe says.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the aromatherapy aspect of the experience probably is a
pleasant effect. When you think about it, for $15, it's a
relatively cheap way of putting a little joy in your life.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
