<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 UPDATE &HT;    UPDATE
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Wednesday, Dec. 9,
1998.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eds: Adds: IMPEACH-NOBLE
</P>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH _ Coverage of White House lawyers' apperance before the
House Judiciary Committee. (Carr/Sherman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   w/BARR _ What role did he play? (Sherman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SPINNERS _ Scandal has become institutionalized in Washington,
with the same spinmeisters working the edges at big events. They
will be out in force Tuesday, trolling the hallways during and
after the hearings. We will watch them work. (Foskett, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-WH-SCENE _ WASHINGTON _ The president's day, and the
mood inside the White House, as Clinton's lawyers present their
defense before the House Judiciary Committee. (Deans, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-NOBLE _ WASHINGTON _ The former top cop in the U.S.
Treasury Department, who punished ATF supervisors in the wake of
the disastrous Branch Davidian raid, will become a witness
Wednesday as the House Judiciary Committee hears the defense case
of President Clinton. Former Treasury Undersecretary Ronald K.
Noble oversaw an investigation of the federal assault on the Branch
Davidians compound near Waco. In an interview, Noble said he will
testify Wednesday that the perjury allegations against Clinton are
``so messy, tawdry and unclear, I can't see why a federal
prosectuor would want to bring a case.'' (Harlan, Cox News Service
300).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-COLOR _ WASHINGTON _ Outside the hearing room where
President Clinton's lawyers were presenting his impeachment defense
to a skeptical GOP majority on the Judiciary Committee, TV
producers scrambled Tuesday to snare prominent guests for their
cameras. After months of dissecting the subject, news and talk
shows were seeing punditry merge with reality before their eyes.
(Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MODERATES _ Saxby Chambliss and Charlie Norwood are among the 30
so-called ``moderates'' the White House has targeted for lobbying
efforts on impeachment. We'll explain why. (Sherman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDS: Photos will accompany this story.
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and
congressional leaders, opening a two-day conference on rescuing
Social Security's finances, agreed Tuesday on the urgency of their
task but diagreed on how to proceed and what the system will look
like once it's reformed. (Lipman, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-COLLEGES _ WASHINGTON _ Black students struggling to
balance academic excellence and cultural diversity gained a new
tool Tuesday as Black Enterprise magazine unveiled a ranking of the
top 50 colleges for African Americans. (Monroe, Cox News Service
450).
