<HEADLINE>
COMPANIES VOW TO HELP SAVE OLD-GROWTH FORESTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE KAY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ More than two dozen U.S. corporations, half of
them Fortune 500 companies, have promised to stop using or selling
paper and other wood products made from the world's disappearing
old-growth trees.
</P>
<P>
   Hallmark Cards, 3M Corp., Starbucks Coffee Co., IBM Corp.,
Hewlett-Packard Co. and Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. are among a growing list
of top corporations that have pledged to find substitutes for
lumber and pulp gleaned from the dwindling store of the planet's
virgin forests, trees hundreds of years old that shelter species of
animals, birds and insects.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-seven U.S. companies have made the pledge, according to
the Coastal Rainforest Coalition, a group of environmental
organizations including the Natural Resources Defense Council,
Rainforest Action Network and Greenpeace.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time that, on a large scale, American
corporate leaders have sent the signal to the marketplace that they
no longer want to purchase wood-based products that originate from
ancient forests,'' said Michael Marks, executive director of the
nonprofit Coastal Rainforest Coalition in Berkeley, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``These companies collectively represent nearly $2 billion of
the U.S. paper and package markets,'' he said. ``They're saying to
the producers of alternative tree-free paper, certified wood and
recycled fibers that there is a market.''
</P>
<P>
   A full-page ad in Tuesday's New York Times, paid for by the
coalition, praises the businesses for earning green points with the
public for helping to save the last of the untouched temperate and
tropical forests, mainly in British Columbia, the United States,
Brazil, Russia and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   At Levi Strauss, scrap denim from plants around the country is
used by an Albuquerque, N.M., mill to make the company's
letterhead, envelopes, note pads and most other corporate paper, a
project that began in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of our desire to be environmentally responsible,''
Derek van Bronkhorst, the company's public affairs director, said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Kinko's Inc. is taking a similar approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not here to be a political instrument of any type,''
said Larry Rogera, environmental manager of Kinko's, which has 900
stores nationwide. ``We realized that commerce can have a negative
or positive impact on the environment. We think if we're going to
be around on a long-term basis we need to do things sustainably.''
</P>
<P>
   At Hallmark Cards in Kansas City, spokeswoman Julie O'Dell said:
``It's our policy to work only with suppliers who do not derive any
products from logging old-growth forests.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rainforest Action Network says only 20 percent of the
world's old-growth forests are left _ only 5 percent of which are
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign to preserve the forests began more than a decade
ago, starting with a worldwide effort to save the Amazon. More
recently, the focus turned toward British Columbia's Clayoquot
Sound, on the west coast of Vancouver Island.
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, environmentalists widened the battle to include
products made from old-growth trees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
