A9067 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-COLOR09-COX     12-08 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-COLOR09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEARINGS AND THE TALK SHOW WORLD MERGE AT THE CAPITOL
 &HT;    570&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Equipped with a cell phone and descriptions of her
prey, Kerri Forrest trolled tirelessly for guests Tuesday in the
corridors outside the hearing room where the House Judiciary
Committee is considering the impeachment of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very competitive,'' explained the ambitious young booking
producer for the MSNBC cable TV network. ``You're always trying to
get to somebody before they show up on some other network's air.''
</P>
<P>
   Booking producers are big game hunters in a media jungle where
the quarry glides seamlessly between TV talk shows and the
televised hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has the same information coming out of the committee
room,'' said Teri Schultz, a freelance producer who was working
Tuesday with CNN correspondent Bob Franken. ``We want Bob to have
something that everyone else doesn't know.''
</P>
<P>
   However, scoops are hard to come by for the correspondents and
producers on the 24-hour news channels where White House scandal
has been a programming staple for nearly a year now. The same
people say the same things over and over again. Only the setting
can cue viewers where the action is taking place.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if former Rep. Elizabeth Holtzman, D-N.Y., is being
interrogated by Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., the venue is the Judiciary
Committee hearing. But if Holtzman is answering similar questions
from Chris Mathews, it's MSNBC's ``Hardball'' talk show. In both
places, she's saying that Clinton should not be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   If Reps. Bob Barr, R-Ga., and Barney Frank, D-Mass., are asking
questions in front of blue curtains, it's the hearing. If they're
talking to Fred Graham with the Capitol dome in the background,
it's Court TV. Both places, Barr and Frank are disagreeing.
</P>
<P>
   Only a three-minute walk separates the hearing room from the
makeshift studios set up on the same floor of the Rayburn House
Office Building. Some witnesses and committee members could make
the trek blindfolded.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no shortage of people here who want to jump in front
of cameras,'' said Carter Yang, a producer with ABC News.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for producers is to get the right person in front
of their cameras at the right time.
</P>
<P>
   So, producers keep an eye on a monitor showing what's going on
in the hearing room, and an ear on a cell phone conversation with a
desired member's press aide. They patrol the halls for witnesses.
They trade gossip with congressional staffers, colleagues and
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Luck is frequently a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard this morning that _ just by accident _ Reuters TV had
caught David Kendall (the president's private attorney) coming into
the building. The Reuters crew was there waiting for the release of
files on Frank Sinatra,'' said Schultz. ``An entrance shot is a
pretty big thing in TV, and CNN is a Reuters client. So I called up
and got a dub.''
</P>
<P>
   John Oglunik, a producer for National Public Radio, recalled
waiting for Rep. Lamar Smith, a Judiciary Committee member, to
finish another interview so he could get the Texas Republican in
front of a microphone. On deadline, ``I needed a Republican for
balance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Oglunik sought help from a fellow he took to be a Smith staffer,
but who actually was Rep. Bob Goodlatte, a Republican Judiciary
committee member from Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Goodlatte ``turned out to be a wonderful interview,'' said
Oglunik.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   National Public Radio and some cable TV news channels provide
gavel-to-gavel coverage when the hearings are in session, so the
scramble comes during breaks. ``We pounce on them,'' admitted
Schultz.
</P>
<P>
   The correspondents covering the hearing from inside the room can
``talk through'' a 10-minute break, said Oglunik, but producers
need guests to fill any longer periods.
</P>
<P>
   ``We avoid the witnesses'' as interview subjects, said Graham,
the on-air correspondent for Court TV. By the time the committee
has finished questioning them, ``every witness is wrung dry,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The producers' workdays are often impossibly long. At 6:30 on
Tuesday morning, Schultz was with a CNN camera crew outside the
McLean, Va., home of Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr. By 9 a.m.,
she was in the Rayburn Building for the committee hearing expected
to last late into the night.
</P>
<P>
   With 24 hours of news programming to fill every day, the
appetite for interviews and talk show guests is insatiable.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of pressure, but it's fun,'' said Forrest.
``Every day can bring a triumph.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
