</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRAIG-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREG CRAIG PUTS A GENTLER FACE ON A STUBBORN WHITE HOUSE DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Blue chip Washington lawyer Gregory Bestor Craig
relied on boyish charm, a deferential manner and the indignation of
a father of five to put a fresh face Tuesday on the White House
defense of President Clinton against threatened impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Craig, a 53-year-old Yale Law School classmate of the president
and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, treated the House Judiciary
Committee to a low key defense of the chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The House panel is exploring the possibility of impeachment in
conjunction with Clinton's sexual relationship with former White
House intern Monica Lewinsky and his attempt to cover up the
liaison with perjurious testimony, obstruction of justice and abuse
of the powers of his office.
</P>
<P>
   Craig told the committee that the White House would mount a
``powerful case'' against impeachment, based upon the testimony of
15 witnesses over two days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Open your mind; open your heart and focus on the record,''
Craig implored the committee. ``Just as no fancy language can
obscure the simple fact that what the president did was morally
wrong, no amount of rhetoric can change the legal reality that
there are no grounds for impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig's earnest manner offered a sharp contrast to last month's
combative presentation before the same committee by his former law
partner, David Kendall, whose rapid-fire, sharp-edged questions to
special prosecutor Kenneth Starr reflected White House efforts to
make Starr _ not Clinton _ the focus of the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Without the edge, Craig pitched the same contentions that
Clinton did not lie in a civil suit deposition last January; that
Clinton did not commit perjury in his nationally televised Aug. 17
grand jury testimony; that Clinton did not obstruct justice by
helping Lewinsky find a job; and that Clinton did not abuse his
office by exerting claims of executive privilege or misleading
aides about an extramarital relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Craig conceded at one point that Clinton may even face criminal
prosecution after leaving office for allegedly misleading a U.S.
District Court in his January deposition in the Paula Jones civil
sexual harassment suit.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Jones settled the case for $850,000 last month.
Critics contend that Clinton misled the court about the nature of
his relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``If did mislead a court under oath, that would be wrong; it
would be unlawful,'' Craig told the committee. ``Most people that
are working with the president in the defense believe that is a
very likely possibility in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior White House official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said that the style of Craig's presentation was designed
to appeal to moderate Republicans who hold the key to whether the
full House votes to impeach Clinton. Such a move would send the
case to the Senate for trial.
</P>
<P>
   The full House is expected to vote next week on any articles of
impeachment approved by the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, at the behest of his wife Hillary, hired Craig as a
White House lawyer on Sept. 10, the day after Starr presented his
sexually explicit findings about the Lewinsky affair to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides said Clinton was looking for a politically
savvy lawyer who could orchestrate the legal, political and
congressional strategy to combat threatened impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Craig was serving at the time as the director of policy planning
at the State Department, a prestigious post once held by George
Kennan, the mastermind of Cold War containment of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Craig had built a reputation in the nation's capital as a man to
see in crisis. Craig, who had served as senior aide to Sen. Edward
M. Kennedy, D-Mass., during the 1980s, endeared himself to the
Kennedy clan by guiding the senator through his ticklish,
nationally broadcast testimony in the 1991 Palm Beach, Fla., rape
trial of his nephew, William Kennedy Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was acquitted. Kennedy subsequently won a tough fight for
re-election in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Craig helped orchestrate the successful insanity defense of John
W. Hinckley Jr., following Hinckley's attempt to assassinate
President Ronald Reagan three months after taking office in 1981.
</P>
</TEXT>
