<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-LINE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Carey, `Line' cronies test recipes for comedy
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Whose Line Is It Anyway?'' is as refreshing as its title is
unwieldy.
</P>
<P>
   Even the best situation comedies run on certain formulas: exit
lines, laugh tracks, wacky neighbors. But ``Line'' is a game show
where the situation is always fluid and unpredictability is the
only certainty. This means it doesn't always work, but even when it
starts to falter, it's already moved on to something else.
</P>
<P>
   Hosted by Drew Carey, ``Line'' is an American rip-off (money did
change hands) of a long-running British game that played on cable
here. Carey and an audience throw ideas and situations at four
hyperactive but intensely focused improvisational comics (including
Ryan Stiles, a supporter on Carey's hit ABC sitcom) and let 'em
rip.
</P>
<P>
   So one guy's going to an imaginary party and has to impersonate
a human pinball machine, and another one's on a ``Dating Game''
where he gets an electrical shock every time he has an impure
thought. A woman from the audience is yanked onstage and given an
off-the-cuff serenade, and a mock newscast features a sports anchor
who thinks he's an emotional preacher giving a eulogy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Line'' was a moderate hit as a summer replacement series, but
ABC, which only sort of gets it, went with ``The Secret Lives of
Men'' for its big fall lineup. ``Men'' tanked, so ``Line'' is back
to fill in. Don't get too attached to it, though; rumor is ABC is
readying a new sitcom with Norm Macdonald for the time slot in the
spring.
</P>
<P>
   There ought to be room for ``Line.'' It's dirt-cheap to make,
gets decent ratings and makes us hope that network TV is capable of
doing something besides churning out the same old chain letters.
Maybe ABC execs ought to get an electrical shock every time they
think about taking it away again.
</P>
<P>
   TV REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Whose Line Is It Anyway?''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   9:30 tonight E.S.T. on ABC
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
