<HEADER>
A9083 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SURFER-COLUMN09-CO     12-08 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Without camp, bio of Susann falls flat
 &HT;    By Lee Smith
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   From its opening shot of a high-heeled, bathing suit-clad
authoress strolling poolside to the strains of Tom Jones' ``She's a
Lady,'' ``Scandalous Me: The Jacqueline Susann Story'' seems to
have limitless camp possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   But as the flashbacks begin, it quickly becomes apparent that
``Scandalous Me'' (9 tonight E.S.T. on USA) is a run-of-the-mill TV
movie, and the unintentional laughs will be few and far between.
</P>
<P>
   Susann (Michele Lee), a failed actress who became a best-selling
writer in the late '60s and early '70s with such potboilers as
``Valley of the Dolls,'' ``The Love Machine'' and ``Once Is Not
Enough,'' yearns to please her demanding father, a Philadelphia
portrait painter. Marriage, childbirth, small parts in TV shows and
hobnobbing with the rich and famous don't satisfy her. Scenes of
infidelity, physical illness, mental problems, booze and pills _ or
``dolls,'' as Susann affectionately calls them _ are blandly
trotted out.
</P>
<P>
   After a bout with breast cancer (which she eventually died of in
1974), she pleads with God to give her 10 more years so she can
achieve success.
</P>
<P>
   Here, about halfway through the movie (when most viewers will
have long lost interest), Susann realizes her purpose and begins
transforming her diaries into trashy best sellers.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, ``Scandalous Me'' picks up steam, showing the
pushy Susann barnstorming the country to publicize her books. She
bullies agents and publishers and cajoles and flatters bookstore
owners to carry her merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Supported by her producer-husband, Irving Mansfield (Peter
Riegert), Susann became one of the first modern brand-name authors,
churning out three No. 1 best sellers and helping to pave the way
for Danielle Steel and Jackie Collins. She brought previously taboo
subjects such as oral sex into publishing's mainstream long before
the Starr report hit the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Portraying the author from her 20s to her 50s, Lee captures the
energy and drive that made Susann a media celebrity. She even
resembles Susann, whose lacquered wigs and fossilized appearance in
bright Day-Glo minis and pantsuits prompted Truman Capote to call
her a truck driver in drag.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Scandalous Me'' doesn't shrink from portraying the
less flattering qualities of Susann, it nevertheless treads lightly
on other issues, such as bisexuality. (Apparently, Susann had a
thing for Ethel Merman, which is never fully explored.)
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps audiences will have to wait till next year for a fuller
portrait of Susann, when Bette Midler appears in a feature film on
the flamboyant author's life. Maybe that one will make us care.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: 1 Doll.
</P>
<P>
   e-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
