</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCKINNEY-RWANDA-1209-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LAWMAKER SAYS U.N. KNEW RWANDAN GENOCIDE WAS PLANNED
 &HT;    430 words
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By NICHOLE MONROE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- U.S. Rep. Cynthia McKinney on Tuesday released two
documents she says support claims that the United Nations knew
about the 1994 Rwandan genocide before it occurred, but did
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   McKinney, D-Ga., also asked at a press conference that an
independent international organization be established to
investigate the United Nations' activities before, during and after
the killings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal of such a commission would not be primarily to pass
judgment on the decisions and those who made them, but to establish
truth,'' McKinney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is of paramount importance to know what the United Nations
and the United States knew of the possibility of genocide and
massive killings in Rwanda and why they did not move to prevent
this,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 500,000 people from the Tutsi ethnic minority and
moderates from the Hutu majority died in the mass killings.
</P>
<P>
   One document released was a February 1994 interoffice memorandum
addressed to Force Commander Canadian Gen. Romero Dallaire.
</P>
<P>
   The letter states that a ``serious threat'' was in the area and
that a group was planning ``murder against Mr. Lando (Landoald
Ndsingwa) and Mr. Joseph Kavaruganda.''
</P>
<P>
   When the genocides began in April 1994, both Ndsingwa,
co-founder of Rwanda's Parti Liberal, and Kavaruganda, president of
the constitutional council, were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Another document released at the press conference is a 1995
letter from Dallaire to senior U.N. officials. McKinney said the
letter is evidence that the general was concerned about the U.N.'s
failure to share with Belgium critical information about the
killings.
</P>
<P>
   The documents were unearthed by Michael Hourigan, a former
investigator for the War Crimes Tribunal, who says the information
was excluded from official U.N. accounts of the killings. The
Washington press conference was held at the same time Belgium Sen.
Alain Destexhe released the documents in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why has it taken over four years for all this precious
information to become available?'' McKinney asked. ``Do we even now
have it all, or are more secrets lurking in the vault of the U.N.
and the countries involved?''
</P>
<P>
   McKinney, who sits on the International Relations and National
Security committees, has long been involved in African issues. In
May, she spearheaded an effort to hold hearings on the Rwandan
genocide.
</P>
<P>
   McKinney also is a staunch supporter of Congolese President
Laurent Kabila, who is now accused of ordering the executions and
imprisonment of political foes.
</P>
<P>
   United Nations representatives could not be reached for comment
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
