<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONO-IMPEACHMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REP. BONO CHALLENGES CLINTON LAWYER TO EXPLAIN LIES TO KIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Mary Bono, the widowed mother of two young
children, asked President Clinton's lawyer Tuesday how he explained
to his children ``that your president has lied and it's okay?''
</P>
<P>
   After White House special counsel Gregory Craig and other
Clinton defenders argued for more than four hours that the
president's infractions were not impeachable offenses, Bono engaged
Craig is a parent-to-parent chat about raising children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have small children at home?'' Bono inquired. ``What do
you tell them? How do you explain to them that the president has
lied and that it's okay?''
</P>
<P>
   Craig, the father of five, responded that he tells his children
that ``one of the reasons that the president is in such trouble is
that he did not tell the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He misled the American people, he misled his family, he misled
his colleagues,'' Craig said. ``And that was wrong. And the
president should have admitted that earlier. And that's a very
important lesson to the children of this country, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig conceded that if Clinton had misled a court in his
deposition in the Paula Jones civil sexual harassment suit, then
the president could face future criminal prosecution after he
leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people that are working with the president in the defense
believe that is a very likely possibility in the future,'' Craig
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bono responded, ```I think this is the hardest thing for me, for
any parent, that we have looked at, we have seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Bono was elected in April to fill the seat left vacant after her
husband, comedian-turned-congressman Sonny Bono, was killed in a
skiing accident.
</P>
<P>
   The lone Republican woman on the House Judiciary panel and a
mother of a son Chesare, 10, and a daughter Chianna, 8, Bono says
she ``trys to avoid legal gymnastics,'' because she is one of three
nonlawyers on the 37-member committee. The others are Reps. Maxine
Waters, D-Calif., and Elton Gallegly, R-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, after House Judiciary Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill.,
presented her at a news conference as the newest member of the
committee, Bono again echoed the parent theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a mother, I know our children will learn as much from what
we do as from what we say,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the Republicans on the Judiciary Committee don't expect
her to become entangled in the fine legal points, but instead
``look to me for `How is this going to play in Peoria?'''
</P>
<P>
   Bono ``brings a common sense woman-on-the-street approach to the
issue,'' said Marshall Wittmann, director of congressional
relations at the conservative Heritage Foundation. ``Obviously the
legal beagles on the panel are bringing a very constitutional
approach. She is someone with a nonlegal background, who might ask
the questions the average person at home might ask.''
</P>
<P>
   On weekends, Bono vacates the Georgetown townhouse she once
shared with Sonny and flies home to her district and home in Palm
Springs, Calif., where her children remain during the week with a
longtime nanny. A good weekend with the kids might involving taking
her son to tennis lessons or watching her daughter as a cheerleader
at football games.
</P>
<P>
   She said when she is ``stressed out'' back in Washington, she
begins to plan her weekends with her children. ``I start to think,
I can't wait to take them to (the movie) `A Bug's Life,''' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bono also says she believes Clinton committed perjury and ought
to be removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   Bono says she is ``overwhelmed'' to sit in judgment of the
president and that ``the gravity of it hits me in the gut.'' She
says she has coped with the impeachment firestorm by ``focusing on
the task immediately at hand,'' and ``taking one step at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I shake when I speak'' at congressional hearings or news
conferences, Bono said.
</P>
<P>
   After observing quietly from the sidelines for months, Bono
announced at Tuesday's hearing, ``I won't be labeled a zealot
because I do believe it was perjury. I do believe it was wrong. And
I won't have a problem supporting that article of impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Bono says she reached her decision last week after hearing the
congressional testimony of two women, psychiatrist Barbara
Battalino and former college basketball coach Pam Parsons who were
convicted for lying under oath about sex. ``No one is above the
law,'' she said. ``This is what happens when you perjure yourself.
The president shows no remorse.''
</P>
<P>
   As the junior member of the Republican majority on the panel,
Bono must wait until the rest of the Republicans have asked their
questions at congressional hearings before she gets to speak. She
says she can feel the adrenaline surge when her turn is just two to
three members away.
</P>
<P>
   Bono, a former high school gymnast and certified personal
fitness instructor who has studied Karate and Tae Kwan Do,
complains that her bicoastal trips and the Judiciary Committee
schedule have left her without time to exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Bono recently cut her long blonde hair short and returned it to
its natural brunette color.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1961 in Cleveland, Ohio, the daughter of a surgeon, Clay
Whitaker, and a chemist, Karen, Bono met her future husband Sonny
Bono while celebrating her graduation from the University of
Southern California at one of his restaurants in West Hollywood,
Calif., which she later managed.
</P>
<P>
   She said her fellow Republicans, and some Democrats like Rep.
Barney Frank, D-Mass., have helped ease the transition to Capitol
Hill by acting as coaches. She admits she still finds it unsettling
to hear camera shutters clicking and must resist the temptation to
turn and make a face.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Steve Buyer, R-Ind., who says he has taken Bono ``under my
wing as a friend,'' said walking into the impeachment hearings was
as if ``she has stepped into a fire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She was the wife of someone famous, but I don't think she was
prepared to have all the attention shift to her,'' Buyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Bono said she is looking forward to shifting her attention away
from the president and toward issues such as education and health
care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to putting impeachment behind me,'' she
said. ``This is so overwhelming. From this point on, it's got to
get easier.''
</P>
</TEXT>
