<HEADER>
A9127 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-NOBLE-1209-CO     12-08 0432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NOBLE-1209-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FORMER TREASURY DEPARTMENT OFFICIAL TO TESTIFY FOR CLINTON AT
PROCEEDINGS
 &HT;    380 words
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By CHRISTI HARLAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. Treasury Department's former top cop, who
punished the supervisors of the disastrous Branch Davidians raid,
will become a witness for the defense Wednesday as the House
Judiciary Committee hears more testimony on behalf of President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald K. Noble, who was undersecretary for enforcement when he
left the Treasury Department in early 1996, said Tuesday that he
will draw on his experience as a federal prosecutor to tell the
Judiciary Committee holding impeachment proceedings that the
perjury allegations against Clinton do not warrant prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The underlying facts and circumstances of what happened are so
messy, tawdry and unclear, I can't see why a federal prosecutor
would want to bring a case,'' Noble said from his office at New
York University Law School, where he teaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take the position that if this case were brought before an
ordinary prosecutor and there was an ordinary defendant, the
likelihood is that the prosecution would never go forward,'' he
said, adding that he can understand why independent counsel Kenneth
Starr and Congress would be tempted to press charges against such
an extraordinary defendant as the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The temptation is so strong because there is no bigger target,
both for assassinations and for prosecutions,'' Noble said.
</P>
<P>
   Noble was appointed by Clinton in 1993 to be the assistant
secretary for enforcement in the Treasury Department, a job that
put him in charge of the Secret Service, Customs Service and the
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Noble's first assignment from then-Treasury Secretary Lloyd
Bentsen was an investigation of the ATF's actions in its Feb. 28,
1993, raid on the Branch Davidians' compound at Mount Carmel, near
Waco, Texas. Four ATF agents died in the subsequent gunfight at the
compound. When the investigation ended in September 1993, at least
four raid supervisors were demoted or otherwise disciplined.
</P>
<P>
   During his three years with the Treasury Department, Noble also
made the controversial decision to close Pennsylvania Avenue in
front of the White House. The closure happened shortly after the
bombing of the Alfred P. Murrah federal building in Oklahoma City
in April 1995, but Noble insists that the closing had been in the
works for some months.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
