<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-TEXAS-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TIES FORTUNE TO OTHER INDUSTRIES
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by OIL-GRAHAM and OIL-FACTS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MITCHELL SCHNURMAN 
and JIM FUQUAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The last time oil prices fell within sight
of $10 a barrel, Jack Huff was starting a real estate brokerage in
Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1986, and the Texas oil and gas business was about to go
into a free fall. Soon the real estate industry would collapse,
too, and hundreds of Texas banks would go belly up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to take on a siege mentality,'' Huff recalled. ``All we
could worry about was survival.''
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forward to December 1998: Oil prices have plunged 40
percent in the past year, sending tremors through the oil patch.
</P>
<P>
   With profits reeling, oil companies are folding up drilling rigs
and preparing to lay off tens of thousands of workers. Mergers,
including last week's megadeal between Exxon and Mobil, are
sweeping the industry.
</P>
<P>
   The impact on Huff this time?
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't really seen it or felt it,'' said the co-founder of
Stoneleigh Huff Brous McDowell. ``We have a few clients in that
sector who are tightening their belts. But it's pretty much
business as usual.''
</P>
<P>
   That view, which would probably be shared by many Texans,
reflects just how much the state has changed in less than a
generation. And it tells us why the current threat, while painful
to those in the industry, is nothing like the oil shock that rocked
Texas a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   To many, Texas still evokes images of rowdy roughnecks and
towering oil derricks, of a state awash in ``black gold.'' The
reality is that today's Texas is as much about semiconductors and
computers, airlines and trucking, retailing and services.
</P>
<P>
   And many of those businesses, along with millions of consumers,
welcome lower oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   Adjusted for inflation, consumers are paying the lowest prices
at the pump since before the oil embargo of 1973. That helps whet
their appetite for big trucks and sport utility vehicles, which
last month topped car sales for the first time since a brief period
after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Low oil prices also contribute to low inflation, which has
spawned a boom in mortgage financing and home construction.
</P>
<P>
   In short, cheap oil is good news for many Texans.
</P>
<P>
   ``When oil prices fall, there are 9 million workers who benefit
every time they go to the gas pump,'' said Gerald Higgins, revenue
analyst for the Texas comptroller. ``And there's a small percentage
who suffer because they work in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a situation that's got good and bad,'' Higgins said. ``It
depends on whose ox is getting gored.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than two decades ago, the state's economic fortunes hinged
on the price of oil, rising and falling with the cycles of the
volatile industry. It is still significant, especially around
Houston and Midland-Odessa, where energy jobs are concentrated.
</P>
<P>
   But oil's influence has dwindled.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, taxes on oil and gas production accounted for nearly 29
percent of state revenues, according to the Texas comptroller.
Today those levies make up less than 4 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
   The industry itself has shrunk by almost half. Texas had more
than 300,000 oil and gas workers in 1981. In October, the total was
156,600, said the Texas Workforce Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Over those 17 years, the rest of the Texas economy boomed,
adding 2.7 million jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a simple story,'' said Stephen P.A. Brown, senior
economist at the Federal Reserve Bank of Dallas. ``The oil industry
shrank, and others grew. Low oil prices still hurt the Texas
economy but not nearly as much as 12 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of oil production has shifted abroad, as new seismic
technologies have boosted exploration, and better machinery has
made it easier to pull oil from the ground and ocean floor.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging countries in South America, the Middle East and parts
of the former Soviet Union also have pumped up oil supplies,
because they are desperate for hard currency.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, Asia's economic troubles led to slower demand
for oil, resulting in the latest drop in prices.
</P>
<P>
   Drilling activity demonstrates how much the landscape has
changed. In 1981, Texas had 1,449 drilling rigs looking for oil.
Now the total is 246.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the number of rigs drilling in the Permian Basin
around Midland-Odessa has fallen 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While the Texas oil and gas business has declined, other
industries have emerged, especially around Fort Worth-Dallas. And
many of them benefit directly from cheap oil.
</P>
<P>
   In the Fort Worth area, oil and gas accounts for an estimated
4,300 jobs, about one-half of 1 percent of the work force. AMR
Corp., the parent of American Airlines, employs eight times that
number of workers in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   AMR, on pace for another year of record profits, said it saved
$238 million in the first nine months of '98 because of falling oil
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the region also benefits because it has become a center
for trucking and rail transportation, especially in the Alliance
Airport area. FedEx operates a hub there, and many companies ship
and store goods at Alliance area warehouses.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
