<SLUG> BC-McCAFFREY-DRUGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG ADVISER WARNS ABOUT GROWTH OF METHAMPHETAMINE USE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAIME CASTILLO  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ America is winning the war against cocaine, but
the drug is being quickly replaced by chemically produced
methamphetamine, a Clinton administration official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago, methamphetamine was a minor, West Coast,
biker-gang drug,'' said retired Army Gen. Barry McCaffrey, the
White House drug policy adviser. ``Now its a dominant drug problem
in the rural Midwest, Hawaii, Idaho and Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   While casual cocaine use has dropped by as much as 70 percent,
he said, methamphetamine use and production are spreading
throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has actually replaced cocaine as the principal emergency
room threat in Southern California and Hawaii,'' McCaffrey told
reporters before he addressed the Council of State Governments
meeting, which ended Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very worried about it, and I think we're going to see
more of this,'' he said of the narcotic methamphetamine.
</P>
<P>
   The organization devoted the last day of its meeting to drug
policy.
</P>
<P>
   During one panel discussion, Kansas Attorney General Carla
Stovall gave a grim account of methamphetamine use in the Midwest.
The narcotic is a powerful stimulant that is relatively easy and
cheap to manufacture.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of people are being injured each year in makeshift labs
that are cropping up in homes in Kansas, Stovall said.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the proliferation of the drug, Kansas lawmakers
want to stiffen criminal penalties.
</P>
<P>
   The officials who addressed the state government organization
agreed that government policy should focus on rehabilitation of
drug addicts and curbing drug use among children.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey said he was concerned by the message being sent to
children by advocacy groups that are pushing for the legalization
of marijuana for medicinal purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pain management is not best done with a joint or two vodkas _
it just doesn't ring true,'' he said. ``Doctors should decide about
medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey, who played video from four public service messages
designed to reduce drug abuse, said the number of eighth-graders
taking drugs has tripled in the last six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge to America is to keep kids from about the sixth
grade to the 12th grade from smoking pot and abusing alcohol,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-98 1819EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981208.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9146 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY09-COX     12-08 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SOCIAL SECURITY CONFEREES AGREE ON GOAL, NOT DIRECTION
 &HT;    480&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and congressional leaders found
common ground Tuesday on the need to preserve the nation's
retirement system, but differed over how to begin the reform
process and what Social Security should look like after it is
completed.
</P>
<P>
   The two-day conference is seeking ways to protect the 45 million
current beneficiaries while preserving Social Security for the 77
million baby boomers and their descendents in the next century. The
meeting's more than 200 participants represented widely divergent
views on how to achieve this, and Clinton urged them to keep an
open mind in their search.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many ways to deal with this, but there is only one
way to get it done,'' Clinton said. ``Let me say to all the people
on all sides of this debate: the only way we can save Social
Security ...is by working together, putting progress ahead of
partisanship, placing the long-term interests of the nation
first.''
</P>
<P>
   The first dispute is over who should step forward first with a
reform proposal _ and become a possible target for political
attacks on its painful remedies.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans want Clinton to offer a specific proposal soon,
while the administration wants to wait until a possible agreement
is taking shape.
</P>
<P>
   There are early signs that the reform battle may center on the
topic of investing part of the Social Security trust fund in
private securities markets, whose higher historical returns may
ease or eliminate the need for tax increases or benefit cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that ...people are looking favorably at
some form of prefunding(cq) that will give a higher return, and a
lot of the debate you're seeing is about what form that would
take,'' said Gene Sperling, the White House's chief economic
adviser.
</P>
<P>
   The key point of contention is whether individuals should be
able to invest their own retirement money, or whether the
government should invest it for them. Advocates of individual
accounts told the conference it would give people greater control
of their future. Advocates of having the government invest the
funds said it would minimize the risk faced by each retiree.
</P>
<P>
   The conference is the culmination of a year-long process that
began with the president's State of the Union message last January.
Early next year, Clinton plans to meet with congressional leaders
to begin negotiating a reform plan that would be voted into law.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will only get harder. Every single year we avoid
resolving this it will get harder and harder and harder,'' Clinton
told the conference Tuesday, pounding the podium. ``And everybody's
favorite idea will have a less beneficial impact the longer we
wait. Now is the time to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Without reform, the Social Security trust fund is expected to be
depleted by 2032, after which payroll taxes would cover only
three-fourths of benefits.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   While predicting reformers would have to ``sacrifice our sense
of the perfect to work together for the common good,'' Clinton
avoided offering a specific plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole point of this conference is to open honest debate
and to build consensus, not to shoot down ideas, or insist that one
side or the other has to go first,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans criticized Clinton's refusal to offer a plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``To save and strengthen Social Security, Mr. President, you
must lead our nation. It's that simple,'' said Rep. E. Clay Shaw
Jr., R-Fla., incoming House Ways and Means Social Security
subcommittee chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw, reading a text prepared by the Ways and Means chairman,
Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, urged Clinton to follow the lead taken
by previous presidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some presidents relied on commissions, some submitted plans,
but from Roosevelt to Reagan they all took a stand and they all
took the lead,'' Shaw said.
</P>
<P>
   After the speeches, Shaw said Clinton indicated he would submit
a plan and that he did not expect Republicans to take the lead with
a plan.
</P>
<P>
   Archer, who missed the opening speeches because of a scheduling
conflict, was harshly critical in his comments to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should the president play politics with the most important
issue facing the American public _ by his own definition _ this
coming year?'' Archer said. He said the conference ``will only be
worthwhile if, at the end of this, he presents a plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, who did not participate in
the conference, issued a statement offering to introduce whatever
Social Security reform bill Clinton sent to Congress as
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The conference _ one day at a Washington hotel, the second day
behind closed doors at the White House _ was designed to give key
lawmakers and interest groups an opportunity to discuss the need
for reform and some possible options.
</P>
<P>
   House Democratic leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri and Senate
Democratic leader Tom Daschle of South Dakota stressed that Social
Security should be renovated, not razed.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw and Sen. Rick Santorum, R-Pa., suggested that while reforms
should protect current beneficiaries, they also should offer
opportunities for higher returns to future retirees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've heard these themes before. The real question is: behind
the rhetoric, how flexible are people?'' said John Rother, AARP's
legislative director.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-98 1819EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
