<DOCNO> NYT19981208.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9147 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-12/08     12-08 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-12/08 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT TRIAL DEBATES BROWSER STRATEGY
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Microsoft antitrust trial took on the guise of
a computer science class Tuesday with the judge seeking to find
whether the ability to surf the Internet must be bolted into the
software giant's Windows operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying for the government as a $300-an-hour expert witness,
David Farber, a University of Pennsylvania professor, argued that a
computer operating system need only perform the basic functions
necessary to make the hardware respond to all applications,
including Web browsers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no technical barriers that prevent Microsoft from
developing and selling its Windows operating system as a stand
alone product separate from its browser software _ or other
software functions beyond the appropriate operating system
functions,'' Farber held in his direct testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The 14 million copies of Windows 98 which Microsoft has sold
since last May ``consists of modules which are malleable and
separable'' Farber wrote in written testimony unsealed late Monday.
Moreover, he added, there are ``no technical efficiencies'' that
couldn't be achieved by mounting Internet Explorer as a distinct
program that ran atop of Windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm sort of stuck with the whole grocery bag,''
Farber complained Tuesday to Microsoft lawyer Steven Holley, who
had proudly posted in the courtroom a large chart of 13 dual-use
functions which Microsoft had built into Windows 98 in such ways
that they cannot be removed without reducing the computer into a
useless box.
</P>
<P>
   Holley's strategy was to post a red ``no'' sign next to each of
the functions, thereby seeking to refute what the Justice
Department and 19 states have alleged: that Microsoft has illegally
tied Internet Explorer into its Windows operating system, thereby
denying consumers an effective choice.
</P>
<P>
   That was a cue for U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson,
who has mainly sat in silence in the eight weeks since the trial
began, to dig more deeply into the issue at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``So an operating system is something that has to be running
with everything?'' Jackson asked the witness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, sir,'' Farber replied.
</P>
<P>
   As Windows is currently packaged, Farber had noted earlier,
``you get the pinball machine and the solitaire game ... as part of
the operating system and that's just absurd.'' Microsoft contends
it includes the games in the package to help novice users learn how
to use a computer mouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average non-technical user ... has no desire to sit and
stare at an operating system idly,'' Holley replied, labeling
Farber's views as ``extreme.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What business people ordinarily refer to as an operating
system is far broader than what you are saying is an operating
system, is that not correct, Professor Farber?'' Holley said.
``...You're not suggesting, are you, that average users should be
subjected to a Chinese menu of system functions from which they
would have to assemble their own operating system?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're dealing with marketing terms as opposed to technical
terms,'' Farber replied. ``One of the problems in the academic
world is staying ahead of the marketing hype.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-98 1820EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
