   ``What business people ordinarily refer to as an operating
system is far broader than what you are saying is an operating
system, is that not correct, Professor Farber?'' Holley said.
``...You're not suggesting, are you, that average users should be
subjected to a Chinese menu of system functions from which they
would have to assemble their own operating system?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're dealing with marketing terms as opposed to technical
terms,'' Farber replied. ``One of the problems in the academic
world is staying ahead of the marketing hype.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
