<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9151 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-HNS &LR;      12-08 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOCIAL SECURITY CONFERENCE ATTEMPTS TO FOSTER BIPARTISANSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, opening a two-day conference
Tuesday on Social Security, called for an end to political rancor
that might block a consensus on how best to fix the government's
63-year-old retirement and disability benefits program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stakes are too high, the issues far too important,''
Clinton told an audience of more than 250 participants drawn from
Congress, advocacy groups, universities, labor unions and religious
organizations. Propping up Social Security is ``not about
politics,'' he said. ``It's about doing right by young Americans
and older Americans and the future of America.''
</P>
<P>
   But even as Clinton spoke, some rancor surfaced in the form of
controversy over the wisdom of turning the government-run system
into one augmented by individual retirement accounts.
</P>
<P>
   As it now stands, Social Security is a pay-as-you-go system
funded through a payroll tax of 12.4 percent, split evenly between
employers and employees.
</P>
<P>
   Under several plans backed by conservatives, Republicans and
some Democrats, individual account holders would receive retirement
earnings through a portion of their payroll taxes invested in
equity funds such as stocks. Under these plans, they would also
continue to receive benefits from the traditional Social Security
program.
</P>
<P>
   Opposing the idea of private accounts is an amalgam of AFL-CIO
unions, women's groups and liberal organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has avoided taking a stand on private accounts.
Clinton said Tuesday only that Social Security ``must remain a
rock-solid guarantee,'' and that beneficiaries must get paid
``regardless of the ups and downs of the economy or the markets.''
</P>
<P>
   But just after Clinton's speech, White House economic adviser
Gene Sperling told reporters, ``There's no question that we are
looking favorably on options that would in some way seek to bring
in higher returns.''
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton has not locked into any one plan, the White House
is exploring ``prudent ways'' to boost the Social Security trust
fund through investments, Sperling said.
</P>
<P>
   Hints that the White House might be leaning toward private
accounts infuriated representatives of unions and women's groups.
``It would be totally wrong,'' said Andrew Stern, president of the
Service Employees International Union. ``I represent a lot of
low-wage workers, people who need a guarantee and not a gamble.''
</P>
<P>
   Betty Friedan, a pioneering feminist and first president of the
National Organization for Women, said: ``I hope the Clinton
administration listens to women and older people, and stands firm
by not allowing any mucking around with Social Security. It's
dangerous. You don't want any Wall Street control over (financial)
security in old age.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of private accounts seemed confident that time is on
their side. ``I think the political dynamics lean toward some kind
of modest private accounts,'' said Martha Phillips, executive
director of the Concord Coalition, which favors a balanced budget
and supports creation of such accounts. ``They have to be there if
you want to get something through Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   One senior administration official, who asked not to be
identified, said the White House is exploring options other than
private accounts. An example: reserving budget surpluses
exclusively for the Social Security trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Budget Office projects a surplus of $1.55
trillion over the next decade, much of it from Social Security
payroll taxes.
</P>
<P>
   At the conference, participants debated topics such as the
impact of the budget surplus, the particular retirement needs of
minorities and women, and ``private market options.'' But much of
the conference's focus seemed to be on Clinton, when and if the
White House would put forward a Social Security plan of its own,
and how the administration ultimately will position itself on
private accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conferences are good for airing points of view, but in the end
there needs to be a decision made and that can come only from
presidential leadership,'' said House Ways and Means Committee
Chairman Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, whose panel has jurisdiction
over Social Security. Clinton ``needs to step up and lead or the
odds of getting this done are insurmountable. Politics as usual
will not get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Sperling responded that Clinton is ``trying to engage with
members of both parties'' on what is necessary to produce ``a
bipartisan agreement.'' He added, ``Whether and when (Clinton) puts
forward specific ideas, and what they will be, is not a decision to
be made at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Archer and Sperling agreed that a fix to Social Security must
come in the first half of 1999 because delay would bump the issue
into the 2000 presidential cycle. Waiting until the next century
would give lawmakers precious little time to overhaul the system
before the massive wave of baby boom retirements kicks in around
2010.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current system, as the 76 million baby boomers begin
swelling retiree ranks, the Social Security payroll tax alone will
not be sufficient to cover benefits. By 2013, the government will
have to dip into interest on the system's trust fund to meet its
obligations. By 2021, it will have to dip into the fund's
principal, and by 2032, the fund itself _ now valued at about
$756.9 billion _ will be depleted, and payroll taxes will provide
only enough to pay 75 percent of the benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Archer and Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, said they did not believe
the impeachment cloud hanging over Clinton would necessarily impede
progress on Social Security. ``We might try to wish it away but we
can't,'' said Gramm, who compared Clinton's troubles to playing a
football game in bad weather. ``You wish it wouldn't rain but you
play anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   The Social Security Administration beamed the proceedings to 57
mini-conferences in all 50 states and Puerto Rico. Wednesday's
wrap-up session will be held at the White House, with top
administration officials and lawmakers hashing out the issue behind
closed doors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
