<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9159 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS &LR;      12-08 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KHRISTICH MAKES A POINT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Bruins' leading scorer has not had a goal in four
games. But Dmitri Khristich is hardly concerned about a perceived
lack of production.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two games, the team scored three goals and I had two
assists, so I'm still getting points and that's what I'm trying to
do,'' Khristich said Tuesday. ``But statistics are really only
important when you are negotiating contracts. It measures how well
a person is doing, and if a person is doing well, the team will do
well. It all goes together.''
</P>
<P>
   Khristich has 11 goals and 16 assists, giving him and linemates
Jason Allison and Sergei Samsonov a direct contribution to more
than 40 percent of the Bruins' 63 goals. They have helped the
Bruins compile a seven-game undefeated streak, and since Nov. 3,
the team is 7-1-4 overall and unbeaten on the road going into
Thurday's visit to Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``When all three are on, they are pretty tough to defend,''
coach Pat Burns said. ``Dmitri is good with and without (the puck).
I was worried about what went on with his contract in the summer.
But it hasn't affected him. He's part of the team and he's fitting
in. His role hasn't changed a lot since last year. Dmitri is just
getting more breaks.''
</P>
<P>
   It is no secret that the Bruins are emphasizing defense, a
strategy that has been successful despite them being 11th in
scoring among the NHL's 14 teams with winning records. They would
not be nearly as effective, though, without an attacking line or
two.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to keep creating chances,'' Khristich said. ``Some
games the puck doesn't go in the net, but you have to keep doing
those things. You can't get frustrated. We had a stretch of some
games where the puck would not go in, but if you keep doing the
right things you will be rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we caught teams by surprise, they didn't know what
to expect from us. It's much tougher this year. We are in a tough
division. We can't take teams by surprise. They play us close, the
game is tight and they check our line. It can be more satisfying if
you beat teams under those conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' first line will be the target of Carolina Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a pretty good team, for sure,'' Burns said. ``Ron
Francis has brought them some experience. They make us scratch our
heads sometimes, but when they are on their game, they are tough to
beat. They are in the same position we are in; they've been off for
a few days. But after the first 10 minutes, the game should settle
down.
</P>
<P>
   Burns is preaching caution, though the Bruins appear to have
confidence and momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't lost a lot of games,'' Burns said. ``We've held our
own. But that could change quick.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
