<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9169 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OIL-TEXAS-2ndTake-TEX     12-08 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-TEXAS-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
FORT WORTH, Texas: area warehouses. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The General Motors plant in Arlington, which employs about 1,300
workers to produce full-size pickups and sport utility vehicles,
has seen the drop in prices improve its prospects. Much of its
hot-selling products' market gains are attributable to cheap
gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   Trucking companies are reporting banner results, thanks to high
traffic and low fuel prices. The American Trucking Association says
the industry has saved about $3 billion from the 15-cent decline in
diesel prices in '98.
</P>
<P>
   Although some clearly benefit from the plunge in oil prices, the
Fed's Brown said that the trend is still a net negative for the
entire state and perhaps the region.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas, for example, has several oil service companies, and
they've been among the hardest hit by the downturn in prices.
Halliburton Co. plans to lay off 8,100 workers companywide in the
next few months.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, many residents receive royalty checks from oil
properties. Those numbers are obviously going south.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas is still not at the point where falling prices are a
benefit,'' Brown said. ``Consumers benefit from low-priced gas, and
that helps with shipping costs, including food.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the layoffs that are coming in oil and gas are going to
have a ripple effect. They'll lead to less spending in retail and
housing.''
</P>
<P>
   And they'll reach into related industries, such as Dale Meyer
Trucking in Odessa. The transportation company, which has 42
trucks, specializes in hauling drilling rigs and pipe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can buy diesel fuel cheaper,'' said Gary Meyer, who heads
the 47-year-old company. ``but if we're not moving rigs, it doesn't
do us any good.''
</P>
<P>
   Even among people who remember oil as king, there is no fear of
the kind of catastrophe that struck the state during the '80s. One
reason is that oil companies are focused on controlling costs and
are quickly responding to the shifting market.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Exxon and Mobil agreed to the biggest merger in
history, with a market value of more than $80 billion. Others have
teamed up: British Petroleum and Amoco, Kerr-McGee and Oryx Energy,
Halliburton and Dresser, Atlantic-Richfield and Union Texas
Petroleum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consolidation has built much bigger, stronger companies that
can weather the storm much better,'' said Larry Helm, who heads
energy lending at Bank One Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Mergers also enable the companies to cut costs quickly. Layoffs
are already apparent, but more are coming. Exxon and Mobil said
they plan to cut at least 9,000 jobs worldwide. BP-Amoco wants to
lay off 6,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
   Oil and gas employment has fallen for four consecutive months in
Texas and is down by 2,100 jobs in the past year. Last week, Union
Pacific Resources Group said it will eliminate 140 jobs in Fort
Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very real pain for these people,'' said Higgins of the
state comptroller's office. ``They have very specialized skills,
and they earn high wages. They don't have a lot of quick
alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Some have decided to wait it out, banking that prices will
recover soon.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Gearhart, owner of Rock Bit Industries in Fort Worth,
said he hasn't laid off any of his 50 employees. He has even gone
ahead with a Christmas bonus _ although he admits to some doubts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been telling our people it won't last all that long,''
Gearhart said of the downturn. ``But with Exxon buying Mobil, maybe
I don't know as much as I thought I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Oil producers say their problems are even worse than they appear
to much of the public. The prices quoted daily from the New York
Mercantile Exchange, the energy industry's marketplace, are for
deliveries in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The price that refiners pay often averages at least $1 per
barrel less than the futures prices. In futures trading Friday,
West Texas intermediate crude closed at $11.17, meaning that many
refiners are paying $10 or less per barrel _ lower than the price
during the 1986 market crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you factor inflation into the price, we're seeing the
lowest spot crude prices in 40 years,'' said Fred Rabalais, an
independent oil producer in Fort Worth, who has been in the
business for four decades.
</P>
<P>
   Low prices also have stung the Permanent University Fund, the
$7.2 billion investment portfolio that supports the University of
Texas and Texas A&AMP;M University.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, royalties and bonuses from oil-producing properties
generated more than $250 million for the fund, accounting for 23
percent of the portfolio's value. Now the 2 million acres of land
dedicated to the fund produce about $70 million in annual income,
equal to just 1 percent of the holdings, said Thomas Ricks, chief
executive of the fund.
</P>
<P>
   Although falling oil production hurts, it also prompted
officials to invest more aggressively in stocks. Since 1990, the
fund earned more in investment returns than it racked up in 75
years of oil profits.
</P>
<P>
   And since '81, the endowment has grown from about $1 billion to
more than $7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fund reflects the transition that's happened with the rest
of the state,'' Ricks said. ``Both of us have evolved from a
resource-based economy to one that is richer and more diverse.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
