<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE HAS COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Several prominent Democrats are already angling for
a chance to take on Vice President Al Gore for the party's
presidential nomination in 2000, despite Gore's intimidatingly
healthy head start.
</P>
<P>
   What makes them think they can outwit, outspend, outtalk and
out-campaign the 800-pound political gorilla who has been the
hard-working, very visible heir-apparent to the Democratic throne
for six years? Are they nuts?
</P>
<P>
   No, not crazy. Just brash and ambitious. And aware that in
politics you can't get ahead if you don't play the game.
</P>
<P>
   At a conference of the centrist Democratic Leadership Council
the other day four politicians provocatively began positioning
themselves for a run for the presidency in two years.
</P>
<P>
   Former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley promptly followed that up
with an announcement that he has formed a presidential exploratory
committee. Nebraska Sen. Bob Kerrey, Massachusetts Sen. John Kerry
and House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt say they will decide soon
whether to join Bradley. Minnesota Sen. Paul Wellstone is also
dropping presidential hints, although he is not taken as seriously
as the others.
</P>
<P>
   Of the bunch, Gephardt might be the strongest contender but is
the least likely to actually take the leap. His prospects for
becoming House Speaker brightened considerably when the Democratic
gain of five House seats in the November election edged his party
close to majority status. The speakership will be a lot easier for
him to attain than the presidency, for which he would have to begin
campaigning and raising money right away.
</P>
<P>
   Gore had hoped that his formidable intellect and pragmatic
political assets would scare away potentially serious rivals.
Compared with the rogue who currently occupies the White House, he
has managed to remain relatively scandal-free. With no independent
counsel on his trail, his dealings with those Buddhist monks and
his questionable fund-raising phone calls won't do him in.
</P>
<P>
   Except in rare instances of a popular incumbent, the presidency,
that ultimate political prize, is never handed over on a platter.
It has to be won by campaigning hard for it.
</P>
<P>
   So Bradley and company are moving to make Gore work for it, and
they will see what happens when they do. There is always the
surprise factor in politics. Today's political fantasy may be
tomorrow's reality. Who knows?
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, former Vice President Walter Mondale expected to coast
to the presidential nomination but found himself blindsided by an
attractive young senator hardly anyone knew much about. Colorado's
Gary Hart so caught the public fancy that Mondale did not cinch the
nomination until the final primaries that June.
</P>
<P>
   One year before the 1992 presidential campaign, President George
Bush was so popular in the wake of the Persian Gulf War that
Gephardt and other leading Democrats declined to challenge him.
That cleared the field for second-tier candidates of dubious
presidential stature.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the party's big shots, that unknown Arkansas governor,
Bill Clinton, and marginal political players _ Iowa Sen. Tom
Harkin, former California Gov. Jerry Brown, former Massachusetts
Sen. Paul Tsongas and Kerrey _ figured they had nothing to lose by
going for it.
</P>
<P>
   There was also the unanticipated, erratic presence of Ross
Perot, who split the vote by running as an independent.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Election Day neared, Bush had fallen like a stone in
the public opinion polls and was defeated by Clinton. The
Democratic nomination had been worth something after all.
</P>
<P>
   The year 2000 is also tempting because it will be one of the few
times in recent history that no incumbent president is on the
ballot. (The last time was 1988 and before that 1960 and 1928.)
</P>
<P>
   Gore has persistently clung to Clinton's side as half of the
best-advertised and congenial White House twosome in memory, but he
is still only the vice president. And being No. 2 is never as good
a deal as being No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   As the clear frontrunner, Gore will be the favorite target of
all others who get into the presidential race. Until now, Clinton
has absorbed most of the slings and arrows of political warfare.
But that will change soon, as the power struggle shifts from
impeachment madness to the 2000 campaign. Gore is bound to take
some hits and look a lot more like damaged goods than he presently
does.
</P>
<P>
   If they are to compete, presidential candidates in both parties
must be up and running soon, which is why hopefuls are getting
itchy. The bulk of the primaries will be held unusually early in
2000. The nomination could be determined by the end of March. That
does not leave much time for fund-raising, identity-establishing
and rival-bashing.
</P>
<P>
   To the winner, who is still likely to be Gore, will go the
spoils. But to the best loser often goes the consolation prize, the
vice presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   And despite all the jokes about the valueless veepdom, it isn't
a bad job. It comes with a nice house, car, free travel and
interesting company. That itself may make the exercise worthwhile
for other wannabes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
