<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: BIG WEEK FOR PREVIN; QUEEN MOTHER HONORS NOEL
COWARD; MAUGHAM PAPERS IN BOSTON; LIGHTS OF BROADWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Great Britain, Mass.)   (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Even if Andre Previn were inclined to rest on his
laurels, he wouldn't have time. He was a Kennedy Center honors
recipient on Sunday night and is to be named Musical America's 1999
Musician of the Year on Tuesday at Lincoln Center. This week he has
two appearances at Avery Fisher Hall, where Kurt Masur and the New
York Philharmonic will celebrate the George Gershwin centennial
through Dec. 19.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday at 8 p.m. and Friday at 11 a.m., Previn will be the
piano soloist in the Concerto in F. On Friday at 8 p.m., he moves
to Alice Tully Hall for a program of Gershwin and jazz with the
bassist David Finck. And on Dec. 30 is PBS' national telecast of
the world premiere of the San Francisco Opera production of his
opera, ``A Streetcar Named Desire,'' starring Renee Fleming as
Blanche.
</P>
<P>
   Blithe Spirits
</P>
<P>
   Britain's queen mother, mouthing the words of ``Mad Dogs and
Englishmen,'' paid tribute to Noel Coward in London. Anticipating
next year's 100th anniversary of his birth, she unveiled Angela
Conner's life-size statue of Coward, the playwright and composer
who died in 1973, in the foyer of the Theater Royal in Drury Lane.
The queen mother, a friend of Coward's, praised him, adding, ``I
think we are fortunate to be the legatees of his lovely music and
his lighthearted fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Penmen
</P>
<P>
   W.Somerset Maugham (1894-1965) will be the focus of attention at
Boston University Thursday when its department of special
collections opens an exhibition of rare manuscripts, personal
papers and memorabilia of Maugham, the author of ``Of Human
Bondage'' and ``The Razor's Edge.'' Saul Bellow, the Nobel laureate
in literature, will speak at the opening ceremony. The Maugham
papers include more than 500 letters from notables like Raymond
Chandler, Winston Churchill, T.S. Eliot and E.M. Forster.
</P>
<P>
   Light Entertainment
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The spectacle on tap for Broadway at 5:30 p.m.
Wednesday is to light up the tree. With stars and members of
virtually every Broadway and Off Broadway show expected and with
Audra McDonald of ``Ragtime'' and Roger Daltrey of ``A Christmas
Carol'' as the switch flippers, the 1998 Broadway holiday tree will
come to life next to the TKTS booth in Duffy Square, at Broadway
and 46th Street. Then comes a holiday sing led by the Broadway
Kids, the 8-to-15-year-old Broadway veterans in a weekend revue at
the Douglas Fairbanks Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Besides sponsoring the event with the Times Square Business
Improvement District, two other groups, the Theater Development
Fund and the League of American Theaters and Producers, are
starting an annual gift of $5,000 to a nonprofit organization
serving theater people. The first recipient is the Actors' Fund.
</P>
</TEXT>
