<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-FACTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVING WITH CHEAP OIL
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: Accompanies OIL-TEXAS) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oil prices have plunged 40 percent in the past year, and, for
the first time since 1986, may be headed to $10 a barrel. Some
effects _ good and bad _ of cheap oil:
</P>
<P>
   _ In real dollars, consumers are enjoying the lowest prices at
the pump since before the oil embargo in 1973. Some Fort
Worth-Dallas gas stations are selling gas for less than 90 cents a
gallon, and lower prices are coming. Cheap oil also contributes to
low inflation, a boon for mortgage financing, home construction and
vehicle loans.
</P>
<P>
   _ American Airlines, the largest employer in North Texas, saved
$238 million in fuel costs in the first nine months of '98.
</P>
<P>
   _ Truck sales topped car sales in November for the first time
since a brief period after World War II. Low gasoline prices makes
it less expensive for consumers to drive larger vehicles. That not
only cheers truck-loving Texas, it's a boost for the General Motors
assembly plant in Arlington, which makes trucks and sport utility
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mergers are sweeping the energy industry. Last week, Exxon and
Mobil agreed to the biggest deal in history. Big layoffs are
coming. Employment in the industry has fallen for four consecutive
months in Texas, and companies plan a slew of layoffs. For example,
Exxon-Mobil plans to cut at least 9,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Trucking companies say they're enjoying their best market in
decades. Traffic is high, diesel has dropped to $1 a gallon _ the
lowest in years _ profits are climbing and they're hiring.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
