<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9180 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OIL-GRAHAM-TEX     12-08 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-GRAHAM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE-TIME CENTER FOR OIL DRILLING SURVIVES BY DIVERSIFYING ECONOMY
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies OIL-TEXAS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAN PILLER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAHAM, Texas _ This town of 9,000, which sits astride the
Brazos River 80 miles northwest of Fort Worth, was a busy oil
community four decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   It's still a busy community. Oil is just not as big a part of it
as it once was.
</P>
<P>
   Oil and gas have been drilled in Young County since World War I,
and Graham has long enjoyed the reputation as one of the state's
centers for independent oil and gas production.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Texas energy industry slumped in the mid-'50s, the
folks in Graham decided to try to diversify the local economy.
</P>
<P>
   Town leaders formed an Industrial Development Commission and,
over the years, it has helped attract industries that made such
products as computer tape, aircraft parts, stadium bleachers and
boating equipment.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Graham will have a cushion for this round of low
oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd been in the business long enough to see that energy could
go up and down and that we'd better get some other industries in
town,'' said Roy Pitcock, who in 1956 was four years removed from
his graduation from TCU and had returned home to help his father
run the family oil business, now called Pitcock Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The diversification, to be sure, has been a slow turn, with a
few bumps along the way. And the oil slumps, which seem to hit at
least once each decade, still sting.
</P>
<P>
   But Graham has not withered away. Indeed, Graham this year has
begun a $600,000 downtown restoration that includes putting in new
sidewalks and upgrading the lighting system.
</P>
<P>
   The first big diversification score came in 1959, when Graham
attracted a Hexcel Corp. plant that made aircraft parts. Plant
employment reached 500 during the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Bleachers later opened a 90-worker plant to make
outdoor seating.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged, the Graham Industrial Development Commission sought
and attracted operations such as Anacomp (originally Graham
Magnetics), a maker of computer tape that now employs 350, and
Texas Recreation, which makes water sports equipment and employs
75.
</P>
<P>
   When Hexcel closed its plant in the early '90s, Graham was able
to snag a relocation of Schlegal Co., which makes weatherstripping
materials, to use some of the abandoned Hexcel space.
</P>
<P>
   The last big energy bust, beginning in 1986, took away most of
the town's roughnecks and locally owned drilling rigs. Today's
energy people are contractors, not operators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago, we had about 80 rigs working out of Graham,''
Pitcock said. ``Each rig needs a crew of 12. Now, we have three
rigs out of Graham.''
</P>
<P>
   So Graham thinks that it can weather the current downturn in
good shape, although it isn't smug about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done a lot to protect ourselves,'' said banker Jay
Gober, who heads the Industrial Development Association. ``But $10
per barrel oil is going to hurt. We'll lose some more operators,
and we'll feel it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Doug Stroud not only oversees the local economic activity
but participates in the energy industry as an investor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Graham is doing well under the circumstances,'' he said. ``But
we're not immune from economic changes.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-98 1842EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
