<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SECRET LIFE OF LEADFOOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let me tell you about the man with the bright blue Corvette, who
drives 55 miles an hour along a residential boulevard, whipping in
and out of traffic, risking his neck and anyone else's to gain a
car length.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, he is hugely vain about that bright blue machine,
and he fears more than anything that he might not be noticed
driving it.
</P>
<P>
   Other things he may be insecure about. His job. His sexual
identity. The cut of his clothes. But when he is behind the wheel
of his bright blue Corvette, all those gnawing worries somehow just
go away.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicle could be a restored classic. I wouldn't know _ or
care. It was built to resemble a racing car, and I am surprised he
has not stenciled VALVOLINE in big letters on the side.
</P>
<P>
   What is the use of having a vehicle that will go from 0 to 55
miles an hour in three seconds if nobody knows it?
</P>
<P>
   I saw him first in the rear-view mirror, weaving from lane to
lane and closing at a great rate. Then he got caught behind a rank
of drivers who deliberately, maliciously, stupidly were driving the
speed limit.
</P>
<P>
   After a block or two, however, he spotted an opening and managed
to break out, rocketing forward with engine screaming, dodging
between lesser machines until he topped a hill and passed from
sight.
</P>
<P>
   I would like to have had a decent view of the fellow _ to see
what he looks like, and know if I speculate correctly about the low
hairline and receding brow.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, all I got as he hurtled past was a brief look at
his hands, white-knuckled on the wheel. They were small hands, and
looked weak. But being in the driver's seat of such a machine must
compensate for many such inadequacies.
</P>
<P>
   Possibly you think I am antagonistic toward this man. But why
would I be? He has not, so far as I know, driven his bright blue
Corvette through a sidewalk restaurant or broadsided a public bus.
Not /{yet,/} anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, I see the fellow as a potential community
resource.
</P>
<P>
   Police are wasting their time, loitering on side streets,
training their radar guns randomly at the passing traffic, hoping
to catch a mom with a car pool driving four miles over the limit.
</P>
<P>
   That just isn't cost effective. Not when you have this Walter
Mitty, fantasizing he's on the speedway at Daytona, not just
bending the law but obliterating it with flair.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of going for small potatoes, why not station an unmarked
car outside his house, and position others _ a great many others _
at strategic points along his daily route, adding up his
transgressions as he passes.
</P>
<P>
   I would be willing to guess that the fines for a single day's
misbehavior would be enough to patch a potholed street, replace a
few blocks of broken curbing or repair one of the city's many
famous crumbling bridges.
</P>
<P>
   A fine notion, you say. But how could the police ever hope to
locate Leadfoot and his dream machine among all the millions of
cars in the city? Where would they even start?
</P>
<P>
   Well, as it happens, the bright blue Corvette had a license
plate _ a Missouri plate, at that. And busybody that I am, I jotted
down the number, on the chance it might someday be of use.
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't dream of giving out the number to just anybody. But
interested law officers are welcome to call.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
