<HEADER>
A9190 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-STERN-NBA-COX     12-08 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-STERN-NBA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As time on season's play clock runs down, no deal in sight for
NBA
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ David Stern surveys the stunning success he has made
of the NBA and winces at fault lines in the foundation and the
cracking sounds that tell us pieces are falling off his beautifully
conceived machinery.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth month of a lockout, the death knell of a season
sounding, the commissioner says wistfully, ``What we would like to
do is sit down with our players and negotiate a deal that could get
them back.''
</P>
<P>
   However, as the bell tolls, very little negotiating is getting
done. The two sides have held three meetings in as many months,
none fruitful. One of the league's premiere events, the All-Star
game scheduled for Feb. 14, was canceled on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The players have suffered huge financial losses, and they beg
the public to take note of that. The teams squirrel away TV money
that will be re-paid later. The commissioner, who quietly has not
taken a paycheck since August, said, ``I'm reminded of it every
time I go to the bank to make a withdrawal.''
</P>
<P>
   It is too late to ask if the NBA acted precipitously by invoking
its lockout of players in July, too late to suggest that the
problem of over-blown salaries might have resolved itself as the
Joe Smiths of the world fell by the wayside.
</P>
<P>
   But if you remember the early 1980s and the rebirth of the NBA
under Stern, the question is, how could a business that brings in
$2 billion have reached the point of self-destruction? How could
the only professional league not to lose a game to labor strife, a
sport that is the darling of NBC and the cable industry, have
suffered such a severe self-inflicted wound?
</P>
<P>
   The common antagonist is money.
</P>
<P>
   When Stern and the late union chief Larry Fleisher hammered out
the first salary cap in 1983, the payroll of each of 16 teams was
$2.6 million, increasing to $3 million in the third year. When the
Hawks paid $1 million for the rights to Dominique Wilkins, the
terms were historic in a league that had so little clout that CBS
refused to televise the championships in prime-time.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the 29-team league unveiled a proposal that would set
this season's salary cap at $31 million per team, approximately
Michael Jordan's pay for 1997-98. The cap would increase to $55
million in 2004-05, when the average salary would jump from last
season's $2.6 million to $4.983 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would guarantee our players that the mean and median
salaries would continue to be the highest in professional sports,''
Stern said during a visit here Monday.
</P>
<P>
   It's not enough to get a deal, however.
</P>
<P>
   After Stern unveiled his proposal for the players last Thursday,
union president Patrick Ewing said he did not believe the numbers
were correct, deepening players' mistrust of the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those numbers are our numbers,'' Stern said. ``I represent
that they are our numbers, and we've agreed with the players and
their accountants that these numbers are accurate and uncontested.
So it's a little late in the game (for posturing).''
</P>
<P>
   So, how can the players say no to a proposal that offers so
much?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because not everything is what it seems,'' Dikembe Mutombo,
Hawks center and union vice-president said Tuesday. ``They don't
tell you about the 20 percent tax they proposed, and we don't know
where it's going. They don't tell you they are taking away our
licensing money (of $25 million last season). And they are
misleading you when they show how much money you can make after 10
years as a Larry Bird guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I'm not stupid,'' Mutombo said. ``I know there's no way
Stan Kasten is going to pay me $24 million dollars after I'm in the
league 10 years. It will never happen except for a guy like Michael
Jordan, so what does it mean? The numbers look nice, but they will
never pay that.''
</P>
<P>
   The owners say they will never ask the players to take a cut and
are, in fact, factoring in a 5 percent annual increase and an
average of 53 percent of the league's profits in the final three
years of the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we've told the players that obviously we're prepared to
negotiate with you further, that there is some give and take,''
Stern said. ``But basically, they've said if there's nothing more
that we have to say, at this point, they refuse to negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the last meeting, they said they had a proposal they would
like to make to us, but we would have had to agree in advance that
it would satisfy us at every other point. We said we couldn't do
that and if they had something to say to us we wish they would.''
</P>
<P>
   Mutombo also disputed that point. ``The way it happened,'' he
said, ``is we asked them for their final number. We said if you are
ready to give us your final number (on percentage of revenues),
we'll see if it's something we can take to our members. They
refused, so what was there to discuss?''
</P>
<P>
   It would appear that such powerful agents as David Falk and Arn
Tellem are blocking an agreement. Falk's clients dominate the
union's executive committee.
</P>
<P>
   Stern won't comment. ``I would only say this: The deal would pay
every contract that's existent, increase the minimum, provide an
exception for the $1.5 million player and have veterans who are
playing at the minimum play for $1 million. That has to come from
some place, and that some place is the high-end players. So the
notion that the agents for the high-end players are protecting the
middle class doesn't quite resonate with us.''
</P>
<P>
   What does resonate is the ticking of the clock. The All-Star
Game is dead. Christmas is coming. If there is no deal by New
Year's, NBA will stand for No Basketball Action.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Denberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
