<HEADER>
A9191 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-GASOUTH-COX     12-08 0479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GASOUTH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former cheerleader will start for Ga. Southern in playoffs
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With an injury-riddled defense increasingly hammered
during the I-AA playoffs, top-ranked Georgia Southern has been
forced to seek help from a group of reserves, including a former
cheerleader.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Butler, a 5-11, 202-pound junior whose sister is the
placekicker at Riverdale High School, will start at linebacker
Saturday when the Eagles (13-0) play the Leathernecks of Western
Illinois (11-2) in a semifinal at Paulson Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Butler, a cheerleader at Georgia State before transferring and
walking on at Georgia Southern in the spring of 1997, has moved
into a starting role because of injuries to several players,
including starters Daryl Morrell and Larry Rogers. ``When nobody
offered Tony a scholarship after high school, he was a little
discouraged, so he went to Georgia State,'' Riverdale High coach
George Spencer said. ``He found out that there was a little
scholarship money in cheerleading, so he said, 'What the heck, I'll
try it.' It was a little strange, him being a cheerleader and his
sister down here as a placekicker.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonya Butler, who will be in a uniform in the Georgia Dome on
Saturday when Riverdale High faces Peach County in a semifinal game
of the state AAA playoff, has made 62 of 63 PATs and seven of 11
field-goal attampts, with a long of 39 yards. According to Spencer,
Tonya could be fortunate enough to get a scholarship, something her
brother still hasn't won.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm just glad he's finally getting the opportunity to
play,'' said Spencer, who made numerous calls to Georgia Southern
for Tony Butler before the '97 spring drills. ``He's a kid who is a
little slow and a little short, but his heart is big as a truck. He
loves the game, and he'll give it everything he's got.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of injuries to Morrell (neck) and Rogers (sprained knee)
and the limited effectiveness of sophomore Dante Harrow (knee),
Butler will start alongside senior Josh Smithers and redshirt
freshman Jason Neese, from McEachern High School.
</P>
<P>
   Of the six or seven healthy linebackers on the Eagles' rosters,
Neese is the only one who was on the two-deep depth chart at the
beginning of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Butler, who appeared in eight games as a special-teams player
last season, has played sparingly in 11 games so far. He pushed his
total number of unassisted tackles to 18 with three solo hits in
Georgia Southern's 52-30 victory over Connecticut this past
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's real scrappy,'' Georgia Southern coach Paul Johnson said,
``and I think he loves playing the game as much anybody I've ever
been around.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnest Reese writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
