u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS09-COX     12-08 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coach, players take exception with notion that focus lacks in
first half
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta Falcons coach Dan Reeves hasn't had much to
gripe about during the last six months, but one question always
seems to hit his hot button. Ask if he is concerned about his
team's tendency to start games slowly, and his lips tighten, his
tone changes, and he makes his feelings clear.
</P>
<P>
   It it is a legitimate question for a squad that has trailed in
eight of 13 games this year. The last three Sundays, the Falcons
trailed the Bears 13-3 in the third quarter, the Rams 7-3 in the
third quarter and the Colts 21-7 in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   They rallied to win all three, a sure sign of a team that has
improved on the way to a stunning 11-2 record. But it's not a good
habit, especially with the playoffs looming and an improved Saints
team waiting in New Orleans on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many different ways can you answer that question?'' Reeves
asked. ``If somebody says, 'Were you motivated or not?' it's one or
the other. All I'm telling you is, I don't think we had a lack of
emotion. I don't think we came out flat. The Colts made some plays,
and we didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good thing is, we didn't lose our poise,'' the coach said.
``We found a way to win. If you think we're going to jump out
because we're 11-2, and regardless of who we're playing it's going
to be 14-0, 21-0, 28-0, you're wrong, because we're not that kind
of football team. OK?''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle Shane Dronett has a different perspective.
``I'm glad we're playing three good teams in the next three weeks,
so we can get focused,'' Dronett said, referring to the Saints,
Lions and Dolphins. ``It's almost an arrogance, where you believe
what you read about yourself or your team, and you don't play as
well. You lose your focus. You're almost content with the ways
things are going.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves doesn't believe that. Neither does tight end O.J.
Santiago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not buying into this about us not being prepared to play
or that we take people lightly,'' he said. ``We came out there
ready to play ball. I had a turnover that put (the Colts) in good
position on the first drive. They only had to go (26) yards to
score, and the next thing you know we're down 7-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams like that have nothing to lose,'' Santiago said.
``They're going to try new things, different looks on offense and
defense for next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said, ``We're not the kind of team that can play on just
turning on a switch.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Falcons have showed an ability to rally fast.
</P>
<P>
   They scored two touchdowns in the final 1:21 of the first half
to tie the Colts, then Ray Buchanan intercepted a Peyton Manning
pass on the first play of the second half. Three plays later,
quarterback Chris Chandler hit Terance Mathis on a 4-yard touchdown
pass.
</P>
<P>
   In a span of 13 plays, nine by Atlanta's offense, the Falcons
went from a 21-7 deficit to a 28-21 lead, with just 3:04 elapsing.
</P>
<P>
   With a defense ranked third in the NFL with 31 takeaways; with
two receivers, Mathis and Tony Martin, on pace to have 1,000-yard
seasons; and with Chandler completing 57 percent of his passes for
an average of 16.2 yards per completion, the Falcons do have the
ability to rally.
</P>
<P>
   But if Atlanta falls behind Sunday at New Orleans, a comeback
figures to be more difficult. It will be the same in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Saints (6-7) have plenty of incentive. They have lost seven
in a row to the Falcons, three in the Crescent City, and they're
tied with Arizona and Tampa Bay in a race for the final wild-card
spot.
</P>
<P>
   A loss to the Saints and a victory by the 49ers over the Lions
would leave both teams 11-3, and San Francisco would hold a
tiebreaker edge over Atlanta in the race for the division title.
</P>
<P>
   So, now would be a good time to break the slow-start habit.
</P>
<P>
   FALLING BEHIND
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have trailed in eight of 13 games this season, but
have rallied six times.
</P>
<P>
   Date Opponent Deficit, Qtr. Result
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 13 Philadelphia 9-0, halftime Falcons 17, Eagles 12
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 27 San Francisco 31-7, halftime 49ers 31, Falcons 20
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 11 N.Y. Giants 3-0, 1st Qtr. Falcons 34, Giants 20
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 18 New Orleans 7-3, 1st Qtr. Falcons 31, Saints 23
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 25 N.Y. Jets 14-0, 2nd Qtr. Jets 28, Falcons 3
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 22 Chicago 13-3, 3rd Qtr. Falcons 20, Bears 13
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 29 St. Louis 7-3, 3rd Qtr. Falcons 21, Rams 10
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 6 Indianapolis 21-7, 2nd Qtr. Falcons 28, Colts 21
</P>
