<SLUG> BC-FBN-INSTANTREPLAY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Owners not ready to reinstate replay rule
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If the NFL floated the possibility of instant replay
for the playoffs to help save face after a 1998 season marred by
questionable officiating, the idea could backfire.
</P>
<P>
   Despite complaints about officiating, indications Tuesday were
that owners would reject replay if commissioner Paul Tagliabue
polled them by conference call next week. Eight votes would block
the return of replays.
</P>
<P>
   A check Tuesday with some owners found eight solidly opposed to
replay and at least two others leaning that way. Several owners
characterized as over-reaction the Monday announcement that the NFL
was considering a limited replay system for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal might not even come to a vote, especially if
Tagliabue senses opposition. ``We've seen the real-life definition
of 'knee-jerk,''' said Bengals owner Mike Brown, a long-time replay
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Retired game official Jim Tunney, one of the most respected
referees of this era, said that implementing replay now would
destroy officials' morale.
</P>
<P>
   At least two owners who voted against replay at the league
owners meeting in March, when it failed 21-9, said they now favor
it. But some owners, including Pittsburgh's Dan Rooney who
supported replay in March, said they could not reconcile
implementing the system for the playoffs and without the debate
that usually accompanies such decisions. Even NFL senior vice
president George Young questioned the wisdom and the timing of
Monday's trial balloon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The league always has maintained the same rules of competition
(for the regular season and the postseason),'' Young said. ``I
don't run the league, but how in the world . . . could we go into
the most critical part of a season without having tested this? What
kind of logic is that?''
</P>
<P>
   Len Pasquarelli writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
