<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-GEMSTAR-SCIATL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scientific-Atlanta, rival sue each other over on-screen TV
guides
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gemstar has counter-sued Scientific-Atlanta over its
interactive on-screen TV guide in what's shaping up as a major
battle over who will control what viewers see when they first turn
on their TVs in the coming digital age.
</P>
<P>
   At stake are millions from advertisers who will pay a premium
for preferred placement on the on-screen guides.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the dispute is use of the software that creates
interactive television guides. The guides have become essential in
new digital TV set-top boxes, which enable viewers to get more than
200 channels. With the technology, viewers can search for shows,
get show descriptions and program VCRs with the touch of a button.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific-Atlanta is a major manufacturer of the boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Gemstar's patent infringement suit was filed in federal district
court in Northern California. It came days after Scientific-Atlanta
charged the Pasadena, Calif.-based company with antitrust and
patent violations in its own suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We view Scientific-Atlanta's anti-trust allegations ... as a
desperate attempt to delay the severe legal consequences of its
willful infringement of Gemstar's intellectual property rights,''
says Henry C. Yuen, Gemstar's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific-Atlanta executives declined to comment, explaining
they never discuss ongoing legal challenges.
</P>
<P>
   The company's suit surprised industry observers and journalists
alike. Scientific-Atlanta executives first announced it Friday on a
bus full of analysts the company was escorting from the Western
Show in Anaheim, Calif. The analysts were being taken to see a
demonstration of the company's digital cable technology in an
Orange County system owned by Atlanta-based Cox Communications.
</P>
<P>
   On-screen guides are the first thing many digital TV subscribers
see when they turn on their televisions. They have become valuable
television commercial real estate, with some advertisers clamoring
to get on.
</P>
<P>
   Interactive guides have been contentious from the start. The
original two developers, Prevue and StarSight, have been battling
legally over the technology since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The battle grew more complex when Gemstar, a longtime supplier
of software to the consumer electronics industry, bought StarSight
in May 1997. StarSight had been a technology start-up funded by the
cable TV industry, including Cox Communications.
</P>
<P>
   When Gemstar bought StarSight, Gemstar's software was already
being used by Scientific-Atlanta. The Norcross, Ga.-based maker of
cable TV equipment was planning to use StarSight as the guide in
its new Explorer 2000 digital set-top system. That system has been
sold to many of the top cable TV operators, including Cox
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific-Atlanta and Gemstar soon were in struggle over
interactive TV guide technology. Scientific-Atlanta lost the first
round when an arbitration panel ruled it had ``misappropriated''
the StarSight technology. It had to pay Gemstar $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   The companies negotiated a new contract, in which
Scientific-Atlanta continued to use Gemstar's StarSight technology
for a fee. But that contract is due to expire July 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assume Gemstar and Scientific-Atlanta were in the process of
renegotiating that contract,'' said Alan Gould, a media analyst
with Gerard Klauer Mattison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scientific-Atlanta realized the fee for using StarSight was
going to go up. It could either pay more or get sued,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gemstar has already sued Scientific-Atlanta's two biggest
set-top competitors, General Instruments and Pioneer, which also
use StarSight in their digital set-top boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Gould says that, in effect, ``Scientific-Atlanta launched a
pre-emptive strike.'' By suing first, he explained, the company
guaranteed its case would be heard in Atlanta _ not Northern
California.
</P>
<P>
   Cable TV operators consider the guides important to winning
subscribers over to digital television service, for which they
charge a premium.
</P>
<P>
   Industry surveys have shown that consumers like the guides,
which is why the operators want Scientific-Atlanta, Gemstar and
others to settle, once and for all, who owns the technology.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
