</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIVATE-JAIL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Officials deny company's claims of new prison dealBy Rhonda Cook
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The nation's largest private prison company plans to
build its third facility in Georgia and claims to have a deal with
the state to house Georgia inmates. But state officials say they
have not negotiated an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Corrections Corp. of America has bought land from the city of
McRae to build another 1,500-bed private institution in the South
Georgia ``prison belt.'' It would be the fourth private prison in
Georigia, including one owned by Cornell Corrections Inc. in
Charlton County.
</P>
<P>
   Although CCA has yet to break ground on the $45 million project,
plans call for the prison to be finished by February 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Local officials and a CCA executive said the medium-security
McRae prison, just a few miles from two state prisons also in
Telfair County, will hold Georgia inmates only.
</P>
<P>
   CCA Vice President Peggy Lawrence said the company does not have
a contact, but there is an understanding with the state. ``This is
not going to be a facility that will house what we call out-sourced
inmates (from states other than Georgia). This is strictly for
Georgia use. That is our understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, State Department of Corrections Commissioner Wayne Garner
said the project was speculative. ``We have not had any
negotiations with them, period, about these facilities,'' said
Garner.
</P>
<P>
   Telfair Commission Chairman Chester Swain said the state was
involved in negotiations that began just two weeks ago, but he
declined to elaborate. ``I've told you all I can tell you. This
thing moved so fast. We're just trying to get everything off the
ground,'' Swain said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence said CCA does not build speculative prisons. ``That is
not our business. We don't always do it (build a prison) with a
signed document, but we do it with. . . a good assurance that those
beds will be used,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gov.-elect Roy Barnes, who must approve money for private prison
beds, said he would not ``preclude'' the McRae facility just
because it was run by the private sector but it would have to meet
the state's specifications. ``We've used a mixture of private and
public (prisons) and it think it's an appropirate thing to use a
mixture,'' Barnes said. House Appropriations Committee Chairman
Terry Coleman (D-Eastman), who represents the Telfair area, said
the talks have progressed to the point where CCA has said it will
charge the state the same $44.95 to $48.10 inmate per diem that it
charges at its other two prisons in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Prisons _ public and private _ provide jobs and boost the local
economy. Even though there are state prisons holding in four of the
six counties adjoining Telfair, local officials still want more
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were needing something in the county for some employment,''
said Telfair County's Swain. ``This supposedly will employ between
350 and 400 people.''
</P>
<P>
   McRae Mayor Quinton Mullis said he is not concerned about
security problems even though dangerous inmates have escaped from
CCA prisons in other states. ``We're just trying to get the
facilities for the jobs,'' Mullis said.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came just days after the U.S. Department of
Justice released a report on the escape of five dangerous inmates
from a CCA prison in Youngstown, Ohio, a medium-security facility
that was holding high security inmates from Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators found, among many things, that CCA
accepted inmates even though the Youngstown prison was not ready to
open, that prisoners were not properly and that security was flawed
and guards were not well-trained.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the start up problems it had are behind it,''
Lawrence said. ``The Justice Department report is perfectly
appropriate, but I view it as old news at this point and what's
critical is how well the facility is operating now.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhonda Cook writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
