<SLUG> BC-WRESTLER-GUILTY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wrestler pleads guilty to assault, threat charges
 &HT;    By Mark Bixler
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A popular pro wrestler known as Big Poppa Pump pleaded
guilty Tuesday in Cherokee County to felony aggravated assault and
making terroristic threats.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Carl Rechsteiner was charged with assaulting and
threatening a road worker for the Georgia Department of
Transportation last April. He faces a maximum sentence of 26 years
in prison, but a lengthy sentence is unlikely. Rechsteiner tried to
plead guilty last month in a deal that would have placed him on
probation for 5 years and fined him $2,676.
</P>
<P>
   Judge C. Michael Roach rejected that deal because he was not
satisfied with Rechsteiner's answers to his questions about the
events that led to his arrest. Rechsteiner was allowed to plead
guilty Tuesday under a provision that allows someone to plead
guilty without admitting guilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ordinarily I do not accept a plea from anyone who's not
willing to get up here and tell me exactly what happened,'' the
judge said.
</P>
<P>
   He did not immediately sentence Rechsteiner, who wrestles in the
New World Order wrestling organization under the name Scott
Steiner. He ordered state officials to conduct an investigation and
recommend a sentence for the wrestler, known for his bulging biceps
and a blond Fu Manchu mustache.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor David Gafnea told the judge Tuesday that he had
evidence to show that Rechsteiner drove down a closed exit ramp off
I-575 on April 21. He said Rechsteiner twice hit DOT road worker
Paul Kaspereen with his Ford F-250 pickup after Kaspereen told him
the ramp was closed.
</P>
<P>
   Kaspereen was not seriously hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Gafnea said witnesses were ready to testify that Rechsteiner
said ``he didn't care who (Kaspereen) was'' and that he said ``he
would kick his ass.''
</P>
<P>
   Rechsteiner, who looked at the floor as Gafnea spoke, stood in
front of the judge and answered Roach's questions in a quiet voice.
His attorney, Alan C. Manheim, said last month that Rechsteiner
pleaded guilty because he was concerned that a jury would convict
him because of his ``public persona.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My client believes that he's innocent,'' Manheim said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bixler writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
