<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELECOMMUNICATIONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Tech project to study new frontiers for fiber optics
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The future is in lights.
</P>
<P>
   That is, the means that could carry and manage much of the
world's high-speed communications of the future is the technology
of fiber optics _ the delivery and handling of data via the photons
that make up light. In an effort to find out just how commercial
that technology can be, a trio of interested companies have joined
with Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth, Nortel and Corning last week announced support of the
second _ and potentially final phase _ of the Ultrafast Optical
Communciations Consortium under way at the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all very leading-edge stuff,'' said Mark Williams,
director of emerging technologies for Nortel.
</P>
<P>
   Fiber-optic networks already carry data all over the globe. But
the Ultrafast Optical Communications Consortium is focusing on the
so-called backbone of the networks, where signals are combined or
separated. In those devices, where data is ``multiplexed'' and
``de-multiplexed,'' huge jams of data can slow down networks.
</P>
<P>
   That work is now commonly done through manipulation of
electrical signals. Researchers supported by the consortium are
hoping to find ways to use optics in those operations in order to
dramatically boost the capacity of the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The all-optical multiplexing and de-multiplexing technologies
that are being explored by the consortium hold the promise of
significant increases in fiber-optic system capacity,'' said
Charles Deneka, senior vice president at Corning.
</P>
<P>
   The project had its start about four years ago with funding from
the Pentagon's high-tech arm, the Advanced Research and Projects
Agency. ARPA has since pulled out, but the private sector has
picked up the slack, hoping for techniques that will improve their
telecommunication businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Georgia Tech has a very good location. They've got very good
talent, and they've come up with an idea that we think is good. It
is a new technology for multiplexing. If you can do it in the
optical domain, you can save a lot of equipment. The question is
whether that is viable economically,'' said Deneka.
</P>
<P>
   Although the companies won't detail their financial involvement,
they are all donating money and people to the project. Nortel is
donating devices, Corning is donating optical components and
specialty fibers, and BellSouth is providing software and business
savvy. All are also sending researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
