A9203 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-BELLSOUTH-COX     12-08 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-BELLSOUTH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth confident, but still working on problem
 &HT;    By Rob Chambers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth is confident about fixing and testing its
Y2K bugs, but according to its recent filing with the Securities
and Exchange Commission, the company still has plenty to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be there,'' said Robert J. Marmorato, who is with the
company's Year 2000 program management office. He was referring to
the company's June 30, 1999, target for a complete fixing and
testing of vital components.
</P>
<P>
   Marmorato said he couldn't disclose the number of
mission-critical systems at BellSouth, nor would the company say
how many embedded chips it has to fix.
</P>
<P>
   The company has also inventoried everything, including 4,000
buildings, 70,000 desktops, 2,500 voice switches and 8,000 servers,
along with about 5,000 unique software elements on company
mainframes, said spokesman Clayton Owen.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has spent $40 million on Y2K thus far. It estimates it
will cost $250 million to $350 million to fix the bug.
</P>
<P>
   The company has launched its Y2K counterattack in three parts,
each of which encompasses hardware, software, embedded chips,
suppliers and third party networks.
</P>
<P>
   The first of these areas, the ``network components'' effort,
focuses on the core of BellSouth's phone business. Suppliers
provide all the hardware and most of the software, and the vendors
are responsible for fixing and testing the equipment.
</P>
<P>
   As of Sept. 30, the company said, the planning, inventory and
impact analysis phases were 75 percent to 100 percent complete, and
the remaining three phases _ conversion, testing and implementation
_ were each about 25 percent complete.
</P>
<P>
   The second area of concern is ``information technology
systems,'' those that support customer operations such as billing.
The software for these systems was developed by both BellSouth
Telecommunications and vendors. Both are doing the work, the
company said.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of September, the first three phases were each about
70 percent to 100 percent done, and the other three phases were
each about 30 percent to 50 percent complete for BellSouth
Telecommunications and about 0 percent to 50 percent complete for
other company operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Building and environmental systems,'' the third area, includes
goods and services not part of network or customer care. Such items
are provided mostly by third parties and include everything from
elevators to aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   As of Sept. 30, the planning phase was about 85 percent to 100
percent complete, the inventory phase was about 75 percent to 100
percent finished, and the impact analysis effort was approximately
67 percent to 100 percent done. The remaining three phases were
approximately 0 percent to 25 percent complete.
</P>
<P>
   For more information _ and for updates _ visit the company's Web
site (http://bellsouth.com/year2000)
</P>
<P>
   Rob Chambers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
