</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUPITER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Time a factor in online news-gathering
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There's a new prime time _ noon to 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New Prime Time'' was one of several topics discussed
Tuesday at Jupiter Communications Digital News conference being
held here. More than 400 attendees gathered for the two-day
conference winding up today at the Omni Hotel in the CNN Center.
</P>
<P>
   This has become a key time period for online news consumption
according to analyst Patrick Keane. It's when workplace Web surfers
hit the Web for news and information in quick news summaries. With
the Web pushing past radio and newspapers as the third major source
of news information, the need to capture and engage the workplace
news junkie is vital.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Jupiter, an Internet research and consulting
company, makes it clear that there is a young wired group of people
looking for a news fix between the morning paper and the evening
news, there is still, even among the most venerable news
organizations considerable concern and discussion about how best to
reach the Net news audience.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists from major news organizations including Forbes, The
Washington Post, The Economist, MSNBC, CNN, and online magazine
Salond talked about the opportunities and the obstacles facing
traditional publishers in the online world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certain kinds of publications are in great jeopardy,'' said
Forbes publisher Rich Karlgaard , ``Others will have a long run
ramp before any of this pays off.'' Karlgaard said some
publications including Forbes can find middle ground. ``We have our
own content and new material,'' he said, ``but what we still don't
know over time is if this will cannibalize our content.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Coll, managing editor of The Washington Post said that for
his newspaper the Web was a welcome outlet for a newspaper that has
long wanted to have a national presence. Coll and Anthony Gottlieb,
executive editor of the Economist, also said they would consider
integrating what works best on the Web into their sites, including
offering readers suggestions for other articles to read, in the
same way Amazon.com recommends books.
</P>
<P>
   There was no great concern about portals such as Yahoo, or
Excite, which provide a variety of services including Web
searching, news, white and yellow pages directories and free
e-mail, siphoning off the online news audience. Most thought that
analysis, even quick analysis, would ultimately draw readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, content providers have the advantage,'' said
Christian Science Monitor Editor David Cook. ``Anyone can post what
Alan Greenspan says, but only a content provider has somebody there
to tell you what it means,''
</P>
<P>
   ``The trouble has never been the editorial model, it's the
business model,'' Coll said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Woelfel, editor-in-chief of CNN Interactive said the Web
site was another way for CNN to reach a wider audience. ``We reach
audiences in a way the other (CNN) networks can't. A Web site can
do a lot more than break one news event at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all the custom home pages, portal strategies, news
alerts and quick summaries, MSNBC's Merrill Brown said online news
still had a long way to go. ``We have not created an Internet news
habit yet,'' Brown said. Jupiter research shows that the average
Web news junkie spends about 10 minutes on a news site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be really focused to be a real stand alone business
... One of our challenges is in developing a voice,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the overriding theme was the importance of having a
coherent vision. ``If you don't know who you are and what your
mission is,'' said the Post's Coll, ``You won't know how to react
when new technologies and situations present themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
