<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-BLACKOUT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSIVE BLACKOUT HITS SAN FRANCISCO AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Updates throughout with details, quotes)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LARRY D. HATFIELD  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A massive power failure brought San Francisco to
a standstill at the height of the morning rush hour Tuesday,
stranding hundreds of people in high-rise elevators and dark
tunnels, freezing traffic and paralyzing businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a million people were without power during the height of
the outage, which was blamed on a construction accident. But the
authorities reported no major injuries or looting.
</P>
<P>
   The blackout hit parts of the San Francisco Bay area when a
Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric substation in San Mateo shut down at 8:17
a.m. By midday, power had been restored to some areas but much of
the region was still without electricity.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E spokesman Corey Warren said power was being restored
station by station, with manual switching required to restore
electricity city block by city block.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Willie Brown said he was told by PG&AMP;E officials that the
blackout was caused by human error. Other officials attributed the
outage to a construction accident at the San Mateo substation.
</P>
<P>
   ``San Francisco has been magnificent,'' Brown said. ``People
have been respectful of each other. The city is essentially
functioning as it previously has, a little bit slower but it's
functioning.''
</P>
<P>
   Of major concern were reports from the San Francisco Fire
Department that as many as 50 elevators in 500 high-rise buildings
were having problems, although it was not immediately known how
many people were stuck inside.
</P>
<P>
   Fire Department Inspector Kaan Chin said the biggest problem was
panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fire Department has been anticipating a situation like
this since the 1989 earthquake,'' he said, adding that it took
about a half hour to free trapped people from each elevator.
</P>
<P>
   According to PG&AMP;E spokeswoman Mary Rodrigues, the San Mateo
substation takes high-voltage power from transmission lines and
lowers it to a voltage that can be used by consumers. She said when
the substation shut down, automatic switches were triggered to
isolate the area.
</P>
<P>
   Without the switches, all of Northern California could have lost
power. Utility authorities said it would take hours to return the
substation to full service.
</P>
<P>
   For commuters, the blackout couldn't have come at a worse time,
hitting right in the middle of the morning rush into San Francisco,
crippling Bay Area Rapid Transit trains, stalling much of the
Municipal Railway's fleet, delaying and rerouting flights at San
Francisco International Airport and jamming various freeways.
</P>
<P>
   An unknown number of people were evacuated from subway tunnels.
</P>
<P>
   At the airport, flight operations continued using separate power
but some flights were diverted to Oakland and San Jose to reduce
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency power lighted the airport terminals but computers were
not working, making it impossible to check in passengers, airport
spokesman Ron Wilson said. Airport personnel used bullhorns to
alert travelers to flight delays.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic lights at intersections throughout the city were off and
some electric buses and trolleys were stuck in the intersections,
blocking traffic. The police and parking control officers directed
traffic at others.
</P>
<P>
   At the Macy's department store on fashionable Union Square,
security guard Dennis Avant said he used a crowbar to rescue people
from elevators on the first and seventh floors. People were still
stuck at mid-morning on some floors, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific Stock Exchange stopped trading as computers failed,
but trading continued at the exchange's Los Angeles office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
