<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPINNERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Day's hearings put forth little drama
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Scott Lauf, director of the Clinton Impeachment
Commission, arrived at the House Judiciary Committee Tuesday with
his 22-month-old daughter hoping to find a big crowd eager to
snatch up his fluorescent pink ``invitations.''
</P>
<P>
   Lauf's flyers invited the public to ``the O.J. Simpson Trial _
Part II,'' featuring ranking member John Conyers (D-Mich.) as
Johnny Cochran and Bill Clinton as ``the juice.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lauf got few takers for his anti-Clinton joke. In sharp
contrast to independent counsel Ken Starr's appearance before the
Judiciary Committee three weeks ago, Tuesday's hearing was sparsely
attended and featured none of the electricity or drama.
</P>
<P>
   Many seats inside the committee room, impossible to get when
Starr testified, were empty. The hallways outside the large
committee room in the Rayburn House Office Building had little of
the hustle and bustle of Starr's visit.
</P>
<P>
   The stand of microphones erected for members to appear before
the media down the hallway from the committee room, which were in
almost constant use when Starr testified, were also quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Even the White House spinners _ the contingent of presidential
aides who work the media with the president's defense _ had a light
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just going through the motions,'' said Sean Wilentz, a
Princeton history professor who testified on the first panel. ``The
drama wasn't there.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the difference had to do with Starr. Three weeks ago,
Starr hadn't uttered more than a few words in public about his
four-year investigation of President Clinton. Republicans were keen
to show the public that Starr was just a hard working prosecutor
trying to do his job. Democrats wanted to unmask him as an
overzealous prude. The public wanted see for itself who the real
Ken Starr was.
</P>
<P>
   Now, few mysteries remain. It is a virtual certainty that
Republicans will vote out at least one article of impeachment
against Clinton. It is equally certain that Democrats will vote
against the article or articles, and instead push a motion of
censure.
</P>
<P>
   No one anticipated that any witness called by the president's
team Tuesday would change any minds on the committee. And no
witness did.
</P>
<P>
   ``The testimony was predictable,'' said George Gekas (R-Pa.).
``There was nothing new.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the purpose of the panel of legal experts and historians
was not to change minds on the committee but to sway the estimated
30 Republican moderates who are believed to be sitting on the fence
about how they should vote when articles of impeachment reach the
House floor next week.
</P>
<P>
   Wilentz, who told members that their ``reputations will be
darkened'' forever if they vote to impeach Clinton, said he was
acutely aware that those moderates were his audience. ``I wanted to
be sure they understood the grave constitutional question they
face,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The empty hallways and light crowds clearly disappointed Lauf,
whose organization has staged a number of protests and stunts to
demand Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really hoping there was going to be a rush of people,''
said Lauf, holding a stack of his invitations.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
