<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-WH-SCENE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON FOCUSES ON POLICY AND CONDOLENCES, NOT IMPEACHMENT
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Days before the House Judiciary Committee is
expected to send at least one article of impeachment to the full
House, President Clinton spent a long day far from Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   As he has done repeatedly during critical stages of the
year-long inquiry into his relationship with former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky, Clinton did his best to project the image
of a president hard at work on the nation's business, even as his
political detractors worked in the background to undo his
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   At a long-planned White House conference on Social Security
reform, Clinton appealed to more than 200 Congress members and
experts to ''march together'' to try to come up with a solution to
the retirement system's projected financial shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   By late morning, when the committee was deep into testimony from
Clinton's personal lawyer, Gregory Craig, and a host of legal
scholars, Clinton was hundreds of miles away, entering the War
Memorial Auditorium in Nashville to hear Vice President Al Gore
eulogize his father, Sen. Albert Gore Sr., who died Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   After returning to Washington on Tuesday night, Clinton was
scheduled to present an award to Sen. Dale Bumpers, D-Ark., and his
wife, Betty Flanagan, for their work in setting up the non-profit
organization Peace Links.
</P>
<P>
   He was to speak later at another awards dinner sponsored by the
National Democratic Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
