<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COATES-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COATES ASSAULT TRIAL OPENS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL LANGNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WRENTHAM, Mass. _ Far from being a domestic abuser, Patriots
tight end Ben Terrence Coates is actually the victim of a jealous
lover who was trying to extort money, Coates's attorney told a
District Court jury here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Coates went on trial Tuesday on one count of assault and
battery. The 6 foot, 5 inch, 250 pounds athlete is charged with
shoving 5 foot 8 inch Jennifer Marshall of Norton to the ground
and, when she got up and flew at him again, of picking her up and
throwing her onto the hood of her car last July 26.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Norfolk District Attorney Glenn Cunha warned the jury
in his opening statement that the defense would try to show that
Marshall was trying to set Coates up to gain an advantage in their
legal fight over child support and other money matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``But after you hear the tapes (of messages Marshall left on
Coates's machine), you will have to ask yourself, `Is this a person
who will set someone up?' '' Cunha asked, and went on, ``At the end
of the trial I will ask you, did an assault and battery happen? Did
the defendant go over the line? Keep in mind the defendant makes a
living off his size and strength.''
</P>
<P>
   But Coates's attorney Mark Berthiaume told the five men and two
women of the jury that ``This is a woman who is motivated by greed
and anger. On that July 26 she was going to stop at nothing until
she had had a confrontation with this defendant.''
</P>
<P>
   As outlined in both opening and in subsequent testimony by
Marshall, she began dating Coates in 1993 and by March 1994 she
became pregnant with their daughter, whom they named Destiny. She
became pregnant after she learned Coates was married and had two
children in North Carolina, she admitted on the stand.
</P>
<P>
   While pregnant, she went onto the Montel Williams show, on a
program called ``Mistresses of Married Men.'' Marshall said Coates
had dared her to. On that program she admitted that she had said,
``I'm having his baby. He's going to pay for this kid.'' She also
said that if he were to jilt her, there were other Patriots players
who had made frequent passes at her.
</P>
<P>
   By 1997, after she was refused admittance to the Patriots'
training camp's family area, she sued him in probate court and was
awarded $4,500 a month, or $54,000 a year, in child support. By
last July they were back in court when she sought an increase in
support payments and tried to ask him to buy her a $46,000 Mercedes
Benz car and a house.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall insisted during testimony that ``I wanted him to buy a
house for his daughter.'' Berthiaume shot back, ``Did you want the
Mercedes for your daughter, too?''
</P>
<P>
   It was when she went to his Franklin apartment on the afternoon
of July 26 to show him two architects' drawings of houses she was
considering having built, the more expensive one priced at
$600,000, that she found a strange car in the driveway.
</P>
<P>
   Coates would not let her in and, accompanied by a friend,
Carrinne Parkinson and by her daugher Destiny, she drove to a
telephone and left an obscenity-laden tirade of threats on Coates's
answering machine.
</P>
<P>
   She made three more such calls that afternoon and camped outside
the house. In the third of these calls, she can be heard on the
tape saying, ``I hope they will trade you over this (expletive).''
</P>
<P>
   She also admitted on the stand she said she would have him
arrested. In one tape she is furious because he is seeing another
woman less than one day after they had sex.
</P>
<P>
   She had Parkinson buy a disposable camera and photographed the
strange car and the lighted bedroom window.
</P>
<P>
   When a young woman at last emerged and got into the car, she
took her photograph, too, she testified, and confronted her and
accused her of being a stripper, told her she and Coates were
lovers and that, moreover, he was married anyway. But she denied
screaming at her.
</P>
<P>
   When Coates came to the door, she reluctantly admitted under
cross examination, she shoved him repeatedly and called him
epithets, until he shoved her and she fell back, catching herself
with her forearms.
</P>
<P>
   When she rose and flew at him, she said, he picked her up and
slammed her onto the hood of her car, causing her to hurt the back
of her head.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
