A9230 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EVERGLADES-1209-COX     12-08 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERGLADES-1209-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PLAN TO RESCUE EVERGLADES DRAWS MIXED REACTIONS
 &HT;    420 words
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By NICHOLE MONROE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Water management officials seeking public comment
Tuesday on their plan to protect and preserve the Everglades and
South Florida ecosystems met mixed reactions.
</P>
<P>
   In the last public meeting before the $7.8 billion plan is
presented to Congress, the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers and the
South Florida Water Management District gave a quick summary of the
plan known as the ``Restudy.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the plan calls for 251,000 acres of marshes, reservoirs
and quarries to store billions of gallons of water for farms,
cities and nature. The proposal also would destroy 200 miles of
interior levees and canals, freeing some of the water the
endangered Everglades requires.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government and the state of Florida each would pay
half the cost of the 20-year project.
</P>
<P>
   Those who spoke against the plan said it was too vague, relied
too heavily on unproven techniques and cost too much money.
Speakers supporting the plan said it was the best available choice
and lauded the efforts to protect area wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Poole, executive director of the management district, said
though the plan isn't perfect, a ``train wreck'' will happen if the
plan is not implemented.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't do something to increase water supply, then all
assurances we can provide will be worthless,'' Poole said. ``We
know there are risks; we know there are uncertainties. If you have
an issue, then let's work to solve it.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the more than 80 people who attended the meeting, about 35
signed up to speak. Most were Floridians.
</P>
<P>
   Loretta Harrington, with the Washington-based Defenders of
Property Rights, said the plan will infringe upon the rights of
residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``By proposing to flood 170,000 acres of private property, the
federal government is in violation of the Fifth Amendment,''
Harrington said. She said officials should work to minimize the
burden on landowners and provide rapid, fair compensation to those
whose property must be flooded.
</P>
<P>
   Speakers who voiced their support of the plan pointed out some
faults but applauded the efforts of the Corps of Engineers and
water management district.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents say if nothing is done, the quality of water in the
area will deteriorate, water shortages for urban and agricultural
users will occur more frequently, and many plants and animals
living in South Florida will become extinct.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Restudy must happen,'' said Gerald Barber, chairman of the
National Wildlife Federation board. ``It represents our best and
possibly last effort to save the Everglades and wildlife.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
