<SLUG> BC-WHALES-SHIPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHIPS REQUIRED TO REPORT PRESENCE IN WHALE WATERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hoping to reduce the leading cause of accidental death for the
world's most endangered species of whale, an international panel
Tuesday ordered large ships to report to the Coast Guard when they
enter the waters off Massachusetts to help avoid hitting the big
marine mammals.
</P>
<P>
   The reporting system adopted by the International Maritime
Organization in London will inform vessels entering Cape Cod Bay
and the main shipping route to Massachusetts about nearby Northern
right whales. A similar system will be set up in the whales'
calving grounds off Florida and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Though only one or two right whales are confirmed killed by
ships each year, biologists say the deaths are potentially
devastating to a species that now has only about 300 surviving
members. The monitoring system, they said, is the first step toward
eliminating those needless deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``This population is so small that saving one individual makes a
difference,'' said Scott Kraus, a senior biologist at the New
England Aquarium in Boston. ``If one ship captain gets the message,
sees the whale, and changes direction, it will have been worth
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The monitoring system, championed for the last year by US Rep.
William Delahunt, a Massachusetts Democrat, marks the first time a
government agency has required the shipping industry to take steps
to protect right whales. Until now, conservation groups have
promoted voluntary reporting when ships are in areas popular with
whales.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the Navy opposed the mandatory reporting plan on
national security grounds, but President Clinton overruled its
objections last May and forwarded the proposal to the International
Maritime Organization, which represents countries with
international shipping industries.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Clinton administration officials were elated at the
unanimous support for the monitoring plan, which would apply to all
boats weighing over 300 tons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision significantly improves protection for the
slow-moving whale, since ship strikes account for 50 percent of
known right whale deaths,'' explained Terry Garcia, assistant
secretary of commerce for oceans and atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Northern right whales, which can grow up to 60 feet long and
weigh up to 80 tons, were hunted nearly to extinction at the turn
of the century when only a handful of sexually mature females
survived.
</P>
<P>
   Today, despite a ban on hunting the whales for more than 50
years and federal protection as an endangered species for 30 years,
the right whales have made only limited progress. The whales
produced record-few offspring this year and biologists are not sure
if the long term population trend is up or down.
</P>
<P>
   Though the species faces a range of problems, from genetic
inbreeding to entanglement in fishing lines, biologists believe
collisions with ships are their number one hazard. The whales spend
a lot of time in heavily traveled shipping lanes such as the Great
South Channel east and south of Cape Cod and the Bay of Fundy in
Canada, and often don't yield as ships approach.
</P>
<P>
   In the southeast, environmentalists fly surveillance over the
whales during winter calving season, but even that extraordinary
measure wasn't enough to prevent the deaths of several right whales
in 1996 during Navy maneuvers. And biologists are investigating a
potential ship strike death off North Carolina two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the New England Aquarium said shipping industry
officials seem eager to help, but few have experience with whales.
Most of the thousands of ships that cross the Great South Channel
never encounter right whales, and captains may not know they have
hit a whale even when it happens.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, environmentalists said the reporting system, which
takes effect next July, should be seen as part of a larger
campaign, raising mariners' awareness and collecting information on
ship traffic patterns for future, perhaps tougher, decisions about
how to reduce collisions.
</P>
<P>
   The monitoring system ``is huge, but it's only a first step,''
said Dave Wiley of the International Wildlife Coalition in
Falmouth, Mass. He predicted the system would save few whales
initially, ``but conservation is a long term thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
