<HEADLINE>
BOY SUES MOTHER OVER INJURIES SUFFERED IN THE WOMB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Five-year-old Ryan Dobson is suing his mother for
injuries suffered in the womb. The case, which could have major
legal implications for the status of fetal and abortion rights in
Canada, was argued Tuesday before the country's Supreme Court in
Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan was delivered by an emergency Caesarean section a few hours
after his mother, Cynthia Dobson, wrecked her car on a snowy New
Brunswick highway in 1993 when she was 27 weeks pregnant. The child
suffers from an array of physical and mental infirmities, including
cerebral palsy, as the result of the accident.
</P>
<P>
   The case revolves around whether the fetus that became Ryan is
an individual victim of the accident, and deserves compensation for
injuries beyond what the insurance company was willing to pay to
cover the costs of the mother's treatment.
</P>
<P>
   That abstract legal question hides an explosive issue. If the
court recognizes that Ryan is an accident victim, it follows that a
fetus has some rights as an individual. Abortion advocates strongly
oppose giving legal rights or protections to the fetus since such
recognition might lead to restrictions on the medical termination
of pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assigning any rights at all to a fetus has the potential to
take away from a woman's right to an abortion,'' said Kim Luton of
the Canadian Abortion Rights League.
</P>
<P>
   But a group of Roman Catholic and Protestant groups that oppose
abortion have entered the case on Ryan's behalf, arguing that a
fetus is an individual with rights separate from those of its
mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unborn child and the mother are distinct human beings,''
said Ottawa lawyer William Sammon, representing the Catholic groups
involved in the case. ``The unborn child is a person deserving of
some protection.''
</P>
<P>
   At present, Canadian law gives no rights or protections to the
fetus at any stage of development. Abortion in this country falls
into a legal gray area. Although laws criminalizing abortion were
lifted in 1988, no federal statute regulates the procedure or
spells out the legal status of a fetus.
</P>
<P>
   In a case that drew international attention last year, Canada's
Supreme Court ruled that a woman who shot her fetus in the womb had
not committed a crime because a fetus is not a person. Upon giving
birth, the woman was given custody of the baby after surgeons
removed the projectile.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian Supreme Court has long hinted that Parliament
should pass legislation defining the rights of the fetus,
especially one close to birth.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan's case was originally brought by his grandfather, who sued
his daughter on behalf of the child in an apparent effort to force
the woman's insurance company to help pay the costs of raising the
disabled child. Ryan lives at home with his mother, and there is no
implication that he has been mistreated since being born.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance company argued the mother's case, claiming that
the fetus was simply an extension of her body, like a kidney or a
toe, and there is no legal obligation to cover the health costs
once the baby is born and becomes a person in the eyes of the law.
</P>
<P>
   But abortion foes argue that the fetus is an individual in its
own right, and that it is absurd to suggest there is no legal
connection between what happened to the fetus that became Ryan and
the disabilities of the child.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryan Dobson is not suffering from injuries that occurred to
his mother. Ryan is suffering from because of injuries he suffered
at the accident scene,'' lawyer David Brown argued on behalf of the
Evangelical Fellowship, a church group opposed to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   It is likely to be months before the Supreme Court rules on the
case.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
