<SLUG> BC-NH-PRIMARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.H. TO URGE PLEDGE ON PRIMARY BY CANDIDATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ Trying to maintain New Hampshire's clout in
presidential politics, a bipartisan commission here said it would
ask potential candidates not to campaign in states that hold
primaries within one week of the Granite State's.
</P>
<P>
   Though such pledges would be voluntary, and no one who refused
would be denied a spot on the ballot, the move illustrates the
jockeying already under way by states trying to maximize their
influence in the 2000 race.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Jeanne Shaheen, a Democrat, said she is urging all
candidates to sign a pledge promising not to campaign in states
that encroach on New Hampshire's sacred first-in-the-nation status.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Missouri Representative Richard A. Gephardt, Minnesota
Senator Paul Wellstone, Vice President Al Gore, and Ohio
Representative John Kasich have signed the pledge. But aides to
former Tennessee Governor Lamar Alexander and publisher Steve
Forbes said their bosses are hesitant to sign.
</P>
<P>
   Shaheen said New Hampshire serves a vital role for the nation,
allowing candidates to meet with voters one-on-one and enabling
politicians without the most money or national exposure to compete
fairly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This simply isn't possible in most places,'' Shaheen said.
``The opportunity for personal, retail campaigning is lost in
larger states, where campaigns are played out in television
commercials and on airport tarmacs.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan brought a strong retort from Delaware, which plans to
hold its 2000 primary four days after New Hampshire. Basil
Battaglia, the Delaware Republican Party chairman, called the
tactic ``cheap,'' ``arrogant,'' and ``heavy-handed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be arrogant for us to tell another state when they
could have their election,'' Battaglia said. ``I would hope that
anyone who seeks our nation's highest office would be able to
resist giving in to what amounts to little more than cheap
political extortion.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Delaware, South Carolina is considering holding its
primary four days after New Hampshire. Furthermore, California
plans to move up its primary to March, while blocs of other states
have begun banding together to hold regional primaries that month,
hoping to gain influence and prestige.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire law states that its primary must be held seven
days before any other primary. Members of the commission conceded
that the pledge is nothing more than an attempt to publicly
pressure the candidates to uphold New Hampshire's tradition, which
dates back to 1920 and brings upward of $30 million into the state.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Keefe, a commission member and former chairman of the state
Democratic Party, urged party activists to refuse to help
candidates that campaign in states such as Delaware. He said
members of the media should vigorously question candidates who
don't comply.
</P>
<P>
   ``So long as they pay no price in New Hampshire for campaigning
in Delaware or any other state, they won't refrain,'' Keefe said.
</P>
<P>
   Former Governor Hugh Gregg, a Republican, said he had begun
contacting Republicans who might run for president and received a
mixed a reaction. Keefe said he is still trying to reach all of the
Democrats who might run for president. Senator John F. Kerry, who
is thinking about running, has not yet received a call about the
pledge.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry was en route to Jakarta, Indonesia, Tuesday and could not
be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Neither chairman of the Democratic or Republican Parties in New
Hampshire said he planned to take any action against candidates who
won't sign the pledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to beat up on any candidate,'' said Steve
Duprey, chairman of the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Strategists for Forbes and Alexander were leery about the pledge
and its implications since neither man is a declared candidate and
the primary schedule is still in flux.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve Forbes is not a candidate,'' said Paul Young, the head
of Northeast operations for Forbes's Americans for Hope, Growth and
Opportunity group. ``He has always supported New Hampshire being
the first in the nation primary and continues to support that and
hopes the process can be worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Griffin, a New Hampshire consultant to Alexander, was
exasperated at the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be suffocated in pledges here,'' he said,
citing two similar pledges from 1996 signed by Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lamar Alexander has not made an announcement conclusively that
he's going to be a candidate for president,'' Griffin said. ``The
schedule is not settled. There's nothing worse than signing a
pledge and breaking a pledge.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
