<HEADLINE>
PROPOSAL CALLS FOR USING RECLUSE'S BEQUEST FOR HEALTH CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GREGORY LEWIS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Some poor people in San Francisco would get free
medical and dental care under a city proposal for the fortune left
by a recluse who died earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Zygmunt Arendt, who died Jan. 24, left at least $4.5 million in
stocks and real estate in a handwritten will stipulating that the
mayor and the Board of Supervisors use 60 percent of the money for
the poor and needy, and the remainder for disadvantaged seniors and
disabled children.
</P>
<P>
   Human Services General Manager Will Lightbourne, assigned by the
Board of Supervisors to propose ways to use the estate, has
recommended that Arendt's bequest be given in the form of health
services to poor people who wouldn't normally receive it.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would ``identify people who are basically very low
income, who are trying to become self-sufficient, and give them
non-emergency medical assistance,'' Lightbourne said. ``We're
talking about single people who are not eligible for MediCal for
things such as eyeglasses, dental.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan, he said, is to use the interest over the next few
years, rather than the principal itself.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisors must first approve the proposal. If they agree, it
would be submitted to Probate Court for final approval.
</P>
</TEXT>
