<HEADLINE>
THE ART OF AARON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BETTY KWONG  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Aaron Yamagata sits poised in his yellow
</P>
<P>
   plastic chair, legs crossed, hands neatly folded over his knee,
discussing his deep passion for art.
</P>
<P>
   Pablo Picasso and Jackson Pollock are among his favorite
artists. He can't wait to see the ``Mona Lisa'' in person. Acrylics
_ no question about it _ are his favorite medium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get to speak to the world when I draw,'' he says. ``When I
want harmony, happiness, peace and love, that's what I draw _ and
that's my message to the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Move over, Michelangelo. This 8-year-old is determined. He's had
an eye on becoming a famous artist since he was 3 _ and he's way
beyond crayons.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron already has won many awards for his work _ plenty more
than the number of years he's been alive.
</P>
<P>
   His latest achievement came last month, when he was chosen from
a field of 10,000 entries to win the seventh annual UNICEF ``Kids
Helping Kids'' Greeting Card Contest. His colorful rendering of a
snowman will be reproduced and sold as a holiday card at Pier One
stores next winter.
</P>
<P>
   The UNICEF honor, shared with 6-year-old Mia Walsh of Toppenish,
Wash., who won in the 7-and-younger age group, earned him a
three-day trip to Manhattan, N.Y.; $500; and a tour of the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   The snowman of Aaron's making holds a garland designed with
symbols: a heart, signifying his wish for love in the world; St.
Nick's face for happiness; a dove for peace; and a reindeer,
symbolizing man's harmony with nature.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't stop there. Aaron didn't choose the snowman image
haphazardly either.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'd take kids helping kids to form a perfect snowman,'' he
explains. ``And the contest was about `Kids Helping Kids.'''
</P>
<P>
   Of course.
</P>
<P>
   The honor will be dutifully added to his two-page resume, which
lists a dozen first-place awards for statewide and national art
contests; firsts for a science fair, a spelling bee and a poetry
contest this year; and appearances across the media landscape,
including a visit to ``The Tonight Show With Jay Leno.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be a very famous artist when I grow up,'' he begins,
``a famous inventor, a great magician, a musician. And I'm a great
tap dancer.''
</P>
<P>
   He practices his tap dancing almost every day, transforming the
same board that's his makeshift drawing table into a temporary
dance floor over the carpet of the modest apartment that's home to
Aaron and his mother, Didi Yamagata.
</P>
<P>
   There was never any grand plan to turn Aaron into an artist _
famous or otherwise, says Yamagata.
</P>
<P>
   Like any parent, she wanted to expose Aaron to as many
opportunities as possible _ sports, music, language, arts. An ad in
a parenting magazine led her to Linda Wherli's Fine Art and Music
Academy, a home-based art school in Valley Village.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really took a liking to it, so much so that it became a
second life,'' Yamagata says laughing.
</P>
<P>
   For five years now, he's been attending the after-school academy
for 90-minute sessions once a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little bit apprehensive about his age at first,'' says
Wherli, who interviewed Aaron to assess his ability when he was a
``teeny little elf'' at 3. ``But he was so astute and so alert.
He's right up there with the rest of my students.''
</P>
<P>
   He's outgrown the need for extra seat cushions, but Aaron still
barely takes up a quarter of his metal folding chair at the
academy, more often than not perched on its edge, shoes dangling
from his toes, head bowed with concentration on his latest drawing.
</P>
<P>
   The recent flurry of media attention surrounding his win in the
UNICEF contest _ including appearances on NBC's ``Today Show,''
``Good Morning America'' and even ``CNN Today'' _ hasn't fazed
Aaron.
</P>
<P>
   It's just one step toward his dream: ``To live in Paris, France,
and sit on the sidewalk, drawing all the ornamental buildings. To
go the top of the Eiffel Tower and see the whole world.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if he never gets to see the whole world from atop the
famous landmark, if he never achieves the fortune that comes with
fame, he already counts himself among the blessed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very fortunate to have my health, a mother that cares for
me and loves me, my talents,'' Aaron said, ``and a big brain.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, his 11-year-old girlfriend at Woodcrest School has
different ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``She doesn't want me to be an artist,'' says Aaron. ``She wants
me to have a legitimate job, like a doctor or a lawyer.'' &QL; 
ENDIT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
