<HEADLINE>
SAFETY PANEL TO SEEK FACTS IN JETLINER NEAR-MISS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The near mid-air collision Sunday night off the coast of Long
Island between a British Caledonian L-1011 and a Delta Airlines
Boeing 767 has drawn the attention of the National Transportation
Safety Board.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are interested and gathering information on it, although it
is not a formal investigation,'' said Paul Schlamm, an NTSB
spokesman. ``We want to look at what occurred and what problems it
may reveal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Globe reported Tuesday that the two planes, with a total of
372 people on board, came within 1.07 miles of each other while
traveling at 500 m.p.h. At the time of the incident _ 10:02 p.m. _
the primary computer system monitoring air traffic at the Boston
Center in Nashua, N.H., had been down for half an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Center is responsible for all high-altitude flights
over New England and much of New York state. Because the computer
was down, controllers had to exchange hand-written notes containing
information about the flights they were monitoring on radar
screens.
</P>
<P>
   When the back-up system, known as DARC, is working, controllers
can monitor traffic electronically, but they have fewer safety
features at their disposal than in the primary system. For example,
the primary system has a conflict alert function in which the
information about two planes that may travel too close to each
other begins to flash on the radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   DARC does not have that function, and, because the primary sysem
failure was so extensive, DARC was not able to display essential
flight information _ such as the plane's airline, flight number,
altitude and airspeed.
</P>
<P>
   Controllers can normally rebuild the system by relying on
computer-generated printouts and then type that information into
the back-up system. The computer, however, was not generating the
printouts, forcing controllers to write notes by hand.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the controllers working the sector east of John F.
Kennedy International Airport had a keyboard that was frozen,
preventing them entering in information even from handwritten
notes. It was in that sector that the loss of a safe distance
between the two planes occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA, which is investigating the incident, has insisted the
nation's air system is safe. A spokeswoman said Tuesday that until
the investigation is complete the agency could not say if the error
was the result of computer problems.
</P>
<P>
   The on-board computers on the two planes alerted the flight
crews to an impending collision and ordered the crews to take
evasive action. Both planes were flying at 33,000 feet where normal
separation is 2,000 feet vertically and five miles horizontally.
</P>
<P>
   The Delta plane was told to climb, and went to 33,600 feet. And
the L-1011, with 271 people on board, dove to 32,700 feet.
</P>
<P>
   A controller told the Globe the British Caledonian pilot
apparently was so shaken by the incident he radioed the Delta pilot
to go to a radio frequency the controllers could not monitor,
ostensibly so the pilots could discuss the incident in private.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB said the preliminary examination of the incident could
be expanded if warranted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will gather information from the FAA and the airlines and
do an assessment of that information and then we will decide where
to go from there,'' said Schlamm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
