<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIFTS-FOOD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EASE THE HOLIDAY RUSH WITH HOMEMADE GIFTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Is the gift-giving search getting to you this
holiday season? You keep hunting for the perfect gift for those on
your list but can't find anything you like? You're probably not
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Now might be a good time to rethink the possibilities and
consider making and giving gifts from your kitchen. Avoid the malls
and head to the grocery store instead.
</P>
<P>
   Food and food-related presents are wonderful because you can
customize them to suit the tastes of the recipients. And they can
also be tailored to the culinary skills of the giver. Homemade
gifts don't have to take hours to make, as long as they look and
taste great and are stylishly wrapped with a professional look.
Remember, appealing good looks are important, because first we
feast with out eyes.
</P>
<P>
   With a little time and attention devoted to content and
presentation, you can create a unique food gift or gift basket that
is a pleasure to give and receive. Remember that often these types
of gifts are the most appreciated and cherished because they are
sprinkled with touches of love _ from your kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Today's recipes include several that beginners as well as
accomplished cooks can pull off without a hassle. Many take only
minutes to prepare and can be made when time is at a premium.
</P>
<P>
   Peruse the options, select the ones that best suit your holiday
schedule and the time you'll have available for shopping,
preparation and wrapping. Then get organized and make lists of
ingredients and gift-wrapping items such as jars, tins, baskets,
napkins, ribbons, plastic wrap and cellophane.
</P>
<P>
   For freshness and the best-tasting goodies, plan to make the
gifts, especially baked items like breads, candies and cookies, as
close to the time of giving as possible _ and avoid freezing at all
costs. Some recipes _ like vinegars and liqueurs _ require several
days of standing time and can be made well in advance of giving.
Others, like preserves, refrigerator pickles, panforte and fudge
sauce, can be made a few days ahead and stored in the fridge. If
you plan to give perishable items, be sure you can deliver them to
the recipient in a timely fashion.
</P>
<P>
   If cooking isn't your bag, it's possible to assemble a fabulous
food gift package or basket with specialty items from supermarkets,
delicatessens, bakeries, specialty coffee shops and international
food shops like Trader Joe's and Cost Plus. You can mix and match
themes and colors, or select a single theme for your basket.
Possibilities include a coffee basket with coffee beans and a
coffee grinder _ and perhaps some muffins or scones tossed in _ or
a cookie basket with assorted cookie cutters, homemade or bakery
cookies, a cookie sheet and a potholder.
</P>
<P>
   A chocolate basket is bound to thrill the chocophile on your
list, and the sky's the limit _ just pack it with anything
chocolate. A soup basket could include bean mixtures, store-bought
gourmet soup mixes and a soup tureen or kettle and ladle.
</P>
<P>
   For salad lovers, how about assorted prewashed lettuces,
tomatoes, an assortment of unique salad dressings and jars of
marinated artichoke hearts and roasted red peppers. A salsa basket
could be fun, too, with assorted trendy salsas like mango and
pineapple, and tortilla chips.
</P>
<P>
   Other ideas might be a bread basket, slow-cooker basket, pasta
basket, wine basket and more. Or you could theme the basket to be
Mexican, Italian, Chinese, Thai, Creole, hot chiles, etc.
</P>
<P>
   A mixed eclectic basket of a variety of items like olive oil,
biscotti, tapenade and salsa is effective as a hostess gift when
you don't know the particular tastes of the recipient. You can
spend as much or as little as desired.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the fun _ whether food items are homemade or
store-bought, or a combination of the two _ is gathering the
wrappings for festive presentations. Import and housewares stores,
drug stores, discount shops and party shops are good sources for
assorted items. For gift containers, consider inexpensive baskets,
mugs, boxes, trays, bowls, jars, crocks, covered tins, paper gift
bags, bread boards, baking dishes, skillets, pans, assorted glass
or plastic containers, plates, cookies jars and the like. Wrappings
and decorations can include ribbons, bows, cinnamon sticks, pine
cones, bells, silk flowers, ornaments, kitchen tools and more. You
might also tuck in a new or favorite cookbook.
</P>
<P>
   To line baskets or containers, use napkins, cut fabric pieces or
dish towels _ with or without holiday patterns.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to wrapping, be sure to prewrap all foods well
first (place on a plastic or paper plate if necessary) in food-safe
plastic wrap before placing in a basket or other container and
overwrapping with clear or colored cellophane (not all of it is
food-safe) and tying with colorful bows and ribbons. If you're
placing several items in one basket or container, cushion them with
excelsior, colorful tissue paper or glitzy-looking metallic
stuffing strips.
</P>
<P>
   Also be sure to label all foods, including storage directions as
well as the shelf life of the food _ and if necessary serving
instructions or ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Capture the spirit of the season by making and sharing some of
these recipes with friends, relatives, teachers or hostesses. Happy
holidays! &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
ORANGE WALNUT CREAM CHEESE FUDGE
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup evaporated milk
</P>
<P>
   1 2/3 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 cups (4 ounces) miniature marshmallows
</P>
<P>
   1 package (12 ounces) semisweet chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons orange-flavored liqueur OR 1 teaspoon orange
extract
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped walnuts
</P>
<P>
   11 ounces cream cheese, softened
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons orange marmalade
</P>
<P>
   In a medium, heavy-duty saucepan, combine butter, evaporated
milk, sugar and salt. Bring to a full rolling boil over medium
heat, stirring constantly. Boil 4 to 5 minutes, stirring
constantly. Remove from heat.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in marshmallows, 1 1/2 cups chocolate chips, liqueur and
nuts. Stir vigorously 1 minute or until marshmallows are melted.
</P>
<P>
   Pour into greased, foil-lined 9-inch square baking pan; smooth
top. Chill.
</P>
<P>
   In a small mixer bowl, combine cream cheese and marmalade. Beat
on medium speed 1 minute or until smooth. Spread over chilled
fudge.
</P>
<P>
   Microwave remaining 1/2 cup chips in a heavy-duty plastic food
bag on high power 1 minute; knead until smooth. Cut tiny corner
from bag; squeeze to drizzle chocolate over fudge. Chill to set
chocolate. Cut into squares. Makes about 6 dozen pieces. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
MULLED CIDER MIX
</P>
<P>
   Scoop some of this heady mix into small plastic or cellophane
bags secured with pretty ribbons. Offer an aromatic sackful with a
jug of fresh apple cider and perhaps a set of holiday mugs.
</P>
<P>
   8 cinnamon sticks, broken into pieces
</P>
<P>
   2 whole nutmegs, crushed
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup whole cloves
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup minced dried orange peel
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup whole allspice
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, combine all ingredients. Tie 1-tablespoon
batches of mix in a small cheesecloth or muslin bags and tie bags
with a string. Cider mix can be made ahead and kept indefinitely in
a tea tin. One bag of mix makes enough to flavor a quart of cider.
</P>
<P>
   To make mulled cider, put bag in a saucepan with 1 quart cider
and bring cider to a boil over moderately high heat. Simmer slowly,
covered 20 minutes. Add 1/4 cup dark rum, if desired, and simmer 5
minutes. Discard bag.
</P>
<P>
   Serve mulled cider hot with a cinnamon stick in each cup.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Gourmet's Holidays and Celebrations.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
OLIVE AND HERB SPREAD
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups juicy black olives
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups cracked green olives
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped fresh cilantro
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped fresh mint leaves
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground white pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 tablespoons balsamic vinegar OR to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Virgin olive oil, to top jar
</P>
<P>
   Rinse olives thoroughly in running water. Taste olives and if
they are still very salty, let stand 1 to 2 hours in warm water
before rinsing again. Dry on paper towels. Remove pits and chop
olives coarsely.
</P>
<P>
   Place olives, cilantro, garlic, mint, pepper, red wine vinegar
and 1 tablespoon balsamic vinegar in a food processor. Process
until you obtain a homogeneous paste, then, with motor running,
slowly add extra-virgin olive oil. Taste and adjust seasonings,
adding a little white pepper or more vinegar if needed.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer olive paste to a jar, top with a little virgin olive
oil so paste is completely covered, cover jar and place in
refrigerator at least 1 day before serving. Will keep up to 1 month
in refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with toasted bread as an appetizer. Makes about 2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Mediterranean Pantry'' by Aglaia Kremezi, Artisan. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHOCOLATE PANFORTE
</P>
<P>
   This dense, chewy Italian fruitcake is a traditional Christmas
favorite in Siena, Italy, where it has been enjoyed for ages.
Traditionally, panforte, which means ``strong bread'' in Italian,
contains citron. This version does not. A nonchocolate panforte
sampled at a casual San Francisco restaurant, Sputino, was the
inspiration for this version, though the restaurant uses dried
sweet cherries rather than the apricots called for here. Chocolate
has been added to this rendition as well.
</P>
<P>
   1 cup hazelnuts
</P>
<P>
   1 cup whole blanched almonds
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped dried apricots
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped candied orange peel
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup unsweetened cocoa powder
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 teaspoons ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   Dash pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup honey
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   Sifted powdered sugar OR unsweetened cocoa powder
</P>
<P>
   Butter a 9-inch springform pan. Line bottom with a round of
parchment or wax paper. Line sides of pan with a strip of paper cut
to fit.
</P>
<P>
   Spread out hazelnuts and almonds on 2 separate baking sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Place in preheated 325-degree oven and bake until almonds are
lightly toasted, about 5 minutes; transfer almonds to a plate to
cool.
</P>
<P>
   Continue baking hazelnuts until nuts are lightly browned and
dark skins are cracked. Rub warm hazelnuts in a terry cloth towel
to remove as much of skins as possible.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, combine hazelnuts, almonds, apricots, orange
peel and flour; mix well. Stir in cocoa, cinnamon, cloves, nutmeg
and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1 1/2-quart saucepan, combine granulated sugar, honey and
butter. Heat to boiling over medium heat, stirring often. Boil,
stirring constantly 5 minutes, or until mixture reaches 248 degrees
F on a candy thermometer.
</P>
<P>
   Working quickly, pour boiling syrup over nut-fruit mixture,
mixing until thoroughly incorporated and evenly coated. Turn into
prepared springform pan. Smooth top with a spatula
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 325-degree oven 35 minutes. Do not overbake.
Panforte will harden as it cools.
</P>
<P>
   Remove cake from oven and let cool completely in pan. Run a
sharp knife around edges of pan to loosen cake. Remove springform
side of pan. Peel off parchment paper and wrap cake well in plastic
wrap; then wrap in foil.
</P>
<P>
   Store at room temperature 3 weeks or freeze 2 to 3 months. Just
before serving, sift powdered sugar on top. Makes 12 to 16
servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``365 Great Chocolate Desserts'' by Natalie Haughton,
HarperCollins. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
PEANUT BUTTER ROCKY ROAD
</P>
<P>
   This is the fastest and simplest way to make rocky road. The
chocolate never streaks and no tempering is required. To give as a
gift, put each candy piece in a paper candy cup.
</P>
<P>
   3 cups semisweet chocolate chips OR 18 ounces semisweet
chocolate, cut up
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup crunchy OR smooth peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   3/4 chopped peanuts OR walnuts
</P>
<P>
   3 cups miniature marshmallows
</P>
<P>
   In a large 2-quart glass bowl, combine chocolate and peanut
butter. Heat in microwave oven on high power 2 to 2 1/2 minutes,
stirring once halfway through cooking time. Stir until chocolate is
melted and smooth. Stir in peanuts and marshmallows.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately spread in a foil-lined 11x7-inch baking pan.
Refrigerate 1 to 2 hours, or until firm. Cut into 35 pieces. Keep
refrigerated. Makes 35 pieces.
</P>
<P>
   From ``365 Great Chocolate Desserts'' by Natalie Haughton,
HarperCollins. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHOCOLATE COOKIES
</P>
<P>
   1 package (18.25 ounces) devil's food cake mix, such as Betty
Crocker SuperMoist
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   Sugar
</P>
<P>
   Mix dry cake mix, oil and eggs in a large bowl with a spoon
until dough forms.
</P>
<P>
   Shape dough into 1-inch balls; roll in sugar. Place about 2
inches apart on ungreased cookie sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven 8 to 10 minutes or until set.
Remove from cookie sheet to a wire rack. Makes about 4 dozen
cookies.
</P>
<P>
   VARIATION: Chocolate Chip Chocolate Cookies, stir in 2/3 cup
miniature semisweet chocolate chips into dough.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Betty Crocker's Cookie Book'', Macmillan. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
HOT FUDGE SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   1 cup evaporated milk OR half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup light corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons (3/4 stick) sweet (unsalted) butter
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces (4 squares) fine-quality unsweetened chocolate
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces (2 squares) fine-quality semisweet chocolate
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 teaspoons vanilla to taste
</P>
<P>
   Combine evaporated milk, sugar, salt, corn syrup, butter and
chocolates in upper pan of a double boiler, or use a heatproof bowl
that can be set over a saucepan containing simmering water.
</P>
<P>
   Set pan over simmering water in double-boiler base and heat
contents, stirring occasionally, until butter and chocolate have
melted. Stir sauce thoroughly and continue to cook until smooth and
slightly thickened, about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   If there are any lumps, strain sauce. Let cool 5 minutes or so,
then stir in vanilla. Scrape sauce into a clean, dry jar or jars.
Cool completely, then cover and store in refrigerator. Will keep at
least 3 months.
</P>
<P>
   For freezer storage up to 6 months, freeze sauce in a tightly
covered food container, preferably glass, allowing at least 1/2
inch of headspace.
</P>
<P>
   To serve sauce, thaw unopened and let come to room temperature
if frozen, or let refrigerated sauce come to room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   To warm sauce, set jar in a bowl of hot water and stir
occasionally until sauce will flow smoothly when spooned over ice
cream. Makes 3 cups.
</P>
<P>
   FUDGE SAUCE WITH ALMARETTO: Replace vanilla with Amaretto
liqueur, adding about 2 tablespoons OR amount desired.
</P>
<P>
   CHOCOLATE PEPPERMINT FUDGE SAUCE: Replace vanilla with a small
amount of peppermint extract OR 1 to 2 tablespoons creme de menthe
OR other peppermint flavored liqueur. Start with 1/2 teaspoon
peppermint extract OR 1 tablespoon liqueur, then taste and
cautiously add more flavoring if needed; peppermint can be
overpowering.
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Good Stuff Cookbook'' by Helen Witty, Workman
Publishing. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHEDDAR CARAWAY BATTER BREAD
</P>
<P>
   1 can (12 ounces) evaporated milk OR 1 1/2 cups half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter OR margarine, cut into pieces
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons EACH salt and caraway seeds
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups (6 ounces) shredded sharp Cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 package active dry yeast
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup warm water (about 110 degrees F)
</P>
<P>
   3 3/4 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   In a pan, combine evaporated milk, sugar, butter, salt, caraway
seeds, garlic powder and cheese. Over medium heat, stir and heat to
about 110 degrees F.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, sprinkle yeast over warm water and let stand
about 5 minutes to soften. Add milk mixture; beat in 1 1/2 cups
flour. Add eggs, 1 at a time, beating well after each addition;
gradually beat in remaining 2 1/4 cups flour until batter is
smooth. Cover with plastic wrap, let rise in a warm place until
doubled, about 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Stir batter down and spoon into a generously greased 10-inch
plain or decorative tube pan or 2 (41/2x81/2-inch) loaf pans. Cover
with plastic wrap. Let rise in a warm place until almost doubled,
about 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven until browned, about 55
minutes for tube pan, about 45 minutes for loaf pans.
</P>
<P>
   Let bread cool in pan on a rack 5 minutes; then turn out onto
rack and let cool completely. Wrap airtight; store at room
temperature up to 1 day, in freezer up to 1 month. Makes 1 large
loaf or 2 small loaves.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Gifts From Your Kitchen'' by the editors of Sunset Books
and Sunset Magazine, Lane Publishing Co. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
GARDEN MARINARA SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   When you give a jar of made-from-scratch marinara sauce, you're
giving your lucky friends a head start on a great dinner _ they
need only add pasta, bread and wine.
</P>
<P>
   6 pounds (15 to 18 medium-size) fresh, ripe tomatoes OR 4 large
cans (28 ounces EACH) whole tomatoes, drained
</P>
<P>
   Water
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 large onions, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 to 4 cloves garlic, minced OR pressed
</P>
<P>
   1 cup lightly packed fresh basil leaves, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 to 1 tablespoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   Dip fresh tomatoes in boiling water to cover 10 seconds; core
and peel. Chop fresh or canned tomatoes with a food processor or a
knife.
</P>
<P>
   Pour oil into a 12x14-inch frying pan; add onions and garlic and
cook over medium heat, stirring frequently, until onions are golden
brown, about 20 minutes. Add chopped tomatoes and basil. Cook,
uncovered, stirring occasionally to prevent sticking, until sauce
is reduced to 8 cups, 45 to 60 minutes. Add sugar; season to taste
with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Ladle sauce into 4 (1-pint) canning jars or freezer containers,
leaving 1 inch headspace. Cover tightly; store in refrigerator up
to 1 week, in freezer up to 6 months. Makes 4 pints.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Gifts From Your Kitchen'' by the editors of Sunset Books
and Sunset Magazine, Lane Publishing Co. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
RASPBERRY VINEGAR
</P>
<P>
   This fruity, tangy pink vinegar is just as successful in
marinades and sauces as it is in salad dressings and vinaigrettes.
</P>
<P>
   1 package (10 ounces) frozen raspberries in syrup, thawed
</P>
<P>
   48 ounces red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Drain raspberries, reserving 3 tablespoons syrup. Place
raspberries, vinegar and 3 tablespoons syrup in a large
non-aluminum saucepan. Let stand covered overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Bring vinegar mixture to a boil over moderately high heat. Boil
uncovered 3 minutes. Cool. Strain vinegar through a damp
cheesecloth into a clean, hot jar.
</P>
<P>
   Store tightly covered at least 2 weeks before using. May be
stored in a cool, dark place 2 months or refrigerated for longer
storage. Makes 6 cups.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Season's Greetings'' by Marlene Sorosky,
HarperPerennial. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
REFRIGERATOR PICKLES
</P>
<P>
   Cold and crunchy, these will last a long time in your
refrigerator _ if you can resist helping yourself. Don't just think
of them as pickles; they also make a splendid salad.
</P>
<P>
   3 hothouse (long, thin) cucumbers, unpeeled OR 4 regular
cucumbers, peeled (about 3 1/2 pounds)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1 large green bell pepper, seeded and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 yellow onion, sliced thin
</P>
<P>
   1 cup white vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons celery seeds
</P>
<P>
   Slice cucumbers into 1/4-inch slices by hand or in a food
processor with a medium slicing blade. Mix slices with salt in a
colander in sink. Let stand 2 hours. Drain cucumbers well and place
in a large bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in green pepper and onion. Stir vinegar, sugar and celery
seeds in a small bowl, until sugar is dissolved.
</P>
<P>
   Pour over vegetables. Refrigerate, covered at least 24 hours
before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Pickles may be refrigerated up to 4 months. Makes about 9 cups.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Season's Greetings'' by Marlene Sorosky,
HarperPerennial. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
APRICOT PRESERVES
</P>
<P>
   1 pound dried apricots
</P>
<P>
   4 1/2 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1 pound sugar
</P>
<P>
   Simmer apricots and water in a medium saucepan until soft, about
10 minutes. Remove apricots with a slotted spoon to a food
processor fitted with a metal blade. Puree until smooth, then
return to water in saucepan.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in sugar and cook slowly over moderately low heat, stirring
occasionally until mixture is thick, about 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately spoon jam into clean, hot jars and seal. Or cool and
store in refrigerator. Makes 5 (8-ounce) jars.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Season's Greetings'' by Marlene Sorosky,
HarperPerennial. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
COFFEE LIQUEUR
</P>
<P>
   1 jar (2 ounces) instant coffee
</P>
<P>
   4 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 cups boiling water
</P>
<P>
   1 pint brandy
</P>
<P>
   1 vanilla bean
</P>
<P>
   Stir coffee and sugar in a medium bowl. Add boiling water and
stir well.
</P>
<P>
   Cool to room temperature and stir in brandy. Cut vanilla bean
into 2-inch pieces. Place in liqueur and pour into a large jar.
</P>
<P>
   Cover tightly and store in a cool, dark place at least 15 days
or longer, turning or shaking jar once a week.
</P>
<P>
   Will keep at room temperature 3 months. Refrigerate for longer
storage. Makes about 6 cups.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Season's Greetings'' by Marlene Sorosky, HarperPerennial.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
