<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9262 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-SCHOOLS-ART-NYT     12-08 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-SCHOOLS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA JOURNAL: A CHANT TO FIRE UP CHILDREN, OR INFLAME ADULTS?
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos and locator map are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GHAZIABAD, India _ The children scattered like pigeons when
their teacher, Shankuntla Sharma, came after them with an old
splintered piece of wood, swinging it at the chatterboxes. There
are 60 boys and girls in her class, and keeping order can be a
trial. ``When I get fed up, I use the stick,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Too many children and too few supplies: Mrs. Sharma's classroom
faces common problems in a nation where the average class size is
63, where a third of the children of elementary-school age are
simply not in school, where almost half the people cannot read or
write.
</P>
<P>
   But the most debated educational issue these days in Uttar
Pradesh, India's most populous state, has nothing to do with low
levels of spending on primary schools, which means that no desks,
chairs or books are provided to the children in Mrs. Sharma's
class. It has everything to do with two words they proclaim in
unison every morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vande Mataram!'' they shout with arms raised to salute India.
</P>
<P>
   The words mean ``Hail the Motherland,'' and they are the title
of the country's national song _ and the only part of it that these
children actually recite. Bankimchandra Chatterji wrote it in the
19th century as a tribute to a popular Bengali rebellion against
the British and a local Muslim feudal lord.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of this century, ``Vande Mataram'' became a freedom
song for many Hindus and Muslims struggling to gain independence
from Britain. But members of the Muslim League, the organization
that pressed for the creation of Pakistan as a homeland for
Muslims, condemned it as a kind of idol worship of India, said
Bipan Chandra, professor emeritus of history at Nehru University in
New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days the song has again become a source of friction,
this time in Uttar Pradesh. The Hindu nationalist government here,
led by the Bharatiya Janata Party, which is also in power
nationally, set off the conflict when its leaders proclaimed that
recitation of the song should be compulsory in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Muslim leaders, including Ali Mian, a prominent Islamic scholar
and chairman of the All India Muslim Personal Law Board, a private
advocacy group, responded with condemnations of the requirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is against Islamic law to bow your head to anyone except
Allah,'' Mian said. ``India is a secular democracy. It is the
responsibility of the government to insure that minorities have the
freedom of their faith and feel secure.''
</P>
<P>
   Hindu nationalist student leaders responded by burning effigies
of Mian and other Muslims, while Hindu nationalists in the state
government suggested that those who opposed the ``Vande Mataram''
requirement were disloyal to India.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Muslims have any problems with `Vande Mataram' they are
welcome to go to the madrasas,'' Ravindra Shukla, Basic Education
Minister in Uttar Pradesh, said in an interview two weeks ago.
Madrasas are private religious schools for Muslims. ``To recite
`Vande Mataram' is a tribute to our freedom struggle and freedom
fighters. Those who are opposing it will be given a fitting reply
by the masses when election time comes.''
</P>
<P>
   But Shukla's widely publicized remarks and his stand on the
national song set off a conflict that cost him his job last week.
</P>
<P>
   The tensions over the song first surfaced just weeks after the
government in New Delhi, which is led by Hindu nationalists,
circulated documents to state education ministers proposing that
students be required to study sacred Hindu scriptures in public
schools. That idea was abandoned after protests from Hindus and
Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Again, in the ``Vande Mataram'' debate, the national government
distanced itself from a divisive proposal _ and put pressure on the
state to withdraw it. Finally, on Friday, the government of the
Uttar Pradesh Chief Minister, Kalyan Singh, issued a clipped
statement rescinding the order and removing Shukla.
</P>
<P>
   This war of words over cultural symbols seems strangely hollow
at the Kanya Pathshala school in Ghaziabad, where 60 students in
the third, fourth and fifth grades sit in rows on a hard, stone
floor, reading from textbooks their hard-pressed parents had to
buy.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Sharma, who has taught for 28 years and doubles now as
principal, said she was told to begin requiring her students to say
``Vande Mataram'' about a year ago at a meeting of teachers and
administrators, long before the issue became public.
</P>
<P>
   Every morning since then she has gathered the primary school's
129 children _ 15 to 20 of them Muslim _ in a small courtyard to
say their morning prayer and to chant ``Vande Mataram!'' three
times. None of the raggedly clothed boys and girls recite the
stanzas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot tell you a lie,'' Mrs. Sharma confessed. ``Even I
don't remember all the words.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabya Basri, a Muslim woman, has four children in public school,
including one in Mrs. Sharma's class. She said she does not care
whether they sing ``Vande Mataram.'' She just wants them to be able
to read and write _ something she and her ailing husband never
learned to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please understand,'' said Mrs. Basri, enshrouded in a
floor-length black burka, or loose garment, ``whether you say God
or Allah, it is one and the same. We have mosques. They have
temples. It is the language that is different, but the message is
the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you cut the fingers of these children, all their blood will
be red,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
