<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-NIGHTLIFE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TABRIZ CELEBRATES A JOYFUL HOLIDAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TABRIZ, Iran _ Among all of Iran's cities, this is the one with
a night owl's reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Some shops along Imam Khomeini Avenue keep lights burning until
midnight, and the ones tucked away in the labyrinthine 15th-century
bazaar do not even open their doors until 10:30 a.m. In summer
months, the century-old El Goli amusement park keeps its Ferris
wheel turning until the wee hours of the morning.
</P>
<P>
   For two days this month, the glittering lights and buoyant song
of a joyful religious holiday dominated the city as nowhere else in
Iran, transforming what is a shabby commercial center by day into a
festival of color by night.
</P>
<P>
   This is still the Islamic Republic, of course, so public
pastimes must be wholesome. Only behind closed doors do local
residents drink and gamble as they did so visibly before the
Islamic revolution of 1979, when the main street and amusement park
were still named for Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi.
</P>
<P>
   But even in the chill of early December, residents of Tabriz
like to stay out late, and if the reason can be rooted in religion,
so much the better.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you mean, late?'' Firouz Alizadeh replied as he pulled
up on a motor scooter, with his two young sons aboard, and headed
toward a mosque for a midnight dinner celebrating the 1,129th
birthday of a prophet whom Shiite Muslims believe will return
someday.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Tabriz, the Shiite branch of Islam, since the revolution
the dominant force in Iranian life, remains a generally gloomy
religion.
</P>
<P>
   Its calendar is filled with mourning days and mourning months
commemorated with mournful dirges and decorated in black. Many are
dedicated to the memory of the first 11 Shiite prophets, many of
whom were slain centuries ago.
</P>
<P>
   But the 12th prophet, Mahdi, is thought to have been an
exception. A many-times great-grandson of the Prophet Mohammed, he
was born in 869 and disappeared as a young child. It is an article
of faith among Shiites that he will one day reappear, as one text
puts it, ``to fill the earth with justice and fairness as it was
filled with oppression and tyranny.''
</P>
<P>
   Even under the shah, who was so reviled by the Islamic
revolutionaries, Mahdi's birthday was a national holiday,
celebrated with a joyful zeal. But perhaps only now, and in Tabriz,
has it reached full flower.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where are you, Mahdi?'' read a banner hung in Clock Square.
``You are our only precious gem!''
</P>
<P>
   In one mosque, men packed into a narrow room to sing songs of
passionate praise, with the celebration broadcast by closed-circuit
television to those who lined the sidewalks outside. As a sign of
good will, many residents pressed candy and coins into the palms of
passers-by.
</P>
<P>
   And even people who said they felt no deep religious faith had
braved a maddening snarl of traffic to take in the late-night
spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the way Tabrizis celebrate,'' said Mohammed Reza
Azizi, 27, as cars whose passengers included a remarkable number of
wedding parties zoomed past on downtown streets.
</P>
<P>
   Shiites take their mourning days seriously, so much so that
weddings are regarded as inauspicious for three months a year. One
of those months, Ramadan, falls just two weeks after Mahdi's
birthday on the Islamic calendar, so Iranian couples often seize on
the holiday as a last best time to wed.
</P>
<P>
   Much socializing in Tabriz involves family visits, and no one
whom a visitor met here could explain why so much goes on so late
in Tabriz, while in Tehran, the capital, most stores shut by 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Some suggested that the reason was impenetrable, in the same way
that devout Shiites unquestioningly accept the idea that the
prophet Mahdi was born so many centuries ago, but has not yet died.
</P>
<P>
   The city's Friday prayer leader used a metaphor that Tabrizis
said they could understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``An insect can stare at the sun for a very long time, but we
human beings cannot do that,'' the cleric, Ayatollah Mossein
Mujtahid Shabestaki, said at one ceremony. ``Still, we should try
to be like the insect, and then we can see the 12th imam.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-98 1926EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
