<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-BROOKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAUL BROOKS, WAS EDITOR IN CHIEF, VP AT HOUGHTON MIFFLIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paul Brooks, a retired editor in chief and vice president of
Houghton Mifflin Co., died Sunday in Carleton-Willard Village in
Bedford, Mass. He was 89.
</P>
<P>
   During his nearly 40 years with Houghton Mifflin, 25 of them as
editor in chief of the general book department, Mr. Brooks dealt
with many prominent authors, including Sir Winston Churchill, James
Agee, Archibald MacLeish, Louis Auchincloss, John Kenneth
Galbraith, Roger Tory Peterson, and Rachel Carson.
</P>
<P>
   In his memoir, ``Two Park Street,'' published by Houghton
Mifflin in 1986, he provided a droll insider's account of
publishing's evolution from one of personal relationships to a
relatively impersonal business.
</P>
<P>
   According to ``Two Park Street,'' his career began at a
convivial Harvard Lampoon dinner in 1931 where a jolly executive
offered him a job. This was a singular event during the height of
the Depression, and, accordingly, Mr. Brooks reported to Park
Street. There he was assigned an office shared by a dignified
gentleman who spent the morning dictating letter after letter about
the marbled godwit, a handsome shorebird. Lunch followed (a bowl of
crackers and milk, with blueberries, at the Union Club). Upon
returning from lunch, Mr. Brooks was introduced to the company
treasurer, who snorted, ``Huh! Another one of those young
puppies!'' Then editorial director Ferris Greenslet presented the
neophyte with a copy of Sir Stanley Unwin's ``The Truth About
Publishing.'' Greenslet never buzzed for subordinates; instead, he
summoned them with a few bars on his flute.
</P>
<P>
   One of Mr. Brooks's early successes was ``Forty-Two Years in the
White House,'' by Irwin Hood (Ike) Hoover, chief usher of the
president, who had come to the White House as a young employee of
the Edison Co. because President Harrison's family feared turning
on the electric lights.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Brooks saw Ross Lockridge (``Raintree County'') and Thomas
Heggen (``Mister Roberts'') destroyed by fame, and helped coax
along Churchill's six-volume ``The Second World War'' in time to
meet production schedules.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote that he derived his greatest satisfaction from the
nature writers he met at Two Park Street, particularly Peterson and
Carson, because they brought about a change in our way of looking
at the world.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Brooks had long been interested in saving remaining
wilderness. In Lincoln, Mass., where he had lived for more than
half a century, he was active on the planning board and the
conservation commission.
</P>
<P>
   He also had served on the boards of such environmental
organizations as the Sierra Club, the Public Lands Institute, and
the Trustees of Reservations.
</P>
<P>
   Much of his writing was aimed at conservation. He felt strongly
that ``the principal destroyers of our environment _ be they
irresponsible giant corporations or government agencies like the
Army Engineers _ are responsive only to informed public opinion''
and that ``anything one can do to reach readers beyond the already
converted is bound to be of some help.''
</P>
<P>
   He wrote numerous magazine articles and several books, including
``Roadless Area,'' ``The Pursuit of Wilderness,'' ``The House of
Life: Rachel Carson at Work,'' ``The View from Lincoln Hill,'' and
``Speaking for Nature.''
</P>
<P>
   He was born in New York City and graduated from Harvard College
in 1931.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the close of World War II, he went abroad for the Office
of War Information as chief of the book section for the European
Theater of Operations.
</P>
<P>
   He was a director of the Massachusetts Audubon Society, a
trustee of the Harvard Lampoon and a member of the Usage Panel of
the American Heritage Dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves three daughters, Elizabeth B. Harris of Dublin, N.H.,
Susan B. Morris of Waldoboro, Maine, and Kate Brooks of Canaan,
N.H.; a son, Samuel J. of Peterborough, Ontario; seven
grandchildren and three great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-98 1926EST &QL; 
