<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HDTV-FLOP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT SAYS HDTV SETS WON'T FLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To consumer electronics companies, the new high-definition
television sets just coming to market are home entertainment's next
big thing. But according to a market research firm, HDTV will
actually be the industry's next big flop.
</P>
<P>
   In a report released Tuesday, Forrester Research Inc. of
Cambridge, Mass. predicts that television makers will sell only a
million HDTV sets between now and the year 2003, and that TV makers
should concentrate on less sophisticated digital sets that are much
cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   After years of planning, TV stations in US cities have begun
limited broadcasts of digital TV, which offers a much sharper
picture than traditional analog TV sets. By the year 2006, all TV
stations in the United States plan to stop analog broadcasting
entirely, and electronics companies are counting on a
multibillion-dollar bonanza as consumers switch to digital TV
systems.
</P>
<P>
   The top-drawer digital TV sets will use HDTV, an advanced system
that produces the sharpest pictures of all.
</P>
<P>
   Today's first-generation HDTV sets cost between $5,000 and
$10,000 each. Prices for consumer electronics products tend to drop
sharply over time. But the Forrester report, prepared by analyst
Josh Bernoff, claims that HDTV set prices will buck this trend,
remaining higher than $2,000 per set for at least the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   In a television picture tube, a stream of electrons draws
horizontal lines across the screen dozens of times every second.
The more lines in the picture, the higher its definition and the
better it looks. Today's TV sets display an image made of 480
lines. A high-definition TV will show well over a thousand lines.
</P>
<P>
   Bernoff agrees the computerized electronics controlling these
HDTV sets will rapidly fall in price, to below $100 by the year
2001. But he adds that there's no cheap way to make
higher-definition picture tubes. ``It's just fundamentally hard
from the perspective of physics to refresh a large screen with that
many lines of resolution 60 times a second,'' he said. So HDTV sets
will stay expensive for years to come, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Bernoff recommends that the television industry support an
alternative digital technology called standard definition TV or
SDTV. He said that SDTV sets use a technology similar to that found
in computer monitors to produce a picture that's almost as sharp as
HDTV. But an SDTV set would use about the same number of lines as
today's TV sets, and so would be much cheaper to make. Bernoff
predicts SDTV sets will sell for less than $1,000 by 2002, and will
capture 80 percent of the digital TV market by 2008.
</P>
<P>
   The Forrester report brought a quick retort from the Consumer
Electronics Manufacturers Association, the Arlington, Va. trade
group representing TV makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're making assumptions about what consumers will do, not
having talked to any consumers,'' said spokeswoman Ann Saybolt. She
predicted that 30 percent of US households will have HDTV sets by
the year 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Saybolt admitted that today's HDTV sets are quite expensive, but
said they would soon become much cheaper. Besides, she said, people
will buy them even if they're much more expensive that traditional
TV sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have said that they want the best technology,'' said
Saybolt, ``and they're willing to pay for it,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-98 1928EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
