<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9269 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONCERTS-CELLPHONES-A     12-08 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONCERTS-CELLPHONES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CONCERT COMMUNION WITH CELL PHONES
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Marion, general manager of the Alltel Arena in Little
Rock, Ark., was at a concert by former Led Zeppelin members Jimmy
Page and Robert Plant recently when he noticed something strange.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike past Led Zeppelin shows, when audience members would hold
their cigarette lighters aloft during the slow, emotional parts of
rock epics like ``Stairway to Heaven,'' this concert had no small
flames illuminating the arena. Instead, he said, during the encore,
``Everybody was holding up their hands, and here and there I could
see guys holding up their cell phones, playing the music for
someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, at concerts you don't have cigarette lighters like
you used to,'' he said. ``It's dark, except for the cell phones.''
</P>
<P>
   A concert tradition has been changing. The cigarette lighter,
long the concert prop of choice, is giving way to the cellular
phone. Once held aloft as the universal symbol of thousands of
hearts joined in the magical unity that a pop concert can create,
the lighter is going the way of smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, at most arenas and concert halls today, smoking is
forbidden; at some clubs, cigarettes and lighters are confiscated
at the door.
</P>
<P>
   With the cell phone becoming as ubiquitous as the lighter was,
its new status at pop concerts may be inevitable. After all, it's
one of the few pocket-or-purse items that lights up. And where
lighters at concerts are like tie-dyed shirts, protest songs, cheap
tickets and other relics of the '60s, cell phones are symbols for
the '90s, where networking is king.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the lighters, the concert cell phones are almost entirely
utilitarian: the fact that they light up the arena is secondary.
``I've called friends from concerts,'' said Laurie Ziegler, a music
producer. ``They wanted to go to a concert but couldn't, so if they
have a favorite song, why not let them hear it? If someone went to
Bob Dylan and he played `Forever Young,' I'd kill them if they
didn't call me.''
</P>
<P>
   A rock-group manager who spoke on the condition of anonymity
(more out of embarrassment than need for confidentiality),
confessed to calling friends during a performance of ``Sweet
Emotion'' at an Aerosmith show and ``Iron Man'' at a Black Sabbath
concert, leaving a song snippet on their answering machines in each
case.
</P>
<P>
   This new form of lighting up is a growing sight, especially at
concerts that attract audiences in their 20s and 30s. Antennae seem
to sprout from people's heads and hands, and there are patterns
made by glowing keypads and flashing green lights, evidence of
concertgoers' calling friends during the good songs or even
checking their answering machine for messages during the boring
parts.
</P>
<P>
   At performances this year ranging from those by the Mighty
Mighty Bosstones to the Pakistani Sufi singer Badar Ali Khan,
concertgoers called other audience members to say hello and find
out where their friends were seated. And at a recent Wu-Tang Clan
concert, a rapper even took a phone call from the stage (a gesture
as inappropriate as a singer flicking a Bic during his or her own
ballad).
</P>
<P>
   The use of cell phones has spread to classical concerts as well,
but it seems likely to remain, like the lighter, mainly a pop
manifestation. When cell phones began ringing at New York's
Carnegie Hall at the season's opening night concert this year by
the San Francisco Symphony, the building's executive director,
Judith Arron, swung into action. She inserted ``An Urgent Note to
Our Patrons'' in the hall's programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a phenomenon that we have noticed with dismay that
has been making its presence ringingly known in the Hall in the
last month: the cell phone epidemic,'' the note states. Ms. Arron
advised patrons to turn off the phones or leave them at home. For
the most part people have been respecting her wishes, but the
occasional call can still be heard.
</P>
<P>
   At other classical music halls, phone jockeys have been escorted
to the exits.
</P>
<P>
   Cell phones are less likely to be disturbing at pop concerts,
typically louder and more social. Although tape recorders and
cameras are confiscated at the door at most pop shows, cell phones
are not yet considered an infringement on the audience's enjoyment
or on performers' rights to their music.
</P>
<P>
   Though concertgoers like Ms. Ziegler may create outgoing
messages on their answering machines from a few seconds of music
taped at a concert (a cheaper alternative to the concert T-shirt as
proof of attendance), arena managers doubt that cell phones will be
banned, even if someone succeeds in recording an entire concert on
an answering machine tape. Marion of the Alltel Arena said that
unless people started making money by capturing music on cell
phones, the accessories were there to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Musicians have been noticing the phenomenon. ``I was doing a
show from Vancouver where we were rocking,'' said Justin
Meldal-Johnsen, who plays bass for Beck, the eclectic performer who
mixes folk and hip-hop. ``And I saw this guy and his girlfriend
with a cell phone, and they were passing the phone back and forth
to each other, sharing the concert with a friend for what must have
been 10 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The sound system must have been blowing their ears out,'' he
said. ``I was so surprised they were able to talk on the phone.
Everyone around them was just smiling, enjoying this perverse
moment where they're in the concert world but in the outside world
at the at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The tradition of fans' holding up lighters is generally traced
back 29 years to Woodstock, which inspired the singer Melanie to
write the song ``Lay Down (Candles in the Wind).'' Her fans took to
lighting candles during the song, then turned to matches when
concert halls began cracking down because candles were forbidden
under some fire codes.
</P>
<P>
   Soon lighting matches between the main set and the encore became
a ritual, as if fans were trying to keep the music's emotional
effect from ebbing. The practice spread especially with the advent
of disposable lighters, popularizing a way for concertgoers to
express the feelings stirred by a sentimental song.
</P>
<P>
   For many in the '90s, however, sentiment goes only so far. Or
perhaps fans see their emotions as too complex to be encapsulated
by a lighter's flame. The cell phone, on the other hand, is a
useful tool at an event where fans now do business, build social
relationships and even get some advice from mom and dad.
</P>
<P>
   Meldal-Johnsen of Beck's band noticed cell phones in use when
tragedy struck at the Tibetan Freedom Concert in Washington this
summer. Several audience members were hit by lightning, and
Meldal-Johnsen recalled ``seeing all these kids crying and talking
on their cell phones with their parents.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked so surreal, so apocalyptic,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A commercial for Ericsson cellular phones tries to make another
kind of utilitarian claim for the cell phone when events go awry.
During a blackout in the middle of a football game, the cell phone
comes to the rescue with fans turning on thousands of them, sending
out little halos of light to save the day.
</P>
<P>
   So, if Melanie's ``Lay Down (Candles in the Wind)'' was the
anthem for matches and cigarette lighters, what will the cell phone
anthem be? The Electric Light Orchestra's ``Calling America,'' New
Edition's ``Mr. Telephone Man'' or Stevie Wonder's ``I Just Called
to Say I Love You''?
</P>
<P>
   Or will it be Blondie's ``Call Me,'' with its phone
permissiveness (``you can call me any day or night''), or Aretha
Franklin's ``Call Me,'' which pleads, ``Will you call me the moment
you get there?''
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe someone will write a new anthem, ``Signal Faded (Cell
Phones in the Air),'' which could give rise to more elaborate
concert traditions, like performers' exhorting audience members to
call their loved ones during a ballad, effectively doubling their
listening audience and perhaps helping to land that cellular phone
company as a sponsor. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
