A9276 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MODERATES-COX     12-08 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MODERATES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Moderate Georgians among Republicans White House seeks to win
over
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Georgians Saxby Chambliss and Charlie Norwood are
among the 20 to 30 Republicans the White House has targeted in a
lobbying effort to fight off impeachment by the House of
Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is working off a list provided by House
Democrats that identifies moderates as well as more conservative
Republicans such as Chambliss and Norwood who may be amenable to
voting against impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans hold an 11-seat majority in the 105th Congress,
which goes out of business Jan. 3. If impeachment supporters do not
hold almost all Republicans in a vote on the House floor, prospects
for passage are dim because the Democrats appear to have all but a
few members of their caucus united in opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Every Republican targeted by Democrats comes from a district
that supported Clinton in the 1996 presidential election. Those
election results give Democrats hope that these GOP colleagues will
think twice before voting for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``These districts are where the vote (for impeachment) would be
the riskiest,'' said Merle Black, an Emory University political
science professor. ``On the other hand, the type of voter who would
support a Republican congressman in those districts would more
likely be in favor of a tougher line.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Chambliss and Norwood, Democrats believe
significant African-American constituencies may influence their
vote, according to a copy of the list obtained by the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Black Georgians make up more than 28 percent of Chambliss's
district, which runs from south from Macon, and more than 34
percent of Norwood's Augusta-based eastern Georgia district.
</P>
<P>
   African-Americans have been among Clinton's most loyal
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Norwood, in addition, worked closely with the White House last
year on a proposed reform of managed care health plans that put him
at odds with most Republicans. Norwood has said he intends to
re-introduce his legislation next year.
</P>
<P>
   Chambliss and Norwood have not said how they will vote if the
House Judiciary Committee, as expected, approves articles of
impeachment against Clinton and sends them to the full House before
year's end.
</P>
<P>
   Chambliss ``really would like to wait and see what the committee
reports,'' said Lindsay Taylor, his spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Norwood also is awaiting the committee's action, John Stone,
Norwood's spokesman, said.
</P>
<P>
   Black said he would be surprised if the Georgians decide against
impeachment ``because that would be a vote they would really have
to explain back home.''
</P>
<P>
   A handful of Republicans on the Democrats' list already have
said they will vote against impeachment, including Christopher
Shays of Connecticut, Peter King of New York and Jack Quinn of New
York. Two other Republicans, John Edward Porter of Illinois and
Mark Edward Souder of Indiana, also are on record as opposing
Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Among the House members on the Democrats' list are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Brian Bilbray of California and Richard Baker of Louisiana,
who narrowly won re-election in their districts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jack Metcalf of Washington, who has a large and traditionally
Democratic union constituency in his district north of Seattle, and
Anne Northup of Kentucky, another GOP member with a large union
presence in her Louisville district.
</P>
<P>
   _ Three other Republicans from the New York suburbs, Michael
Forbes, Ben Gilman and Rick Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sherman writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
