<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9282 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-JUSTICE-RETIRE-BOS     12-08 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-JUSTICE-RETIRE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRIED SAYS HE'LL STEP DOWN NEXT JULY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLEMENT AND PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Supreme Judicial Court justice Charles Fried confirmed
Tuesday he will leave the state's highest court next July to resume
teaching at Harvard Law School. Governor Paul Cellucci said he
wants a ``tough law-and-order'' replacement, but not necessarily a
death-penalty supporter.
</P>
<P>
   Fried's seat will be the first of four expected vacancies
Cellucci will have the chance to fill in the next two years,
including the chief justice. Observers say Cellucci will apparently
become the first governor in state history to select a majority for
the seven-member bench.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci said he would like to fill Fried's seat with ``a strict
constructionist, someone who's going to enforce the law'' rather
than personal views. ``Obviously, I'm looking for people who have a
tough law-and-order approach to crime,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the governor, who supports the reinstatement of the death
penalty, repeated a past vow not to impose ``any real litmus test''
on applicants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone could be personally opposed to the death penalty,''
but still uphold a constitutional amendment reinstating it,
Cellucci said. Several legal sources said no clear frontrunners
have emerged for Fried's seat.
</P>
<P>
   Two Cellucci advisers predicted the governor would likely wait
until after his Jan. 7 inauguration to begin a serious search for a
candidate because he wants to choose new cabinet secretaries first.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said it is likely that the number of
vacancies within the next two years could allow a number of
apparent long-shot candidates to emerge as favorites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may see a lot of interesting folks come to light that the
governor and others might not think of off the tops of their
heads,'' said one downtown lawyer active in GOP politics who spoke
on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice Herbert P. Wilkins is expected to resign next
summer shortly before he reaches the mandatory retirement age of
70, and Justices Neil L. Lynch and Ruth I. Abrams both will retire
in 2000. Remaining will be Justices John M. Greaney, Margaret H.
Marshall and Roderick I. Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Healy, general counsel for the Massachusetts Bar
Association, said that while Cellucci may have ``an unprecedented
opportunity'' to make his mark on the court, ``it also is an
overwhelming task to find four intellectual giants to serve on the
court.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci would not say if he intends to look within the state
court system or go outside of it, as former governor William F.
Weld did when he selected Fried and Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers have speculated that Cellucci may want to name a
Latino or Asian-American to enhance the diversity of the court.
``Diversity is always a consideration when you are making
appointments,'' Cellucci said.
</P>
<P>
   Fried, a conservative, squeaked onto the court by a 5-4
Governor's Council vote in 1995 after liberal activists mounted a
massive campaign against him. He said Tuesday will step down June
30 from the $115,000-a-year seat on the bench and begin work as a
tenured Harvard law professor the following day.
</P>
<P>
   A former US solicitor general, Fried was on the bench Tuesday as
the SJC reviewed several first-degree murder cases. He declined a
request for an interview.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued Tuesday, Fried said he is leaving the SJC
with ``real regret.''
</P>
<P>
   ``After much reflection, I have concluded that I can make my
best contribution as a full-time teacher and scholar,'' he said.
``I cherish the friendship and collaboration of warm, dedicated and
exceptionally able colleagues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
