<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9289 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARTENDERS-SMOKE-BOS &LR;      12-08 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARTENDERS-SMOKE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO BARTENDERS BENEFIT UNDER SMOKING BAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The respiratory health of San Francisco bartenders improved
significantly just weeks after California banned smoking in bars
and taverns where they were exposed to high levels of second-hand
smoke, says a study.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers said the findings are among the first to show that
second-hand smoke can cause short-term respiratory problems as well
as raising the risk of long-term diseases like cancer and heart
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Those breathing-related problems, moreover, improved quickly
after the offending smoke was eliminated, said the scientists.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits gained by eliminating most of the second-hand smoke
to which the bartenders were exposed ``was somewhere in the range
of what you would see with someone stopping smoking,'' said Dr.
Mark D. Eisner, a pulmonary specialist at the University of
California in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   He was the lead author on the report appearing in the current
issue of the Journal of the Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, where smoking in restaurants was banned effective
last Oct. 1 but remains legal in bars and taverns, the new findings
``could have significant impact in propelling this issue forward,''
commented Michael Siegel, an assistant professor in the Boston
University School of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel previously published research showing that levels of
second-hand smoke in bars were four to six times higher than in
offices where smoking was allowed. His research also revealed that
second-hand smoke increased the risk of lung cancer in restaurant
and bar workers.
</P>
<P>
   The new report from San Francisco, said Siegel in an interview,
``documents that not only is this second-hand smoke dangerous for
long-term health, it is causing suffering every day they (the bar
workers) go to work.''
</P>
<P>
   The research study took advantage of the sharp drop in exposure
to second-hand smoke in bars that occurred when the California ban
took effect last Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner and his colleagues asked the owners of 83 bars and
taverns in San Francisco for permission to test the bar workers:
ultimately, the owners of 25 bars complied.
</P>
<P>
   During December 1997, the researchers interviewed 53 bartenders
about respiratory symptoms and performed a test of lung capacity
called spirometer. Forty-five percent of the bartenders said they
themselves smoked.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists found that 39 of the bartenders, or 74 percent,
had respiratory symptoms such as difficulty breathing, wheezing,
cough, or production of phlegm, and 77 percent said they
experienced irritation of the eyes, nose or throat.
</P>
<P>
   On repeat testing about eight weeks later, only 17, or 32
percent, of the bartenders still had respiratory symptoms. Of the
39 who had complained of symptoms, 23 subsequently said they were
free of symptoms. And most of those who had reported eye, nose or
throat irritation said they now were free of those problems.
</P>
<P>
   There was also a small but significant improvement on the lung
function tests, Eisner and his colleagues reported. Though not a
dramatic difference, it was probably enough to be noticeable to the
bar workers, though they were not asked about it, Eisner said.
Researchers say they statistically controlled for personal smoking
so that it didn't influence the findings.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gail Wienmann, a medical officer at the National Heart, Lung
and Blood Institute, which funded the study, said that the
before-and-after difference in the lung function test results ``is
pretty significant, considering that these were normal''
volunteers. ``If it occurred in someone with low lung function, it
could be the difference between feeling well and not feeling
well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-98 1935EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981208.0278 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9292 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOMESTIC-PARTNERS-HNS     12-08 0406
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOMESTIC-PARTNERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL WOULD PROVIDE INSURANCE FOR UNMARRIED PARTNERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL DOUGAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A California lawmaker has reintroduced a bill
that would require health insurers and health maintenance
organizations to offer businesses the option of covering unmarried
partners of employees.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation was approved by the Legislature but vetoed by
Republican Gov. Pete Wilson, who leaves office at the end of the
year. The sponsor of the bill, Assemblywoman Carol Migden, D-San
Francisco, hopes the incoming governor, Democrat Gray Davis, will
support the bill.
</P>
<P>
   If passed and signed by the governor, it could be the first bill
in the nation to mandate that health coverage for unmarried
partners be made available by insurers. A similar measure is before
the Hawaii Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   The bill does not require companies to offer the coverage to
their employees, but would guarantee that it would be available if
they make that choice.
</P>
<P>
   Migden reintroduced the legislation Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``She thinks she's got a shot to make this become law,'' said
Alan LoFaso, a spokesman for Migden.
</P>
<P>
   LoFaso said some big health plans _ including Kaiser Permanente,
Blue Cross, Blue Shield, Health Net and PacifiCare _ already
offered such health plans.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance industry does not oppose Migden's bill, said
Maureen O'Haren of the California Association of Health Plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry has been neutral on this as a concept and plans
to (be) neutral on the bill this year, if not supportive of it,''
she said. O'Haren said industry representatives had worked with
Migden to ensure that the language of her bill is legally and
technically correct.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to make it work,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   LoFaso said the bill, while applying to companies of all sizes,
would have its greatest impact on small businesses that have been
unable to provide health benefits to their unmarried partners of
their employees.
</P>
<P>
   He said large companies had always been able to provide those
benefits if they wished because ``they have negotiating leverage or
they self-insure. They can pretty much tailor-make their insurance
packages.''
</P>
<P>
   In his veto message, Wilson said the bill would ``increase the
cost of insurance because premium rates for dependent coverage are
based on stable family relationships.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
