<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-MOOD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARING DRAWS THOSE WITH A SENSE OF HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Texas)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As gray skies and a gray mood soaked the nation's
capital Tuesday, Jayson Winn, a student at George Washington
University, had to decide whether to study history or watch it
unfold.
</P>
<P>
   It was nearly the end of his first semester at college. The exam
for History 72, American History 1866 to the Present, loomed. So
Winn did what Madison and Jefferson and maybe even his college
professors would understand: He went to see the first impeachment
hearings in his lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were to sit at home and not watch this in person, I'd be
denying myself an opportunity,'' said Winn, 19, who joined a small
line of history buffs and accidental tourists waiting for a seat in
the Judiciary Committee hearing room.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the gray suits, Winn was the only one with a toothpick in
his mouth, a baseball cap on his head, a Dr Pepper in his hand, and
a flannel shirt completely unbuttoned to reveal a rumpled T-shirt.
But then again, he was probably the only one with a copy of ``The
US Constitution and Fascinating Facts About It'' and a paperback
edition of ``The Federalist Papers.'' (``I read it for fun,'' he
said.)
</P>
<P>
   As the president's witnesses made their rebuttals Tuesday,
Washington didn't come to a standstill _ that tends to happen
mostly when police halt traffic for a presidential motorcade. But
many in the city did pause for updates from the water cooler of the
'90s: the Internet. In the warrens of Capitol Hill, aides immersed
in transportation, health care and other non-Judiciary, non-Monica
issues gave at least a glance to the television sets tuned to
gavel-to-gavel coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The need to know at least something was infectious. Down the
hill, parking lot attendant Solomon Assefa listened to the
testimony on C-Span radio in the booth where he escaped the rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``These Republicans in Congress are crazy,'' said Assefa, an
immigrant from Ethiopia who has followed news of the Monica S.
Lewinsky affair for nearly 11 months. ``If the president does
something in private, that's his business.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman Gold and Joan Sterling, visitors from New York, had a
sheaf of color maps of the Capitol they had printed from a web site
(www:senate.gov). They had taken the ``virtual tour'' on a computer
back home, but their real tour happened to coincide with the
hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Gold thought Clinton was getting his comeuppance after
``demonizing'' his critics, but Sterling sympathized with the
president. ``I admit that what Clinton did was wrong, but I don't
think it's an impeachable offense,'' she said. ``He didn't kill
anybody. He didn't rape that girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Old friends found themselves divided over impeachment. Mary Beth
Totten, a visitor from Chicago, didn't vote for Clinton but thought
Congress was letting the hearings drag on. But a family friend,
Dennis Lenard, a congressional staff member who was guiding her
through the Capitol, said, ``I think that Clinton's honesty, or
dishonesty, discredits the United States in foreign affairs.''
Lenard was a Marine lance corporal who served in the Persian Gulf
War.
</P>
<P>
   Before the proceedings started, radio stations crackled with
arguments. C-Span took callers on pro- and anti-impeachment lines.
But outside Room 2141 in the Rayburn House Office Building, where
the hearings are being held, there were few spectators and even
fewer protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Capitol Police let in a half-dozen people every half hour or so,
as others left. Ken Nitschke, who works for the California state
government, happened to be calling on legislative aides and stopped
by. ``I think it's time to put an end to this _ it's gone on too
long,'' said Nitschke, who twice voted against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But Anthony G. Marasco, a Justice Department employee in the
middle of taking week-long seminar on Congress, was pleased by the
quality of the debate at the hearings. ``This shows that the system
works,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Winn, the college student and political aficionado, thought
Clinton deserved to be impeached. He predicted the House would vote
for impeachment but the Senate would balk at ousting the president.
</P>
<P>
   Winn got a seat shortly after 2 p.m., although the police
officer who ushered him into Room 2141 sternly told him to throw
away his soda. He figured he'd return Wednesday so that he could
report to his family and friends in Centerville, Texas (``halfway
between Dallas and Houston, population 812'').
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a misconception that no one cares about this,'' Winn
said. ``I'm going home at Christmas to talk about it, and I'm all
booked up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
