<HEADER>
A9302 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACKS-COLLEGE-GUIDE-     12-08 0461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKS-COLLEGE-GUIDE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGAZINE RATES TOP COLLEGES FOR BLACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Fla., Ga., Md., Mich., Ohio, Pa.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(rl) 
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new guide ranking the 50 top colleges and universities where
African Americans are most likely to succeed will be published next
month as a 10-page feature in the monthly business magazine, Black
Enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Joining a host of national magazines that publish annual college
guides, including Time, Newsweek and U.S. News and World Report,
Black Enterprise has ranked colleges based on responses from 1,077
African-American professionals in higher education at 987 colleges
and universities. They assessed things like academic strengths and
social environment. The study also factored in measurements like
graduation rates.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the list are nine historically black colleges and
universities, beginning with Spelman College in Atlanta, Morehouse
College in Atlanta and Florida A&AMP;M University in Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   After the top nine come Stanford University, Georgetown
University, Oberlin College and Swarthmore College.
</P>
<P>
   ``In making our rankings, we separated out the historically
black schools because they have the overwhelming advantage of
having the greatest number of black students,'' said Marjorie
Whigham-Desir, a senior editor who worked on the project. ``That
way, they became their own category, and so we wound up with what's
called a weighed model.''
</P>
<P>
   The list and rankings were developed by Thomas LaVeist, a
professor of health and public policy at Johns Hopkins University
and CEO of DayStar, the research company that conducted the study.
</P>
<P>
   The primary criterion, LaVeist said, was that the college or
university had to be an accredited four-year institution that has
an African-American enrollment of at least 1.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If an institution did not meet those criteria but was well-known
and would be of significant interest to black students, it was
added to the survey.
</P>
<P>
   The educational professionals graded the institutions on a scale
of 1 to 5 from strongly recommended to strongly not recommended.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred Edmond, executive editor of Black Enterprise magazine,
said he hoped that the rankings would stimulate the dialogue on how
to achieve greater diversity on college campuses.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if there were any surprises in the rankings, Ms.
Whigham-Desir laughed and said LaVeist was surprised. ``He went to
the University of Maryland's Eastern Shore campus, and then got his
master's and Ph.D. at the University of Michigan, and neither of
them showed up in the top 50.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
