<HEADER>
A9303 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CENSURE &LR;      12-08 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CENSURE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS TRY TO REVIVE CENSURE RESOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The push by some Democrats to pass a resolution
censuring President Clinton, which has seemed to founder in the
last few days, is being revived in what the White House views as a
last-ditch effort to stave off a vote for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders have said they are opposed to censure,
leading to speculation that a vote will not be allowed and thus
making the issue moot.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats said Tuesday that private negotiations are heating
up with key Republicans in an effort to gain permission to bring a
vote on the measure to the House floor after the expected vote on
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   If swing-vote House members know they could vote for censure,
they would be more likely to vote against impeachment, according to
Representative Rick Boucher, a Virginia Democrat involved in the
censure talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been no fizzling of the effort'' for censure,
Boucher said. ``We are working very heard, albeit somewhat quietly,
to achieve an opportunity for censure to be considered.'' Boucher,
a member of the House Judiciary Committee, expects the
Republican-controlled panel to oppose censure, but he said a House
vote might lead to approval of censure if the motion is allowed.
</P>
<P>
   The censure move, while still a longshot, picked up a little
steam Tuesday when Representative Amo Houghton, a New York
Republican, prepared to announce Wednesday that he would vote
against impeachment and favored censure. Another New York
Republican, Representative Peter King, has said 20 or more GOP
members oppose impeachment. Republican leaders have said that
number is inflated and there are enough votes to impeach Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   While the Constitution does not provide for censure of a
president, Congress often votes on statements that condemn or
censure a variety of actions. As House Judiciary Committee Chairman
Henry Hyde said this week, ``We can condemn a ham sandwich if we
want to.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hyde is among the strongest opponents of censure. ``I don't
think censure is an appropriate sanction,'' Hyde said. ``I don't
think Congress has the constitutional authority. In a government of
delegated powers, when it comes to disciplining the chief
executive, the Constitution has delegated impeachment, not
censure.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hyde gave some hope to Democrats when he said, ``I'm not
for it, but I'm not saying that I will go to the death to resist
it.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Judiciary Committee approves one or more articles of
impeachment, as expected, the best-case scenario for Democrats is
that both impeachment and censure would be considered on the House
floor. In that case, Democrats are expected to argue a bipartisan
censure would send a stronger signal than a vote for impeachment
mostly along party lines.
</P>
<P>
   But Republican leaders have said that censure is too weak,
noting that it can be reversed by a subsequent Congress, as
happened after President Andrew Jackson was censured by the Senate
in 1834.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders prefer that Clinton be impeached by the
House, even though they recognize that there is little chance that
he will be convicted in a Senate trial and ousted from office.
Impeachment, unlike censure, would be a permanent mark against
Clinton that could not be revised by a later Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats Tuesday continued their criticism of Republican
efforts to turn impeachment into a ``super censure,'' as it was
called by former New York Representative Elizabeth Holtzman, a
Democrat who testified Tuesday before the House Judiciary
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Representative William Delahunt, a Massachusetts Democrat who
has led the drive for censure, said through a spokesman Tuesday
that the first step will be to get the House to decide that a
censure motion would be germane. That will be decided by the GOP
leadership and the Rules Committee. The second step, spokesman
Steve Schwadron said, is to draft a censure motion that would be
accepted by some Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are proceeding aggressively on both fronts,'' Schwadron
said. But Schwadron said that Delahunt so far hasn't released a
draft of the censure motion and is still talking to colleagues
about it.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of how prospects for censure have waned,
Representative Christopher Shays, a Connecticut Republican, joined
with House Whip Thomas DeLay of Texas on Monday in signing a
statement opposing censure. DeLay is a chief advocate for
impeachment and thus a likely opponent of censure. But Shays had
been targeted by Democrats as a possible censure advocate because
he is one of the few Republicans on record saying he will vote
against impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The hope among Democrats and moderate Republicans who favor
censure is that the House will realize that the public opposes
impeachment and that there would be a public backlash for such a
vote. An ABC News poll conducted from Dec. 2 to 6 found that 64
percent of respondents opposed impeachment, while 59 percent
favored censure.
</P>
<P>
   White House communications director Ann Lewis said that
``clearly there is less talk'' about censure, but she didn't rule
out the possibility that such a motion might be approved. She said
Clinton has not publicly backed censure because Republicans might
resent any effort by the president to tell them how to act. But
Lewis said the White House has made clear that ``we are for a
solution that is prompt, constitutional and fair and acknowledges
that what he did was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, White House officials acknowledge they are surprised
that the impeachment effort has moved forward, saying that they may
have been too quick to assume that the November election results
and the ouster of House Speaker Newt Gingrich would end the
impeachment drive. White House officials said that they were
unprepared for the way DeLay has moved the power vacuum left by
Gingrich's departure and DeLay's effectiveness in urging
Republicans to back impeachment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
