<HEADER>
A9305 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PIZZA-ADS-COX     12-08 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIZZA-ADS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ad agency churns out Papa John's pizza ads despite lawsuit
 &HT;    By Mickey H. Gramig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Despite complaints, counterattacks and courtroom
drama, Atlanta's Fricks/Firestone continues to roll out new Papa
John's ads.
</P>
<P>
   The agency is about to release its latest TV commercials that
continue what's being called the ``Pizza War'' between powerhouse
Pizza Hut and Papa John's.
</P>
<P>
   Pizza Hut has been the $22 billion industry's No. 1 chain in
size, sales and market share since 1971, while 14-year-old Papa
John's, the fastest growing competitor, is giving its rivals a run
for their money.
</P>
<P>
   The feud is so intense, Pizza Hut has filed a federal lawsuit
against No. 4 Papa John's International, alleging the
Louisville-based chain's ``better ingredients, better pizza''
mantra and other marketing claims are deceptive.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas-based Pizza Hut is seeking an injunction to halt the
disputed marketing practices and $12.5 million in damages, along
with attorney fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Papa John's is totally off the mark when they say this is a PR
stunt. We consider it very serious,'' said Pizza Hut spokesman Jay
Allison. ``We've run some comparative advertising to set the record
straight.''
</P>
<P>
   John H. Schnatter, Papa John's founder and chief executive, has
called the lawsuit ``frivolous'' and commissioned full-page
newspaper ads likening the case to a David and Goliath battle.
</P>
<P>
   Pizza Hut, with 7,200 restaurants, spent $147 million on
advertising last year, compared with the $16.6 million ad budget
for Papa John's, according to Competitive Media Reporting. Yet Papa
John's, with 1,800 locations, nearly doubled its market share in
the last two years, while share grew only slightly for Domino's and
fell for Pizza Hut and Little Caesars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Papa John's is rattling a lot of cages,'' said Gerry Durnell,
publisher of Pizza Today, a trade magazine. ``They have an intense,
laser focus on quality, and they've never taken their eye off that
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Fricks/Firestone President John Fricks said the agency has
stressed that focus on quality since winning the Papa John's
account in spring 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until they came along, nobody talked about quality,'' he said,
pointing out how Pizza Hut's advertising focused on its variety and
trend-setting menu items. Ads for Dominos stressed dominance in
delivery, while Little Caesars positioned itself as the low-price
leader, Fricks said.
</P>
<P>
   Pizza Hut has been rocked by the Papa John's quality-centered
ads because ``the first to say something owns that truth,'' Fricks
said.
</P>
<P>
   Creative director Elliott Firestone cooked up the idea for the
first national Papa John's campaign _ the ads that touched off the
blood war when they first began airing in May 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign features Frank Carney, who co-founded Pizza Hut in
1958 and continued on as president and a board member after the
chain's 1977 purchase by Pepsico. Pizza Hut was a billion-dollar
company, with 4,000 restaurants worldwide, when Carney left in
1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found a better pizza,'' Carney, a Papa John's franchisee
since 1994, matter-of-factly explains in the ads. One of them
playfully depicts his portrait and bust being carted off from Pizza
Hut headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Carney is more than just a figurehead endorser for the chain. He
runs more than 70 Papa John's restaurants and has rights to develop
700 more in the U.S., Australia and the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   The commercials landed Papa John's on Advertising Age's list of
the top 100 marketing campaigns for 1997, alongside such
attention-getters as Beanie Babies, Starbucks coffee and Tickle Me
Elmo. They also led to Pizza Hut filing the first of two complaints
against Papa John's with the National Advertising Division of the
Council of Better Business Bureaus.
</P>
<P>
   The NAD ruled that it was accurate for Papa John's to advertise
that consumers significantly prefer its regular and thin crust
pizzas over comparable Pizza Hut products. It also ruled the
comparison of Papa John's fresh-packed tomato sauce to Pizza Hut's
remanufactured paste is meaningful and relevant to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Papa John's made two minor modifications to its ads after the
rulings, which are non-binding. But that wasn't enough to satisfy
Pizza Hut, which filed the federal lawsuit in August. The trial
date has been set for October 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Mickey H. Gramig writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
