<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-CLONES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE ACHIEVE MULTIPLE CLONING OF COW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Japanese scientists say they have created eight cloned calves
from cells of a single cow, and in doing so have significantly
improved the efficiency of the mammalian cloning technique that
produced the lamb Dolly.
</P>
<P>
   But four of the calves died soon after birth. The scientists
said they thought the deaths were unrelated to the cloning, but
couldn't rule out some undiscovered effect of the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   In a report scheduled for publication in the journal Science
Friday, the scientists from Kinki University in Japan said that
they made 141 embryos by combining adult cow cell nuclei with
recipient cow eggs. Of these embryos, 38 matured to a stage deemed
ready for transfer to surrogate cow mothers, and 10 were
transferred.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the team led by Ian Wilmut at the Roslin Institute
in Scotland reported in 1997 that Dolly was the only surviving
clone from 277 embryos that were created.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese report suggests that they have achieved greater
efficiency, but other scientists said the study was too small to be
a reliable indicator of future efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Wilmut, who Tuesday spoke on cloning at Harvard Medical School,
called the new report ``useful'' and a ``step toward'' greater
efficiency. In his talk, however, he stressed that scientists still
have far to go in understanding the abnormalities of some cloned
offspring and the generally low efficiency rate.
</P>
<P>
   The Science report was released Tuesday after a British
newspaper broke the embargo that had been set for Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese scientists used generally the same method pioneered
by Wilmut. Wilmut and his colleagues took specialized cells from
the udder of an adult ewe and transplanted their nuclei _ which
contain the genetic material _ into a sheep egg from which the
nucleus had been removed. The genetic instructions in the adult
mammary cell underwent a ``reprogramming'' that returned them to an
embryonic stage, able to direct the development of an entire
individual.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese researchers, led by Yoko Kato, did not use mammary
cells. Instead, they obtained cow ovaries and oviducts from a
slaughter house and isolated two types of cells: cumulus cells,
which surround the egg made by the ovary, and epithelial cells that
line the oviduct, through which the egg passes to the uterus.
</P>
<P>
   They transplanted 37 nuclei from cumulus cells and 88 nuclei
from the oviduct cells into cow eggs whose own genetic material had
been eliminated, and bathed them in laboratory culture fluid for 8
to 9 days. About half the embryos made with cumulus cells began
developing normally, as did about one-fourth of the embryos created
using oviduct cells.
</P>
<P>
   Next, the scientists took 10 of the thriving embryos, which had
reached the so-called blastocyst stage consisting of a microscopic
ball of cells, and transferred them to the wombs of surrogate
mother cows.
</P>
<P>
   Eight of those pregnancies led to live births.
</P>
<P>
   James Robl, a cloning researcher at the University of
Massachusetts at Amherst, noted that the Japanese emphasis on using
adult cells is aimed at eventually making genetic copies of elite
animals for agricultural use.
</P>
<P>
   Many US researchers, by contrast, are more interested in using
cloned animals as a source of tissue for medical transplants. For
those uses, cloning fetal rather than adult cells is more
appropriate, said Robl.
</P>
<P>
   The UMass scientist said that the main significance of the
Japanese report is that ``with more groups having success with
(cloning), it means this technology is real and is here to stay.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
