<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-LAYOFFS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAYTHEON CHIEF SEES LAYOFFS HALTING AT ANNOUNCED LEVEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raytheon Co.'s new top executive said he doesn't expect major
layoffs beyond an ongoing reduction of 14,000 jobs announced in
October.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Burnham, who became chief executive of the Lexington,
Mass. defense contractor on Dec. 1, said in an interview this week
that the company intends to avoid further job cuts by becoming more
efficient and winning more military contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope and believe it's the last one like this,'' Burnham
said, referring to the current round of layoffs. Two months ago,
Raytheon said it will eliminate 14,000 jobs by the end of 1999 _ up
from its forecast last January that it would cut 8,700 positions. A
total of about 115,000 jobs will remain after the cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Employees likely to lose their jobs _ including 1,200 in
Massachusetts _ were all notified last month so as to minimize
uncertainty through the holiday season, Burnham said. ``By
mid-November, everybody knew their situation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts come as part of a restructuring meant to improve
productivity and to reduce Raytheon's debt, which now stands at
around $10 billion. Most of the debt was taken on as part of
Raytheon's acquisition streak last year, when it paid $12.5 billion
for the defense operations of Texas Instruments Inc. and Hughes
Electronics Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Former Raytheon chief executive Dennis Picard was the architect
of the expansion, part of a broader consolidation in the defense
industry. Picard stepped down as chief executive Dec. 1, and plans
to turn over the chairman's role to Burnham sometime next year.
Burnham, previously vice chairman at AlliedSignal Inc., joined
Raytheon July 1 as president and chief operating officer and was
charged with integrating Raytheon's disparate new units.
</P>
<P>
   To help do so, Burnham said he plans in January to introduce a
quality control program that will provide about 40 hours of
training to every employee.
</P>
<P>
   Modeled on similar efforts at AlliedSignal, the program will be
known as Raytheon Six Sigma after the Greek letter used by
statisticians to denote deviations from the norm. (Six-sigma would
indicate fewer than four defects per million units). Burnham said
he wants to reduce manufacturing costs, impose more statistical
controls on operations and improve employee satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is improved productivity and higher profits. ``The most
productive company at the end of the day wins,'' Burnham said. The
program also fits employees' sentiments, he said. In a Dec. 1
letter to employees he wrote that ``You . . . want greater
delegation of authority, less bureaucracy, less disruption, and
more investment in training and development. I agree.''
</P>
<P>
   By making these improvements, Burnham said, the company will be
on track to grow revenue between 6 percent to 8 percent annually
over three years, and to improve earnings between 10 percent to 12
percent over the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham cautioned those goals also depend on overall defense
spending by the federal government. But analysts think Raytheon is
on track to meet projections. S.G. Cowen &AMP; Co. analyst Cai Von
Rumohr has rated the company's stock a ``strong buy'' since Burnham
was named over the summer, citing his expectations of cost cuts
from the merged defense businesses.
</P>
<P>
   For 1998, 13 analysts surveyed by Nelson's Investment Research
expected Raytheon to earn an average of $3.31 a Class B share. They
expected an increase to $3.77 a share for 1999. In 1997, earnings
were $2.20 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon's Class B shares closed at 56 1/8, up 7/8. Class A
shares rose 13/16 to 55 7/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
