<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9336 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RIGHTS-POLICY-BOS &LR;      12-08 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIGHTS-POLICY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
50 YEARS AFTER HISTORIC DOCUMENT, US STILL SEEKS RIGHTS BALANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i, w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the eve of the 50th anniversary of the Universal
Declaration of Human Rights, the United States stands as both
guarantor and violator of the lofty ideals embodied in a document
that has inspired generations and created a new body of
international law.
</P>
<P>
   Born after the barbarities of World War II, the UN General
Assembly's declaration of civil, social, political and economic
rights for all people was a feel-good measure, glorified but
largely set aside by the perceived imperatives of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until Jimmy Carter's presidency that the goal of
extending human rights became an explicit objective of US foreign
policy. In the intervening two decades, US policy has swung like a
pendulum between viewing the extension of human rights as an end in
itself, and the use of human rights as a useful tool to further US
strategic interests.
</P>
<P>
   Although the struggle to balance a commitment to democratic
ideals with the pragmatism required by superpower status continues,
political observers say human rights have evolved under the Clinton
administration, assuming a more secure and permanent place in
foreign policy. At the same time, however, they say policy is still
fragmented.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights advocates are less generous, calling President
Clinton approach ``incoherent'' and ``hollow.'' They say he has
squandered his post-Cold War opportunity to lead on the issue,
hobbled at every turn by excessive concern for national security
and trade issues.
</P>
<P>
   And while human rights advocates concede they have greater
access and a stronger presence than ever before in the
administration, they say they don't have influence.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, they say, has continued the Cold War
practice of turning a blind eye to human rights violators that are
allies, such as Turkey and Indonesia, while being quick to condemn
violators like Cuba, Burma and Sudan, which are not. Clinton also
failed to respond quickly to genocide in Rwanda, continued human
rights abuses in China and ethnic cleansing in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   But his worst offense, they say, is his refusal to join the
international community in supporting the major human rights
initiatives of the decade: a ban on anti-personnel land mines and
the establishment of a permanent international criminal court.
Washington also is bucking the move to raise the minimum age of
child soldiers from 15 to 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still see that human rights are subjected to other
considerations,'' said Reed Brody, advocacy director for Human
Rights Watch. ``Of course, they always will be, but they don't have
to have second tier status as they do today.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials maintain that the issue of human rights
plays a major role in national security thinking, which in itself
is a sign of progress _ even if trade and security concerns
sometimes win out.
</P>
<P>
   To back this up, they cite from decisions to intervene in
Somalia and Haiti, to support for war crime tribunals after the
Rwandan genocide and the civil war in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, they say, is that the administration has
reinvented a foreign policy practice that marries the global
pursuit of human rights with US political self-interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We increasingly appreciate that a world with governments that
respect their people is a world that is more congenial to American
interests,'' noted Eric Schwartz, senior director of the National
Security Council's multilateral and human rights affairs division.
``It's not an either/or. Promoting human rights not only reflects
our values, but it's smart as well.''
</P>
<P>
   But while human rights lobbyists believe Clinton has not been
responsive enough to their demands, the business community has the
opposite complaint: that US policy is in the thrall of ``human
rights extremists who have tried to use trade as an enforcement
mechanism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The US government has become sanctions-happy in the past six
years,'' said Willard W. Workman, vice president of international
affairs for the US Chamber of Commerce. ``The most fundamental
right is food and shelter and the best way to secure it is through
trade and exports.''
</P>
<P>
   In Carter's day, simply talking about human rights was novel,
according to David A. Martin, profesor of law at the University of
Virginia who worked in the State Department's first human rights
bureau established by Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Although there was continuous battle between the rest of the
State Department and the bureau, its creation was Carter's greatest
lasting contributions to the movement, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's outspoken stance on human rights abuses in places like
Chile and Argentina also saved lives, according to Eric Stover,
director of the Human Rights Center at the University of California
at Berkeley, even if his policies were sometimes inconsistent.
</P>
<P>
   When President Reagan took office, his administration
immediately repudiated Carter's efforts and ``all-out war'' broke
out between the human rights community and the administration,
remembers Holly Birkhalter, advocacy director for the Boston-based
group Physicians for Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan, however, came to see that having a human rights agenda
helped him stake out the moral high ground during the Cold
War.However, he also equated human rights and democracy with
voting, regardless of whether basic rights such as free speech were
guaranteed, said Kenneth Roth, executive director of Human Rights
Watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``This allowed him to massively fund the Salvadoran government
and the Contras in Central America even though they were
systematically committing the most severe abuses,'' said Roth.
``But it also showed that even Reagan couldn't be oblivious to
human rights pressures, that he had to distort the facts to
maintain the facade.''
</P>
<P>
   Reagan's emphasis on electoralism, however, also translated into
forceful action against corrupt dictators in Haiti and the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   Once George Bush came to office and the Berlin Wall fell,
however, human rights lost their ideological punch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush didn't do much,'' said Henry Teune, professor of
political science at the University of Pennsylvania. ``He wanted to
create an architecture of international cooperation, but human
rights was never a big part of his message.''
</P>
<P>
   It may not have been a priority, but human rights were used in
US efforts to marshal support for the Persian Gulf War, the
no-flight zone to protect Iraqi Kurds, and a series of innovative
international humanitarian missions.
</P>
<P>
   It is obvious that Clinton has borrowed from all three of his
predecessors: Carter's idealism, Reagan's electoralism, and Bush's
pragmatism. But as the anniversary of the Universal Declaration of
Human Rights approaches, the president's legacy appears anything
but clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton has undertaken some the best initiatives ever _ and
also some of the worst,'' said Burkhalter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
