<DOCNO> NYT19981208.0304 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9341 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-BOS &LR;      12-08 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE FAVORING EQUITY INVESTMENT TO AID SOCIAL SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A White House official says the Clinton
administration is ``looking favorably'' on plans to use the stock
market to raise money for the financially ailing Social Security
program, an idea that could mark a significant change in philosophy
for the national retirement system.
</P>
<P>
   The development came as President Clinton, speaking while a
congressional committee debated his possible impeachment, appealed
for lawmakers to set aside all bipartisanship and come to agreement
on a financial fix for Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's agree we have to march together. That's the only path to
the finish line. Our ears, our minds must remain open to any good
idea and to any person of good will,'' Clinton said in opening a
two-day White House conference that aims to prod lawmakers into
settling on a plan to shore up Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's speech came at an odd moment, timed just as the House
Judiciary Committee was convening for a final week of hearings
before its vote on whether to refer impeachment charges to the full
House.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts say Clinton could create a lasting legacy for
himself if he guides Congress to a long-term solution for Social
Security's problems. But a House decision to send impeachment
charges to the Senate might consume the attention and good will
that is needed to reach agreement on a program as politically
sensitive as Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security will hit financial problems in about three
decades, when too few workers will be paying taxes to cover the
benefits for millions of baby boom retirees. By about 2032, the
system will raise enough tax money each year to cover only about 72
percent of promised benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, there are only three ways to fix the problem: cut
benefits, raise taxes, or try to increase the reserves that the
system already has by investing them in the stock market or in
corporate bonds.
</P>
<P>
   As they have for the past year, Clinton's staff said Tuesday the
White House is open to nearly all proposals. But at the same time,
Gene Sperling, a senior economic aide, said the idea of stock
investing, or seeking ``higher returns,'' has gained momentum in
White House deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is no question that we are looking favorably on
options that would in some way seek to bring in higher returns,''
Sperling said. ``But I would also say that the president has not
made any final decision or locked into any proposal. But certainly
we _ as are most people in the debate _ are looking at a prudent
way there could be higher returns.''
</P>
<P>
   Sperling's comments left the White House wide latitude, as stock
investing can be made part of the Social Security system in many
ways.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans favor the idea of allowing workers to pay some
of the 12.4 percent Social Security tax into privately owned stock
and bond accounts, rather than to the government. That would turn
Social Security into something like a giant 401(k) plan, the
tax-deferred savings program that is already available to about
half of US workers through their employers.
</P>
<P>
   But under an alternative plan, Social Security's own managers
could invest some of the system's current surplus in stocks and
corporate bonds, rather than in the Treasury bonds they now buy,
which yield about 6 percent interest. Instead of individual
accounts, Social Security as a whole would benefit if stocks rose
in value, and all workers and retirees would share the risk if they
fell in value.
</P>
<P>
   That alternative might win support from the 32 million-member
American Association of Retired Persons and from Democratic allies
like the AFL-CIO. The labor union opposes individual accounts,
saying Social Security should be an insurance program in which
workers help each other through disability and old age, not an
investment plan in which workers gain or lose according to their
own stock-picking skills.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, one person following the White House discussions
said Clinton about six weeks ago was rumored to be favoring a plan
by economist Martin Feldstein to shore up Social Security.
Feldstein, a Harvard professor and former chief economist to
President Reagan, has proposed requiring workers to invest 2
percent of earnings _ above the current Social Security payroll tax
_ in private accounts, with the cost of those contributions
essentially offset by the federal budget surplus through tax
credits.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a rumor that this was an idea that had taken on some
luster'' at the White House, the source said, and so Democratic
lawmakers and the AFL-CIO lobbied Clinton's staff to back away from
the Feldstein plan.
</P>
<P>
   The White House invited about 250 lawmakers, policy analysts,
and interest group members to Tuesday's conference, where they
heard from several panels on Social Security reform. The event
continues Wednesday, with Clinton scheduled to meet behind closed
doors with lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   One prominent Republican, Representative Bill Archer, chairman
of the powerful House Ways and Means Committee, Tuesday said the
process was doomed to failure. He said lawmakers would not come to
agreement unless Clinton laid down a specific plan first.
</P>
<P>
   Archer said Clinton has refused to send a plan to Congress
because a similar strategy failed in 1994, when Clinton tried to
overhaul the US health care system. In addition, Archer said, the
White House fears that offering a specific plan might hurt Vice
President Al Gore's chances to become president in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's decision not to submit his own Social Security
plan ``is devoid of leadership,'' Archer said. ``They're saying,
`We don't want to be criticized.' Well, if you're a leader, you
have to be prepared to be criticized.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Rick Santorum, Republican of Pennsylvania, spoke to the
conference in favor of private accounts, saying they were the only
way to avoid relying on tax increases or benefit cuts to shore up
Social Security. But House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt
denounced the idea as more radical than needed to fix the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daring and innovative ideas are always attractive and
interesting, but we must remember that we aren't looking for reform
for its own sake,'' Gephardt said.
</P>
<P>
   John Rother, director of public policy for the AARP, said he
would not be surprised if Clinton turned to the stock market as
part of his solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at what Bill Clinton historically has done in
these issues, it's taking conservative mechanisms and using them to
achieve liberal ends,'' Rother said. One previous example, he said,
was Clinton's attempt in 1994 to create a system of ``managed
competition'' among health insurers to bring health insurance to
all Americans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-98 2003EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
