A9347 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-SUPREMECOURT-COX     12-08 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-SUPREMECOURT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida politicians work together, create history for state
Supreme Court
 &HT;    By Shirish Date
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE _ A constitutional showdown over the makeup of the
state Supreme Court was averted Tuesday, as Florida's departing
governor and arriving governor instead made history by jointly
appointing the first black woman to that post.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Ann Quince, a native of Norfolk, Va., will move from her
seat on the Second District Court of Appeal in Tampa to replace
retiring justice Ben Overton next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am proud and humbled,'' said Quince, one of six children
reared on by a longshoreman father on his own. ``I will work hard
and I will do an excellent job on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Lawton Chiles and Gov.-elect Jeb Bush both claimed the
right to name the replacement for Overton, who is scheduled to
retire the same day Bush will take office. In the end, both men
interviewed all four nominees for the job and, on Monday, quickly
agreed to pick Quince.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider it mine, he considers it his, we consider it
ours,'' Chiles quipped of the appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Left unsettled was the question of which governor has the legal
authority to appoint a justice in such circumstances, said Roberto
Martinez, the general counsel for Bush's transition team.
</P>
<P>
   Quince, 50, joins Barbara Pariente as the second woman on the
seven-member panel, and Leander Shaw as the second black justice.
She called her appointment ``a marvelous opportunity for all of the
citizens of the state of Florida to really see that you can work
hard and . . . that it really will pay off.''
</P>
<P>
   She graduated from Howard University in 1970 and earned her law
degree from the Catholic University of America in 1975. Five years
later she was interviewing with the Attorney General's Office in
Florida, a job she held for the next 13 years under Jim Smith and
Bob Butterworth. She argued death penalty cases for the state and
then ran the 25-lawyer appellate office in Tampa before being named
to the state appellate bench there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so pleased I could jump out of my skin,'' said Pete
Antonacci, who as Butterworth's deputy was Quince's boss until he
left the office last year. ``Florida wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Quince's appointment came the day after Chiles replaced retiring
justice Gerald Kogan with Miami trial lawyer R. Fred Lewis. All
Supreme Court justices, who now earn $141,000 a year, must come
from certain geographical regions, and Overton's replacement had to
come from a 14-county area of Collier County to Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Chiles picked Quince over two other Tampa judges and a
Clearwater judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``One stood out above all others,'' Bush said of Quince.
``She'll make an outstanding justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Quince, accompanied at the announcement by her lawyer husband
and one of her two daughters, said she was pleased that two
governors agreed to name her and that she would try to honor her
father's advice: ``He told me two things that I have always tried
to live by, and that is to get an education and to work as hard you
can.''
</P>
<P>
   Shirish Date writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
