<SLUG> BC-MALDEN-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALDEN MILLS FIRE SUIT TARGETS   MAKER OF NYLON FIBER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A lawsuit seeking damages on behalf of employees injured in the
Dec. 11, 1995, fire at Malden Mills in Lawrence, Mass. was filed
Tuesday against the manufacturer of nylon fiber used in the
building where the devastating fire apparently began.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was filed in by lawyer Robert C. Autieri, who earlier
told a local newspaper he represented eight of 13 workers who
planned to sue E.I. du Pont de Nemours &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   A Malden Mills spokesman said du Pont, based in Wilmington,
Del., was one of two suppliers of nylon used in the textile mill's
flock upholstery division, where the fire began.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for du Pont said that ``there is no evidence that
any du Pont product caused the fire, and no one has been able to
definitively identify its cause.''
</P>
<P>
   The fire destroyed three buildings and caused dozens of injuries
and monetary loss of nearly $500 million, capturing worldwide
attention as Malden Mills owner Aaron M. Feuerstein, then 70,
continued to pay 3,100 idled employees for months afterward until
most of the lost facilities could be rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
   Malden Mills spokesman Jeffery Bowman, said the company did not
expect to be cited in the personal injury lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Autieri did not return phone calls Tuesday, but, in a story
published Sunday in the Lawrence newspaper, told of his intentions
and predicted litigation could last for years.
</P>
<P>
   Feuerstein won national acclaim and a presidential citation as
he continued to pay employees and, before insurance claims could be
settled, dipped into his own wealth to begin designing and
rebuilding.
</P>
<P>
   The reconstruction was largely completed by late summer 1997 and
all but a handful of workers were back on the job by Labor Day that
year. However, citing weak sales, Malden Mills this year shut down
its auto upholstery division, eliminating 300 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   More than 22 months after the blaze, investigators for the
Massachusetts fire marshal concluded it was ``most probably''
caused when tiny, airborne nylon fibers caught fire in the section
where nylon was used to make upholstery fabric.
</P>
<P>
   They suggested an electrical spark set off a dust explosion that
swept across two production lines. That fire quickly died out, but
not before setting a smaller fire which, fanned by winds, destroyed
the complex.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said when the report was released they had uncovered
no one piece of ``absolute'' evidence.
</P>
<P>
   But they did determine that nylon dust, previously thought to
have too high an ignition point to cause a flash fire, in fact can
burn under certain circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   The US Occupational Health and Safety Administration reached a
similar conclusion and issued a warning to other mills where a
similar risk might exist. OSHA said, however, because of the prior
doubt about flammability, Malden Mills was not to blame for the
fire and had committed no safety violations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-98 2009EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
