<HEADLINE>
ECKERSLEY FACES CAREER DECISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Dennis Eckersley, cut loose by the Red Sox Monday, will
decide by next week whether he intends to continue his playing
career, his attorney said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Eckersley, 44, had said last month that he was leaning strongly
toward coming back in 1999, but only with the Red Sox and only if
he felt his right shoulder was healthy again; Eckersley spent seven
weeks on the disabled list last summer.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, the deadline for teams to offer their free agents
salary arbitration or lose the right to re-sign them until May 1,
Eckersley met with Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette in the
Boston offices of the player's attorney, Jack Sands. Duquette
informed Eckersley that the club had decided not to bring him back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan was very forward, very straight up,'' Sands said Tuesday.
``Dan said the team was looking at people for Dennis's position
that could help the club for more than one year, so they were going
to explore other alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Dennis's age, what have you, he wasn't surprised, but he
was slightly disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Eckersley has expressed an interest in broadcasting, and this
fall did some work on ESPN during the World Series. If he elects to
retire _ a strong possibility _ he would probably have interest in
talking to the Sox about a broadcasting role, but will most likely
have to wait until the team's TV affiliation is determined.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reach Eckersley were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   The righthander had signed with the Red Sox last winter because
he wanted to end his career in the city where he made his home.
Originally slated to be a ``co-closer'' with Tom Gordon, Eckersley
quickly fell out of that role after a rough spring training, and
did not pitch well in the first weeks of the season.
</P>
<P>
   He was placed on the disabled list June 4 with a strained
posterior rotator cuff in his right shoulder, and did not return
until July 24. Reduced for the most part to pitching in mop-up
situations or to just a batter or two, Eckersley ran off 17
straight scoreless appearances between Aug. 13 and Sept. 17, and on
Sept. 26 in Fenway Park against the Orioles he broke Hoyt Wilhelm's
major league record by making his 1,071st career appearance.
</P>
<P>
   But in his last three appearances in Fenway Park, Eckersley gave
up home runs, including a blast to Manny Ramirez in Game 3 of the
Division Series that proved to be decisive in a 5-4 loss to the
Indians. His regular-season ERA in Fenway Park was 7.48.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Eckersley was 4-1 with 1 save and a 4.76 ERA, a
dramatic comedown for a future Hall of Famer who has 390 career
saves, second all-time to Lee Smith (478), and 197 career wins.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that he might be at the end, Eckersley said
last month he still had the desire to compete. If he does, it won't
be with the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to sit back and evaluate his options,'' Sands said.
``By next week, he'll make a decision what his plan is for the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other issues facing Duquette this winter is the need to
replenish the bullpen. He's set at closer with Gordon, and has two
above-average setup men in Jim Corsi and Derek Lowe. But the Sox
have only one experienced lefty, Ron Mahay, after Greg Swindell
signed as a free agent with Arizona. Also, Rich Garces (``El
Guapo'') was released, and Dario Veras was claimed on waivers.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette also is in the market for starting help, especially a
lefthander, after the team cut ties with three lefties Monday _free
agents Steve Avery, Butch Henry, and Pete Schourek, none of whom
were offered arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   The baseball winter meetings begin Friday in Nashville, where
Duquette's top priority will be to find a slugger to compensate for
the loss of Mo Vaughn. But there were strong indications Tuesday
that the market may be a tight one. White Sox GM Ron Schueler has
told confidants that Frank Thomas won't be available, and Marlins
GM Dave Dombrowski, Expos GM Jim Beattie, and Dodgers GM Kevin
Malone are disinclined to trade Cliff Floyd, Rondell White, and
Raul Mondesi, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   There is talk that the Braves, who signed free agent outfielder
Brian Jordan, might be willing to move outfielder/first baseman
Ryan Klesko, but in any major deal the Sox make, they almost
certainly will be asked to surrender Lowe, whom the Sox project as
having a big future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
