<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA CANCELS ALL-STAR GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With dwindling hope of seeing any games soon, the NBA Tuesday
canceled the one singular attraction in its schedule that has
absolutely nothing to do with basketball: the All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner David Stern officially deep-sixed the Feb. 14
marketing vehicle scheduled for Philadelphia, blaming it on nothing
more than the ``inexorable march of the calendar.'' In other words,
the no-end-in-sight lockout made it impossible for Stern to assure
what he called his ``business partners'' that they could raise
their corporate banners during the Valentine's Day Weekend while
toasting the Gimmick Games on Saturday and the hideous contest
itself on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Stern did say, however, that Philly will get first dibs on the
2002 game; the next two already have been earmarked for Oakland and
Washington. That's assuming there are seasons. This marks the first
time since 1951 that there will be no All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with reporters, the commissioner and
aide-de-camp Russ Granik sounded more resigned than ever to losing
the entire season, although neither would offer a drop-dead date.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're dealing with the ramifications of losing the first part
of our season,'' the commissioner said. ``We understand fan
reaction, sponsor reaction, network reaction, and licensee
reaction. It has been overwhelmingly negative and it will be
geometrically worse if the season goes.''
</P>
<P>
   The All-Star Game is the latest casualty of the lockout, now
into its sixth month with nothing promising on the horizon. There
are no negotiation sessions scheduled with the players, whose
latest response to the lockout has been to schedule an exhibition
game in Atlantic City Dec. 19 for their down-on-their-luck
brethren. The sides are far apart on the apparently irresolvable
issue of how to split approximately $2 billion in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Stern did say that he did not think the season could start by
mid-January even with an imminent settlement, given all the issues
still unresolved and the need for training camps. He said that he
didn't feel the league would start a season in February and Granik
indicated that there was perhaps 10 days of wiggle room in June to
extend the Finals. He said extending the season into July was ``not
a realistic possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern said, ``Our focus now will be to see if there is a season
to salvage without an All-Star Game. Our goals remain the same: to
sit down and try and negotiate a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The freeing up of four days in February, however, does not help
the league in rescheduling games. Granik said every NBA arena with
the exception of the one in Philadelphia is booked on Saturday
night, the 13th.
</P>
<P>
   Should a season be saved, Stern said, it is probably inevitable
that teams would play games on three consecutive nights, a no-no
for years. Granik said there would likely be an unbalanced schedule
and added, ``Not every team is going to see every other team at
home. That's impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern again rejected mediation as an option, saying there has
been plenty of dialogue, if not agreement. Asked why the league
simply didn't declare an impasse, end the lockout, and impose its
own working conditions, Stern said there were two problems with
that. The first is that returning players could strike at any time.
The second is that they could take legal action, as was the case in
baseball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
