<HEADER>
A9366 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-MODERATES-BOS     12-08 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-MODERATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODERATE VOICES TO SPEAK FOR CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former Massachusetts Governor William F. Weld, who
once described his role during the Watergate hearings as a ``swing
man,'' will perform a similiar task Wednesday as a witness for
President Clinton before the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Weld, who was an associate minority counsel for the Judiciary
Committee in 1974, returns as somewhat of a mystery witness: His
name was excluded from the original list of 14 people tapped by the
White House to testify while a conflict with his schedule was
worked out. Weld's participation was confirmed Tuesday by the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican who headed the Justice Department's criminal
division under President Reagan, Weld is the prototype of the GOP
moderate considered vital to Clinton's efforts to avoid being
impeached. In an interview in 1978 about his Watergate involvement,
he said: ``I was a swing man. The Republican who got along best
with the Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Weld is being summoned to appeal to those 20 to 30 undecided
House Republicans the White House is targeting in its defense
presentation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people have tried to make this a party line. He speaks up
as a Republican and says there are other issues of consideration,''
said White House communications director Ann Lewis. ``He is an
example of a Republican getting elected governor in Massachusetts
and being held up as a real example by members of his party, as a
success story, and he can talk about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Weld may find some common ground with the clutch of undecided
Republican moderates whose votes may largely decide whether Clinton
is impeached.
</P>
<P>
   Like Weld, many of them hail from northeastern states, primarily
New York, New Jersey and Connecticut. The New York group is
especially large, including Representatives John McHugh, Rick A.
Lazio, Michael P. Forbes, Benjamin Gilman, and Sherwood Boehlert.
</P>
<P>
   But some undecides also hail from California, Ohio, Michigan and
Iowa. They include Representatives Brian P. Bilbray of California
and Jim Leach of Iowa, chairman of the House Banking Committee,
both of whom represent districts that voted for Clinton in 1992 and
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Bilbray barely survived a stiff challenge, 49 percent to 46.4
percent, in last month's election from his Democratic challenger,
San Diego City Council member Christine Kehoe.
</P>
<P>
   Though several GOP moderates represent districts that twice
voted for Clinton, not all of them do. Boehlert's mostly rural
district in upstate New York, for example, went for President
George Bush in 1992 and Clinton in 1996. And the congressman
coasted to victory last month with about 80 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Several undecided House members said through their aides Tuesday
that they were reserving judgment until the Judiciary Committee
finishes its job, while others were not tipping their hand until
the matter goes to the full House.
</P>
<P>
   ``She really is keeping her own counsel on this thing,'' said
Mary Anne Leary, a spokeswoman for Representative Constance A.
Morella of Maryland. ``She wants to have her own head on straight.
She doesn't want our suggestions or thoughts to influence her.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He stands firmly in the middle,'' said Suhail Khan, a
spokesman for Representative Tom Campbell of California. ``He's not
going to make up his mind until it's all over; he wants the inquiry
completed.''
</P>
<P>
   At least two undecided Republicans, Representatives Michael N.
Castle of Delaware and McHugh of New York, attended the annual
Congressional Ball at the White House on Monday night. McHugh wrote
Clinton a letter Sunday saying he hoped the White House lawyers
would stick to refuting the specific charges against Clinton rather
than attacking the process during their two-day defense this week.
</P>
<P>
   McHugh never got a response to his letter from the White House,
but Tuesday he watched the committee hearings sporadically from his
home in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, a former prosecutor, watched the hearings intermittenly
from his home on Long Island. ``He feels the White House's
remorseful comments today were welcomed, but it might be a matter
of too little too late, though he is going to wait and see,'' said
his spokeswoman, Emily Miller.
</P>
<P>
   This small group of Republicans are ``critically important'' to
Clinton, said White House spokesman James Kennedy. ``They can spell
the difference between impeachment and no impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Some moderates, including Representatives Jack Quinn and Peter
T. King, both of New York; John Edward Porter of Illinois and Mark
Edward Souder of Indiana, have already come out against
impeachment. Amo Houghton of New York is expected to announce
Wednesday that he also will oppose impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Weld's advent at the hearing makes the White House strategy of
appealing to these swing vote all the more apparent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bringing in Weld is a symbol of bringing in the middle
moderate position in the Republican Party.'' said James A. Thurber,
director of the Center for Congressional and Presidential Studies
at American University. ``I don't know whether it will influence
anybody, but it certainly will not hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Weld, who has been a friend of the Clintons since he worked with
Hillary Rodham Clinton on the staff of the Judiciary Committee
during the Watergate investigation, has said he was ``repelled'' by
Clinton's behavior in the Lewinsky matter and described it as
``horrible, horrible conduct.'' But Weld said he did not think
Clinton's lying about an affair with a White House intern rose to
the level of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Weld did not return phone calls Tuesday seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said Weld will be part of a six-person
panel discussing ``prosecutorial standards for obstruction of
justice and perjury.'' He is expected to make the final
presentation on the panel, just before White House counselor
Charles F.C. Ruff makes his closing argument against impeaching the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Weld's last foray on Capitol Hill was during his aborted attempt
to become ambassador to Mexico last year after Clinton nominated
him for the post. His efforts were derailed by conservative
Republicans, led by Senate Foreign Relations Committee Chairman
Jesse Helms of North Carolina.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
