<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: FREQUENT-FLIER CHANGES; FAA'S ORDER ON 747S;
ELECTRIC RENTAL CARS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (Also moved in ``t'' category.) 
(lb) 
 By JANE L. LEVERE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Next year will bring less variety among U.S. airlines'
frequent-flier programs and the disappearance of miles that expire,
an expert on loyalty programs predicts.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Petersen, publisher of Inside Flyer, a magazine for
frequent travelers, said this week that he expected that features
of programs offered by airline marketing partners _ Northwest
Airlines and Continental Airlines, AMR's American Airlines and U S
Airways, and UAL's United Airlines and Delta Air Lines _ would
change next year to more closely resemble one other.
</P>
<P>
   ``1999 will be the year that domestic programs become singular
frequent-flier programs rather than dual programs.'' Petersen said.
``You'll see the programs of alliance airlines edging closer to
each other. Members of each program will win something and lose
something.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Petersen said he expected that participants in U S
Airways' program would be required to abide by mileage-redemption
rules of American Airlines' program, which he said were stricter
than those of U S Airways.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said Northwest's recent decision to eliminate its
mileage-expiration requirements _ bringing it in line with the
Continental program, which has no expiring miles _ would ultimately
force American and United to follow suit; unlike their respective
marketing partners, U S Airways and Delta, these two carriers still
offer mileage that expires. ``You're going to see the complete
death of expiring miles,'' Petersen said.
</P>
<P>
   He also predicted that there would be more lawsuits next year by
disgruntled frequent fliers against airlines, following preliminary
resolution of a 10-year-old class-action suit against Delta.
</P>
<P>
   Now in the Cook County, Ill., Circuit Court, the suit involves
claims that Delta violated contractual rights of participants in
its loyalty program when it changed some rules in 1988. The
preliminary approval affects close to 600,000 frequent fliers;
final approval is expected in January.
</P>
<P>
   Petersen said he believed that the resolution of the Delta suit
``would open up the gate for many legal challenges of the airlines,
about the number of free seats available and changes in awards.
It's going to be a lawyer's heyday.''
</P>
<P>
   No Long-Haul Changes
</P>
<P>
   A Federal Aviation Administration emergency order issued last
week, affecting fuel storage in Boeing 747s, will not force
operators of these planes to change their flight patterns, despite
initial reports to the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   The order required pilots of all 747s to shut off the pump in
the center fuel tank once the fuel reached a certain level. It also
required operators of long-range 747-400s to stop using a fuel tank
in the horizontal stabilizer in the tail, an action that could cut
the distance the plane could fly. Both measures were taken to
prevent fuel-tank explosions but are unrelated to the 1996
explosion of Trans World Airlines flight 800.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines like United, Northwest and Cathay Pacific, all of which
operate the 747-400s, said last week that they might need to change
long-haul routings or add refueling stops in order to comply with
the FAA's order. However, these carriers subsequently devised
inspection systems that would allow them to operate safely, or they
are choosing to carry less cargo to compensate for any decrease in
fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Charge and Go
</P>
<P>
   Budget Rent-a-Car, a subsidiary of Budget Group Inc., this week
will start renting electric vehicles at its Los Angeles
International Airport location.
</P>
<P>
   Offered in conjunction with EV Rental Cars, a privately held
company based in Calabasas, Calif., the cars will be available at a
special daily rate of $39.95 through early February.
</P>
<P>
   Budget, which already rents electric cars in France, initially
will have about 15 electric vehicles in the airport fleet,
including models by DaimlerChrysler, Ford Motor, General Motors,
Honda and Toyota. The Los Angeles Department of Water and Power, a
partner in this program, is also adding an electric bus to Budget's
airport-shuttle bus fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Budget said it planned to increase its fleet of electric
vehicles at the Los Angeles airport to 60 cars by next spring; it
also expects to eventually expand the fleet to other locations
throughout California. According to the rental-car company, there
are now more than 300 charging stations for electric vehicles
throughout Southern California.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
