<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: REVISITING ANCIENT EGYPT AND 1968 AMERICA
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a combination of what one Fox executive called ``Fox hype and
Discovery Channel content,'' the Fox network will broadcast the
live excavation of several previously unopened Egyptian tombs in a
two-hour program March 2.
</P>
<P>
   The network announced the deal Tuesday, predicting everything
from the possible discovery of a mummy to an expedition to an
undisclosed location that ``may reveal one of the most significant
discoveries of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   The special is a result of a long courtship of Egyptian
officials in charge of antiquities by Fox executives and an
independent producer, Peter Isaacson, a former actor who once
appeared in the NBC comedy ``CPO Sharkey.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox executives did not disclose exactly what the network was
paying for the rights to this event, though they said most of the
money was going for the benefit of archaeological work and the
preservation of the Egyptian monuments. Fox will market the program
internationally as well.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Egyptian officials involved is Dr. Zahi Hawass, a
widely renowned archaeologist and Egypt's undersecretary of state
for the Giza Plateau. He is also well known as the chief debunker
of numerous speculative theories about the planning and
construction of the monuments of Egyptian civilization.
</P>
<P>
   Fox plans to give a lot of time to those theories, some of which
include the notion that space aliens may have inspired the
construction of the Pyramids or that the great Egyptian
civilization of the second millennium B.C. was only a follow-up to
the civilization of the lost continent of Atlantis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be mentioning Atlantis,'' said Nancy Stern, the
supervising producer of the program. ``But we also have Dr. Hawass
debating the advocates of that theory.'' Indeed, Fox has already
filmed Hawass with two authors who have advanced the Egypt-Atlantis
connection in a heated debate in a Cairo coffee shop, Ms. Stern
said.
</P>
<P>
   About half the special will be devoted to the live opening of
tombs, at 3 a.m. Cairo time. One of these is in the pyramid of
Queen Khamerernebty II (wife of the Pharaoh Menkaure), and one is
called the ``Tomb of the Unknown,'' which has been undisturbed (Fox
executives say) for some 4,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   The program, with former NBC correspondent Arthur Kent as host,
promises to include much historical and archaeological background,
an attempt at some re-creation of life in ancient Egypt, and even a
trip with Hawass into a crypt on the neck of the Sphinx. But it is
the live tomb opening that moves the show into the more familiar
realm of the Fox special.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Darnell, the Fox executive vice president in charge of
specials, acknowledged that the subject matter was not typical of
either his network or his department, which has built a name (and
ratings) for itself in recent years with specials like ``When
Animals Attack'' and ``World's Scariest Police Chases.''
</P>
<P>
   While denying that the program would ultimately be called ``When
Good Mummies Go Bad,'' Darnell played with the idea: ``Like, we
discover there was a pit bull in there, and that's what actually
killed the pharaoh.''
</P>
<P>
   He is the executive who made the comparison to the Discovery
Channel, which, coincidentally, has scheduled its own Egypt special
12 days later, a study of what is believed to be the submerged old
city of Alexandria as it was in the time of Cleopatra, before it
was swallowed up by the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
   Darnell said other Fox executives, like chairman David Hill,
liked the subject matter for its historical value.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the hype factor,'' Darnell said. ``I'm sure our
promotion department will create a hyped event: Do be there, don't
be square, for the live tomb opening.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first such excavation on live television.
Geraldo Rivera made television history of a kind in 1986 when he
opened a vault supposedly belonging to Al Capone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He found nothing,'' Darnell said. ``We know we'll find
something. We may find treasure. We may find another Rosetta Stone.
Who knows?''
</P>
<P>
   But Darnell said he wouldn't mind matching something Rivera did
find: lots of viewers. ``He got a 38 share,'' Darnell said, proving
he had done his own digging into the past. That is still the
highest-rated syndicated special in the history of television.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   Tumultuous Era
</P>
<P>
   ABC News is putting a program on the air Thursday night that is
unusual for two reasons. First, a two-hour documentary is rare in
broadcast television these days, with the notable exception of PBS.
Second, the subject matter, the United States in 1968, sounds
almost too familiar.
</P>
<P>
   The film's title, ``The Whole World Was Watching,'' sums up the
challenge faced by the producers in looking back at 1968, when the
Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. and Robert F. Kennedy were
murdered, the Vietnam War was escalated with the Tet offensive, and
students rioted in the streets at the Democratic National
Convention in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't jumping up and down with excitement when we got the
assignment,'' said Paul Fine, who is a co-producer of the program
with his wife, Holly Fine. But they realized that a sizeable number
of young people might have heard tales of the tumultuous '60s and
early '70s without really learning anything in depth about that
period.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, when they screened the film for their 25-year-old son,
Fine said, ``he was fascinated to see people his age who really
felt they could change the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Sawyer and Connie Chung, who were in their early 20s
during that era, are the reporters for the documentary, with each
woman handling two of the four segments examining the lives of
people involved in events of 1968 to see how they have changed in
the 30 years since.
</P>
<P>
   ``The selection of people was brilliant,'' Ms. Chung said,
praising the Fines, who left CBS News last spring, after 16 years
as producers for ``60 Minutes'' and ``CBS Reports,'' and who have
won dozens of major awards, including three Peabodys and 10 Emmys.
</P>
<P>
   ``They found people who were profoundly affected by the times,''
Ms. Chung added, ``and yet who still have relevance to us today.''
</P>
<P>
   The people interviewed range from some well-known figures _
Coretta Scott King, Lady Bird Johnson (who reveals how she learned
that her husband, Lyndon B. Johnson, did not intend to run for
president in 1968), Bernardine Dohrn and Bill Ayres, the former
Weathermen anti-war radicals _ to less familiar ones, like Lloyd
Bucher, the former commander of the Navy intelligence ship Pueblo,
which was captured along with its crew by the North Koreans in
1968.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still unanswered questions inside this story; it
doesn't have pat lessons,'' Ms. Sawyer said. ``There are questions
you can still debate today.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
</TEXT>
