<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981208.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9402 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-REPUBS-2NDTAK     12-08 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-REPUBS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: these issues.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   That view was echoed by Rep. Ray LaHood, R-Ill. ``The only
person who can save him from impeachment is him,'' said LaHood, who
has often displayed an independent streak from his leadership.
``He's got to get out from behind the shroud of his attorneys and
his staff who spent the entire year maligning Ken Starr and Henry
Hyde and trying to dig up dirt on members of the House.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel, and
Rep. Henry Hyde of Illinois, the Republican chairman of the
Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the undecideds watched Tuesday's all-day hearing at home
or ensconced in their Capitol Hill offices, and several said they
planned to read through several hundred pages of background
material the White House presented to the Judiciary Committee on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the historic nature of the impending vote, many
undecided members of Congress were scattered across the globe,
unable to pay attention to Tuesday's testimony because of other
pressing congressional business or equally consuming vacations.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Johnson, R-Conn., was in New Zealand to discuss trade
issues, along with other members of the Ways and Means Committee.
Rep. W.J. Tauzin, R-La., spent the day deer hunting in the wilds of
Maryland. And Rep. Wayne Gilchrest, R-Md., was in London at a
meeting of the International Maritime Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Some said they did not bother to watch the hearing on Tuesday
because they were already familiar with the facts of the case and
did not expect to be enlightened by new testimony on behalf of the
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hearings don't make much difference,'' said Rep. Scott Klug,
R-Wis., Wisconsin, who said he remains undecided. ``Most of the
hearings at this point sound like a bunch of lawyers fighting a
personal injury case. Lots of legalistic polka dancing on the head
of a pin.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lincoln Diaz Belart, R-Fla., said he has been reading up on
the impeachment of President Andrew Johnson and listening closely
to his constituents about the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the first topic of conversation,'' Diaz Belart said.
``I'm sure in the next days it will become something very much at
the forefront of people's attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Several undecided Republicans said that they were pleased that
the panel of witnesses presented by the White House on Tuesday did
not criticize Starr, and that Clinton's lawyer, Gregory Craig, had
adopted a more conciliatory tone with the committee's Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   But one undecided Republican, Rep. Bob Ney of Ohio, said Craig
had not helped the president's case when he said that the president
had not necessarily lied about the Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``C'mon, everyone in the country knows the president didn't tell
the truth,'' Ney said. ``Ask my children. Everyone knows it. The
president said he misled the country. For him to play coy is
absurd. Playing straightforward is what we need. He didn't do him
any justice.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But Ney, who watched several hours of the hearing before flying
back to his district in rural, eastern Ohio, said he would not vote
for impeachment just because of a poor performance by the
president's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   A few moderate Republicans said privately that they had been
contacted either by White House officials or Democratic colleagues
in Congress. But most said they had not been lobbied strenuously by
either side.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Rep. Gary Ackerman, D-N.Y., said that he and other
Democrats have been calling their Republican friends, urging them
to buck their leadership and vote for a motion to censure the
president. Acknowledging that the chances of that happening were
not good, Ackerman said he has been telling undecided members that
they must be prepared to be remembered in history as someone who
voted ``to throw out the president for lying about sex.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They say they understand that,'' Ackerman said. ``But a lot of
them fear for the political lives in their districts. And they are
fearful about whether there will be retribution from the Republican
leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., who opposes impeachment, said
lobbying by the White House and its allies at this late date could
only hurt the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were thinking of voting for impeachment, and the White
House generated calls urging me to vote against it, I think I might
be less inclined to accommodate them,'' he said. ``Because the
thought that I would vote based on political pressure would be an
insult to me. Contrition won't do it, honesty will. That's their
best hope.''
</P>
</TEXT>
