<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARING LOOMING, KRAFTS GO ON PR BLITZ IN CONNECTICUT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding; includes Patriots-Labor material)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY AND GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ On the eve of Wednesday's public hearing to
bring the New England Patriots here, team owner Robert Kraft and
his son Jonathan went on a statewide public relations blitz,
meeting with newspaper editorial boards, attending a pep rally at
the Civic Center mall, and later donating $15,000 to youth
football.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative leaders at the state capital seemed to delight that
Kraft's tour of the state might distract the media from growing
problems with the initial agreement Kraft signed with the state. As
attorneys put the finishing touches on legislation that will
authorize more than $350 million in state borrowing to build a new
68,000-seat home for the football team, union organizers and some
key legislators tried to publicly pressure the team and the state
into making some concessions, arguing that Connecticut is being too
generous to the Patriots' owner.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the promise of several thousand new jobs stadium
construction would bring, the president of the Connecticut AFL-CIO
Tuesday took to the airwaves and the streets to urge members of the
state legislature to view the deal with skepticism
</P>
<P>
   John W. Olsen, whose union represents 24,000 workers in more
than 600 affiliated unions in Connecticut, said he is concerned
that the state may have ``better public works projects'' to finance
than a football stadium. But if the state decides to borrow money
to build it, Olsen said, it should done at the expense of working
men and women of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many aspects of this represent the height of corporate
welfare,'' Olsen said. ``I just want to remind everyone that Mr.
Kraft was the fellow who said he was buying the Patriots to keep
them in Boston. Our schools are crumbling and our roads and bridges
are cracking..Do we really think that this is the only deal we can
have, to have a public works project?''
</P>
<P>
   The $350 million deal will essentially give Kraft free use of
the state-owned stadium and contains lucrative guarantees that will
protect him from falling revenues in years the team cannot sell all
of its expensive club seats and luxury boxes. Meanwhile, the
state's own figures show Connecticut will just break even on its
$350 million investment over 30 years. No direct taxpayer money
will be used in building the stadium if all of the state's
financial assumptions, which some have dubbed widely optimistic,
are met.
</P>
<P>
   Olsen insisted that he was not against the stadium project but
that neither he nor ``any worthwhile legislator'' knows enough
about the deal to approve it. He called on members of the General
Assembly to be thorough in their work, beginning with a hearing
scheduled for Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is such a good deal, why isn't it put out there fully,
and for a couple of weeks, so that everyone can take a good hard
look at it,'' Olsen said. ``If it is that good, what's the rush?''
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut AFL-CIO also launched a radio campaign Tuesday
urging lawmakers to get guarantees that the proposed stadium will
mean good jobs and wages.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear what impact the union's campaign Tuesday will have
on the stadium issue in Hartford. A small group of legislators
already aligned with organized labor are expected to press Kraft on
some of the issues. But their numbers have never appeared large
enough to stop a deal they do not like.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the AFL-CIO unions, especially those in the building
trades, endorsed Rowland's successful candidacy for governor this
year.
</P>
<P>
   A vote on the proposal is scheduled for December 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a close vote, it might make a major difference,'' said
state Representative Demetrios Giannaros, D-Plainfield, who is also
a professor of economics at the University of Hartford. ``I think
that while most legislators want to bring the Patriots to Hartford,
the majority are waiting to here more specific information.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the memorandum of understanding signed by Governor John
Rowland and Kraft commits both sides to a so-called project labor
agreement that would require union wages and benefits, or to comply
with prevailing wage law, Olsen said he will lobby members of the
General Assembly for tough language to secure those standards.
Olsen also called on Kraft to make similar promises to workers who
will eventually staff the hotel and activities center.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently trying to score points with fans and shore up any
wavering support, Kraft Tuesday brought along players Tebucky
Jones, a first round defensive back who grew up in New Britain,
along with linemen Chad Eaton, Bruce Armstrong and Ed Ellis, a
Hamden native.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to hear the enthusiasm that's been restored here
today,'' said Ellis, Hamden native, referring to criticism of the
lucrative stadium deal.''It's really good to be back home.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Jones: ``I don't need a map to get here...Let's start
building that stadium now.'
</P>
<P>
   Star quarterback Drew Bledsoe, who was expected to attend
Tuesday's events, was at Mass General Hospital having his broken
finger tended to.
</P>
<P>
   Hartford Mayor Michael Peters presented Kraft with a golden key
to the city and, in return, got a Patriots jersey with his name and
the number 1 on it.
</P>
<P>
   The obviously pro-Patriots crowd, an assortment of office
workers, shopkeepers and parents with kids seeking autographs who
turned out in the middle of the day were handed blue and white
pompoms leftover from the Patriots/Jets game while a speakers
blared recorded the fight song from the University of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   The college's football team will benefit greatly from playing in
the new facility and getting attention from the NFL coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots spokesman Don Lowery said the city organized the rally
and the charity event right after it, during which PopWarner
players from across the state got to ask questions of the team
members still on hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you really want to come to Hartford?'' one boy asked.
</P>
<P>
   Several players simply said yes and they moved on to the next
question. ``Do you guys think you will change your name to the
Hartford Patriots?'' No, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The rally capped the day for Kraft who visited six newspaper
editorial boards, including the Hartford Courant and the New London
Day, answering questions about just how sweet the deal is for the
team.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft avoided reporters, saying he would answer all questions
about any changes to the agreement during the marathon hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of things have been floated,'' said team vice president
Andy Wasynczuk. ``But We haven't heard'' of any changes that have
actually been made.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key theme I've heard here is, is this a sound investment
and how does it compare (to other deals) around the country?''
</P>
