<SLUG> BC-GE-APPOINT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAD OF GE CAPITAL SERVICES IS REPLACED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By REED ABELSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a management shake-up that had been the subject of months of
speculation, Gary Wendt resigned on Tuesday as the head of GE
Capital Services, the huge financial-services arm of the General
Electric Co.
</P>
<P>
   Wendt, 56, viewed as the executive largely responsible for
creating the powerhouse that fuels General Electric's impressive
earnings growth, was replaced by Dennis Dammerman, General
Electric's long-time chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being named chairman and chief executive of GE
Capital Services, Dammerman, 53, was appointed a vice chairman of
the parent company.
</P>
<P>
   While General Electric and analysts and investors sought to play
down the significance of Wendt's departure and the possibility of
any changes at GE Capital, the impact of his resignation is
unclear.
</P>
<P>
   GE Capital, which consists of 29 businesses ranging from credit
cards to truck leasing, provided about 40 percent of General
Electric's profits last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's going to be run the same way,'' said Marvin
Roffman, the president of Roffman Miller Associates, a Philadelphia
money-management and independent research firm. He predicted there
would be be ``a lot of changes in the company over the next few
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Regarded as a visionary who is extraordinarily skillful at
assessing risk and doing the right deals, Wendt oversaw GE Capital
for the last dozen years. Over that period, its assets grew from
$24 billion to $300 billion, and profits rose from $300 million to
nearly $4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In describing the reasons for the changes, John F. Welch Jr.,
General Electric's 63-year-old chairman and chief executive
officer, emphasized that the moves were part of the company's
overall efforts to put in place a younger team of executives and
prepare General Electric for his retirement in two years. ``We're
trying to get all the ducks in a row,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Denis Nayden, 44, who had been serving as president and chief
operating officer at GE Capital Corp. which represents the bulk of
GE Capital Services, was promoted to chief executive. Keith Sherin,
40, the vice president of finance and financial services at GE
Medical Systems, replaced Dammerman as chief financial officer for
General Electric.
</P>
<P>
   Wendt's departure, which was reported in Tuesday's Wall Street
Journal, came as little surprise. Despite his much-publicized
success in running GE Capital, he and Welch were believed to have
strained relations. During his very public and messy divorce
proceedings, Wendt admitted that he and Welch were not close, and
people who know both men said that they did not get along.
</P>
<P>
   The primary reason for the executive changes, according to
Welch, was his desire to create a stable environment for the
company before he stepped down.
</P>
<P>
   Wendt ``was not a candidate'' to become the next chief executive
of General Electric, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Welch would not say whether Wendt was precluded from
competing with GE Capital in the future, the company said that he
had agreed to stay on in a consulting role until the middle of next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Wendt did not comment on Tuesday's events, although he issued a
statement in which he thanked Welch for his support and described
the business as ``well positioned'' and ``staffed with bright and
enthusiastic people well qualified to help maximize GE shareholder
values in the future!''
</P>
<P>
   While General Electric's stock initially dropped $1.75 on the
news, it closed on Tuesday at $90.4375, down 37.5 cents. Analysts
and investors generally applauded the way the move was handled and
the decision to place the group under the supervision of Dammerman,
a highly regarded financial executive who played a key role in
cleaning up the mess created by General Electric's ill-fated
acquisition of Kidder Peabody, which was later sold to PaineWebber.
</P>
<P>
   Dammerman ``surely knows as much as there is to know about GE
and GE Capital,'' said Jeanne G. Terrile, an analyst at Merrill
Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   Dammerman is viewed as one of Welch's closest advisers and one
of the candidates to succeed him as chief executive. But analysts
say that the job was more likely to go to a younger executive with
more operating experience. Among the executives' names bandied
about were Jeffrey Immelt, the head of GE Medical Systems, and W.
James McNerney Jr., the head of GE Aircraft Engines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
