s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANBY-THEATER-ART-2TA     12-08 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANBY-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN `ELECTRA' POWERFULLY CURRENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 13)  
 (af)  
 By VINCENT CANBY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Theatergoers who admired Diana Rigg's grand, actressy,
haute-couture appearance in the Euripides ``Medea,'' which came to
Broadway from London in 1994, are in for a shock when they see the
``Electra'' now at the Ethel Barrymore Theater.
</P>
<P>
   This production also has its quota of high-fashion, post-modern
effects, but neither these, nor the occasional tin-eared line, can
get in the way of the primal intensity of the Sophocles text.
Played without an intermission, ``Electra'' runs only a little more
than 90 minutes, while leaping the centuries with the speed of
light-years.
</P>
<P>
   Though you may come out of the theater quibbling about various
aspects of the production (as I did), you may also be surprised to
find that it haunts your consciousness for days afterward. Not just
the fine, stern, unfancified performances by Zoe Wanamaker and
Claire Bloom, but the play itself.
</P>
<P>
   No matter that it is 2,400 years old or that its concerns seem
arcane in our world, ``Electra'' remains an eerily fundamental,
theatrically dynamic work.
</P>
<P>
   In Electra, daughter of the hero and king, Agamemnon, who was
murdered by her mother, Clytemnestra, and her mother's lover,
Aegisthus, we have a primitive, starkly realized Hamlet figure, one
who has been stripped of all doubts and is committed to revenge.
Also like Hamlet, Electra has become a trial to her family. Though
years have passed since Agamemnon's murder, Electra continues to
mourn him noisily and to harangue anyone who will listen with tales
of the lovers' treachery. There is a curse on the House of Atreus.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Electra is not allowed off the premises of the family
compound. She is a rabid, foul-tempered public spectacle: a tiny,
eccentric wretch, hobbling around in her father's old British Army
greatcoat, which dwarfs her and drags on the ground. The hair she
hasn't yet pulled out of her head in paroxysms of grief stands up
in lunatic tufts. In repose, which isn't often, the figure she cuts
reminds you of Giulietta Masina's Cabiria on a terrible day. Yet
she is anything but pathetic.
</P>
<P>
   Electra is a strong, aggressive woman, impatiently awaiting the
return of her brother, Orestes, whom, she sent away for safekeeping
on the day of the murder. He was then a small boy. On this day,
which is the time of the play, the now grown Orestes at last comes
home. The rest of the tragedy can be played out as it must, the
gods appeased and the cycle of violence ended.
</P>
<P>
   Or so audiences in Athens (circa 418 B.C.-410 B.C.) were told by
the Chorus at the end. Contemporary audiences don't have that
reassurance. We have two choices: we can accept the play as we
understand the Athenians saw it, which keeps the events at a polite
distance; or we can see it in our own terms _ violence breeding
violence that breeds more violence, with no end of it in sight, all
set in the interior landscape explored by Freud.
</P>
<P>
   The gods are dead but, for us, the good doctor from Vienna
marches on. For the time being, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Sophocles' ``Electra,'' which I had read but never seen before
this production, seems to be a much more vital, more profoundly
disturbing work than any of the ``Medea'' versions I have seen. In
addition to Diana Rigg's, they would include the Robinson Jeffers
adaptation done on Broadway in the late 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Anderson, later to become a real Dame, more or less
declaimed the text in various vocal moods while standing, sitting
and sweeping around in front of a great Mycenae house that looked
like the Supreme Court Building in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medea'' is much less complex in dramatic structure, being
virtually one long monologue audited by the Chorus, the Nurse and
others, and interrupted by the brief appearances of Jason, the
husband, and Creon, the king. No wonder actresses love to play the
role: there is scarcely anybody to upstage them. The actual
dramatic confrontations are kept to a minimum. It is a great show
of conflicted nobility and sacrifice: the woman pays, and dearly.
</P>
<P>
   Euripides is considered to have brought a degree of humanity to
Greek drama lacking in the work of Sophocles, his contemporary. Yet
the ``Electra'' of Sophocles appears to be a far more theatrical
work.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Electra's confrontation with her mother when
Clytemnestra, cool and in complete control of herself, points out
the perfectly reasonable motive for the murder of Agamemnon. Weak
man that he was, she says, he had sacrificed Iphigenia, her
daughter and Electra's sister, to insure fair winds to Troy. She
could never forgive him for that. Why didn't Menelaus, Agamemnon's
brother and the husband of the purloined Helen, sacrifice one of
(italics)his(end italics) children?
</P>
<P>
   Nonsense, Electra says in effect. The gods demanded the
sacrifice after Agamemnon shot a deer while hunting in a sacred
grove. Then she backtracks a bit. Even if the story about the deer
is not true, Iphigenia's sacrifice, which made possible the
successful Trojan campaign, was hardly worth the backstairs murder
planned and executed by Clytemnestra and her lover.
</P>
<P>
   The two women are equals in furious family combat, as well as in
the performances by Zoe Wanamaker as Electra and Claire Bloom as
Clytemnestra. Their scene is the production's most stunning and
rewarding section. Ms. Wanamaker suddenly has a living being on
whom she can direct her sarcasm and loathing. It's as if she takes
new heart in hate. She almost struts in her rags with pent-up
satisfaction. Yet as viciously as she attacks, she can never
penetrate the barrier of steely serenity that appears to protect
Clytemnestra.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bloom is as spectacular an image in her way as Ms. Wanamaker
is in hers. With her head held high, her right profile turned to
the audience, wearing a skin-tight scarlet gown, she sits in a
once-exquisite, now soiled, satin-backed 18th-century chair amid
the rubble that now clutters the forecourt to the House of Atreus.
Her voice is carefully pitched, almost musical. Electra's is lower,
sandier, as if she slept too many nights outside, using her
father's greatcoat as a sleeping bag.
</P>
<P>
   Almost as effective is the later, tantalizingly drawn out
recognition scene in which Orestes (Michael Cumpsty), identifying
himself only as a friend, turns up in Mycenae to confront Electra
with what he says is the urn containing Orestes' ashes. This sends
Electra off into another fit of grief, the depth of which prompts
Orestes at last to reveal himself.
</P>
<P>
   Their reunion is sweet but necessarily brief; Orestes, attended
by his faithful old servant (Stephen Spinella) and a friend Pylades
(Ivan Stamenov), must dispatch Clytemnestra before the return of
Aegisthus (Daniel Oreskes). When Orestes emerges from the house,
having killed their mother, Electra, in her joy, licks his
blood-splattered arm. Expiation of this kind is intoxicating. The
murder of Aegisthus is something of an anticlimax.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The production, directed by David Leveaux, began life last year
in England at the Chichester Festival, before moving to the Donmar
Warehouse in London. It was recreated by Leveaux earlier this year
at the McCarter Theater in Princeton, N.J., with a new cast
supporting the star. The credits of all concerned are impressive.
</P>
<P>
   The American-born, London-bred Ms. Wanamaker (daughter of the
late Sam Wanamaker) won the Olivier Award for her ``Electra''
performance. Leveaux was the director of the hit Roundabout Theater
Company revival of Eugene O'Neill's ``Anna Christie,'' with Natasha
Richardson and Liam Neeson in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The new adaptation is by Frank McGuinness, the Irish playwright
who wrote ``Someone Who'll Watch Over Me,'' as well as the
adaptation of last year's celebrated revival of ``A Doll's House''
with Janet McTeer.
</P>
<P>
   McGuinness' adaptation of ``Electra'' is laudably clean,
efficient and free of hackneyed language most of the time, but
adaptations of this sort are tricky. A single misstep can throw you
off for minutes at a time as when, at the beginning of the play,
Orestes says of the House of Atreus, ``Let me put this house back
on its feet.'' Back on its feet? A house? But maybe that was a
last-minute insert to touch corporate America.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wanamaker and Ms. Bloom are splendid. Also extremely good
are Marin Hinkle, as Electra's loyal, pragmatic sister,
Chrysothemis, and Pat Carroll as the Chorus. Cumpsty and Spinella
are both fine actors, but they are unfortunately miscast, possibly
even misdirected.
</P>
<P>
   Cumpsty is too old to play with conviction an Orestes gone, one
would suspect, no more than 20 years. He also seems physically
uncomfortable in those stylized moments when, remaining still,
supposedly attending the action or speech of another, he seems as
inanimate as a totem pole.
</P>
<P>
   As Spinella was too young to play the lawyer in the recent
revival of ``A View From the Bridge,'' he is even more out of the
age bracket to be convincing as Orestes' loyal old servant. There
is nothing much wrong with his readings, but his voice is youthful.
</P>
<P>
   In some perverse way, this is made even more obvious by the
remarkably snowy-white hair that he is now sporting. Hair of that
fluffy brilliance may be home grown but it looks as if it had been
picked in a cotton field.
</P>
<P>
   The post-modern set by Johan Engels (who also did the costume
design), which takes a bit of time getting used to, is visually
arresting and works quite well. This House of Atreus looks like the
brick-walled back alley of a great antique store.
</P>
<P>
   The store may front on a fashionable boulevard, but the alley is
a mess. Among the debris: wrecked chairs of worthy provenance and a
slab of marble leaning against the remnant of an ancient column, in
this way to suggest a partly collapsed bier.
</P>
<P>
   Like Ms. Wanamaker's Electra, it intrigues the mind as well as
the eye. Far better this than another mockup of the Supreme Court
Building. &QL; 
 &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
 &QL;
<P>
   Diana Son's ``Stop Kiss,'' now at the Shiva Theater in the
Joseph Papp Public Theater, is an artfully constructed, well acted
comedy-drama that has been directed with skill by Joe Bonney. I
suspect it could move tomorrow to a larger house for an extended
run.
</P>
<P>
   It is the kind of piece that makes people feel good in direct
relation to the pain they suffer vicariously after each situation
that makes them laugh. Read on; you will understand what I mean.
</P>
<P>
   At its center: the brutal beating of two young women (one of
whom may never fully recover) on a park bench in Greenwich Village
at 4 a.m. The perpetrator: a young thug who seems to have gone
berserk at the sight of their kissing. The words he called them
can't be reported in a family newspaper, though gay-bashing can and
is.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, that near-fatal kiss was the first time that Callie
(Jessica Hecht) and Sara (Sandra Oh) had openly acknowledged the
extent and meaning of their feelings for each other. It seems that
Sara, a third-grade teacher newly arrived from St. Louis, has known
she was gay for some time.
</P>
<P>
   For Callie, who delivers traffic reports for an all-news radio
station, the awareness that she loves another woman is a great
liberating breakthrough. She is tired of meeting her old college
friend George just for sex, while dating other guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stop Kiss,'' which is performed without an intermission, is
cannily composed of short scenes that recall how Callie and Sara
met and fell in love, alternating with scenes that follow the
progression of the police investigation and Sara's rehabilitation.
There is never any doubt about what happens, only about the
physical and emotional consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Son writes insistently quirky dialogue for ordinary people
in a commonplace world that suddenly reveals its ugliness. Yet for
all of the play's honesty and largeness of spirit, something about
it doesn't ring quite true: ``Stop Kiss'' has been nontraditionally
cast in the way of a progressive television sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   Callie is white, Sara is Asian, Callie's lover, George, is
black, though there is never a single mention of these important
differences or of the polarized world they inhabit.
</P>
<P>
   This can't be explained away by the fact that Callie and her
friends live in the Village and its environs. Rather, it seems to
suggest that Callie, Sara, George and the others exist in a world
as unreal and disconnected as that of a sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   Either that, or Ms. Son is saying that this is the way things
should be. Here, only gay-bashing is acknowledged. Life is perfect
except for one thing, and because of that one thing, Sara may be a
wheelchair case for life.
</P>
<P>
   There is possibly more to be said in ``Stop Kiss'' than Ms. Son
has yet written. Even at this stage, though, the play demonstrates
a professionalism you don't often find downtown or up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
