<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-BOTANIKA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTMAS COULD MAKE OR BREAK GARDEN BOTANIKA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CONSTANCE SOMMER  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ This holiday shopping season could determine the
future of Garden Botanika, the troubled bed and bath retail chain
based in Redmond, Wash., the company's president said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a fragile state,'' said Michael Luce, president and
chief executive. ``Certainly the holiday season is very
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Incorporated in 1990, Garden Botanika today owns and operates
274 stores across the country, selling products ranging from
cosmetics and fragrances to skin care items, bath and body care
goods and accessories.
</P>
<P>
   Emphasizing natural ingredients and targeting young working
women, the company looked promising enough for investors to bid its
stock up to $35 a share soon after it went public in May 1996. But
continued financial losses _ coupled with the closing of eight
stores this year and the conversion of five others into clearance
centers _ steadily drove the share price down well below a dollar.
It closed Tuesday at 62.5 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   Now more store closings may be in the offing. In a report filed
on Dec. 1 with the Securities and Exchange Commission, Garden
Botanika said it plans to close an undisclosed number of stores
before the end of its fiscal year, on Jan. 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``Following the holiday season, the Company plans to review the
productivity of each of its stores with a view toward closing those
stores that fail to meet performance standards,'' Garden Botanika
wrote in the report.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the company is banking on November and December's sales
figures to stave off a possible bankruptcy filing, Luce
acknowledged yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that's out of the question,'' he said. ``But I
don't think that's likely at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   That's largely because the company's most recent sales figures
are not spelling out disaster, he said. November sales decreased by
3 percent compared to the same month the year before, but Garden
Botanika attributed most of the decline to the last week of the
month.
</P>
<P>
   Loyal customers who joined the company's discount sales program
may be responsible for much of that downturn, as well as for the
leap in sales on Tues., Dec. 1, Luce said. The program promises 20
percent off all purchases by members on the first Tuesday of every
month.
</P>
<P>
   Had the company's accounting period extended through Dec. 1, the
picture would be considerably more upbeat, he said. Luce refused to
discuss December's sales numbers so far.
</P>
<P>
   Garden Botanika rings up as much as half of its yearly business
in the fourth fiscal quarter, which ends on Jan. 30. The retail
industry average is slightly less than 25 percent of sales occuring
during the holiday season, according to the National Retail
Federation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
