<SLUG> BC-AMY-FISHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMY FISHER SEEKS TRIAL AND CLAIMS AFFAIR WITH LAWYER
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINEOLA, N.Y. _ Amy Fisher is seeking to withdraw her guilty
plea and go to trial over the 1992 shooting of Mary Jo Buttafuoco,
charging that her former lawyer, Eric Naiburg, lied to her and had
a sexual relationship with her that clouded his judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fisher, 23, made the charges in an affidavit filed Tuesday
in Nassau County Court by her new lawyer, Bruce Barket, who argued
that Naiburg's personal and sexual relationship with Ms. Fisher
constituted a conflict of interest that interfered with his ability
to effectively represent her.
</P>
<P>
   All of the charges were denied Tuesday by Naiburg, who said he
was stunned by the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Barket said that Naiburg lied to Ms. Fisher when he told her
that if she agreed to plead guilty to assault and illegal
possession of a weapon, the Nassau County district attorney's
office would agree to help her enter a work-release program and
obtain parole within three years of imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   And he said that Naiburg's interest in his client was obscured
by their relationship. ``Rather than consider all possible
strategies available to the defense,'' Barket said in his argument,
``Naiburg became obsessed with personally exploring Ms. Fisher's
sexual proclivities in a manner designed to satiate his own
perverse needs.''
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney's office has repeatedly denied that anyone
ever promised Naiburg help in getting Ms. Fisher into a
work-release program. The district attorney, Denis Dillon, said
that he intended to oppose the motion and would file the necessary
response in due course.
</P>
<P>
   If the case does go to trial, Ms. Fisher, if found guilty of the
original charge of attempted murder, could be sentenced to 12 1/2
to 25 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   In an affidavit he signed several months ago, Naiburg said he
had had an informal agreement with John Klein, the prosecutor in
the case, on the matter of early parole. Reached by telephone
Tuesday at his office in Hauppauge, Naiburg reiterated that he had
such an informal agreement, but described it as ``unenforceable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an understanding that if Miss Fisher behaved herself
in prison, Dillon would support parole,'' Naiburg said. ``However,
Amy committed at least 30 violations of prison rules by the time
she first came up for parole.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fisher admitted to shooting Mrs. Buttafuoco, the wife of her
lover, Joey Buttafuoco, in May 1992. Prosecutors had charged that
Ms. Fisher committed the crime after Buttafuoco decided to end
their affair. A bullet remains lodged in Mrs. Buttafuoco's neck,
but she has recovered from her injuries, and she and her husband,
who served four months in jail for statutory rape, have since moved
to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   In her affidavit, Ms. Fisher said that within a week of being
released on bail from the Nassau County jail in 1992, she began an
intense relationship with Naiburg that included kissing and the
acting out of sexual fantasies. But, she said, they did not engage
in intercourse ``because he said he did not want to do to me what
Joey did to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Naiburg denied all of the charges in Ms. Fisher's two-page
affidavit. ``These statements are a desperate attempt by a
desperate woman to gain her freedom without regard to human
decency,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am offended, angry and beside myself. There is not one line
of truth in the entire affidavit. Each line, chapter and verse, is
a lie,'' Naiburg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am one of the last of a long line of individuals of whom she
has alleged improper conduct,'' he said, noting that the most
recent to be accused of sexual misconduct by Ms. Fisher were eight
prison officers. He said the accusations were ``dismissed as being
incredible, as will be the charges against me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fisher, who is serving a 10-to-15 year term in the state
correction facility in Albion, provided Barket with dozens of
poems, notes and letters that Naiburg sent to her in prison over
the last six years. One of the poems submitted to the court to show
that Naiburg was besotted with Ms. Fisher included the following
lines:
</P>
<P>
   I came to know a different Amy
</P>
<P>
   One as charming as the devil
</P>
<P>
   I came to care quite a bit
</P>
<P>
   And that is on the level!
</P>
<P>
   Naiburg said Tuesday that he regretted writing to Ms. Fisher and
described the release of the poems as ``embarrassing.'' But he said
the correspondence in no way suggested an improper relationship or
indicated that he was acting other than as ``a friend, a father
figure trying desperately to cheer her up when she was morose.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I visited her on many occasions and sometimes I would put my
arm around her or kiss her on top of the head, but only in a
fatherly way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   State law governing professional conduct by lawyers does not
specifically prohibit them from having sexual affairs with clients,
court officials said. But various elements of the law have been
invoked occasionally to discipline lawyers who were involved
sexually with clients.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers are required to maintain independence from a client, for
example, and to avoid a personal interest in litigation. They are
also supposed to avoid conflicts of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Allegations of misconduct against lawyers are investigated by
disciplinary or grievance committees created by the Appellate
Division of the state court system. After investigation, a case
goes to an independent panel that holds hearings and issues a
report, with recommendations on possible penalties. Final decisions
are made by judges in the Appellate Division. Penalties in such
cases can range from censure to suspension to disbarment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-98 2101EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
