<DOCNO> NYT19981208.0347 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9432 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUS-INSURANCE-COX     12-08 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUS-INSURANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Minorities forced to pay higher insurance premiums, report says
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ All across Texas, poor and minority drivers in urban
and rural areas are being forced to buy auto insurance from
companies that generally charge the highest prices, according to a
report released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Lon Burnam, D-Fort Worth, a member of the House
Insurance Committee, said the report and its analysis of
company-by-company insurance sales in the first three months of
this year show that ``many lower-cost, standard insurers appear to
systematically deny coverage to consumers who live in poor and
minority areas.''
</P>
<P>
   In neighborhoods with a minority population of less than 14.2
percent, more than 84 percent of all drivers are insured by
cheaper, standard policies, the study said. By contrast, in areas
where minority population is 85 percent or greater, only 49.7
percent of drivers are insured by the less costly lines of
insurance, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The poorest consumers _ those who most desperately need access
to standard insurance rates to be able to comply with financial
responsibility laws _ are forced to pay the higher rates charged by
non-rate-regulated county mutual insurers'' and the high-risk Texas
Automobile Insurance Plan Association.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Automobile Insurance Plan Association is a state
program meant to help the worst drivers get insurance, and its
rates are extremely expensive. On average, the study said, rate
regulated rates in Texas in 1997 were $800 a year. Non-rate
regulated rates averaged $1,300 a year or $500 more.
</P>
<P>
   County mutual companies, once made up of groups of individuals
pooling their resources, have become the most likely insurers for
drivers with poor records. Many are now associated with standard
insurance companies that use the county mutuals to insure bad
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   The county mutuals tend to have higher rates than standard,
rate-regulated insurers, though generally lower than Texas
Automobile Insurance Plan Association rates.
</P>
<P>
   Burnam, consumer advocates and even insurance industry officials
say there is no correlation between bad driving records and income
or race. Even so, low-income Texans and minority drivers are more
likely to end up with the higher-priced insurance offered by county
mutuals and the automobile insurance plan, Burnam said.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance industry officials denied any systematic attempt to
force anyone into higher-priced policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing sinister about their findings,'' Johns said.
Low-income and minority areas of the state ``may be where people
who have less than desirable driving records may live.''
</P>
<P>
   Johns said it would be ludicrous to draw any lines between race
and income and insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Race, or the color of one's skin, or economic condition has
nothing to do with insurance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Birnbaum, a former state association insurance commissioner,
said regulated insurance companies, those with generally the best
rates, appear to be avoiding low-income and minority areas across
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would the poorest consumers choose to buy from the
highest-cost providers of that product?'' Birnbaum asked. He could
not give details about specific companies because of state law and
a court order.
</P>
<P>
   Burnam also announced a package of proposed laws including a new
system to regulate county mutual insurance rates; stronger laws to
keep good drivers from being forced into county mutuals and other
high-priced insurance; and improved enforcement of the mandatory
liability insurance law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The results of this study indicate that legislative action is
necessary and appropriate to address availability and affordability
problems in the Texas automobile insurance market,'' Burnam said.
</P>
<P>
   Burnam also called on the Texas Department of Insurance to
investigate the sales practices of nine companies. After Birnbaum
produced a similar report last year, the department investigated
several companies and has proposed a $10 million fine _ the largest
in that department's history _ against Nationwide Insurance for
illegal discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Birnbaum's report, which was censored to keep company-specific
information secret, was based on company reports to the Insurance
Department. Industry attorneys last year fought to make sure that
the records are secret.
</P>
<P>
   Under a court order and state law, legislators and their staffs
have access to such records for legislative purposes. They are
required to sign confidentiality agreements to use them and face
fines and jail time if they release specific details.
</P>
<P>
   When Burnam announced this year that he would hire Birnbaum to
review the ``millions of pieces of information,'' industry
attorneys sued to prevent that from happening. They argued that
Birnbaum had illegally released records while working for the
insurance department and should not be allowed access to the
company-specific data.
</P>
<P>
   Birnbaum denied any illegal releases in the past and said he
made certain no company-specific information was in the public
version of his report.
</P>
<P>
   Birnbaum and other consumer advocates have argued in the past
that consumers should have the right to know how insurers are
setting their prices and treating customers because they sell a
product Texans are required to buy.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance company officials have successfully argued that if
other insurers knew how they were operating, competition would
suffer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
