<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CINERAMA-DOME-FIXUP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LANDMARK CINERAMA DOME THEATER TO BE PRESERVED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Pacific Theatres announced a compromise agreement
with preservation groups over its plan to revamp Hollywood's
Cinerama Dome, the largest movie theater in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific, which originally planned to renovate the dome by
replacing the interior and removing the 86-foot-wide curved screen,
said Tuesday it will retain basic elements of the 937-seat
auditorium and will add state-of-the-art sound, projection,
lighting and acoustics.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific executives, who had previously claimed the theater was
outmoded and unable to compete effectively with more modern rivals,
admitted they were impressed by the flood of opposition to changing
the 35-year-old landmark.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been moved by the passion and connection that people
feel for the Cinerama Dome,'' said Michael Forman, chairman of the
chain. ``Our goal always has been to ensure that it is the best
place to see a film in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The chain has also agreed to scale back the height of the
surrounding retail-entertainment center, which will include a
12-screen multiplex, restaurants and stores. The shopping center
will shrink from four stories to three in order to showcase the
50-foot-high dome. In exchange, preservationists agreed to support
the project.
</P>
<P>
   The structure is the only geodesic dome made entirely out of
concrete. ``The Cinerama Dome is the only theater of its kind in
the world and an important example of futuristic architecture,''
said Linda Dishman, executive director of the Los Angeles
Conservancy.
</P>
<P>
   The project, one of several planned for Hollywood, will occupy
most of the massive parking lot surrounding the dome. Construction
will start next spring, with an opening date planned for May 2000.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
