<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES--PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        SANTORUM CALLS FOR PRIVATIZING SOCIAL SECURITY
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Mark Stricherz  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Dec. 8 -- Wading into the national debate on
reforming the country's Social Security system, Sen. Rick Santorum,
R-Penn., outlined a plan Tuesday to allow recipients to invest part
of their benefits in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a White-House sponsored conference on overhauling
the 63-year-old program, Santorum, an economic conservative,
proposed that Social Security rely at least partly on the free
market, rather than solely on the federal government and it's
pay-as-you-go setup.
</P>
<P>
   ``An improved Social Security system will synthesize the
traditionally Democratic commitment to provide citizens with
security through government programs with the Republican commitment
to economic opportunity and individual freedom,'' he said, going on
to criticize the program as it was created in 1935.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the current system, individuals have no legal claim to
either their acccrued contributions or their anticipated benefits.
One of our most critical insights is that ownership changes
behavior. It creates hope, and a commitment to the future one's own
and that of one's country.''
</P>
<P>
   With 77 million baby boomers reaching retirement age beginning
in 2010, Social Security faces mounting insolvency. It is expected
to lose money by 2013. And by 2032, the program is expected to pay
only 75 percent of benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Fixing Social Security is particularly urgent in Pennsylvania
and Johnstown, which have many elderly, 16 percent and and 19
percent respectively. Nationwide, 12.6 percent of the population is
65 years old or older and thus eligible for Social Security
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Of the roughly 9 main proposals Congress is considering to fix
the disability and retirement program, Santorum's plan would go
further than most in privatizing it. Privatization is a substitute
for raising payroll taxes, currently set at 12.4 percent and split
among employers and employees.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a recipient earning $23,000 could set aside up to 4
percent of his or her monthly benefits. Under competing proposals,
such as that sponsored by Sens. John Breaux, D-La., and Judd Gregg,
R-N.H., workers would have to deduct 2 percent of benefits for
private investment.
</P>
<P>
   In allowing partial privatization, Santorum's plan hinges on
whether middle-class and poor beneficiaries can make money in the
stock market or other private investments. Presented as a populist
idea, Santorum expressed optimism that it will.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that 1 percent of Americans own more wealth than the
bottom 90 percent and that this gap is growing, Santorum said,
``Under a funded system with personal accounts, all workers will
have the chance to accumulate to real wealth. Such a system also
offers the opportunity for ownership.''
</P>
<P>
   Among local lawmakers, reaction to Santorum's plan, which he
introduced during the fall, was frosty.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Murtha, D-Johnstown, expressed deep skepticism toward
any privatization proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are very concerned about the stability and sureness of
payments and opposed to risking this stability by gambling in the
stock market,'' said Murtha in a prepared statement. ``In addition
... many retirees in our area are feeling a sharp pinch from
low-cost-of-living increases coupled with sharp increases in
medical and prescription drug costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bud Shuster, R-Glassport, did not return repeated phone
calls.
</P>
<P>
   However, Breaux, a leading moderate, was notably more
enthusiastic about Santorum's plan, calling it a ``step in the
right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Moderates and conservatives argue that privatization will not
only create personal wealth but save the system from bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   While Santorum presented his proposal as bipartisan -- a word
invoked repeatedly by Democrats and Republicans at the conference
-- it actually represents a dramatic change in the program, a
cornerstone of President Franklin Delano Roosevelt's New Deal.
</P>
<P>
   The program began as a social safey net, in which employers and
employees would contribute through a payroll tax. Under the system,
known as pay as you go, benefits are invested in U.S. Treasury
securities.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate prospects for reform may hinge on the first six
months of 1999, said lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. E. Clay Shaw, Jr., the incoming House chairman of the
Social Security Subcommittee, said divided government may help
overhaul efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``With one party in power, you have the other party throwing
rocks,'' said Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, political leaders said the 1999 election cycle will
kick in during the summer, thus further politicizing an already
touchy subject.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's event was the first of a two-day event. Political
leaders are more likely to hammer out specifics on Wednesday, when
they meet a closed-door, lawmakers-only session.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-98 2133EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
