<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9464 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-REPORT09-COX     12-08 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-REPORT09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON LAWYERS SUBMIT WRITTEN DEFENSE
 &HT;    By KEN FOSKETT and BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's legal team laid out a detailed
contention Tuesday that he did not commit perjury, obstruct justice
or abuse the power of his office in the Monica Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   While admitting that Clinton's conduct in the sex-and-deception
scandal was ''wrong,'' the lawyers portrayed Clinton as the victim
of a biased investigation, a flawed report of the inquiry's
findings and erroneous conclusions by his political foes.
</P>
<P>
   None of Clinton's behavior posed the ''grave harm to the
Republic'' required to justify impeachment, his lawyers argued in a
184-page filing with the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''The wrongdoing alleged here does not remotely meet that
standard,'' the president's lawyers asserted in what amounted to a
written summary of two days of testimony that concludes Wednesday
before the committee.
</P>
<P>
   The president's memorandum was signed by a battery of lawyers
led by Clinton's personal lawyer, David Kendall; special counsel to
the president, Gregory Craig, and White House Counsel Charles Ruff.
</P>
<P>
   It was immediately dismissed by the Judiciary Committee's
chairman, Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., as a repackaging of White House
''legal hairsplitting and semantic gymnastics.''
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee is expected to vote this week on three
articles of impeachment, charging Clinton with perjury, obstruction
of justice and abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to the president at Tuesday's Judiciary Committee hearing
conceded that the new legal memorandum was unlikely to change any
minds on the committee, which has been bitterly divided for weeks
along party lines.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the document was aimed at a small, but potentially
decisive, number of other House Republicans who the White House
believes still haven't formed a final opinion about the president's
conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure the partisans are going to say 'nothing new'
...because their minds are made up,'' said White House spokesman
Jim Kennedy. ``But we do believe there are a lot of people who have
an open mind ...and will conclude that a reasonable case of
wrongdoing has not been made.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the committee likely to vote out at least one article
of impeachment this week and a full House vote expected next week,
not even the White House can say for certain how many such members
exist.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Zoe Lofgren, D-Calif., said it was impossible to know how
many moderate Republicans might be swayed by the president's latest
arguments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The moderates are just getting hammered by the right wing and
as a consequence are keeping their heads down,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde issued a statement three hours after the memorandum was
delivered to the committee. He appeared particularly peeved that he
received the report after its contents had already been reported by
CNN.
</P>
<P>
   ``This document, the contents of which we learned from
television news, appears to contain no new evidence or challenge
the truthfulness of any testimony the committee now possesses,''
Hyde said. ``What it also includes is more legal hair-splitting and
semantic gymnastics we have come to expect from this White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, meanwhile, appeared in no rush to read the document.
At least one Democrat, Rep. Robert Wexler, D-Fla., said the
document answered the criticisms from Republicans that the
president had offered no defense of the actual allegations
contained in the impeachment referral submitted by Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Wexler said the president's brief shows that the president did
in fact acknowledge an ``inappropriate intimate relationship'' with
Lewinsky in his grand jury testimony, while denying that he had
``sexual relations'' with her, as defined by lawyers for Paula
Jones in her civil sexual harassment lawsuit against the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American public needs to understand that the Republicans
want to impeach him over that distinction,'' Wexler said.
</P>
<P>
   In their new document, Clinton's lawyers attacked the
impeachment process on three fronts:
</P>
<P>
   _ That the president has not committed perjury, obstruction of
justice or abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   _ That the charges, in any event, do not rise the the level of
impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   _ That Starr exhibited a ''bias'' against Clinton during his
investigation and in his report to the Judiciary Committee in
September.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the memorandum charges that Starr, in his report,
knowingly omitted evidence that would suggest Clinton's innocence.
</P>
<P>
   On the issue of perjury, the article of impeachment that appears
most likely to be approved by the committee, Clinton's attorneys
attempted to draw a fine distinction between lying and committing
perjury.
</P>
<P>
   ''A vast range of testimony that is imprecise, unresponsive,
vague, and literally truthful, even if it is not completely
forthcoming, simply is not perjury,'' the filing states.
</P>
<P>
   ''The law is aware of human foibles and shortcomings of memory.
...Perjury requires proof that a defendant, while under oath,
knowingly made a false statement as to material facts.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We are duty-bound to draw a distinction between immoral
conduct and illegal or impeachable acts,'' the lawyers asserted.
''The record before this committee does not justify charges of
criminal conduct or impeachable offenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Stressing Clinton's contrition, the lawyers stated in a preface
to the filing that ''he is profoundly sorry for the wrongs he had
committed and for the pain he has caused his family, his friends
and our nation.''
</P>
<P>
   As they have done repeatedly, Clinton's lawyers argued that to
impeach Clinton on the basis on the evidence now arrayed against
him would set a dangerous precedent. It would shift the
constitutional balance of powers strongly toward Congress, they
argued, by letting presidential foes on Capitol Hill overthrow a
president on grounds that were solely political.
</P>
<P>
   ''This new impeachment weapon would be a permanent,
extra-constitutional power of Congress,'' the lawyers asserted, ''a
poison arrow aimed permanently at the heart of the Presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   Should the Judiciary Committee approve any articles of
impeachment, those articles would then go to the full House for
debate and a floor vote, possibly as early as next week. The Senate
would conduct a trial on any articles approved by the full House. A
conviction in the Senate, which would require a two-thirds majority
vote, would result in Clinton's removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
