A9495 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-STRATEGY-HNS &LR;      12-08 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-STRATEGY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON DEFENSE WITNESSES QUERIED ON PERJURY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
and NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican members of the House Judiciary Committee
aggressively pressed White House defense witnesses Tuesday about
whether President Clinton lied under oath about his relationship
with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   But despite intense and repeated questioning, White House
counsel Greg Craig refused to budge on the perjury issue as GOP
lawmakers sought to justify what will almost certainly be a
decision later this week to recommend impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an effort by the president to testify accurately but
not to disclose information about his relationship. That may be
blameworthy, it may be wrong. You may judge that he crossed the
line. But in fact there is no testimony, no proof, that President
Clinton knew he was wrong ... and intentionally lied,'' Craig
insisted.
</P>
<P>
   His testimony Monday opened two days of hearings in which
Clinton's lawyers, former members of Congress, constitutional
scholars and historians will try to head off GOP efforts to force a
vote by the full House next week on whether Clinton should be
impeached. The panel is expected to vote out some form of
impeachment resolution by week's end that would require a special
session of the lame-duck 105th Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In their questioning of Craig and other Clinton witnesses, the
21 Republicans on the judiciary panel generally ignored the legal
and historical arguments against impeachment to emphasize their
assertion that ``the facts'' of the Lewinsky scandal clearly show
the president knowingly lied under oath and ought to be removed
from office because of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did he lie to the American people when he said `I never had
sex with that woman?''' asked Rep. Robert Inglis, R-S.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't believe that he did. He does not believe that he
lied,'' Craig said, though he admitted Clinton's testimony may have
been ``evasive, incomplete, misleading, even maddening ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``How could his testimony be those things without being a lie?``
asked Rep. Elton Gallegly, R-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Inglis later added: ``There's nothing new here ... the score is
zero facts and zero evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Republicans focused much of their questioning on the
grave nature of perjury and protecting the rule of law, Democrats
on the committee and the White House defense team contended that
the allegations against the president do not amount to impeachable
offenses and that Clinton truly regrets his actions.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic defense is aimed more at undecided Republicans
still home in their districts than at committee members. Only five
Republicans have announced against impeachment so far, but the
White House took heart from a CNN report that veteran Rep. Amo
Houghton, R-N.Y., will announce his opposition Wednesday at a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   The White House also will call moderate Republican William Weld,
the former Massachusetts governor and former Justice Department
attorney under President Reagan, as a witness. The White House
evidently hopes Weld will sway wavering Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The defense strategy is also directed at the American people
whom many Democrats fear have lost track of the proceedings during
this holiday season. Public opinion surveys show two-thirds of the
people oppose impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Marty Meehan, D-Mass., noted the committee vote favoring
impeachment was ``a foregone conclusion'' regardless of the
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``The will of the people is about to be ignored in the hope that
the people won't care enough to say anything,'' said Meehan, adding
the testimony is important to help sway the 20 to 30 undecided
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just came in from California last night, and people at home,
many of them, were asking me when is this going to be wound up?
They thought it was over, and people are getting ready for the
holidays,'' said Rep. Zoe Lofgren, D-Calif. ``So I think this
hearing today is very important in terms of informing not just the
committee and the House, but the American public that something is
actually happening.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House appeared to be caught off guard last week as it
became clearer that the move toward impeachment by the full House
was gaining momentum. The impeachment amounts to an indictment that
would force a trial to be held in the Senate to determine whether
Clinton should be removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   After their surprisingly strong showing in the Nov. 3 elections,
the Democrats appeared to have quashed the impeachment push,
interpreting their success to mean the public wants to put the
year-long sex scandal behind them.
</P>
<P>
   But an all-or-nothing strategy by Republicans and complaints of
Clinton's continued arrogance revived the impeachment movement. Led
by House Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, who has refused to consider any
compromise punishment such as censure, impeachment proponents have
gained enough strength to make a vote of the full House too close
to call.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
