<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9504 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-INSURANCE-RATES-     12-08 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-INSURANCE-RATES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas lowers auto rate standard
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ The lowering of a key factor in the price Texans pay
for auto insurance could signal another round of rate cuts next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance Commissioner Elton Bomer, who's preparing to leave
office to become a senior aide to Republican Gov. George W. Bush,
Tuesday lowered the statewide auto insurance benchmark rate 5.5
percent, effective Feb. 15.
</P>
<P>
   In Travis County, the benchmark rate will drop up to 7.2
percent. That maximum drop would be for typical drivers who buy the
required level of liability insurance and optional insurance to
protect themselves from underinsured and uninsured drivers. The 7.2
percent cut means the benchmark rate would drop from $363 to $337
for those drivers.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Department of Insurance defines a typical driver as a
man 25 to 64 or woman 21 to 64 with no at-fault wrecks or major
traffic convictions who generally drives to and from work.
</P>
<P>
   The statewide benchmark rate is an average of benchmark rates
set in more than 50 auto insurance territories in Texas. Insurers
use those rates to help determine the rates they charge their
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Bomer said he lowered the statewide benchmark rate _ and most of
the underlying territorial benchmark rates _ because the amount of
money insurers pay in claims continues to ``lag well behind'' the
money they collect to pay for those claims. He said fewer lawsuits,
safer cars, less drunken driving and other factors have reduced the
number and cost of claims. Insurance premiums must be lowered to
reflect that, Bomer said, echoing consumer groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to close this gap so that consumers don't pay too much
for their car insurance,'' the commissioner said. ``All the
evidence justifies a substantial rate reduction that still should
leave the companies a fair profit on their Texas business.''
</P>
<P>
   While the benchmark rates are a key factor in each company's
rates, their lowering doesn't mean every company will lower rates
or do so at an equal pace. Bomer and consumer advocates urge
consumers to shop around and compare rates.
</P>
<P>
   Regulated auto insurers, who cover the majority of cars in
Texas, can set their rates 30 percent above to 30 percent below the
state-set benchmark in each area. After the new state rates take
effect in February, companies will have 30 days to file their own
rates.
</P>
<P>
   When companies filed their rates last year _ after Bomer lowered
the statewide benchmark by 5 percent _ the commissioner and
Insurance Department officials persuaded many companies to further
reduce rates, saying the rates they filed remained too high based
on the number and costs of claims.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Slivinske, a spokeswoman for the trade group Texas
Insurance Organization, said that while the cost of some types of
claims has fallen, other costs have gone up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commissioner's decision failed to set an adequate
benchmark rate for the Texas marketplace,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Johns, president of Southwestern Insurance Information
Service, another industry group, said the entire benchmark rating
system should be replaced because it relies on old information.
</P>
<P>
   ``The information on which the commissioner's decision was based
is not a true reflection of what is going on in the auto insurance
market today,'' Johns said. ``The auto benchmark decision today was
based on data 18 months to 2 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   In the upcoming legislative session, which will begin Jan. 12,
insurers are expected to back proposals to replace the benchmark
system with one that allows companies to set their rates without
regard to a state rate. The department would be able to take action
against companies if the rates filed appeared excessive.
</P>
<P>
   Elizondo writes for the Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
