<HEADER>
A9511 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLOVES-AD-COLUMN-695&AMP;     12-08 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLOVES-AD-COLUMN-695&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: A CO-CHAIRMAN OF LOWE STEPS DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Marvin Sloves, a consummate ``suit'' with a strong
creative sensibility, who has been one of the leading figures on
Madison Avenue since the 1960s, is stepping down at the shop that
he helped to expand substantially in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Sloves, 65, who has worked on the account-management side of
agencies from Leo Burnett Co. to Scali, McCabe, Sloves to Lowe &AMP;
Partners/SMS, will retire on Dec. 31 from Lowe, part of the Lowe
Group unit of Interpublic Group of Cos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this is the time to go,'' Sloves said Tuesday in a
telephone interview. ``As I write at the end of every memo, onward
and upward.''
</P>
<P>
   In his four years as co-chairman at Lowe, based in New York, the
agency has more than doubled its billings, to $740 million from
$300 million, and opened an office in San Francisco. Lowe has
attracted accounts like Eddie Bauer, Excite, Heineken USA, KPMG
Peat Marwick and Sun Microsystems, while expanding relationships
with big clients like Coca-Cola, Gillette and Mercedes-Benz of
North America, a unit of DaimlerChrysler.
</P>
<P>
   Sloves is relinquishing his post as co-chairman with the
expiration of a two-year extension on what had originally been a
three-year contract that he signed in 1993. Beginning Jan. 1,
Sloves will serve as a consultant to Lee Garfinkel, co-chairman of
Lowe, who is also the agency's chief creative officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will still be involved with the agency as chairman emeritus
and as a counselor and adviser to Lee for at least two years,''
Sloves said.
</P>
<P>
   Garfinkel, 43, will become the sole chairman as Sloves retires.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to maintain what we've created,'' said Garfinkel,
who joined Sloves for the interview, ``and keep pushing the
envelope.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been speculation in trade publications like The
Delaney Report that Sloves, a robust man who clearly still relishes
the advertising business, had discussed with Frank Lowe, chairman
and chief executive at Lowe Group, staying on at Lowe beyond Dec.
31.
</P>
<P>
   Sloves, asked whether he sought to continue as co-chairman for
at least a little longer, replied: ``No, no, no, I never really
thought about it. It was the end of my contract. We mutually felt,
the company and myself, that this is a good time for me to stop
helping Lee run the company operationally.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe praised Sloves effusively in a statement, calling him ``one
of the legends of our industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Sloves joined Lowe as a vice chairman in November 1993 when Lowe
Group acquired Scali, McCabe, a well-known creative New York
agency, from WPP Group PLC. Scali, McCabe, which created
cutting-edge campaigns for brands like Perdue chicken and Volvo
automobiles, was merged to form Lowe &AMP; Partners/SMS.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen months later, near the end of a tough year for the
merged agency, Sloves and Garfinkel, who had also been a vice
chairman, were named co-chairmen.
</P>
<P>
   The assumption by Sloves of day-to-day responsibilities with
Garfinkel played a large part in re-energizing and turning around
Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had an extraordinary four years,'' Sloves said.
</P>
<P>
   Sloves recalled that his first job in advertising was in Chicago
``in approximately 1960, in the research department at Burnett, as
an assistant research analyst on, of all things, Marlboro
cigarettes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to report every single Friday to Leo Burnett himself,''
Sloves added, ``because he was very involved with Marlboro.''
</P>
<P>
   Sloves relocated to New York in about 1963, working for such
agencies as Ted Bates Advertising and Papert, Koenig, Lois. He and
a group of employees from Papert, Koenig started Scali, McCabe
along with the copywriter Ed McCabe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to sound like I'm living in the past, but if I
were a client, what I would want is personal attention from my
agency, someone who will die if I don't do well and cheer if I do
well,'' Sloves said. ``That's missing from the advertising business
as it gets conglomeratized and bureaucratized.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And I've always felt that successful agencies are agencies
that grow from within,'' he added, ``not only wooing new business,
which is part salesmanship, but being rewarded by clients with more
business.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sloves has been especially close to executives at Mercedes-Benz,
an account that Scali, McCabe landed in 1992 to replace Volvo, and
resigned after a scandal involving a faked commercial. The account
came to Lowe with the merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's here because of me,'' Sloves demurred.
``It's here because the agency does all the work for Mercedes, soup
to nuts: sales promotion, television, direct marketing, media.''
</P>
<P>
   Before joining Lowe in 1992, Garfinkel, a copywriter with a dry
wit, who began in advertising in 1978, worked on accounts like
Subaru and Pepsi-Cola at Levine, Huntley, Schmidt &AMP; Beaver in New
York and the BBDO New York unit of Omnicom Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``In no way do I think I embark on this journey alone,''
Garfinkel said, referring to his duties as the sole chairman.
``Over the last year, more executives have been taking on more
managing duties.'' They include Gary Goldsmith, vice chairman and
executive creative director; Robert Kantor, president for U.S.
operations, and Alan Jurmain, executive director for media
services.
</P>
<P>
   As for reports that Garfinkel's name is to be added to the
agency's, there are no immediate plans for this to be done. That's
adspeak for something that will happen fairly soon.
</P>
<P>
   Sloves is not the only longtime agency executive to announce
retirement plans in recent days. Jack Cohen, a specialist in print
and outdoor media, will retire on Jan. 1 after 41 years in
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, 64, has been director for print and outdoor media buying
at DDB Needham Worldwide in New York, a unit of the Omnicom Group,
since 1983, working for such clients as Amtrak, Hershey Foods and
Mobil. Cohen joined a DDB Needham predecessor, Doyle Dane Bernbach,
in 1960, and before that spent three years at the old Cunningham &AMP;
Walsh agency.
</P>
<P>
   DDB Needham has named no successor to Cohen, who will continue
as a member of the board of a media organization known as the
Certified Audit of Circulation.
</P>
<P>
   Though Sloves and Garfinkel will no longer be co-chairmen at
Lowe, there is a tie they will always share.
</P>
<P>
   Sloves, who has a collection of boxing memorabilia inspired by
his father, Herman Sloves, who fought under the name Johnny Murray,
was looking one day at a list of his father's fights, Garfinkel
said, ``when I said, `Let's see if Marvin's father ever fought my
uncle.'''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Garfinkel said, his uncle, Jack Gritzhandler, who fought
under the name Jack Gritz, once boxed Sloves' father in the
mid-1920s, ``and his father knocked my uncle out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-98 2157EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
