<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKI CROWD POLES APART FROM NORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BY BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As much as I like cold weather, part of me wishes it hadn't been
so chilly Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Then we would have found out whether the people who filed into
the Orpheum Theatre in downtown Phoenix to see Warren Miller's
``Freeriders'' would have decked themselves out in ski-lodge finery
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   I'm guessing they would have. Miller's 49th annual
ski-and-snowboarding movie played over the weekend at the Orpheum
and at Gammage Auditorium in Tempe. Miller's movies have a rabid
following; I was curious to find out just who goes and, more
importantly, why.
</P>
<P>
   They're not really movies in the traditional sense in that they
don't have plots (although you could say the same thing about Adam
Sandler movies). They're more like ski-themed travelogues with
MTV-like production. That means a soundtrack filled with bands of
the moment (``Freeriders,'' for instance, includes music by the
Samples and the extremely overrated Dave Matthews Band).
</P>
<P>
   In addition, they're also nearly ski trade shows with lots of
sponsors on hand and plenty of prizes given away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won something just walking in the door,'' Doug Terrell of
Phoenix said. Naturally, he already owned a pair of goggles, so he
gave his prize to friends.
</P>
<P>
   GETTING `JAZZED'
</P>
<P>
   Terrell attended last year's movie, as did everyone else I spoke
with.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a snowboarder of 14 years,'' he explained. ``You rarely
get to see it on a big screen.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right about that. This made once by my count.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, the look of the crowd surprised me _ scads of fleece
pullovers and multicolored sweaters, a real ski look. I figured
with snowboarders you'd find skateboardlike fashions. Yet I saw
only one kid wearing the chain for a bathtub stopper as a necklace
and pants baggy enough in which to hide a VW Beetle.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Linda Ahumada of Scottsdale, who wore a navy
business suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted to look good,'' she said of herself and her
husband, Ron (multicolored sweater). They were there with their
teenage sons and talked about the movie as if it were a
motivational film.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really gets you jazzed,'' she said. ``After we leave, we
can't wait to go skiing.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, I figured I'm game. I have an open mind. So I watched, and
although the movie was entertaining enough, what with expert skiers
slicing down mind-bending runs on snow so fresh it looked like
great mounds of whipped cream while high-adrenaline rock blared
away, I could tell by the energy in the room that I just didn't
quite . . . get it.
</P>
<P>
   I realized the problem right away. To me, skiing is _ I know
this is going to sound ridiculous _ a recreational activity. To
this crowd, it's pretty much a religion. It's like Bob Costas and
baseball, only with cooler clothes and weirder haircuts.
</P>
<P>
   BEING `ON THE EDGE'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost cultish, in a good sense,'' Carol Brown said.
She's 51 and a skier, as is her son, David, 16. David, in fact, is
an ``extreme'' skier, as were most of the skiers and snowboarders
in the movie _ extreme in this case apparently a synonym for
``having little sense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the best of the best,'' David gushed. ``It's who you
want to be like.''
</P>
<P>
   His mom explained the appeal of the movies: ``Wouldn't it be
nice to be on the edge, just for a little while?''
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely. But as I explained to my wife, with the right music
and camera work and narration, you could produce an exciting movie
about making ham sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's something about skiing,'' she said, staring at the
screen with a faraway look in her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Egad, she was one of them, too! I felt like Kevin McCarthy in
``Invasion of the Body Snatchers.'' ``They're here already! You're
next!'' I screamed, only not really, because tickets were $13 and
that would have been rude.
</P>
<P>
   Oh well, could have been worse. They may be nuts over skiing.
But at least they dress well.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at 444-8828, or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
