<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9530 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-H     12-08 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
LOGICALLY, the NBA's All-Star Game had to go, and so it went
Wednesday, leaving Philadelphia in a lurch.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, Philly. This is war. Say a prayer for peace while you
figure out how, on short notice, to make up for the millions in
lost economic impact.
</P>
<P>
   You could always pawn the Liberty Bell, or perhaps, if you ask
nicely, the players will hold a benefit on your behalf, too, after
they take care of their poverty-stricken brethren.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, staging an All-Star Game five or six weeks into a
thrown-together season would have been pretty silly. But
symbolically, at least, the stakes of the ongoing lockout _ 23
weeks old and counting _ just got elevated to a new level by its
inevitable cancellation.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, we have real consequences. The NBA's deputy
commissioner, Russ Granik, called the star showcase ``the only
landmark left,'' and, yikes, raised the specter of the whole
season's being lost.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some folks might call that a blessing, considering
how the only season that matters is the one that starts at the end
of April, never mind how expensive attending those preceding 82
exhibition games has become.
</P>
<P>
   But I suppose it would be difficult to begin the playoffs
without some kind of preliminary knockout competition to establish
the seedings.
</P>
<P>
   While common sense, as well as the historical record of the
other sports' labor battles, dictates a solution will be reached
before Armageddon, there remains no tangible evidence that either
the players or the owners are capable of compromising enough to
forge a settlement. And compromise _ by definition, a major meeting
of the minds requiring true concessions _ is the only way out of
the canyon-sized hole into which they've dug themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Two truths are self-evident if the NBA is going to resume
playing:
</P>
<P>
   The players can't be guaranteed any more than 50 percent of the
gross revenues. Why? Because they don't deserve any more, or less,
than that. Period.
</P>
<P>
   The owners can't put anything approaching a hard cap on
salaries. Why? The players know the equity value of the franchises
is increasing at 20 percent to 25 percent a year. If an owner can't
control his costs, he can always sell the business and still make
out like Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   So market forces must be allowed to do their thing. If the
league's revenues continue to grow, then both sides will be happy
together. If they don't, then both sides will have to cry on each
other's shoulders. Very simple stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Every day that passes, however, threatens near-term profit
margins for everybody, and the latter sobathon scenario becomes a
more likely long-term outcome. By and large, fans haven't missed
the NBA, because of an extra-interesting football season and the
fact that since the thump-thumpers never began to play, nobody has
any emotional investment in what hasn't been.
</P>
<P>
   How many of you truly care about the NBA in November and
December under the best of circumstances?
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, when baseball shut down cold in 1994, a crescendo
finish to the season was beckoning. There were hot races raging in
both leagues and individual battles galore. The customers felt
robbed, cheated and deprived. The anger from coast to coast was
extreme.
</P>
<P>
   The World Series would be lost, and baseball wouldn't be
completely well again for four seasons, when a pair of burly
populists hellbent on erasing poor Roger Maris from the record book
assured the sport a full recovery just this past summer.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to say how much time basketball will need to overcome
its losses, financial as well as emotional. The NBA was already
experiencing an image slump before the lockout because of a glut of
dreadful teams and the general insolence of its twentysomething
superstars, most of whom show no appreciation for lives so
wonderful they would move Jimmy Stewart to tears.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they probably couldn't care less about the financial
hardship being incurred by those who don't deserve it and can least
afford it: The ordinary people who supplement working-class incomes
by moonlighting at the arenas selling popcorn, securing the doors,
etc. They're the ones who deserve to be the beneficiaries of
``charity'' games.
</P>
<P>
   Fat chance.
</P>
<P>
   Alonzo Mourning, amazingly, would like us to believe we have no
understanding of the extent of the players' financial obligations,
as though they're the only ones with mortgages to pay, kids to feed
and cars to maintain. Never mind that their weekly paychecks, by
and large, come in five- or even six-figure chunks.
</P>
<P>
   Any NBA player who has spent three or more years in the league
even at or near its minimum wage should _ should _ have established
a solid financial base. His core needs should be well-covered, more
so than probably 95 percent of the real world's work force.
</P>
<P>
   If he has wasted his money, that's his fault. Nobody is entitled
to be set for life after just a few years of child's play
marginally disguised as honest labor.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the owners have been such pillars of decorum
themselves. They appear as out of touch with reality as the punk
element, considerable proof of which can be found in letters such
as the ones Rockets season-ticket holders received offering them
the golden opportunity to roll their lockout refunds over into down
payments on next year's tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Surely none of you is letting Leslie Alexander keep your money,
on which he has been earning interest since midsummer. If you have,
you are also part of the problem here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-98 2209EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
