<SLUG> BC-DAMATO-IMPEACH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D'AMATO URGES REPUBLICANS TO VOTE AGAINST IMPEACHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At a farewell party given by his staff, Sen.
Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., said Tuesday night that it would be ``a
grave mistake'' for the Republican Party and the nation if the
House impeached President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato, who after 18 years in the Senate was defeated last
month by Democratic Rep. Charles Schumer, led Whitewater hearings
in the Senate two years ago that were sharply critical of the
president, Hillary Rodham Clinton, and many of their top aides.
</P>
<P>
   During the Senate race, D'Amato refused to state his views about
the impeachment referral. Polls show New Yorkers overwhelmingly
oppose the removal of Clinton, and on Tuesday D'Amato said for the
first time that he agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not suggesting that we ignore the misdeeds of the
president,'' D'Amato said. ``But I am suggesting that we look to
what the people are saying. I'm not saying we give the president a
gold star. But for the Senate to spend weeks and weeks mired in
this doesn't make sense. If we want to be a unified national party
and have a country that is unified, we have to get this behind
us.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said House approval of any articles of impeachment
``would result in great and unnecessary discord.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-98 2210EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981208.0397 </DOCNO>
