<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCIAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Powerless Pacific Exchange  &HT;       
 By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
The lights dimmed and the computers crashed at the Pacific Exchange
yesterday, halting stock and options trading for the day and
leaving the city's bourse as the Financial District's main casualty
of the power interruption.
</P>
<P>
   Other financial institutions in areas that lost power, such as
discount broker Charles Schwab in downtown San Francisco and mutual
fund giant Franklin Resources in San Mateo, shrugged off the
interruption of electrical service, relying on backup sources of
power or routing business to unaffected facilities.
</P>
<P>
   At the brokerage firm Hambrecht &AMP; Quist, the San Francisco stock
trading room stayed in operation supported by a diesel generator.
At BancBoston Robertson Stephens, though, trading was cut back when
the firm was forced to switch to backup power, a spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Several institutions, including Franklin and Wells Fargo Bank,
no longer have their most vital data operations in the Bay Area,
having moved facilities to seismically stable areas after the 1989
Loma Prieta earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   Among banks, Bank of America, Wells Fargo and many smaller
institutions closed branches in affected areas, and ATMs stopped
functioning without electricity. But major banks have located their
back office operations and data centers outside the city. With
power unaffected at those facilities, the banks were able to
restore service quickly in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Pacific Exchange were at a loss to explain why
their operations failed when most other major financial
institutions continued to function.
</P>
<P>
   ``People told us this couldn't happen,'' said Robert Greber, the
exchange's chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Greber said the exchange was connected to three separate power
grids, which should have provided backup power.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been assured that our power was redundant and there was
no need for an uninterrupted power supply,'' Greber stressed.
``This is really a black eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Greber said the exchange will add a backup power source outside
the prime electrical grid when it revamps its options exchange
floor in connection with its pending merger with the Chicago Board
Options Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   On the exchange's options trading floor, normally a frenzy of
activity as traders try to outshout each other to buy and sell
stock options contracts, business screeched to a halt shortly after
8 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Computer screens flickered ``as the generators tried to kick in,
and then everything went dead,'' said Ted Thomsen, an exchange
employee. ``Everybody cheered because they thought they could go
home.''
</P>
<P>
   The exchange routed stock trades to its Los Angeles trading
floor. But buying and selling of the 800 stock options issues
handled in San Francisco stopped altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific Exchange handles an average of 18 million shares of
stock and more than 200,000 options contracts a day, spokesman
Morrison Shafroth said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm losing money because I can't get commissions when I don't
trade,'' said an options broker, who declined to give his name,
waiting outside the exchange on Montgomery Street. ``And my
customers are out there doing business with another broker.''
</P>
<P>
   At Schwab, backup power sources provided electricity at the
firm's downtown headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's telephone service centers are located outside San
Francisco except for a few specialized business units, such as the
one that handles active traders. Calls were routed to facilities in
Phoenix and Indianapolis, spokeswoman Tracey Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   BankAmerica didn't consider the outage serious enough to
activate its disaster recovery plan designed for major calamities.
While 20 area branches and 180 ATMs shut down when power went out,
few data or back office facilities were hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a printer in our automated clearing house that was not
working,'' said Jack Arrington, the bank's chief of data operations
in the West, about the San Francisco unit that handles electronic
payments for corporate customers. ``We were able to print the
information at an alternate site.''
</P>
<P>
   Credit card giant Visa, based in Foster City, may have found the
ultimate solution to power blackouts. Visa would face disaster if
its worldwide processing of credit card payments were interrupted.
</P>
<P>
   The outage ''had absolutely no implications,'' said Kristina
Scott, a Visa spokeswoman. ``We have our own power and we're not on
utility power.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
