<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEVRON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Web Site Says Shell May Buy Chevron   By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
A Dutch Web site reported Monday that Royal Dutch/Shell plans to
acquire San Francisco's Chevron for $65 billion, generating jitters
at the oil company's headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   A Chevron representative had no comment on the rumor, which was
reported on  &LR; www.dutchstocks.com &LR; , a Web site that tracks Dutch
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street shrugged off the rumor, and Chevron shares rose just
25 cents to $82.44 yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   But coming in the wake of last week's giant Exxon-Mobil merger
announcement, the rumor could not be dismissed, either by Chevron
employees or oil industry analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Although the story was not widely reported in the United States,
analyst Albert Anton of Carl. H. Pforzheimer &AMP; Co. in New York said
he had seen the same speculation in a trade publication he declined
to name. He also said several clients had called to ask him whether
he considered such a deal likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course anything could happen, but a Royal
Dutch/Shell-Chevron combination would have problems,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among them would be the fact that Royal Dutch/Shell is a
holding company owned 60 percent by Netherlands-based Royal Dutch
and 40 percent by London-based Shell.
</P>
<P>
   So a stock swap with Chevron would be a very complex merger, in
which Chevron shareholders would have to accept some Royal Dutch
and some Shell shares.
</P>
<P>
   A cash transaction would be simpler, but Anton said the European
giant might not want to borrow the $65 billion it would take to
swallow Chevron, which has a current market value of roughly $54
billion.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Chevron and Shell have competing gas stations in
California and across the Southern United States, a fact sure to
invite antitrust scrutiny at the Federal Trade Commission, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, analysts could not conclusively debunk the possibility
of such a deal, given other mergers and the drop in crude oil
prices, which have squeezed industry profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chevron has been pretty vague about how it is going to
respond'' to these conditions, said Brian Eisenbarth with Collins &AMP;
Co. in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron, which employs 34,000 worldwide and 8,300 in the Bay
Area, is already one of the world's lowest-cost oil producers,
Eisenbarth said. Other companies are merging to bring down their
cost of oil production. Still, if oil mergers continue and Chevron
doesn't get hitched, ``they might get left behind,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Royal Dutch/Shell rumor, other unconfirmed reports
had Chevron pairing up with Atlantic Richfield or Texaco.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron has not commented on those rumors either. ``It is our
long-standing policy not to comment on rumors or speculation about
anything that may or may not be under consideration,'' spokeswoman
Dawn Soper said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Dutch Web site, Royal Dutch/Shell would offer
about $100 per share for Chevron at a December 14 analyst meeting
in London.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Dutch is scheduled to meet with analysts in New York on
the same day, said one industry watcher. Chevron is scheduled to
brief analysts on December 16, the source said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be sheer coincidence, but it means top officials
from both companies will be in the city at about the same time,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-98 2215EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
