<DOCNO> NYT19981208.0405 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9546 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-SFCHRON &LR;      12-08 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
  
 Why Wall Street Should Dim the Lights on PG&AMP;E Stock, Teach It
a  Lesson  By Mark Veverka  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Perhaps investors should short-circuit PG&AMP;E stock.
</P>
<P>
   If America Online goes down for hours at a time, its stock
generally gets jolted. But when the power company turns out the
lights on one of the biggest cities in the country, its shares go
sideways. Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   Even though PG&AMP;E's own incompetence brought San Francisco to a
screeching halt for about four hours, PG&AMP;E shares went unpunished
by closing at $32.19, down a mere 13 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Is that any way to rail against the power company when they turn
off the juice?
</P>
<P>
   It's not as though some act of God, such as a terrifying temblor
or wicked storm system, ripped through the utility's
infrastructure. Yesterday's debacle was caused by human screw-up.
Sure, people make mistakes; we all make mistakes. (Need I mention
how many of mine you point out regularly?) But a major utility with
a $13 billion market-capitalization ought to have systems and
safeguards in place that make this kind of failure rare and
infrequent.
</P>
<P>
   What if a couple of United Airline pilots just kind of messed up
and smashed a Boeing 727 into the side of Mount Tamalpais? I
suppose that airline's public relations spin meisters would only
have to say: ``Oops. S_ happens. A couple of our employees made a
mistake.'' I just don't think that would fly, so to speak.
</P>
<P>
   But we have been conditioned by utility companies to put up and
shut up. Last year, there seemed to be in inordinate number of
power outages in my particular neighborhood in San Francisco.
PG&AMP;E's most-often used excuse was that a certain substation in our
energy grid was being sabotaged. Sure, from time to time, nut cases
will slash lines, flip switches or do whatever they do. But after
more than a few instances, a bill-paying consumer yearns for
reliable service. After a while, it gets old having to empty the
refrigerator every time the power company fails to deliver its
product.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer choice can't come soon enough. California supposedly is
on the vanguard of energy deregulation, eventually leading to a
break-up of the monopolies that provide our gas and electricity.
</P>
<P>
   However, consumers won't have total choice. PaineWebber
financial analyst Barry Abramson in New York reminds us that a
monopoly still will control the power lines and infrastructure that
deliver the energy to our homes and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Still), it's not as though you will have no recourse. There
will be penalties (meted by regulators) for bad care of lines and
infrastructure,'' Abramson says.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, economic fines might have an impact on a utility's
profit and loss statement. Of course, yesterday's blackout is
likely to have little bearing on the financial performance of
PG&AMP;E's stock. But it seems less than a coincidence to know that
Wall Street doesn't think much of PG&AMP;E shares.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 18 financial analysts that follow the stock, not one but
two of them actually recommend that their clients ``sell'' the
shares, and a whopping 12 analysts rate PG&AMP;E a ``hold,'' according
to Bloomberg.
</P>
<P>
   Financial analyst Robin Diedrich of Edward Jones in St. Louis is
one of the bears that has slapped PG&AMP;E with a ``sell.''
</P>
<P>
   While she is ``fairly positive'' on the energy utility group,
Diedrich says she is bearish on PG&AMP;E because it has been earning
fewer profits than California guidelines allow.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, investment in PG&AMP;E has lagged behind that of its
peers. The value of the Dow Jones Utilities index has increased
about 23.4 percent during the past 12 months, including dividends,
compared with only a 17.6 percent rise for PG&AMP;E shares, Diedrich
says.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, PG&AMP;E shares are surrounded by uncertainty because
the utility is in the midst of a rate-hike request before the state
Public Utilities Commission, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that (PG&AMP;E) still has some issues before them,''
Diedrich says.
</P>
<P>
   Such as getting affordable power to its customers on a regular
basis.
</P>
<P>
   GUSHER: Is Chevron in play? As suggested in this column last
week, the San Francisco energy giant is ripe for a merger. A Dutch
Web site is reporting that Royal Dutch-Shell is negotiating to buy
Chevron in a $65 billion stock swap. But if this deal isn't real,
consolidation in the energy patch still seems inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(at sign)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
