<HEADER>
A9548 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CASSTEVENS-COLUMN     12-08 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CASSTEVENS-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAPPY ENDINGS NEED $2.74 A DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing hasn't said which players will receive the
proceeds from an exhibition game scheduled Dec. 19 in Atlantic
City.
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, the president of the NBA players union does not
want to embarrass those who are ``in need.''
</P>
<P>
   But they are out there.
</P>
<P>
   The faceless, the forgotten, the forlorn.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Or Ewing, for that matter. The Knicks center figures he will
survive the owners' lockout, even though he is losing $244,000 per
game. His concern is for others, the less fortunate. He has seen
them around Times Square, standing in the cold holding signs that
read, ``Will Dunk For Food. God Bless You.''
</P>
<P>
   What will happen to (itals)them (end itals)?
</P>
<P>
   The NBA average salary is $2.6 million. But many players earn
much less. Those making the NBA minimum had to live on $272,500
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with no regular income, some players who are accustomed to
living well _ ``We have a lot of expenses,'' Alonzo Mourning said _
apparently have fallen on what the real world calls Hard Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at people who play pro sports, not a lot of them
are financially secure,'' Ewing said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how much money they've made throughout their
careers, if they're in need now, it's up to us to try to help
them.''
</P>
<P>
   So players will stage a kind of all-star game, near the casinos.
The exhibition will replace the real NBA All-Star Game, which was
canceled Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Some money will go to charity. The rest will be distributed to
the NBA needy.
</P>
<P>
   A $1,000 donation _ the price of a courtside seat _ figures out
to $2.74 a day for a year.
</P>
<P>
   That small love offering could go a long way toward saving an
NBA player who grows more anxious and depressed with each passing
day.
</P>
<P>
   Will there be gifts under the tree?
</P>
<P>
   How many players may look into a child's big round eyes and say,
``Sweetheart, I'm not sure we'll have Christmas this year . . .''?
</P>
<P>
   It breaks your heart.
</P>
<P>
   But you can help by attending the game. (Please bring a can of
food, or a toy.) Or you can support the cause by upgrading your
cable TV package and watching the game on Showtime.
</P>
<P>
   Now and then, life imitates art. The plight of
down-on-their-luck NBA players brings to mind the Frank Capra movie
classic we enjoy every holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   George Bailey is a 6-foot-9 forward at tiny Bedford Falls
College. George quits school after his junior year. The Golden
State Warriors sign him to a three-year, $4.1 million contract with
an extension that will pay him $20 million a year over the next six
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly wealthy beyond his dreams, George buys a Mercedes for
himself and a Jaguar for his wife, Mary. Everyone remarks how she
looks like Donna Reed.
</P>
<P>
   They put a down payment on a $1.4 million home with a tennis
court and pool.
</P>
<P>
   They purchase three kids.
</P>
<P>
   And a small boat.
</P>
<P>
   And a cabin in Vail.
</P>
<P>
   It's a wonderful life.
</P>
<P>
   Then one day, the greedy owners crunch the numbers and decide
the players are making too much money, so they impose a lockout.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey's paychecks stop. The bills keep coming.
</P>
<P>
   George hocks his Rolex and sells his golf clubs through the want
ads.
</P>
<P>
   One morning while he's finishing breakfast, the last Pop Tart, a
repo man tows his Mercedes. Next day, Mary's Jag disappears.
</P>
<P>
   The house gone, the family moves into the boat.
</P>
<P>
   George becomes despondent. He wishes he had never been born.
</P>
<P>
   On Christmas Eve, at wit's end, George decides to jump off the
Golden Gate Bridge, but suddenly Mary appears in the mist waving a
check _ his cut of the proceeds from a benefit game staged by NBA
stars for players in financial need.
</P>
<P>
   George can't believe it.
</P>
<P>
   He weeps, grateful beyond words.
</P>
<P>
   See what $2.74 can do? &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at david.casstevens(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
