<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREDERICKS-FOR-SALE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREDERICK'S OF HOLLYWOOD SELLING DISTINCTIVE BUILDING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The landmark Frederick's of Hollywood building,
Tinseltown's shrine to Lycra, spandex, stiletto heels and feather
boas, now carries a $4.5 million price tag, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The art-deco building at 6608 Hollywood Blvd., with its
distinctive hot-pink awnings, is listed on the National Register of
Historic Places and is home to such trendy products as the H20
water-bra collection and marabou baby-doll nighties inspired by the
hit film comedy ``Austin Powers: International Man of Mystery.''
</P>
<P>
   Frederick's, famous for its catalogs featuring scantily clad
models, alluring window displays and in-store lingerie museum, will
remain a tenant for at least 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The company already has agreed to stay in the office and
warehouse portion of the building for two years and will lease the
boulevard frontage for the next decade, said John Tronson, an agent
with Ramsey-Shilling Co., the real estate company handling the sale
for the clothier.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Frederick's will relocate its office and warehouse
functions to another site yet to be chosen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just decided to kind of test the waters and see if someone
is interested in acquiring the building and leasing it back so we
can maintain our presence here. We don't want to leave the
boulevard because we are Frederick's of Hollywood,'' said Ed
Zorehkey, the company's real estate and retail development
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Built in 1937, the structure is on a half-acre lot and includes
8,100 feet of retail space and a penthouse. Frederick's bought the
building in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Seth Dudley, executive managing director at Julien J. Studley
Inc., a Los Angeles commercial real estate company, said the
building is coming on the market as Hollywood is in a recovery
mode.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since both the east and west ends of Hollywood Boulevard are
getting renovated, I would not be surprised to see some
cutting-edge, Melrose-type retailers moving up to Hollywood,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Studley just negotiated a deal for the House of Blues to move
its corporate headquarters from the 8400 block of Sunset Boulevard
into the Hollywood district.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Tronson said some Hollywood buildings have made
big appreciation gains in the late 1990s. For example, a
300,000-square-foot office building at 6255 Sunset Blvd. that was
bought for $15 million a year ago was sold for $30 million in
September.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is just as much growth in this market remaining,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
