<P>
   (NYT21) CROTONVILLE, N.Y. -- Dec. 8, 1998 -- GE-APPOINT, 12-08
-- Dennis Dammerman, standing, and Denis Nayden, pose during a
recent meeting. Both will be heading up GE Capital, the huge
financial-services arm of the General Electric Co. GE Capital,
which consists of 29 businesses ranging from credit cards to truck
leasing, provided about 40 percent of General Electric's profits
last year. (Joyce Dopkeen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) UNDATED -- Dec. 8, 1998 -- ZENECA-ASTRA, 12-08 --
Bottles of Nolvadex, a breast-cancer drug, on a Zeneca plant
assembly line in Delaware. Zeneca Group PLC, the third-largest
British drug maker, and Astra AB of Sweden said Tuesday that they
were discussing a merger that would be worth at least $30 billion
and would create the world's fourth-largest pharmaceutical company.
(Marty Katz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) STAFFORD, Calif. -- Dec. 8, 1998 -- TREE-SITTER, 12-08
-- Julia Hill reads at dusk by candlelight inside a small tent-like
shelter lodged in a giant redwood tree 100 feet above the ground.
in an attempt to save a tree state foresters estimate to be 600
years old from the chain saws of the Pacific Lumber Co., Julia
``Butterfly,'' as she likes to be called, has lived there for
nearly a year. (John Burgess/The Press Democrat)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- Dec. 8, 1998 -- AT&AMP;T-IBM, 12-08 -- Louis
Gerstner, Jr., chairman and CEO of IBM, left, speaks to reporters
as his counterpart at AT&AMP;T, C. Michael Armstrong, looks on during a
news conference at AT&AMP;T headquarters. AT&AMP;T is buying IBM's global
communications network for $5 billion in cash, marking its latest
effort to extend its reach to big business customers. (Librado
Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Dec. 8, 1998 -- BBO-AUCTION, 12-08 -- Mark
McGwire's historic 70th home run ball (shown) will be put up for
bidding early next month by Guernsey's, an auction house in New
York. The ball was hit into the stands in St. Louis by McGwire on
Sept. 27, the final day of a regular season in which McGwire, with
70, and Sammy Sosa of the Chicago Cubs, with 66, both broke Roger
Maris's record of 61 homers, hit in 1961. (Sara Krulwich/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) BETHLEHEM, West Bank -- Dec. 8, 1998 --
PALESTINIAN-PRISONERS, 12-08 -- From bottom left: Amouneh Abed
Rabu, Mazumeh Abu Srur and Aziza al-Hiraimi sit inside a tent
holding portraits of their sons. Since Saturday, they have been
fasting in solidarity with their sons, prisoners on hunger strike
in Israeli jails. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) CHICAGO -- Dec. 8, 1998 -- CHICAGO-DALEY, 12-08 --
Chicago Mayor Richard Daley signs autographs at a school earlier
this week. Daley, who has run this rough-edged, electric city for
nearly a decade, declared that in 1999 he will try to win election
as mayor for the fourth time. (Todd Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) GHAZIABAD, India -- Dec. 8, 1998 -- INDIA-SCHOOLS, 12-08
-- Children in Ghaziabad, in India's most populous state of Uttar
Pradesh, chant the title of the national song, a daily classroom
ceremony that has caused anger among many Muslims. The local Hindu
nationalist government, led by the Bharatiya Janata Party, which is
also in power nationally, set off the conflict when its leaders
proclaimed that recitation of the song should be compulsory in
public schools. (Celia Dugger/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) BOSTON -- Dec. 8, 1998 -- CONCERTS-CELLPHONES, 12-08 --
Mary Judge speaks on her cell phone during a Billy Joel concert in
Boston. Once held aloft as the universal symbol of the magical
unity that a pop concert can create, cigarette lighters are giving
way to the cellular phone. (Evan Richman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) BOSTON -- Dec. 8, 1998 -- GENX-IDEALIST, 12-08 -- From
front row, left, Eric Dawson of Peace Games; Aaron Lieberman of
Jumpstart; Jenny Sazama and Karen Young of Youth on Board;
background from left: Earl Phalen of Bell Foundation; Karilyn
Crockett and Denise Thomas of Mytown; and Katya Fels, with the
group On the Rise. Whoever decided that Generation X is apathetic
and cynical has never met this group. (Tom Herde/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) BOSTON -- Dec. 8, 1998 -- MA-GARRITY-BOS, 12-08 --
Federal Judge Arthur Garrity sits in the jury box in his courtroom.
Twenty-four years after his court order desegregating Boston
schools, Garrity is donating all his papers on the ruling to the
University of Massachusetts at Boston. (Bill Brett/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) HADDO ESTATE, Scotland -- Dec. 8, 1998 --
SCOTLAND-PHEASANTS-2, 12-08 -- Alexander Gordon, Earl of Haddo,
with Lachy, his Labrador, leads pheasant hunters at his Scottish
estate. Workers on the estate have spent months getting ready for
the hunting season where scores of well-dressed shooters pursue
their sport from throughout Europe and the United States. (Jonathan
Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 8, 1998 -- IMPEACH-4, 12-08 -- White
House Special Counsel Gregory Craig testifies before the House
Judiciary Committee on Tuesday. Mustering historical, legal,
philosophical and political arguments, President Clinton's lawyers
assembled a battery of nine witnesses who virtually conceded that
Clinton's behavior was reprehensible, but it did not warrant the
Constitution's most extreme sanction of impeachment. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 8, 1998 -- IMPEACH-3, 12-08 -- From
left: White House Special Counsel Gregory Craig; former Attorney
General Nicholas Katzenbach; Yale Professor Bruce Ackerman;
Princeton University professor Sean Wilentz and Harvard Professor
Samuel Beer, take their oath before testifying before the House
Judiciary Committee on Tuesday. Mustering historical, legal,
philosophical and political arguments, President Clinton's lawyers
assembled a battery of nine witnesses who virtually conceded that
Clinton's behavior was reprehensible, but it did not warrant the
Constitution's most extreme sanction of impeachment. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7)NEW YORK -- Dec. 8, 1998 -- FOOD-NOTES-2, 12-08 -- A
Gingerbread version of New York's Washington Square Arch be
purchased at Grace's Marketplace in Greenwich Village. Using
gingerbread, rather than granite, anyone can be a Donald Trump or
even a Stanford White this season. (Carol Halebian/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) SOUTH BURLINGTON, Vt. -- Dec. 8, 1998 --
ICE-CREAM-TASTER, 12-08 -- Shawna Parizo, sensory analyst for Ben &AMP;
Jerry's Ice Cream, evaluates some samples. Parizo is the person
whose job it is to decide how the ice cream tastes and how to keep
it that way. (Paul O. Boisvert/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5)NEW YORK -- Dec. 8, 1998 -- FOOD-NOTES, 12-08 -- A
Gingerbread version of a Russian Orthodox church can be purchased
at Grace's Marketplace in New York's Greenwich Village. Using
gingerbread, rather than granite, anyone can be a Donald Trump or
even a Stanford White this season. (Carol Halebian/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) HADDO ESTATE, Scotland -- Dec. 8, 1998 --
SCOTLAND-PHEASANTS , 12-08 -- A pheasant hunter takes aim on the
9,000-acre Haddo Estate in Scotland. Workers on the estate have
spent months getting ready for the hunting season where scores of
well-dressed shooters pursue their sport from throughout Europe and
the United States. (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 8, 1998 -- IMPEACH-2, 12-08 -- Former
Attorney General Nicholas Katzenbach looks at a copy of the
Constitution during testimony before the House Judiciary Committee
on Tuesday. Mustering historical, legal, philosophical and
political arguments, President Clinton's lawyers assembled a
battery of nine witnesses, including Katzenbach, who virtually
conceded that Clinton's behavior was reprehensible, but insisted
that it did not warrant the Constitution's most extreme sanction of
impeachment. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) SAN FRANCISCO-- Dec. 8, 1998 -- SANFRAN-BLACKOUT, 12-08
-- Traffic is backed up on the Oakland-Bay Bridge just outside San
Francisco on Tuesday. A power outtage cut off electricity to nearly
a million people Tuesday, creating a traffic nightmare in the city
by the bay. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 8, 1998 --IMPEACH, 12-08 -- President
Clinton listens to a speaker during The White House Conference on
Social Security at a Washington Hotel on Tuesday. While the
conference was taking place, Clinton's lawyers began a two-day
defense before the House Judiciary Committee to persuade waverers
in the House that Clinton's behavior did not merit impeachment.
(Justin Lane/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
