<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9557 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDINALS-REPLAY-     12-08 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-REPLAY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIDWILL, TOBIN SPLIT ON INSTANT RE PLAY  
 BAD CALLS DON'T FAZE CARDS OWNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This instant-replay deal might not be such a bad idea, Cardinals
Coach Vince Tobin said Tuesday after his team was victimized in
three of its past four games by questionable calls.
</P>
<P>
   But even though Tobin supports a movement by the NFL office to
bring an electronic second-look to playoff games this season,
Cardinals owner Bill Bidwill, a longtime opponent of instant
replay, said Tuesday the rash of bad calls against his team has not
caused him to change his stance.
</P>
<P>
   Two other owners who have been longtime opponents, Detroit Lions
owner William Clay Ford and Buffalo Bills owner Ralph Wilson, have
said they are tired of lousy officiating and are likely to vote the
other way this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game should be left on the field,'' Bidwill said.
``Nobody's perfect. Players, coaches, officials, they all make
mistakes. But players don't get a second chance if they drop a
pass. Coaches don't get a second chance to change a call on
third-and-short, unless there's a penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Play the game, the way other sports do.''
</P>
<P>
   Bidwill's continued employment doesn't hinge on a potential
game-turning play being negated by a bum offside call, or a referee
reaching for his flag on an obvious pass interference penalty in
the end zone on the final play of the game and then freezing.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals were denied chances to win their past two home
games by officials' decisions.
</P>
<P>
   First was a no-call against Dallas Cowboys cornerback Kevin
Smith, who was clinging to receiver Rob Moore's chest in the end
zone. Instead of having one final play from one yard away, the
Cardinals lost the critical NFC East showdown, 35-28.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, the Cardinals needed seven points to regain the
lead against the New York Giants. Jake Plummer ran 30 yards on a
quarterback draw to the New York Giants' 3-yard line in the closing
6 minutes. The play was brought back by a phantom offside call
against wide receiver Ronnie Anderson, who says he asked the
official before the snap if he was properly aligned. Anderson was
not involved in the play. The Giants won, 23-19.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, an apparent fourth-quarter touchdown pass from
Plummer to Moore in a tight game at Kansas City was nullified. The
official ruled that Moore was out of bounds. A replay showed that
he was in. The Cardinals later scored to cut their deficit to seven
points, but they used an additional 2{ minutes doing so before
suffering a 10-point loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a proponent of instant replay even though our
organization is against it,'' Tobin said. ``I had experience with
it when I was coaching in the USFL. I liked the opportunity to have
a challenge. I don't have a problem with the challenge system that
some coaches do. If something happens where another look at it
might help rectify it, then I think we should do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL said Monday that it will ask owners to vote on whether
to bring back instant replay for this season's playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin believes the Cardinals have been victimized by officiating
in several other games during his tenure with the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``For three years it seems there have been very, very
controversial pivotal calls, and most have gone against us,'' he
said. ``I keep waiting for it to even out. But I'm sure every team
has a litany of them as well, and I do recognize that it is a very,
very difficult job. There are so many subjective judgments that
have to be made instantaneously.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in our league they are under a lot more scrutiny. On every
call there are a bunch of cameras looking at it from every angle
and a bunch of guys up in the booth who are second-guessing them.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest NFL proposal would permit two challenges per game per
team. It comes in the aftermath of a 32-31 New York Jets' victory
over Seattle on Sunday in which Jets quarterback Vinny Testaverde
was awarded a game-winning touchdown when replays showed he was
tackled short of the goal line. The league issued an apology to the
Seahawks for the blown call.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin said game films also substantiate the Cardinals' claim
that Anderson was lined up correctly on the controversial penalty
against the Giants. The league has not gotten back to the
Cardinals, according to Tobin.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's 25 yards from the ball,'' Tobin said of Anderson. ``It
looks like he's got his foot at or behind the line of scrimmage. He
doesn't move or flinch. And he has no material outcome on the
play.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-98 2224EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
