<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981208.0413 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9559 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NOALLSTARGAME-HNS     12-08 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOALLSTARGAME-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
In an unprecedented move, the NBA on Tuesday announced the
cancellation of the 1999 All-Star Game, which was scheduled to be
played in Philadelphia on Feb. 14. It will be the first season
without an All-Star Game since the showcase event was born in 1951,
the league's second year.
<TEXT>
<P>
   All-Star Weekend, which includes such events as the slam-dunk
contest, the 3-point shootout, the rookie game and the
fan-interactive ``Jam Session,'' is just the latest casualty of the
161-day lockout that has caused the league to cancel 258
regular-season games to date.
</P>
<P>
   Many are beginning to wonder if the season is next, since there
is no end in sight to the lockout and no further bargaining
sessions are scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner David Stern announced the All-Star Game
cancellation, saying it would be ``unfair to the city of
Philadelphia'' to hold out hope that All-Star Weekend might be
salvaged, even if a new labor agreement is reached with the
National Basketball Players Association in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a result of the inexorable march of the
calendar,'' Stern said. ``There just isn't enough time left to have
a season and an All-Star Game. In other words, you would like to
have some kind of season before the All-Star Game, and that's
slipping away from us.
</P>
<P>
   ``So our focus now will be to see whether there is a season
itself to salvage without the All-Star Game. We apologize to the
city of Philadelphia, but we promise to bring the All-Star Weekend
back as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   That wouldn't be until 2002, since next year's game is being
hosted by the Golden State Warriors and the 2001 game is expected
to go to the Washington Wizards.
</P>
<P>
   Union executive director Billy Hunter saw Tuesday's announcement
by Stern as just another weapon in the ongoing labor war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sadly, the owners have elected to cheat millions of fans and
the city of Philadelphia out of a wonderful spectacle,'' Hunter
said. ``Their effort to further intimidate the players will not
succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Losing the ``wonderful spectacle'' is expected to cost
Philadelphia an estimated $35 million, but the league has been
negotiating with the mayor's office to figure out ways to ``soften
the economic blow'' of losing the game.
</P>
<P>
   Sorting out the economic mess that triggered the lockout _ how
to equitably divide $2 billion _ has proved far more challenging
and rancorous than anyone on either side imagined.
</P>
<P>
   The last meeting between the two sides was Thursday's marathon
session that contributed little toward ending the stalemate. One of
the biggest issues remains the ``timing-rules'' change, which would
force a team that signed another team's free agent to forfeit the
right to go over the salary cap to re-sign its own free agents
under the Larry Bird exception. It is a change that is opposed by
the players as adamantly as it is coveted by the owners.
</P>
<P>
   One source close to the negotiations said the NBA promised a new
proposal, only to offer ``the same proposal, only with the
timing-rules change phased in over a period of years. That wasn't
really a change.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other issues still to be hammered out.
</P>
<P>
   It was reported that the players had agreed to the owners'
demand for a 200-percent tax to be used with a proposed escrow plan
to slow salary growth. In this plan, players would have 15 percent
of their salaries withheld at the beginning of the season, to be
refunded to the owners should salaries rise above a specified
percentage of revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Players, wanting owners to share in the responsibility for
slowing salaries, proposed that the highest-spending owners be
taxed for wild spending that forced salaries to go over that
specified percentage, but feel that 200 percent is too drastic a
penalty and would restrain salary growth too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's too restrictive,'' said one source of the 200-percent
tax. ``We do agree that there should be some kind of tax and
penalty involved during the last three years of this escrow
arrangement. If an owner really wants to sign a guy, they'll do it,
and there should be some sort of tax involved. But do you make that
tax so prohibitive that nobody is going to want to venture outside
of whatever that agreed-upon limit is? No.''
</P>
<P>
   With the season on the line and time running out, the union gave
the owners three options in that meeting last Thursday: Cancel the
season; stay in the room and hammer out a deal, regardless of how
long it takes; or get a mediator.
</P>
<P>
   The league reportedly declined on all three.
</P>
<P>
   Said Hunter: ``The owners should either come to the table now
and negotiate in good faith so that they may end their lockout, or
take us up on our offer to bring in a mediator that will examine
the issues from a neutral perspective and help settle the
differences.''
</P>
<P>
   Until those differences are settled, what is left of the season
remains in jeopardy. And losing the remainder of the season could
be a colossal public-relations disaster for a league that has
always prided itself as being fan- and corporation-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are dealing with the ramifications of losing the first part
of our season,'' Stern said. ``We understand the fan reaction. We
understand network reaction. We understand sponsor reaction, and we
understand licensee reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are our businesses, and we are dealing with those on an
ongoing basis. The negative is extraordinary. We can only imagine
that it would be geometrically multiplied if we lost the entire
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if an agreement could be reached this week, the league
could not start play until around Jan. 10. The reason is that any
new agreement would have to be drawn up and ratified, a process
that could take up to two weeks, and around three more weeks would
be needed to make trades, sign free agents and have an abbreviated
training-camp period.
</P>
<P>
   A Jan. 10 start date would leave the Rockets with 50 games on
their schedule, which officially ends April 21.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy commissioner Russ Granik said Tuesday that the NBA is
willing to extend the playoffs until the end of June, perhaps to
accommodate an extra week or two being tacked on to the regular
season. Finding arena space wouldn't be a problem, since all arenas
must be available anyway in case the local team makes the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   While it would seem that a 56-game schedule, with every team
playing the others twice, on a home-and-home basis, would be
feasible should an agreement be reached soon, Granik said the
league is not planning on such a balanced schedule and would
perhaps go with fewer than 50 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would expect that whatever number of games is agreed upon,
you're going to see a conference-type schedule with perhaps some
mix of interconference games,'' Granik said. ``But not every team
is going to see every other team at home. I think that's going to
be virtually impossible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
