<DOCNO> NYT19981208.0420 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9570 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH09-COX     12-08 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP says president's team not making many converts
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman and Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House struck back Tuesday, trying to fend
off President Clinton's impeachment with an impassioned plea to
undecided Republicans to ``open your mind, open your heart.''
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee heard from several waves of
Clinton supporters, and the White House released a 182-page report
that sought one more time to rebut the charges laid out in
independent counsel Kenneth Starr's report to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever there is in the record that shows whatever the
president did is wrong . . . there is nothing in the record that
would justify his impeachment and removal from office,'' White
House special counsel Gregory Craig told the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Craig used the words ``misleading,'' ``evasive'' and
``maddening'' to describe Clinton's testimony about his sexual
relationship with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   But he never said directly that Clinton lied, to the
consternation of committee Republicans who said they were
increasingly frustrated by what they see as the president's lack of
contrition. There is little dispute that the panel will approve at
least one article of impeachment this week, probably along party
lines. Indeed, committee member Charles Schumer, a New York
Democrat who will cross over to the Senate in January, complained
that the divided panel of 21 Republicans and 16 Democrats is ``just
going through the motions.'' Late Tuesday, the White House released
a report that sought to contrast the allegations against Clinton of
perjury, obstruction of justice and abuse of presidential power
with President Nixon's actions during Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   The administration plans to continue trying to woo moderate
Republicans today by calling former Massachusetts Gov. William
Weld, himself a moderate Republican, to testify on Clinton's
behalf. Clinton nominated Weld last year as ambassador to Mexico,
but his nomination foundered amid objections from Senate
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Weld's presentation, like much of the Clinton defense, is aimed
at undecided, mostly moderate Republicans, who could decide whether
the House passes an impeachment resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Given that three Democrats will likely vote for impeachment,
Democrats need 14 Republicans to cross the aisle to stop
impeachment _ if all 435 House members take part in the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton got some good news Tuesday when New York Republican Rep.
AmoHoughton joined the ranks of lawmakers opposed to impeachment.
But it was unclear whether enough colleagues would follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the little I saw, I'm not certain a lot of what is going
on will change people's minds,'' said fellow New York Republican
Jack Quinn, who estimated that as few as 10 Republicans remain
undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats continued to push hard for an alternative to
impeachment. A censure of the president would allow the House to
punish Clinton properly, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, scholars, former House Democrats and
ex-prosecutors invited by the White House to appear before the
committee agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a historian, it is clear to me that the impeachment of
President Clinton would do great damage . . . to the rule of law,
much greater damage than the crimes of which President Clinton has
been accused,'' said Sean Wilentz, a Princeton University history
professor.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Wilentz were Nicholas Katzenbach, former U.S. attorney
general under President Johnson; Bruce Ackerman, a professor of law
at Yale University; and Samuel Beer, a professor of government at
Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   The general theme among White House witnesses was that even if
Clinton were guilty of everything Starr charged, his transgressions
did not rise to the level of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   To make that case, the White House brought in three former
Judiciary Committee Democrats from the Watergate era: former Reps.
Wayne Owens of Utah, Elizabeth Holtzman of New York and Robert
Drinan of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Drinan, a Catholic priest, took direct aim at the
Republican-propelled drive for impeachment, likening it to the
politically drenched attempt to drive Andrew Johnson from the
presidency after the Civil War. ``The only time in American history
that has seen anything like the process this fall . . . occurred in
1868,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Drinan's assertion that Republicans were motivated by vengeance
and vindictiveness and Wilentz's comments that impeachment
supporters were ``zealots'' or craven drew an angry response.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. George Gekas (R-Pa.) called Wilentz's remarks
``despicable,'' while Rep. Howard Coble (R-N.C.) promised he would
meet later ``in the parking lot'' anyone who said vengeance was
driving the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   A third panel of witnesses included James Hamilton, former
assistant chief counsel to the Senate Watergate Committee, and
Richard Ben-Veniste, former chief of the Watergate task force in
the special prosecutor's office.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans were particularly upset that Clinton's lawyers did
not call witnesses who could testify to the facts of the
allegations against the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zero for three,'' said Rep. Bob Inglis (R-S.C.), complaining
that none of the witnesses on the three panels fulfilled Craig's
promise to dispute the facts of the case against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Craig said the White House report that was released late Tuesday
and the scheduled testimony today by White House counsel Charles
Ruff would form the basis of Clinton's defense.
</P>
<P>
   Amid testy exchanges with the witnesses, Republicans said they
believed the evidence showed a clear-cut case for perjury and
possibly obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Goodlatte (R-Va.) suggested the White House defense was
nothing more than an effort ``to raise the bar'' on impeachment so
that only improprieties that rivaled Nixon's could constitute
grounds for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republicans also chastised the president for his
unwillingness to admit his wrongdoing openly and completely,
without resort to legalisms, and for his hubris.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the faults of the White House,'' Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.)
said, is that it has a tendency ``to break out the champagne or
light up the victory cigar a little bit early sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Committee Democrats, as well as several witnesses, said
Republican pique at Clinton or the belief that he has been
insufficiently remorseful are not grounds for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may wake up next week and find that we voted to impeach the
president because he was not contrite enough,'' Schumer said.
</P>
<P>
   One question confronting the committee is what will happen if
the full House approves articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman argued impeachment would die when the 105th Congress
expires Jan. 3, along with all other pending legislation.
</P>
<P>
   But a report by the Congressional Research Service contradicted
the professor, saying impeachment is the one piece of unfinished
business that does carry over from one Congress to the next.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sherman and Rebecca Carr write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
