<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-MERCURY_STEPANOVA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCURY TEENAGER HAS NEW TEACHER 
 EX-SUNS STAR CHAMBERS HELPS STEPANOVA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maria Stepanova has a holiday secret that doesn't take much to
unravel.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury's 6-foot-8, still-teenage center _ she doesn't turn
20 until Jan. 23 _ has been in the United States since early
November, first touring with the Russian Junior National Team that
beat the likes of 22nd-ranked George Washington, then for the past
few weeks training here with Coach Cheryl Miller. And strength
coach Robin Pound. And an English instructor.
</P>
<P>
   And Tom Chambers.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who watched the Suns revive themselves during the
pre-America West Arena, pre-Charles Barkley days knows what the
6-10 Chambers is teaching Stepanova.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opportunities are endless for Maria,'' said Miller, who
has free time for such projects because of a broadcasting career
put on hold by the NBA lockout. ``I was talking to Danny (Ainge),
and he said she might be the female version of Tom Chambers. And
it's so true.
</P>
<P>
   ``She can square up, face the basket and put it on the floor,
and that's what we want her to do. I want to bring her away from
the basket because what other big player wants to do that? She can
knock it down, and that'll give her room to put the ball on the
floor and get to the rack.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the pick and roll that Kevin Johnson and
Chambers worked so masterfully from 1988 to 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Practicing with Chambers ``gave her a lot of new incentives,''
Stepanova said Tuesday through an interpreter, Platon Perepelkin.
``He shows her what she needs to put emphasis on.''
</P>
<P>
   And the pick and roll?
</P>
<P>
   Her two-hour daily English classes include not only the alphabet
but basic basketball phrases, so the pre-translated words bring a
smile: ``It's supposed to be a secret,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said she has ``two little KJs'' in 5-7 Michele Timms and
5-4 Kristi Harrower and dreams of the magic they could work with
Stepanova. Not to mention the options created with Stepanova and
6-3 Jennifer Gillom, runner-up as the WNBA most valuable player, in
the lineup together.
</P>
<P>
   Little of that was possible last season because half of the
Mercury, including Stepanova and the Australian point guards,
missed training camp because of the World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   Stepanova had some moments _ 11 points in 10 minutes vs.
Washington, 15 points and eight rebounds in a two-point win over
Detroit _ but mostly sat the bench while the 34-year-old Gillom
carried the load.
</P>
<P>
   Then after not playing Stepanova a minute in the five preceding
games, Miller turned to her in the second half of the deciding game
of a playoff semifinal series against Cleveland. The WNBA's
second-tallest player responded with six points, two rebounds, one
assist, one steal, one block and six fouls in an uninhibited nine
minutes that left the Rockers reeling and the Mercury looking
confidently toward the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically, you can't expect a whole lot from a 19-year-old
because she's still growing into her body,'' Miller said. ``It's
the mental part I'm excited about. I'm telling you, the kid is so
dang amazing. She's very, very willing to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   And a good employee, too.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of Timms, who was here during the last
off-season, Stepanova and Toni Foster have shouldered appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Miller and Stepanova will meet with a woman who was
recently severely injured in a biking accident and came out of a
coma inquiring about the Mercury. On Thursday, Stepanova will
surprise homebound seniors and disabled residents when she delivers
lunch to them in conjunction with the Glendale YWCA Meals on Wheels
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like a second home,'' Stepanova said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she calls her parents almost every day and will leave
after a Mercury holiday party on Dec. 17. She'll be accompanied by
her English books and workout charts as she heads overseas to play
a partial European season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
