<DOCNO> NYT19981208.0423 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9574 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-DEFENSE-BOS     12-08 1487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-DEFENSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE LAWYER ACKNOWLEDGES CLINTON'S ``SINFUL'' CONDUCT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER AND MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Casting President Clinton's sex scandal as
``sinful'' and ``maddening'' but ``not impeachable,'' a White House
lawyer Tuesday launched a climactic effort to end the impeachment
drama by appealing to a critical bloc of undecided House members
who might control the president's fate.
</P>
<P>
   The last-ditch quest unfolded as the White House last night
presented the House Judiciary Committee with a 184-page rebuttal to
probable impeachment charges and Clinton's lawyer, Gregory B.
Craig, pleaded with the panel to draw ``a sharp distinction between
immoral conduct and illegal acts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As surely as we all know that what he did is sinful,'' Craig
said, ``we also know it is not impeach-able.''
</P>
<P>
   The rebuttal, a central element in the full-bore effort to spare
Clinton the shame of facing formal impeachment charges, lays out
the most detailed response yet to evidence against the president,
although the document closely parallels previous White House
rebuttals to allegations stemming from Clinton's illicit affair
with Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The report is intended to provide swing-vote Republicans with
enough doubts about the case to oppose impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   While the document says Clinton's relationship with Lewinsky was
wrong, it suggests that testimony appearing to implicate him should
not be used against him without corroboration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contradictory testimony from two witnesses does not indicate
that one has committed perjury,'' the document says. ``A perjury
case must not be based solely upon the testimony of a single
witness.''
</P>
<P>
   Committee Democrats, moving to exploit broad public opposition
to the president's ouster, joined the 11-hour White House
counterattack by invoking a rash of potentially dire consequences
of a lengthy impeachment ordeal, including the prospect of a
crippled presidency harming domestic and international affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Representative Zoe Lofgren, a California Democrat,
questioned whether the global economy might be shaken and the US
export market ``might fall apart.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House effort featured several hours of testimony from
a battery of additional witnesses, including three former lawmakers
who sat on the Judiciary Committee that passed articles of
impeachment against President Richard M. Nixon in 1974, who argued
that Clinton's conduct paled in comparison with the Watergate
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   In a particulary pointed warning to lawmakers who are
considering voting for impeachment charges, a Princeton University
historian, Sean Wilentz, warned that any member who supports the
charges without being ``absolutely convinced'' that they warrant
Clinton's ouster ``will be fairly accused of gross dereliction of
duty and earn the condemnation of history.''
</P>
<P>
   Committee Republicans, united in their conviction that Clinton
committed ``high crimes'' that merit his removal from office, said
the White House defense effort failed to dissuade them from
approving several impeachment charges later this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't score any points with anybody who has any respect
for the truth,'' said Representative Charles T. Canady, a Florida
Republican. ``The facts are still very troubling.''
</P>
<P>
   But White House officials said Clinton's final, two-day defense,
which ends Wednesday, was aimed beyond the hearing room at 15 to 30
undecided moderate Republicans and conservative Democrats who are
likely to determine if the full House sends articles of impeachment
charges to the Senate for only the second presidential impeachment
trial in history.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was too early to gauge the White House effort's
success, a congressional source said Representative Amo Houghton of
New York, a Republican lawmaker who has wavered on the impeachment
issue, has called a news conference Wednesday to announce his
opposition to removing Clinton from office.
</P>
<P>
   In a surprise twist, the White House bolstered its effort to
sway the uncommitted lawmakers by calling a star Republican
witness, former Massachusetts governor William F. Weld, to testify
Wednesday that Clinton's misdeeds do not warrant his impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's allies immediately siezed on the Houghton news and
Weld's willingness to break with Republican leaders to defend the
president as signs of progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing the beginning of the engagement of the American
public in the gravity of what we're about to do,'' said
Representative William D. Delahunt, a Quincy Democrat on the
Judiciary Committee and a founder of a bipartisan group of panel
members. ``The reality has set in, and it is looming larger and
larger.''
</P>
<P>
   Weld, a former US attorney for Massachusetts and top Justice
Department official under President Reagan, is seen as enhancing
the White House effort to persuade undecided GOP lawmakers that
they can support Clinton without suffering a backlash.
</P>
<P>
   Weld will testify a week after former US attorney general Elliot
M. Richardson, also a moderate Massachusetts Republican, argued
against Clinton's impeachment before the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very powerful,'' said Representative Barney Frank, a
Newton Democrat, in an interview. ``Bill Weld is an important
figure to moderate Republicans, and some of them who didn't want to
vote for impeachment are getting pounded by the right wing. Bill
Weld can help them understand the importance of withstanding
this.''
</P>
<P>
   However, one committee Republican after another in the hearing
room cited Clinton's alleged misconduct and continued to lash out
at his defense team's refusal to admit that the president
repeatedly lied under oath before a federal grand jury and a civil
deposition in a sexual harassment case that was filed against him
by Paula Corbin Jones and was settled last month.
</P>
<P>
   Although Craig characterized the statements in questions as
``evasive, incomplete, misleading, even maddening,'' he maintained
Clinton's position that the statements did not meet the legal
standard for lies or acts of perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Bob Inglis of South Carolina echoed many of his
GOP colleagues by telling Craig that Clinton's refusal to admit he
lied effectively negated his acknowledgment that he misled the
American people.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an amazing thing, that you sit before us, and you are
taking back all his apologies,'' Inglis told Craig.
</P>
<P>
   Several Democrats shared the sentiment, among them
Representative Tom Barrett of Wisconsin. Barrett joined
Representative Martin T. Meehan, a Lowell Democrat on the
committee, in calling on Clinton to address the nation again and
offer a fuller apology.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could acknowledge that people could take his statements as
lies without saying they are lies,'' Barrett said. ``I think it
would be helpful to bring some more Republicans around.''
</P>
<P>
   Meehan underscored his view of the difference between the
Lewinsky scandal and Watergate by quoting several passages from
conversations on Nixon's Oval Office tapes. Notable among them was
Nixon's order to White House aides to obtain documents at the
Brookings Institution in Washington about President Lyndon B.
Johnson's handling of the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   ``God damn, get it,'' Meehan quoted Nixon as saying. ``And get
those files. Blow the safe and get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Meehan then suggested to the former Judiciary Committee members
that Clinton's conduct ``doesn't even hold a candle to President
Nixon and what he did.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House rebuttal struck the same theme. ``Unlike the
series of lies told by President Nixon, President Clinton's denials
bore no relationship to his use of the powers of the presidency,''
the lawyers wrote.
</P>
<P>
   As for Clinton's statement under oath that he did not have sex
with Lewinsky, the lawyers cite five dictionaries that define
sexual relations as intercourse or coitus. ``This is indeed what
President Clinton believed,'' wrote the lawyers, who went on to
quote Lewinsky as saying that Clinton ``does not consider oral sex
to be sex.''
</P>
<P>
   At another point, the lawyers seem to attack Lewinsky, noting
``internal inconsistencies'' in some of the 10 different statements
she made about gifts from Clinton. For example, the Clinton lawyers
noted that Lewinsky said in one statement that Clinton ``didn't
really say anything'' in response to her comments about concealing
the gifts, while Lewinsky said in another statement that the
president responded by saying, ``Let me think about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the arguments in the report are based on interpretation
of the Constitution's language on impeachment. For example, the
Clinton lawyers say that Clinton's actions were not impeachable
because they did not cause ``injury to the state,'' a standard of
English law, on which the Constitution's impeachment clause was
based.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
