<HEADER>
A9578 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-TYSON-LADN-(SLANG     12-08 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBDUED TYSON TO FACE BOTHA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Mike Tyson Part III promises to be kinder and
gentler. Obviously, he feels he has no other option. Tyson was at
the Hollywood Athletic Club on Tuesday afternoon to announce
formally that he will face South African Francois Botha on Jan. 16
at the MGM Grand in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   It will be Tyson's first fight since he bit Evander Holyfield's
ears and subsequently lost his boxing license for 16 months.
</P>
<P>
   However, Tyson, wearing a black muscle T-shirt and maroon beret,
was more interested in protecting himself than selling the fight.
He shoved down the throats of those at the packed news conference
that his mission now is simply to be well-behaved in light of his
most recent legal troubles.
</P>
<P>
   He will be sentenced Feb. 5 for allegedly punching a man and
kicking another after a traffic accident in Maryland in August.
After that, a judge in Indiana will decide whether that incident
was a parole violation and, if so, whether it was serious enough to
send him back to prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows I'm on parole and I'm trying to be very nice up
here. You have to understand the position I'm in,'' Tyson said,
smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after the news conference began, Tyson, surrounded by
his new handlers at the dais, slipped into a familiar position:
hands cupping face, seemingly bored stiff. However, when it was his
turn to speak, he came to life.
</P>
<P>
   He was neither the sullen Tyson of the Don King days nor the
friendly Tyson those close to him describe. Instead, he was mostly
sarcastic in a light-hearted, even humorous way in an overstated
effort to avoid saying the wrong thing.
</P>
<P>
   When he was asked why he is so adept at finding trouble, he said
cheerfully: ``I'm sorry, but I learned my lesson. I won't do it
anymore. . . . I've been a bad boy, sir, and I'm sorry, sir,''
which drew laughs
</P>
<P>
   When the crowd jumped on heavyweight Jeremy Williams for
questioning from the audience why Tyson is fighting Botha and not
him, Tyson said: ``Let's be nice to this guy. Let's all be nice.''
Again, laughs.
</P>
<P>
   And when he was asked how many tune-up fights he'll need before
a third fight with Evander Holyfield, he said: ``I'm just here to
fight one fight at a time. I don't want no trouble from nobody,
sir.'' More laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson, 32, had his serious moments.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he was asked why he selected Tommy Brooks as his
new trainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody else wanted me, that's why,'' Tyson
responded, again joking before adding: ``He came down and worked
with me (in Phoenix) and we got along. I'm just glad he chose to
work with me. I'm happy. He didn't seem like a guy who just wanted
that paycheck. I've met a lot of guys like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, this was more ``The Mike Tyson Comedy Hour'' _ perhaps
with some underlying tension from so many years of tribulations _
than a thoughtful conference on his second boxing comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Again, it was his way of trying to survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was great,'' said Dan Goossen, who has signed to
promote Tyson's next two fights. ``I thought he was being honest.
And you can't ask for more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost lost in the hoopla surrounding Tyson was Botha.
</P>
<P>
   A casual fan might deem him the proverbial sacrificial lamb, a
la Peter McNeeley, Tyson's opponent when he fought for the first
time after his three-year prison term for rape. Tyson fed that
perception, saying, ``I know you guys don't think he's going to
beat me. Regardless of my layoff, I know no one believes that.''
</P>
<P>
   And few do. However, Botha is no McNeeley.
</P>
<P>
   He's 39-1, with 24 knockouts. He outpointed Axel Schulz in 1995
to win the vacant IBF heavyweight title, but the fight was declared
``no contest'' when he tested positive for steroids. He
subsequently was knocked out by then IBF champion Michael Moorer in
the 12th round in spite of a courageous effort that won him
admiration.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, he's not expected to play dead like so many of
Tyson's opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never in my whole boxing career been intimidated and this
won't be the first time,'' he said. ``I know what the public
perception is, that this guy is a sacrificial lamb for Tyson. The
public doesn't know boxing like people in the business know boxing,
though.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a rude awakening for him. This was a huge mistake
on their side.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-98 2244EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
