<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9583 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS &LR;      12-08 1276
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S TESTIMONY WAS `EVASIVE' BUT NOT PERJURY, HOUSE PANEL TOLD &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House opened its defense of President
Clinton on Tuesday and for the first time disputed evidence that
prompted the House Judiciary Committee to begin considering his
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to counter the panel's anticipated approval late this
week of articles of impeachment, a White House lawyer said the
president's case rests on the ``distinction between immoral conduct
and illegal acts'' growing out of his affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's sworn testimony about his relationship with Lewinsky
was ``evasive, incomplete, misleading, even maddening, but it was
not perjury,'' said Gregory Craig, a special counsel to the
president.
</P>
<P>
   While Craig took a conciliatory tone during his testimony,
several scholars, prosecutors and Watergate veterans summoned to
help defend Clinton were more combative, warning Republicans their
impeachment drive was extreme and could win them condemnation by
history.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the perjury accusations against Clinton are true, former
Attorney General Nicholas Katzenbach said Congress would be unwise
to impeach the president and remove him from office unless the
public has lost confidence in his ability to perform his duties.
``For whatever reason,'' Katzenbach said, ``the public remains
unpersuaded.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert J. Drinan, a Jesuit priest who served as a member of the
House committee that approved impeachment articles against Richard
Nixon in 1974, said Clinton's alleged crimes pale next to Nixon's
behavior. Drinan predicted an ``explosion of anger'' directed at
Congress if Clinton is impeached.
</P>
<P>
   As the White House defense effort unfolded inside the same
hearing room where the Judiciary Committee 24 years ago voted to
impeach Nixon over his role in Watergate, Clinton kept his focus
away from Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton kicked off a two-day conference on reforming Social
Security, then left for Tennessee to attend the funeral of the late
U.S. Sen. Albert Gore Sr., father of Vice President Al Gore. Later,
the president returned to Washington for two awards dinners
honoring his efforts to forge peace in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's witnesses before the sharply divided committee were
the first of two days of testimony the White House was to present.
On Thursday the panel begins consideration of articles of
impeachment against Clinton. The panel is expected to approve at
least one article alleging that the president lied under oath,
setting up a vote by the full House next week.
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton's blessing, Craig delivered a statement of
presidential contrition for his behavior in the Lewinsky affair and
subsequent investigations. ``The president wants everyone to know _
the committee, the Congress and the country _ that he is genuinely
sorry for the pain and the damage that he has caused,'' Craig told
the committee.
</P>
<P>
   As for Lewinsky, who has never appeared before the committee,
Craig said, ``We think in some areas she provided erroneous
testimony that is in disagreement with the president's testimony.''
</P>
<P>
   Bolstering Craig's arguments, the White House late Tuesday
delivered to the Judiciary Committee a 182-page brief denying that
Clinton conspired with Lewinsky to lie under oath or tried to
influence the testimony of his secretary, Betty Currie, allegations
the panel's lawyers are considering as they draft articles of
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., said the
document ``appears to contain no new evidence or challenge the
truthfulness of any testimony'' included in the report submitted by
independent counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said the president's rebuttal to Starr's charges includes
``more legal hairsplitting and semantic gymnastics we have come to
expect from this White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Craig promised to present a ``powerful'' case that
there are no grounds for impeachment, Republicans on the committee
said they were not persuaded. The White House will sum up the
president's case Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have yet to hear any new facts and evidence here that would
lead us to conclude the president did not lie,'' said a disgusted
Rep. Bob Inglis, R-S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Craig said that Clinton worded his testimony to the grand jury
carefully to mislead but not to lie. ``As surely as we all know
that what he did is sinful, we also know it is not impeachable,''
Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   In one exchange, Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla., repeated Clinton's
claim under oath in the Jones case that he had no ``specific
recollection'' of ever being alone with Lewinsky, and asked Craig
if the president was telling the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was evasive, it was misleading, he tried to be narrowly
accurate, but congressman, he did not violate his oath,'' Craig
said.
</P>
<P>
   Canady responded, ``For you to contend that that is truthful, I
think, is not credible ... I don't see how anybody in the country
could believe that was a truthful answer in light of all the
evidence that is before us.''
</P>
<P>
   Princeton historian Sean Wilentz riled Republican lawmakers when
he cautioned that anyone voting to impeach ``risks going down in
history with the zealots and fanatics.'' He went on to warn that
``history will track you down and condemn you for your
cravenness.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. George Gekas, R-Pa., responded that Wilentz's remarks are
``a despicable way to characterize such a serious vote as this.''
</P>
<P>
   Gekas was angered again when Drinan warned that by pushing
Clinton's impeachment the committee would be branded ``in the
history books as dominated by vindictiveness and by vengeance and
by partisanship.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you use the word `vengeance'?'' Gekas furiously demanded
of the priest.
</P>
<P>
   Drinan, who teaches ethics at Georgetown University, did not
retreat. ``I'll leave God to judge that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gekas responded curtly: ``Then maybe God's messenger should not
prejudge.''
</P>
<P>
   If the full House approves Clinton's impeachment, the Senate
would then open a trial with Chief Justice William Rehnquist
presiding. It would be only the second trial of a president in U.S.
history, and witnesses Tuesday estimated it would tie up Congress
and the Supreme Court for up to a year.
</P>
<P>
   This week's hearings are being held against a background of
public opinion opposed to impeaching the president. Three surveys
released on Tuesday found roughly two-thirds of Americans opposed
to impeaching the president, a number that has remained fairly
consistent over the past four months.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, polls commissioned by CNN, USA Today and ABC
News indicate that three of every five people give unfavorable
marks to the way congressional Republicans are handling the
impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The White House decided over the weekend to scrap plans to again
attack Starr, whose report to Congress in September alleged that
Clinton lied under oath, obstructed justice and abused his
presidential authority in trying to conceal his affair with
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the president's legal team disclosed that it was
scheduling an appearance today by former Massachusetts Gov. William
Weld, a moderate Republican who served as associate attorney
general during the Reagan administration. Weld, whose nomination by
Clinton to be ambassador to Mexico was rejected by the Senate, was
head of the Justice Department's criminal division.
</P>
<P>
   Following Weld's appearance, White House counsel Charles F.C.
Ruff will summarize the president's defense and respond to
questions from committee members.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
