<HEADLINE>
TOLEDO, ASSISTANT IN MINOR ACCIDENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA coach Bob Toledo and assistant Mark Weber
were injured in an automobile accident Monday while recruiting in
Atlanta. Neither was seriously hurt, according to UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo might have suffered a separated shoulder but did not go
to the hospital. Both he and Weber, the offensive line coach, had a
plethora of aches and bruises.
</P>
<P>
   The woman who hit them supposedly lost control of her car when a
balloon she was carrying obstructed her vision.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo continued recruiting and will return to Los Angeles
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recruiting is too important,'' said Randy Taylor, director of
football operations. ``You can always get another shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Injury update: Linebacker Brendon Ayanbadejo will miss about
two weeks with sprained knee ligaments but is expected to play in
the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Ayanbadejo suffered the injury on the first play of the Miami
game. He returned briefly before watching the remainder of the game
on crutches from the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to say yeah, I'll be back by Christmas, but I don't
know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Status pending: The final grade on UCLA's season _ success or
failure _ won't be determined until the Rose Bowl against
Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The season hasn't been a disappointment,'' quarterback Cade
McNown said. ``The (Miami) loss was a disappointment. What happens
in the Rose Bowl and how we respond will dictate what sort of
season it is.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Roster update: Reserve cornerback Eric Whitfield has been
reinstated after serving a one-game suspension for fighting.
Whitfield was involved in the same Oct. 4 fight that prompted
Jermaine Lewis' one-game suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Whitfield will play in the Rose Bowl if he fulfills certain
obligations, UCLA said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' case has been dropped by the L.A. City attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just relieved it's over,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   __ And finally: Center Shawn Stuart, a Saugus native, was named
first-team GTE Academic All-American. Stuart has a 3.62 grade-point
average as a graduate student in education.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
