<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL CHANGE 
ENTER DERSHOWITZ 
TWO-FACED WRITER
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brill's Content, the six-month-old magazine that bills itself as
a watchdog of the media industry, has a new editor. Steven Brill,
chairman and editor in chief, said Tuesday that Michael Kramer had
left the magazine and that the editorial director, Eric Effron, had
taken over.
</P>
<P>
   Brill would not elaborate on why Kramer had departed. ``It's an
unhappy circumstance,'' he said, adding that he didn't say anything
more than that when he announced Kramer's departure to the staff
and was ``going to try my hardest not to now.''
</P>
<P>
   Unhappy circumstance?
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to do with something internal, an internal personnel
issue,'' Brill said. ``Therefore, I just haven't wanted to talk
about the reasons for it.'' Kramer did not return calls seeking
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reasons, Brill's singlemindedness has made him a
famously difficult boss; some staff members at other Brill
publications have said he has a hair-trigger temper and no patience
for small slip-ups. Some readers began to wonder if Kramer's days
were numbered when Effron, who had been editor and publisher of
Legal Times, a newspaper Brill owned in Washington, arrived in
September.
</P>
<P>
   Super-Lawyer
</P>
<P>
   It's appeals time again.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Dershowitz, the Harvard law professor who has been involved
in high-profile appeals for such defendants as Claus von Bulow and
Michael Milken, has joined the team representing Ronald Perelman,
the several-times-married billionaire who is fighting for custody
of his 3-year-old daughter, Caleigh.
</P>
<P>
   Perelman, one of the not-so-anonymous parties in a case known as
Anonymous vs. Anonymous, lost a round in his custody battle with
his third wife, Patricia Duff, last week. The Appellate Division of
state Supreme Court in Manhattan ruled that their custody hearings
must be conducted in open court. Perelman had wanted private
hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, with advice from Dershowitz, Perelman's lawyers
appealed the decision. Adria Hillman, who handled Perelman's
divorce case, said she had approached Dershowitz because she knew
that he favored a balance between the public-interest need for open
courts and the privacy of individuals and their families. (
Dershowitz's secretary said he was in a class at Harvard Tuesday,
one of the few times, no doubt, when his cellular telephone is
turned off.)
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Warner, a lawyer for Ms. Duff, said of Dershowitz's
sudden presence on the case: ``It doesn't change anything. We think
that the decision opening the courtroom was correct.''
</P>
<P>
   Split Personality
</P>
<P>
   As Gil Schwartz, he is a senior vice president of communications
at CBS. As Stanley Bing, he writes about the corporate battlefield.
His double identity is ``probably the worst-kept secret in
corporate America,'' Schwartz said Tuesday. ``Fortunately, people
seem to learn it and then forget about it, which is fine with me,
because Stanley Bing finds Gil Schwartz to be an annoyance and an
intrusion into his life. Schwartz has to go to work everyday. Bing
would rather sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Somebody is going to be busy for the next few months. David
Hirshey, executive editor of HarperCollins, said he had signed a
Bing book called ``What Would Machiavelli Do?'' Schwartz described
it as a lighthearted look at how the Renaissance-era statesman and
writer might handle 20th-century problems like ``living in a
downsizing environment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Machiavelli is often seen as advising people to do nasty
things,'' Schwartz said, ``when in fact what he was was a superb
strategic thinker who wasn't burdened by squishy sentiment. It's
military and political strategy with a little bit of the World
Wrestling Foundation thrown in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
