<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-CLARK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS SIGN CLARK, STILL PURSUE CLEMENS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Rangers yesterday signed right-hander
Mark Clark to a two-year contract worth a guaranteed $9.3 million,
but this latest acquisition should not be interpreted as a sign of
surrender in the team's pursuit of right-hander Roger Clemens,
general manager Doug Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto Blue Jays general manager Gord Ash acknowledged receipt
of six trade proposals for Clemens, the five-time Cy Young Award
recipient who demanded a trade seven days ago to a organization
closer to his Houston-area residence or a contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have gotten through the first wave, and we're into the
serious contenders,'' Ash said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers appear to be one of those.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assume we are,'' Melvin said. ``I haven't been told that
we're not.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark, 30, provides the Rangers additional inventory and the
ability to include a member of their rotation in Melvin's trade
proposal for Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives us more depth to talk about trades,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Ruben Mateo, the No. 1 prospect in the
organization's minor-league system, likely serves as the
centerpiece of the Rangers' proposal for Clemens. Melvin called it
``very unlikely'' that catcher Ivan Rodriguez or left fielder Rusty
Greer would be included in any proposal for Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, who this past season went 9-14 with a 4.84 earned-run
average for the Chicago Cubs, will receive $4 million for 1999 and
$5 million for 2000. The Rangers also hold an option for the 2001
season worth $5 million or can purchase it for $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of good players on the club, and I think it's
going to be a good time,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Clark earned $5.05 million during 1998, but a disappointing
season forced him to accept a reduction in salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It actually went a hell of a lot better than my wins and
losses show,'' Clark said. ``I pitched into some tough luck. I
pitched a lot of ballgames into the seventh and eighth inning and
came out with nothing to show for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Five times, Clark was in line for a victory before the Cubs'
bullpen surrendered the lead. The bullpen also allowed 19 of the 30
runners it inherited from Clark to score. That represented the most
runs charged to any National League pitcher after departing a game.
</P>
<P>
   Clark also received the least run support (4.3 per nine innings)
among members of the Cubs' rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pitched deep into a lot of ballgames,'' said Clark, who
pitched at least six innings in 25 of his 33 starts. ``With the
runs that \Rthe Rangers\S score, that can lead to a lot of wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark pitched more than 200 innings in each of the past three
seasons, and Melvin cited that as one reason the Rangers viewed him
attractive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been out there every fifth day for the past three
years,'' Clark said. ``I don't think I've missed but one or two
starts in three years. The one thing I can say is that I've been
healthy for three years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs did not offer Clark, a Type B free agent, salary
arbitration. That means the Rangers will not be required to forfeit
a draft choice as compensation for signing Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin now will turn his attention toward acquiring left-handed
pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're so right-handed heavy, but \Rleft-handers\S are just not
out there,'' Melvin said. ``I've talked to clubs, but there's just
none available. Maybe they'll come available later.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
