<HEADLINE>
CARDINAL RULE: LIFE AT TOP IS TOUGH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stanford didn't lose its second game of last season until Jan.
31. This year, the Cardinal already has two defeats, three
injuries, one Sports Illustrated cover subject (North Hollywood
High alumnus Arthur Lee) and a great big target on its back.
</P>
<P>
   It's the world of spotlight and survival. Arizona and UCLA have
lived there for years.
</P>
<P>
   Now, don't misread the situation. Stanford (5-2) lost on neutral
courts to two of the nation's best teams, many of its problems are
correctable and it remains the class of the Pac-10. But the No. 6
Cardinal is quickly learning life isn't easy at the top, regardless
of coaching, experience, size, depth or execution.
</P>
<P>
   First, the vaunted depth has dwindled. Sharpshooter Ryan Mendez
is out until Christmas with tendinitis. Second-string point guard
Mike McDonald is out five to seven weeks with a bad foot. And
reserve center Jason Collins, from Harvard-Westlake High, is out at
least two weeks with a dislocated bone in his wrist suffered Monday
against George Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Mike Montgomery strengthened the schedule to test his
veterans early and prepare them for the rugged Pac-10. After
thrashing UC-Davis, Southern Methodist and Southwest Missouri in
Maples Pavilion, the Cardinal left home _ and left its shooting
touch behind.
</P>
<P>
   In a victory over St. John's and loss to North Carolina in the
preseason NIT in Madison Square Garden, the Cardinal shot 33.6
percent _ evoking memories of past Stanford teams that played
brilliantly at home but struggled on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``We chose to play at this level,'' Montgomery said. ``We knew
with this schedule that we'd be in position to lose a few games.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee, perhaps empowered by his NCAA Tournament success, is
forcing the pace and shooting a beat too quickly. Guard Kris Weems
and small forward Peter Sauer are smothered by defenses designed to
limit their 3-point marksmanship. And center Tim Young's offense
was so offensive, Montgomery threatened to bench him in favor of
Collins. Young responded with 12 points against George Washington,
but the concern has not abated.
</P>
<P>
   More, the book on Stanford has changed. Instead of collapsing on
the big men, opponents are stopping the perimeter attack and daring
Young and Mark Madsen to beat them in one-on-one situations in the
low post. It's a sound strategy, given Young's ineffectiveness and
Madsen's style: He's best when moving off the ball and grabbing
offensive rebounds, not breaking down a defense with the dribble.
</P>
<P>
   What's ahead? The current glitches won't derail Stanford's
long-term progress. Most likely, the Cardinal will roll through the
Pac-10 and make a deep run in the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   __ Unlawful schedule: As if New Mexico coach Dave Bliss doesn't
have enough problems with his best player, senior Kenny Thomas,
ineligible for 10 more days, now state lawmakers are hammering
Bliss about the Lobos' schedule.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. New Mexico Rep. Kiki Saavedra (D-Albuquerque)
called the schedule ``pathetic'' and ``a laugh at the taxpayers of
New Mexico'' in a recent interview with the Albuquerque Journal.
Other politicians have supported Saavedra and said they cannot give
tickets away.
</P>
<P>
   The Lobos' early-season schedule includes Arkansas-Pine Buff,
Texas-Pan American, Sacramento State, McNeese State and three bad
teams in the Lobo Classic: Cornell, La Salle and Northeastern.
</P>
<P>
   Bliss, who sent a letter apologizing for Saavedra's comments to
Cornell coach Scott Thompson, said the schedule is purposefully
soft because of Thomas' absence. (He was suspended for the semester
because of an eligibility dispute dating to his freshman year.)
</P>
<P>
   The pols don't care _ and apparently don't have anything better
to do.
</P>
<P>
   __ Back for more: College of Charleston's upset of North
Carolina on Saturday was not the shocker it seemed. The Cougars,
who took eventual national champ Arizona to the wire in the 1997
NCAA Tournament, are once again a team to avoid in March.
</P>
<P>
   Coach John Kresse has all five starters back to handle
Charleston's upgrade from the Trans-America Athletic Conference to
the Southern Conference. Senior forward Carl Thomas scored 20
points against the Tar Heels, and center Jody Lumpkin outplayed UNC
center Brendan Haywood. The Cougars won 24 games last year but were
a little young to stun Stanford in the Midwest Regional.
</P>
<P>
   This year, watch out.
</P>
<P>
   __ Around the Pac-10: The Pac-10 is 3-6 this season against
teams ranked in the Top 25, with victories over Tennessee, Oklahoma
State and St. John's.
</P>
<P>
   Against the elite _ North Carolina, Kentucky, Connecticut and
Maryland _ the Pac-10 is 0-5. Unless the trend reverses, that could
hurt the league's chances of getting a fifth or sixth team in the
NCAA Tournament. And that could be UCLA or USC. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Washington's loss at Boise State wasn't close to the league's
worst defeat. That would be Washington State's 88-75 loss at
Alaska-Fairbanks. . . .
</P>
<P>
   No doubt about it: This UCLA team plays harder than any version
since the last national-championship season. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State forward Mike Batiste returns Dec. 19 after serving
an eight-game academic suspension. . . .
</P>
<P>
   USC transfer guard Brandon Granville leads the Pac-10 in assists
(seven per game). . . .
</P>
<P>
   Arizona point guard Jason Terry is averaging 41 minutes per
game. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Circle Dec. 29 on the calendar. In addition to UCLA and USC
hosting Loyola Marymount and Arkansas State, respectively, Rhode
Island visits Pepperdine _ URI coach Jim Harrick's first appearance
in Southern California since his dismissal from UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   And in the Bay Area, the Newell Classic matches Stanford against
Temple and Cal against North Carolina. &QL; 
THE TOP 10
</P>
<P>
   __ 1. Maryland (10-0) _ Terps spank Stanford and DePaul within
36 hours.
</P>
<P>
   __ 2. Connecticut (6-0) _ Not even the best team on its campus.
</P>
<P>
   __ 3. Duke (7-1) _ Florida will feel the Devils' wrath tonight.
</P>
<P>
   __ 4. Cincinnati (5-0) _ Bearcats taking time off to study. Yuk,
yuk.
</P>
<P>
   __ 5. Stanford (5-2) _ Collins twins need to play more, Tim
Young less.
</P>
<P>
   __ 6. Kentucky (7-1) _ Cats began grueling month with Indiana on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   __ 7. North Carolina (8-1) _ Any more foul trouble and he'll be
Brendan Haypine.
</P>
<P>
   __ 8. Indiana (8-1) _ General Bob finally has players who like
him. It shows.
</P>
<P>
   __ 9. Arizona (4-0) _ Wildcats fans want a piece of UCLA . . .
football.
</P>
<P>
   __ 10. Purdue (7-1) _ Wing guard Jaraan Cornell might be Big
Ten's best shooter.
</P>
<P>
   __ Five to watch: Kansas, St. John's, Minnesota, Syracuse, UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   GAME OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   Maryland at Kentucky &QL; 
Saturday, Rupp Arena &QL; 
Should be one of the best games of the season and the first road
test for unbeaten Maryland. Wildcats must control tempo to keep
Terps' athletes in check. Kentucky's December schedule includes
Kansas, Indiana, Maryland, Georgia Tech, Duke and Louisville. Terps
won't be challenged until Jan. 3 collision with Duke.
</P>
</TEXT>
