<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-HITCHCOCK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HITCHCOCK, STARS FLOURISHING DESPITE SEASON'S ODD TWISTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The past wrapped itself around Ken Hitchcock like a warm coat
last weekend when the Stars coach returned to the memories of his
youth in Western Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny, I'm really finding myself enjoying this more than
ever,'' Hitchcock said of returning to his childhood home of
Edmonton, Alberta. ``I'm finding myself a lot more reflective these
days, I'm able to look back to how I got here and where I'm going
from here. It's a good feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   The timing couldn't have been more perfect for Hitchcock, who is
enduring quite possibly his strangest season in professional
hockey. Already, the Stars coach has survived a delicate public
debate with newcomer Brett Hull, drawn the ire of his team for a
Thanksgiving Day practice and been the subject of a newspaper
report that he was ``losing the team.''
</P>
<P>
   All that while the Stars are off to a 15-5-3 start.
</P>
<P>
   And while the old Ken Hitchcock might have been a bundle of
nerves during the sometimes controversial moments of the season's
first quarter, the new Ken Hitchcock emerged from Alberta
introspective and positive _ a man saying he is learning more about
coaching, and more about himself, every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I have to improve on as a coach is I have to continue to
remove myself from the emotion of the game,'' Hitchcock said.
``That's something I talk to myself every day about. My job is to
make sound decisions at the right time. And to do that, you have to
be less emotional than your players.''
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't always been easy for Hitchcock, who said he has been
driven toward success since dropping out of college to sell
sporting goods in Edmonton 25 years ago. But he said he's learning
that being patient doesn't mean he's losing his drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``People expect coaching a team to be this methodical roll up a
hill or something. It's not,'' he said. ``It's a lot of peaks and
valleys and hard, hard emotion. It's a lot of pushing and pulling
and dragging players, and you're going to have plenty of volatile
moments in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Those volatile moments have been more public this season.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock publicly reprimanded Hull for commenting on his
reduced ice time. And the Stars coach said afterward that the
sometimes tense experience that had Hull posting the ``no comment''
sign to the media for five days brought the superstar winger closer
to the group.
</P>
<P>
   In the most recent incident, the ``Arizona Republic'' quoted a
source saying players had criticized Hitchcock's coaching technique
and that one player wanted to take a swing at Hitchcock. He also
said the end result was a team that came closer together.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are good lessons for us about how the media operates in
the '90s and how we as a team have to react to that,'' Hitchcock
said. ``And I think we're learning that you have to draw in closer
as a family in situations like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Hitchcock is using those revelations to soften a coaching
style that players admit is often abrasive but typically
successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a team that plays together and likes playing
\RHitchcock's\S game,'' winger Grant Marshall said. ``He expects us
to play hard, and we expect the same thing of ourselves. And every
time we've done that in this system, we end up winning a lot of
games.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock's system is the same hard-skating style he developed
while coaching youth hockey in the Edmonton suburb of Sherwood
Park. It's the same demanding forechecking style _ one that can be
compared to basketball's full-court press _ that helped him post a
291-125-15 record with the Kamloops Blazers in major junior hockey.
</P>
<P>
   It's a team-first style _ one that spreads playing time and
requires individual sacrifices _ that Hitchcock demands his players
adapt to.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't care about about how much money you make, he
doesn't care about how old you are,'' said center Brian Skrudland,
who is in his 14th season and playing for his fifth NHL team. ``If
you're playing the best, you're the guy in the lineup. A coach can
earn a lot of respect that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock was even joking about the ``Arizona Republic'' report
that the Canadian media kept bringing up last week. When asked how
things went after one practice, Hitchcock replied, ``Well, nobody
took a swing at me.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, it took a little control on his part to keep his
sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to tell you that it didn't hurt at first,'' he
said of anonymous accusations that players said he was being
outcoached. ``But I'm finding that I can handle it much better.
Now, I find that I'm even more self-confident that I know what I'm
doing. I think you have to be that way or you end up coaching just
to satisfy people, and that never works.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said Stars general manager Bob Gainey has helped him
steel his self-confidence from the brazen ``I'm right'' attitude
that he used to favor to more of a quiet self-assurance _ well,
quiet by Hitchcock's standards, at least.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob is able to show me the big picture,'' Hitchcock said.
``Whereas I want to fight every fight and battle every day against
anything that I see detracting from the team, Bob shows me how each
situation will affect the team down the road. He's really shown me
how to be more patient.''
</P>
<P>
   That's been Hitchcock's biggest shortcoming in coaching, he
said. He wants results now, he wants to win every game, every
shift. But mostly he wants maximum effort. He earned some amount of
disdain from the players when he made them practice on Thanksgiving
after an abysmal 5-2 loss to the New Jersey Devils. But Hitchcock
said that practice wasn't for punishment's sake.
</P>
<P>
   ``My background is that I believe in the supreme value of the
group. If I see anything threatening that, I probably don't have
the amount of patience I should,'' he said. ``And I'm probably not
an easy guy to play for if you don't respect the group. That said,
I find now I can bounce back a lot quicker from a loss, because
I've had a little more experience with it.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the new Ken Hitchcock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-98 2332EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
