<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ZASLOW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHAEL ZASLOW, ACTOR PUBLICIZED LOU GEHRIG'S DISEASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Michael Zaslow, an actor who played a victim of Lou
Gehrig's disease on the soap opera ``One Life to Live'' and who
struggled with the illness in real life, died on Sunday at his home
in Manhattan. He was 54.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a heart attack, said Brynn Thayer, who played his
wife on the show in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Zaslow won a daytime Emmy Award as best actor in 1994 for his
role as the villainous Roger Thorpe on CBS' ``Guiding Light,'' a
role he played at various times for 25 years. He was dismissed from
the show in April 1997, some eight months after the early symptoms
of his illness caused his speech to slur.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Zaslow appeared on ABC's ``One Life to Live,'' reprising
his role as the pianist David Renaldi, which he had played from
1983 to 1986. When Lou Gehrig's disease, or amyotrophic lateral
sclerosis, was diagnosed in late 1997, he incorporated the
degenerative nervous-system disorder into the life of his character
to raise awareness about it.
</P>
<P>
   With his wife, Susan Hufford, Ms. Thayer and other friends, he
founded Zaz-angels, an organization under the umbrella of the
Greater New York Chapter of the Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis
Association, which works for a cure.
</P>
<P>
   Zaslow's last appearance on ``One Life to Live,'' a Thanksgiving
segment, was broadcast on Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Zaslow also appeared in the 1977 movie ``You Light Up My Life''
and the television series ``Law and Order.'' He appeared in the
Broadway productions of ``Cat on a Hot Tin Roof,'' ``Fiddler on the
Roof'' and ``Boccaccio,'' as well as in off-Broadway and regional
productions.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, he is survived by two daughters, Marika
Hufford-Zaslow and Helena Hufford-Zaslow, both of Manhattan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
