<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLAIBORNE MULLS TCU AND NFL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Now that USC has had a couple of days to ponder
Texas Christian as its opponent in the Sun Bowl, the Trojans
believe the 6-5 Horned Frogs pose a big dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just kind of in a lose-lose situation,'' linebacker
Chris Claiborne said. ``If we win by seven points, people would
say, `God, they only won by seven.' But if we lose, it's even
worse.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Bowl is a long way off for Claiborne, who has a busy
itinerary this month. He gets to go to Orlando this weekend for the
presentation of the Butkus Award, for which he is a finalist with
Texas A&AMP;M's Dat Nguyen and Florida's Jevon Kearse. The honor goes
to the nation's top linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm extremely excited,'' Claiborne said. ``It's good for me
and the university. I'm just looking to go there and have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Claiborne will also meet with USC coach Paul Hackett today for
the first of several meetings in which his NFL stock will be
discussed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Hackett and I have a lot of talking to do,'' Claiborne
said. ``We'll talk and discuss my options. Hopefully, I can use him
as a measuring stick of where I am as a player.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said he has already talked to a couple of teams and will
speak to several more about Claiborne's pro prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``My role is to gather as much information as I can and be
supportive of Chris,'' Hackett said. ``He's also my No. 1 recruit.
If he returns, that makes our defense infinitely better (next
season).''
</P>
<P>
   It figures to be impossible to keep Claiborne in school. He is
listed by draft guru Mel Kiper as the No. 3 pick in the first round
of Kiper's mock draft.
</P>
<P>
   Claiborne said he isn't swayed by how the Trojans perform in the
Sun Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just my own man,'' Claiborne said. ``I just have to do
what's best for me.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Hawaii interviews Young: University of Hawaii athletic
director Hugh Yoshida and four other members of a search committee
interviewed USC defensive coordinator Bill Young on Tuesday morning
as a possible replacement to Fred vonAppen, who was fired last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Young is one of several candidates for the job, including San
Diego Chargers coach June Jones, Utah coach Ron McBride and Arizona
assistant coach Duane Akina.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always feel good after you interview, but who knows?''
Young said. ``I think it's a job that will take a lot of effort and
a lot of work. I think it'sa program that can be turned around. I
don't know what the pecking order is. All the people have strong
points.''
</P>
<P>
   Young said he expects Hawaii to hire a coach by this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be really disappointed if we lost him,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Injury update: Hackett said he was optimistic wide receiver
Windrell Haynes (sprained big toe) would be able to return to
practice before the Sun Bowl. Offensive lineman Matt Welch did not
practice Tuesday because he has tests to undergo regarding heart
palpitations he experienced during the Notre Dame game. Welch is
expected to return sometime before Christmas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
