<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-CHIEFS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET RICH QUICK SCHEME: COWBOYS FOCUS ON PASS RUSH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
ANALYSIS  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Kansas City team the Cowboys will face
Sunday at Arrowhead Stadium bears little resemblance to the boring
Chiefs teams of past seasons or the bumbling offensive group that
got off to a slow start this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs (5-8) may be out of the playoff chase, but their
offense is playing as well as any in the league. Kansas City has
topped the 30-point barrier in each of the past three games _ a
first in 10 years under conservative coach Marty Schottenheimer and
a first for the franchise since 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said it's no coincidence that the
scoring explosion coincided with Schottenheimer's decision to go
with Rich Gannon at quarterback instead of Elvis Grbac. During the
three-game span, Gannon has completed 68 of 104 passes for 774
yards with seven touchdowns, two interceptions and a sizzling
quarterback rating of 102.1.
</P>
<P>
   He threw three touchdown passes in each of the past two weeks to
become the first Chiefs quarterback to accomplish the feat since
Steve DeBerg in 1990. Gailey said he likes Gannon's ball
distribution, considering that four Chiefs have caught at least 35
passes _ running back Kimble Anders (51), tight end Tony Gonzalez
(43) and wide receivers Derrick Alexander (40) and Andre Rison
(35).
</P>
<P>
   Gannon ``is playing pretty well,'' Gailey said. ``He is throwing
the ball deep and accurately. And he's got a lot of different
weapons. They are spreading the ball around like we've done and
made plays.''
</P>
<P>
   However, what worries Gailey and the Cowboys is not only
Gannon's arm but his legs. A scrambler, Gannon has hurt defenses by
moving around and creating plays on the corners. He has proved
dangerous throwing the ball on the move and taking off for big
runs.
</P>
<P>
   And the Cowboys have had trouble lately with mobile
quarterbacks, namely Arizona's Jake Plummer and New Orleans' Kerry
Collins. The Cowboys have gotten pressure, but have not been able
to get sacks on a consistent basis and have allowed quarterbacks to
slip out of the pocket and make plays.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' defense has recorded five sacks in the past three
games, the worst three-game stint of the season. Defensive ends
Greg Ellis and Kavika Pittman have recorded 1.5 sacks combined in
the past six games.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys will likely use a linebacker or safety as a ``spy''
on the quarterback on obvious passing downs. But defensive line
