<HEADER>
A9784 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     12-08 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPLAY NOT THE ANSWER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Right. What the NFL really needs is a bunch of confused,
middle-aged guys, crowded around a sideline Sony, trying to decide
if what they think they see is what they thought they saw.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, I'm not against instant replay. I think it's the closest
thing to root canal surgery going in sports.
</P>
<P>
   I especially like the NFL's proposed new system for the
playoffs, whereby coaches can ``challenge'' an official's eyesight
at an opportune moment of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Yep. That should make calls go the challenging coach's way in
those final two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   And behind which team's sideline will the TV replay monitor be
placed? Just wondering. Does the team with the TV get to help?
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the NFL has an officiating crisis. In the past two
weeks alone, we've seen major officiating gaffes cost games for the
Buffalo Bills, Seattle Seahawks and Pittsburgh Steelers. We've seen
80-year-old Ralph Wilson, owner of the Bills, openly defy
whippersnapper commissioner Paul Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   And we've seen reports, conspicuous by their timing, that
indicate the league might be willing to employ a shake-and-bake
replay system after a thorough preparation period of, oh, three
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, I'm not against instant replay. Some, I suppose, is better
than none at all.
</P>
<P>
   But for Tagliabue's office to even acknowledge that a playoff
revival of replay is being considered cleverly masks the real
point.
</P>
<P>
   Namely, the officiating stinks. The zebras can no longer keep up
with the cheetahs and the hyenas. It's as if things are happening
too fast for the men in striped shirts, a notion that lacks
scientific merit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got robbed _ it was awful!'' Wilson said after not one, but
two, bad calls in the final minute cost his Bills a 25-21 defeat to
New England.
</P>
<P>
   As one of the old American Football League's original owners,
Wilson has been voting against NFL instant replay proposals for the
better part of 13 seasons. Bill Parcells, whose New York Jets
benefited from Sunday's mythical Vinny Testaverde touchdown, once
coached the Giants, who have voted against replays nine out of nine
times.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells said he would change his Jets vote in a minute if he
thought it would cure the problem. But the more important thing,
Parcells added, is that the officials get things right.
</P>
<P>
   Is that asking too much?
</P>
<P>
   These days, alas, the answer is probably yes. Officials in the
NFL have lost their edge. Though 112 strong, the corps of officials
is not deep in talent. More than one-third of them have four years
or less of pro football experience.
</P>
<P>
   They are paid anywhere from $1,200 to $4,000 to work a game. And
when it's over, they go home _ home to their ``real'' jobs of being
school principals and investment advisers.
</P>
<P>
   In all probability, none of them has ever been roused from a
quiet Monday night's sleep by an angry Tagliabue. Or an
even-angrier Tex Schramm.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue has bankers to call, I suspect. He is an owners
commissioner, and he must spend his days figuring out ways for the
league's Jeffrey Luries and Jerry Joneses to recoup their NFL
investments.
</P>
<P>
   Forget pass interference. The current commissioner deals more in
seat licenses and finding a team for the big TV market in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   When Schramm ran the Cowboys, he was a member of the most
powerful and far-ranging inner circle in pro football _ the NFL's
competition committee. Pass interference may not have been easier
to call in the '70s, but almost without fail the competition
committee would script an annual official interpretation of it.
</P>
<P>
   The nuts and bolts of the game, the delicate balance between
offense and defense, the game's ongoing and projected trends _
Schramm and his committeemen would study the issues and prepare
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Those recommendations invariably involved the way NFL games were
officiated. It was a league priority when Pete Rozelle ruled the
pro football earth.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, there's this vision of lawyer Tagliabue, trying to put
the league's genie back in the bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody expects perfection. Referees aren't perfect. Clergymen
aren't perfect. Sportswriters aren't perfect.
</P>
<P>
   But in the latter two cases, there is somebody to answer to.
</P>
<P>
   Hiring full-time officials would help. You wonder how many of
the NFL's weekend ``temps'' still have the problems of their
Monday-through-Friday jobs on their minds when Sunday comes. It's
only natural.
</P>
<P>
   Instant replay? It'll do. Firing some officials? Absolutely, but
replace them with what?
</P>
<P>
   The problem remains. NFL officiating has to get better _ not
simply watched over and over.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Wilson, 80 years wise, knew what he was talking about last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner, were you listening?
</P>
<P>
   (Gil LeBreton is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
