<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9788 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-IMPEACH-ART-1STLD-W     12-08 0486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-IMPEACH-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE OPENS FORMAL DEFENSE OF PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating entire story)  (Eds.: SUBS lead and 4th graf to recast for clarity; SUBS 7th graf
bgng, But even ..., to CORRECT rebuttal is 182 pages, sted 184; 2nd
and 3rd takes stand.)  
(See also: IMPEACH-ASSESS, IMPEACH-LEGAL, IMPEACH-SCENE,
IMPEACH-CRAIG, IMPEACH-REPUBS, IMPEACH-LAME, IMPEACH-REBUTTAL,
CLINTON-DAY, CLINTON-TEXT) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(htv) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER with LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House opened its formal defense of
President Clinton on Tuesday, addressing in greater detail than
before the facts and issues of the impeachment case against Clinton
and adopting a more conciliatory tone in testimony before the House
Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lawyers and three panels of anti-impeachment witnesses
conducted a grueling day-into-night tutorial for the 37-member
committee on why Clinton should not be removed from office for his
admitted misconduct in the Monica Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as no fancy language can obscure the simple fact that
what the president did was morally wrong,'' said Gregory Craig, the
White House special counsel who led the defense effort Tuesday,
``no amount of rhetoric can change the legal reality that there are
no grounds for impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's lawyers assembled a battery of witnesses who
virtually conceded that his behavior was reprehensible, but said
impeachment was graver threat to the nation than allowing the
president to serve out his tarnished final two years in office.
</P>
<P>
   The president's defenders tried to blur the hard edges of his
fundamental point of defense _ that he misbehaved and misled, but
did not obstruct justice or commit perjury. His conduct was surely
sinful, said Craig, but just as certainly not impeachable.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides said Tuesday night that Clinton was likely to
make some public comment on the committee's deliberations, perhaps
offering another statement of remorse to temper lingering concerns
among wavering Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   But even as Craig and his nine friendly witnesses was trying to
put a gentler face on the president's defense, White House lawyers
released a 184-page rebuttal that once again harshly attacked
Kenneth Starr, accusing him of slanting the case against the
president by excluding exculpatory evidence in his impeachment
referral to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The presentation from the president's men did not appear to sway
any minds on the bitterly divided Judiciary Committee. But the
debate, which was by turns tedious, riveting and mildly salacious,
was aimed more at a body of moderate Republicans outside the
committee who hold in their hands the president's fate.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Republicans on the committee were insistent on
pinning down what they believe to be a pattern of perjury by the
president and evasions by his lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Craig and Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla., engaged in a sharp
exchange over what Canady said was a clear lie by Clinton, a
statement in his deposition in the Paula Jones lawsuit that he
could not recall having been alone with Monica Lewinsky in the Oval
Office area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now Mr. Craig,'' Canady asked, ``is it your position here
today on behalf of the president that when the president gave those
answers in the deposition, he was telling the truth?''
</P>
<P>
   Craig replied: ``That's correct, congressman. He answered the
question that it was possible that he was alone with her. This is
in the civil deposition, so all the description that I gave to that
civil deposition is accurate. It was evasive, it was misleading, he
tried to be narrowly accurate, but congressman, he did not violate
his oath.''
</P>
<P>
   An exasperated Canady said, ``It seems to me that the president
unequivocally denied that he had any specific recollection of being
alone with Ms. Lewinsky. And for you to contend today that that's
truthful, I think, is not credible.''
</P>
<P>
   As the damp, dreary day grew dark at mid-afternoon, a few rays
of hope appeared for the White House. Rep. Amo Houghton a moderate
New York Republican, announced that he would oppose impeachment on
the floor of the House.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Alphonse D'Amato, a frequent critic of Clinton, said
Tuesday night that the House should heed popular will and refrain
from impeaching the president. D'Amato, who lost a reelection bid
last month, said that tying up the Senate in a trial of Clinton
``doesn't make sense'' for the nation or the Republican party.
</P>
<P>
   White House lobbyists also reported progress toward persuading
several other wavering Republicans to vote against any bill of
impeachment that reaches the House next week.
</P>
<P>
   William Weld, the former Republican governor of Massachusetts,
was recruited Tuesday to appear as a witness on the president's
behalf on Wednesday and was reported to be making calls to
Republican friends in Congress to persuade them to vote against
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
