<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9792 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-LAWYERS09-COX     12-08 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-LAWYERS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lawyers go to battle over fees in tobacco settlement
 &HT;    By Osler McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas' controversial tobacco settlement got more
controversial Tuesday as plaintiffs' lawyers who represented three
states against cigarette makers trained their guns on each other in
an effort to get as much as they can of a $500 million yearly cap
on attorneys' fees.
</P>
<P>
   The swelling dispute grew with reports in two newspapers that
the Texas lawyers _ already vilified by politicians and tort-reform
advocates for seeking as much as $2.6 billion in fees _ were now
seeking 10 times that for their pay.
</P>
<P>
   Texans for Lawsuit Reform, one of several critics of the tobacco
settlement and the lawyers representing the state, called the $25
billion a ``public relations ploy'' to justify the lawyers'
original fees request.
</P>
<P>
   But sources involved on several sides of the tobacco fees fight
said the $25 billion figure was misleading. They said it was only
one projection offered by an independent financial analysis
commissioned by all the plaintiffs' lawyers involved in Texas,
Mississippi and Florida tobacco settlements _ and now scrambling to
get as much from the yearly limit as they can.
</P>
<P>
   In settling lawsuits with 49 states, the tobacco industry capped
at $500 million a year the amount it would pay out in attorney's
fees. So as the arbitrators decide how much tobacco must pay the
lawyers, what goes into one legal team's pocket must come from
another's. The arbitrators' decision could be announced as early as
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Texas followed Mississippi and Florida in first settling a
nationwide assault on the once impregnable U.S. tobacco companies
to recover state payments for treating poor people with smoking
diseases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The $25-billion figure is totally ridiculous, totally
misleading,'' said one person who heard presentations last weekend
to three arbitrators chosen to decide how much the tobacco
defendants would pay attorneys who sued them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are jockeying for relative position,'' said of the
lawyers involved.
</P>
<P>
   All parties in the arbitration have agreed to keep their
proposals confidential until the arbitration panel rules. But
sources close to the five Texas lawyers Attorney General Dan
Morales hired to represent Texas _ as well as others without a
stake in the Texas fees _ said the $25 billion represented one
scenario posed by a Yale management professor hired by all private
lawyers in the fees arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   Under the financial analysis, prepared by Yale professor William
Getzman and based on common assumptions for all states, Texas
lawyers could get as much as $25 billion over 50 years if
arbitrators were to award them 25 percent of what the state
recovered _ as Florida lawyers seek and as their contract with the
state specifies. Under that scenario, Florida lawyers would get
about $18 billion and Mississippi's lawyers would get $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Getzman would not comment. But one source with direct knowledge
of presentations that arbitrators heard in New York last weekend
said lawyers who represented Mississippi _ the first state to sue
and settle with the tobacco makers _ demanded no less than what
lawyers in any other state got.
</P>
<P>
   Under Getzman's calculations, that would mean Mississippi
lawyers would recover as much as Texas lawyers get and possibly
more than Mississippi _ the client _ got.
</P>
<P>
   One source close to the Texas lawyers said their written
proposal to the arbitrators asked for the amount under their
contract with Morales _ 15 percent of the $17.3 billion Texas
recovered in its settlement, or $2.6 billion. But they noted that
they could have asked for more under the contract. The Texas
lawyers noted that their contract with Morales also specified that
they could ask for more than 15 percent if their expenses exceeded
a certain amount.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Morning News reported that Morales had endorsed to
the arbitrators in New York the Texas lawyers' request for $25
billion. But that was wrong, the attorney general said in a
statement Tuesday. Morales insisted that he told the arbitrators he
supported the 15 percent the lawyers would get under his original
contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no role, nor do I have any knowledge about the private
lawyers' arguments using various economic models to inflate the
value of the Texas judgment,'' he said. ``I was not present for
that portion of the panel discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas tobacco lawyers were led by Beaumont attorney Walter
Umphrey and included Harold Nix of Daingerfield, Wayne Reaud of
Beaumont and John Eddie Williams and John O'Quinn, both of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Another source said Getzman's calculations established that
tobacco companies would never pay more than $7 billion for legal
fees in total for all lawyers making claims because of the $500
million-a-year fees limit. Tobacco companies settled with Texas and
all other states but Minnesota by requiring their total obligation
for lawyers' fees could not exceed $500 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   The limit does not have an inflation factor. That means that no
matter how much all attorneys get from arbitrators, the cigarette
companies will pay no more than $500 million each year even as time
reduces how much money is worth.
</P>
<P>
   Based on reduced values of money over time, Getzman calculated
his $7 billion limit on what the tobacco companies would ever pay,
the source said.
</P>
<P>
   One source surmised that the tobacco companies were the true
winners in the tobacco cases because of how the companies
structured the settlements to avoid bankruptcy _ and avoid a
bankruptcy trustee's control of their companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only can you live with it,'' he said, ``but you can make
out like a bandit.''
</P>
<P>
   Osler McCarthy writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
