<DOCNO> NYT19981208.0464 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9793 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-IMPEACH-ART-1STLD-W     12-08 1744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-IMPEACH-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: against impeachment.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the first time, after months of bitter name-calling and
diversionary tactics, both sides engaged in a sober debate on the
merits of the case against Clinton. The president's witnesses,
while not answering all the specific factual accusations, presented
a detailed argument as to why the president's offenses were serious
but were not the basis for a constitutional cataclysm.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the flurry of paper and the cacophony of testimony, Clinton
was silent on all matters legal. He opened a two-day White House
conference on Social Security before flying to Nashville to attend
a memorial service for Albert Gore Sr., the father of the vice
president. He returned to Washington this evening to receive an
award for his peacemaking efforts in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The defense team assembled by the White House offered few new
arguments against impeachment, but there was a discernible shift in
approach. Led by the soothing Craig, the White House witnesses,
with a few pointed exceptions, attempted for the most part a
strategy of apology rather than argument. None raised objections to
the possibility of a Congressional vote of censure as a way of
expressing displeasure short of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Ivy League scholars, congressional veterans of the last
impeachment debate and former Watergate prosecutors all carried the
White House message that Bill Clinton is not Richard Nixon and that
sexual misconduct does not constitute a great offense against the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Craig implored members of Congress, and through them a
nationwide cable television audience, to listen to Clinton's case
before deciding on the momentous step of impeaching and removing a
popularly-elected president.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we begin this undertaking,'' Craig said at the outset of
the marathon presentation, ``I make only one plea to you, and I
hope it is not a futile one, coming this late in the process. Open
your mind. Open your heart, and focus on the record. As you sit
there listening to me at this moment, you may already be determined
to vote to approve some articles of impeachment against this
president. That is your right and your duty, if you believe the
facts and the law justify such a vote.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he said, the White House would present a powerful case
to the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the close of tomorrow, all the world will see one simple
and undeniable fact: whatever there is in the record that shows
that what the president did was wrong and blameworthy, there is
nothing in the record in either the law or the facts, that would
justify his impeachment and removal from office.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House and its Democratic allies in Congress held out
little hope of averting a committee vote on one or more articles of
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone was expecting any movement from the
members of the committee,'' one White House strategist said
tonight. ``The committee long ago determined they were not going to
be an audience for our defense. That's not who we are addressing
today and tommorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House on Tuesday offered the 20 to 30 Republicans who
appear to be undecided on impeachment what many of them have
demanded _ more contrition and less legal artifice; more facts in
defense of the president's actions and less spin.
</P>
<P>
   Craig conveyed to the committee what he said was Clinton's
``profound and powerful regret'' for his actions and equivocations.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has insisted and personally instructed his lawyers that no
technicalities or legalities should be allowed to obscure the
simple moral truth that his behavior in this matter was wrong,''
Craig said in his opening remarks. ``The president wants everyone
to know _ the committee, the Congress and the country _ that he is
genuinely sorry for the pain and the damage that he has caused and
for the wrongs that he has committed.''
</P>
<P>
   But if anyone thought that was to be a prelude to a confession
to perjury, obstruction of justice or abuse of power, they were
disappointed. Craig vigorously defended the president's misleading
testimony before a judge in a civil case and a criminal grand jury,
using the same legal contortions that have maddened prosecutors and
Republican opponents all year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's testimony was evasive, incomplete, misleading,
even maddening,'' Craig said, ``but it was not perjury.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Inglis, R-S.C.,, tried to pin Craig down on the
president's statements about his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did he lie?'' when he said that he had not had sex with Ms.
Lewinsky, Inglis repeatedly demanded to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``He certainly misled and deceived,'' Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   Inglis repeated, ``He doesn't believe that he lied?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, he does not believe that he lied, because his notion of
what sex is is what the dictionary definition is,'' Craig answered.
``I understand you're not going to like this, congressman, because
you will see it as a technical defense or a hair-splitting, evasive
answer, but sexual relations is defined in every dictionary in a
certain way, and he did not have that kind of sexual contact with
Ms. Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   The morning session before the committee included scholars from
Harvard, Princeton and Yale who had previously expressed opposition
to impeachment, as well as Nicholas deB. Katzenbach, who served as
attorney general under President Lyndon B. Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Wilentz, professor of American history at Princeton,
angered several Republican members of the committee by warning them
that what he characterized as an unjustified vote to impeach
Clinton would bring them the opprobrium of history.
</P>
<P>
   Wilentz argued that Clinton's alleged offenses _ even if all
were proven true _ do not warrant impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you believe they do rise to that level, you will vote for
impeachment and take your risk at going down in history with the
zealots and the fanatics,'' Wilentz said. ``If you understand that
the charges do not rise to the level of impeachment, or if you are
at all unsure, and yet you vote in favor of impeachment anyway for
some other reason, history will track you down and condemn you for
your cravenness. Alternatively, you could muster the courage of
your convictions. The choice is yours.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress do not take kindly to such lectures.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Steve Buyer, R-Ind., said that he did not appreciate being
called a fanatic and a coward.
</P>
<P>
   ``That type of name-calling by the president's defense is
disappointing and demeaning to this proceeding,'' Buyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenbach made the point that impeachment was devised by the
authors of the Constitution as a means to remove a president who by
his behavior had so compromised his position that he could not
longer fulfill the functions of the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenbach said that most instances of perjury would not
undermine a president's ability to remain in office. And he noted
that Clinton continued to enjoy high public-approval ratings and
therefore had not squandered his mandate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I am correct, then it seems to me the fundamental question
is simply whether the president has done something which has
destroyed public confidence in his ability to continue in that
office,'' Katzenbach said. ``If the public doesn't believe that
what he has done seriously affects his ability to perform his
public duties as president, should the committee conclude that his
acts have destroyed public confidence essential to that office?''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Ackerman, professor of law at Yale University, said that
the House was confronted with the question of whether Clinton's
conduct represented ``an assault on the fundamental principles of
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Arguing that it does not, Ackerman added that if such were the
case, ``our history over the last two centuries would be littered
with bills of impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman also asserted that any articles of impeachment voted by
the current lame duck Congress would expire when the new Congress
takes office in January. He said that the new Congress, with five
fewer Republicans, would have to vote again on articles of
impeachment before a Senate trial could take place.
</P>
<P>
   The scholars were replaced at the witness table in the afternoon
by three former Democratic members of the Judiciary Committee who
voted to approve articles of impeachment against Nixon in 1974 _
Elizabeth Holtzman of New York, Robert Drinan of Massachusetts and
Wayne Owens of Utah.
</P>
<P>
   They appeared as ``the three ghosts of impeachment past,'' as
Owens put it.
</P>
<P>
   Drinan, now a law professor at Georgetown University, called the
drive toward impeachment an act of ``vengeance'' and he predicted
that it would lead to an explosion of anger among the American
people.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. George Gekas, R-Pa., thundered, ``Do you seriously believe
that any member of this committee or this House will be driven by
vengeance?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will leave God to judge,'' replied Drinan, a Jesuit priest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe God's messenger should not be prejudge that,'' Gekas
retorted.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Holtzman, who served as U.S. attorney in Brooklyn, N.Y.,
after leaving Congress, argued that there is a huge difference
between impeaching one of hundreds of appointed federal judges and
removing from office the nation's lone elected president.
</P>
<P>
   She expanded on her point in response to a question from Rep.
James Sensenbrenner, R-Wis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that many on this committee and many in the country
believe the president's conduct to be reprehensible and
unacceptable,'' Ms. Holtzman said. ``I do not disagree, and I'm not
here to excuse that conduct. Let us remember, however, that the
goal of impeachment is not to punish a president but to protect the
nation. Impeachment now will punish the nation, not protect it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nightfall brought the day's two final witnesses, Richard
Ben-Veniste and James Hamilton, prominent Democratic lawyers and
former Watergate prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Ben-Veniste criticized Starr for conducting a crusade against
the president and employing relentless and unfair tactics to bring
him down.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, who once advised Clinton to aggressively employ all
legal methods to thwart the numerous investigations plaguing his
presidency, said that Clinton's offenses were ``low crimes'' worthy
of censure, not impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   If all lying politicians were chased from office, Hamilton told
the weary committee, ``I fear the halls of government would be
seriously depleted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-98 2355EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
