<DOCNO> NYT19981208.0469 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9801 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIVIL-THEATER-REVIEW-     12-08 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIVIL-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CIVIL DISOBEDIENCE': PROVING THAT ACTIONS SPEAK LOUDER THAN WORDS
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
(nk) 
 By   D.J.R . BRUCKNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Denise Stoklos enunciates a program for the new
millennium in her one-woman show ``Civil Disobedience: Morning Is
When I Am Awake and There Is an Aurora in Me.'' But if you ignore
it _ that is quite easy to do _ you are likely to enjoy the
performance much more. The title comes from Thoreau's famous essay,
and Ms. Stoklos' message is that for the next thousand years,
thoughtful people have an obligation to dissent from any idea or
social arrangement that would constrain creative living. She draws
part of her text from Thoreau and ties it into ideas of Brazilian
educator and philosopher Paolo Freire. This would draw you to the
theater?
</P>
<P>
   No. But Ms. Stoklos should. The Brazilian actress, who for 20
years has staged inventions of a bewildering variety in more than
30 countries, is a master of illusion and surprise and has an
irrepressible sense of humor. In ``Civil Disobedience,'' while she
talks about certain of Thoreau's ideas, she gives the impression
that her body has a mind of its own, one bent on sending up the
ideals she is presenting.
</P>
<P>
   Thus Thoreau's declaration that to open people's minds he had no
choice but to write and speak out leads to a riff on Times Square
and its signs _ impressively ridiculed on eight television screens
that appear over her head. She conjures up the scene so well all by
herself that we can practically hear the sounds of traffic and
crowds, and the point of the sudden leap away from the woodsy
solitude of Walden Pond does not have to be labored.
</P>
<P>
   And when Thoreau observes that most lives are simply wasted, the
Stoklos version of waste is a long and hilarious routine of the
actress' putting on makeup, the viewpoint of the audience being
that of the mirror. Ms. Stoklos has a large repertoire of clowns'
tricks to reshape her face, but she also has some that seem
original. With tongue in cheek, or better yet, in upper lip, she
can so completely distort her profile that it is difficult to
believe she is not wearing some kind of hidden prosthesis, or even
a mask. She ends this routine opining that she's lower than a worm
and her exit is a vermicular crawl no human being should be capable
of.
</P>
<P>
   She can also be tartly entertaining about Thoreau's praise of
simple furnishings and such pleasures as the isolation as reading.
Her simple furniture includes, of course, the eight television sets
that are never turned off lest she miss something. And her reading
is one of the more emphatic texts of Gertrude Stein that, in Ms.
Stoklos' exaggeratedly regular rhythms, reduces the audience to
helpless giggling.
</P>
<P>
   Repeatedly Ms. Stoklos returns to philosophical meditations by
Thoreau and others and seems to be quite serious about them, but
the moment she moves, or looks directly at the audience, her body
completely undermines what her mouth is saying. The whole act is
like a conversation with an inspired lunatic whose skeletal
framework is rubber, not bone. If the coming millennium aspires to
what she does and not what she says it could be paradisal.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `CIVIL DISOBEDIENCE: Morning Is When I Am Awake and There Is an
Aurora in Me'
</P>
<P>
   Concept, direction, adaptation, additional text, soundtrack and
performance by Denise Stoklos. Text by Henry David Thoreau;
costumes by Rebecca Nassauer; sets by Gringo Cardia; lighting by
Maneco Quindere. Presented by La Mama E.T.C. At 74A East Fourth
Street, East Village.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-98 2357EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981208.0470 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9803 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-IMPEACH-NYT &LR;      12-08 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-IMPEACH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: UNFAZED BY EXCESS, PUNDITS CHATTER ON ... AND
ON
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The beauty part of the television blowhard's calling
is that you never have to say you're sorry. When you are obliged to
talk as incessantly as demanded by that line of work, especially on
nonstop cable, you are bound to utter foolish, pointless, peculiar
things, and the louder, the more authoritative. But neither excess
nor error nor eccentricity can stay these spouters from their
anointed rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians can be kicked out of office, corporation executives
can lose their perks, athletes can be fined. But the privileged
cadre nicely named the chattering class goes on forever.
</P>
<P>
   Programs that started out as discussions have slid down the
slopes of entertainment into sheer blather. One might have thought
that NBC News worthies would by now have slinked away in chagrin at
the Monica merchandising that has been MSNBC's stock in trade for
months. But no, respectables like Tim Russert are still lending
themselves to that dubious enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   The grapplings on CNBC, the Fox Network and elsewhere as
debaters vie in the ferocity stakes are about as reasoned as
wrestling matches. For viewers, the saving grace of a McLaughlin
gang or one of its clones is that half the time you can't make out
what any of them is saying.
</P>
<P>
   Over in more sedate precincts, one might assume that the
remarkably wrong predictions of the regulars on ABC's ``This
Week,'' who announced President Clinton's forced departure from
office a year or so ago, would have earned them a vacation. But
there's Sam Donaldson still delivering bombast and Bill Kristol
indulging in wishful analysis. George Will, who one assumes was
hired to bring a touch of class to the gab, is descending into
vituperation.
</P>
<P>
   Thus do the imperatives of show business impinge on the
discipline of journalism. Call it all talk, rarely listen
television. It's in the nature of a medium that never stops
running; any sound is preferable to the sound of silence.
</P>
<P>
   The spirit blossoms in all its glory on talk shows and call-ins,
but it infiltrates what used to be known as hard-news programs,
too. From the wackiest to the relatively conventional, the people
we are hearing often don't seem to be hearing themselves. Does
anybody care? Polls tell us that the nation doesn't particularly
like or trust journalists, but there's no escape. Nonstop news
abhors a vacuum; the model has become the mayhem of the Internet or
of upchuck radio.
</P>
<P>
   It's head-to-talking-head competition, not over anything as
rarefied as depth or analysis but simply over attention grabbers.
On the networks as well as on cable, Monica Lewinsky guaranteed
ratings; and what was actually heard amid the din was mostly
filler.
</P>
<P>
   The hawkers of those commodities tend to come on loud and fast
and are never caught in the dead air of reflection. Assertions
abound; reservations are risky. A pause for breath may send
millions of viewers to the remote control. So you repeat what you
or somebody said yesterday. If you're really stumped, take a call
from Freddy in Philadelphia. Does anyone notice that the callers
are given to parroting what they have just heard? That would be
like criticizing elevator music on esthetic grounds.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, words of sense do emerge, but they are quickly
drowned in the commotion. It may be imagination, but I think I've
detected more than once a look of alarm as some stunned sobersides
who actually has something original or interesting to say suddenly
realizes that he has accepted an invitation to bedlam.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict here is between freedom, or the illusion of
freedom, and responsibility, which brings with it some sort of
control. When communication is reduced to noise and populism runs
rampant, not only is everyone entitled to be heard, but courtesy
requires that all opinions be treated as of like worth. Expertise
becomes window dressing; the experts, too, after all, are competing
for who will be called back; stutterers need not apply.
Credentials, education, knowledge become a form of discrimination.
Standards become stuffy, elitist. Larry King is the great leveler.
</P>
<P>
   The loose-talk formula has appeal; it can be infectious. The
intelligent Will cannot fail to notice that in this contest anybody
can get away with anything; no one is called to account, so why
strain for some rigor of discourse when rival performers are
mouthing off on all sides without nice distinctions that might slow
down the hustle to be first to nowhere? If network news has been
getting soft at the edges, with graphic fripperies and an endless
supply of revelations of medical wonders, that's in part an effort
to keep up with or down with the cable crowd.
</P>
<P>
   In this universe of deafening interactive nonstop hot air,
journalists find themselves in competition not just with their
peers but with everybody. The lately liberated audience members
turn out to have a lot to say and is increasingly insistent on
saying it, and their hosts are in no position to tell them to stuff
it.
</P>
<P>
   A dedication to ratings is democratic, all right, but not a sure
route to information. Becoming informed sometimes requires that one
shut up and listen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-08-98 2357EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
