<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981208.0471 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9805 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NCAA-SUPREME-COURT-CO     12-08 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NCAA-SUPREME-COURT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    High court decision may affect college sports rules
 &HT;    By Osler McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Had it been a game, Tuesday's legal argument
about college football before the Texas Supreme Court would have
been an NCAA victory by forfeit.
</P>
<P>
   With the opposition withdrawing from a lawsuit last week, an
Amarillo attorney representing the National Collegiate Athletic
Association played both offense and defense as he tried to persuade
justices to keep a one-time Texas Tech University football player
from being allowed to do an end run around intercollegiate athletic
rules.
</P>
<P>
   What the justices decide could affect whether the NCAA can
sanction a school after an ineligible player gets a court order to
let him play. The Supreme Court made no ruling Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the NCAA's rules, it can later sanction a school if the
court order was wrongly granted.
</P>
<P>
   But in this case, Tech and its player may have proved more
nimble than the courts. Before any court had a chance to decide if
the order was wrongly granted, the player finished his last season
and the courts dismissed the case as moot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes for a toothless bylaw if all that has to happen is
for an athlete or a school to go to a friendly court for a
temporary injunction,'' said the NCAA's public relations director,
Wally Renfro. ``It makes it very difficult for us.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case, the NCAA disqualified Tech football player Joel
Casey Jones when he was a fifth-year senior because of an
eligibility question related to its so-called 75 percent rule. The
rule requires student athletes to have completed three-quarters of
their course work by the ninth semester.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, an All-State high school player from the Houston area,
had changed his major and claimed that Tech academic advisers
miscalculated under an NCAA rule.
</P>
<P>
   Tech asked for a waiver, but the NCAA denied it.
</P>
<P>
   Jones then requested _ and got _ a temporary order from a
Lubbock County state district court judge. The judge allowed Jones
to compete until a trial was held to decide his eligibility. But
the hearing to decide this was put off until the season ended.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA tried to get the 7th District Court of Appeals in
Amarillo to overturn the temporary order, but the court decided it
had no authority to hear the case because it was moot: the season
had ended.
</P>
<P>
   Absent that court ruling, the athletic association _ the
rules-making body for most college sports in the United States _
could not enforce its rule and sanction Tech, said Todd Lafferty,
the Amarillo attorney representing the NCAA. The trial judge never
reached that point.
</P>
<P>
   It placed the NCAA in a legal netherworld _ sort of a perpetual
time-out.
</P>
<P>
   If the Supreme Court does not overturn the appeals court, Renfro
said, then the NCAA rule that could allow it to force schools to
forfeit games in cases like this would be toothless.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no relief,'' he said. ``There's no way to get to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Osler McCarthy writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
